{"title_page": "David E. Lownds", "text_new": "{{Infobox military person\n| image = MG Rathvon M. Tompkins and David E. Lownds.jpg\n| caption = Lownds (right) with [[3rd Marine Division (United States)|3rd Marine Division]] commander MG [[Rathvon M. Tompkins]] at Khe Sanh, 1 February 1968  \n| nickname = \n| birth_date = {{birth date|1920|10|4}}\n| birth_place = \n| death_date = {{death-date and age|August 31, 2011|October 4, 1920}}\n| death_place = [[Naples, Florida]]\n| placeofburial = [[Quantico National Cemetery]]\n| placeofburial_label = Place of burial\n| allegiance = [[United States of America]]\n| branch = [[File:USMC logo.svg|25px]]&nbsp;[[United States Marine Corps]]\n| serviceyears = 1942\u20131991\n| rank = [[File:US-O6 insignia.svg|28px]] [[Colonel (United States)|Colonel]]\n| unit = \n| commands = [[26th Marine Regiment (United States)|26th Marine Regiment]]\n| battles = '''[[World War II]]'''<br>'''[[Korean War]]'''<br>'''[[Dominican Civil War]]'''<br>'''[[Vietnam War]]'''\n*[[Battle of Khe Sanh]]\n| awards = [[Navy Cross]]<br>[[Bronze Star]]<br>[[Purple Heart]] (2)\n| relations = [[George R. Christmas]] (son-in-law)\n| laterwork = \n}}\n\n'''David Edward Lownds''' (October 4, 1920 \u2013 August 31, 2011) was a [[United States Marine Corps]] [[Colonel (United States)|colonel]] who served in the [[Vietnam War]], notably as ground commander at [[Khe Sanh Combat Base]] during the [[Battle of Khe Sanh]] in 1968.\n\n==Early life and education==\n{{empty section|date=January 2019}}\n\n==Military career==\n===World War II===\nLownds joined the Marine Corps on 3 March 1942. He was a first lieutenant with Company B, [[1st Battalion, 24th Marines]] during the [[Battle of Kwajalein|Battle of Roi-Namur]].<ref name=24th>{{cite web|url=https://1stbattalion24thmarines.com/the-companies/baker/l/david-e-lownds/|title=David E. Lownds|publisher=1st Battalion, 24th Marines|date=|accessdate=5 November 2018}}</ref>\n\nLownds was wounded while leading Company B, 1/24 Marines during the [[Battle of Saipan]].<ref name=24th/>\n\nDuring the [[Battle of Iwo Jima]] Lownds was attached to Headquarters Company, 1/24 Marines and was again wounded in the battle.<ref name=24th/>\n\nLownds returned to the US following the end of the war, and joined the Marine Reserves on 25 October 1945.<ref name=24th/>\n\n===Korean War===\nLownds returned to active duty during the [[Korean War]].\n\nLownds was serving with the [[I Marine Expeditionary Force]] when they were deployed to the [[Dominican Republic]] aboard {{USS|Boxer|CV-21|6}} during [[Dominican Civil War#U.S. intervention|Operation Powerpack]] in April 1965.\n\n===Vietnam War===\nOn 12 August 1967, Col. Lownds assumed command of the [[26th Marine Regiment (United States)|26th Marine Regiment]] which was conducting [[Operation Ardmore]], continued as [[Operation Scotland]], around [[Khe Sanh Combat Base]] in northwest [[Qu\u1ea3ng Tr\u1ecb Province]].<ref>{{cite book|last=Telfer|first=Gary|title=U.S. Marines in Vietnam: Fighting the North Vietnamese 1967|publisher=History and Museums Division, Headquarters, U.S. Marine Corps|year=1984|url=https://archive.org/details/FightingTheNorthVietnamese|isbn=978-1494285449|page=[https://archive.org/details/FightingTheNorthVietnamese/page/n153 142]}}</ref><ref name=Shulimson>{{cite book|last=Shulimson|first=Jack|title=U.S. Marines in Vietnam: 1968 The Defining Year|publisher=History and Museums Division, Headquarters, U.S. Marine Corps|year=1997|url=https://archive.org/stream/USMarinesInVietnamTheDefiningYear1968#page/n0/mode/2up|isbn=0-16-049125-8|page=62}}</ref>\n\nLownds led the defense of Khe Sanh throughout the [[Battle of Khe Sanh]], ultimately commanding over 6000 Marines at the base. Lownds was criticised by some for failing to send reinforcements to [[Battle of Lang Vei|Lang Vei]] when it came under attack on the night of 6/7 February 1968, but he defended his decision on the basis that Khe Sanh itself was under artillery attack with a ground assault believed to be imminent and that any attempt to reinforce Lang Vei at night would be suicidal. Lownds' decision was accepted by the US command.<ref name=Shulimson/>{{rp|275}} Lownds received further criticism when he refused to allow the approximately 6000 Laotian survivors and dependents of the Lang Vei garrison into the base on the basis that it would compromise base security. These refugees were initially housed outside the base perimeter with most eventually seeking refuge further east.<ref name=Shulimson/>{{rp|276\u20137}}\n[[File:A416482.tif|thumb|right|President Lyndon B. Johnson attaches the Presidential Unit Citation Streamer to the colors of the 26th Marine Regiment as Lownds looks on]]\nLownds was described by [[Michael Herr]] in his book [[Dispatches (book)|''Dispatches'']] as follows: \"Lownds was a deceptively complicated man with a gift (as one of his staff officers put it) for \"jerking off the press\". He could appear as a meek, low-keyed, distracted, and even stupid man (some reporters referred to him privately as \"The lion of Khe Sanh\"), as though he had been carefully picked for just these qualities by a cynical command as a front for its decisions... He was a small man with vague, watery eyes, slightly reminiscent of a rodent in a fable, with one striking feature: a full, scrupulously attended regimental moustache... His professed ignorance of [[Battle of Dien Bien Phu|Dien Bien Phu]] drove correspondents crazy, but it was a dodge. Lownds knew very well about Dien Bien Phu and what had happened there, knew more about it than most of the interviewers.\"<ref>{{cite book|last=Herr|first=Michael|title=Dispatches|publisher=Picador|year=1977|isbn=9781447275077|page=}}</ref>\n\nOn 11 April 1968 Lownds was relieved by Col Bruce F. Meyers.<ref name=Shulimson/>{{rp|287}}\n\nOn 23 May 1968 President [[Lyndon B. Johnson]] presented the [[Presidential Unit Citation (United States)|Presidential Unit Citation]] to the 26th Marines in a ceremony at the [[White House]] attended by Lownds and the 26th Marines Regimental Sergeant-Major.<ref>{{cite book|last=Jones|first=Gregg|title=Last Stand at Khe Sanh: The U.S. Marines' Finest Hour in Vietnam|publisher=Hachette|year=2014|isbn=9780306821400|page=}}</ref><ref name=Shulimson/>{{rp|288}}\n\nLownds was awarded the [[Navy Cross]] for his service at Khe Sanh.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://valor.militarytimes.com/hero/4124|title=David E. Lownds Navy Cross|publisher=Military Times|date=|accessdate=5 November 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Later life==\nLownds died at his home in [[Naples, Florida]], on 31 August 2011.\n\n==References==\n{{Marine Corps}}\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Lownds, David}}\n[[Category:1920 births]]\n[[Category:2011 deaths]]\n[[Category:American Marine Corps personnel of World War II]]\n[[Category:American Marine Corps personnel of the Korean War]]\n[[Category:United States Marine Corps personnel of the Vietnam War]]\n[[Category:Burials at Quantico National Cemetery]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox military person\n| image = MG Rathvon M. Tompkins and David E. Lownds.jpg\n| caption = Lownds (right) with [[3rd Marine Division (United States)|3rd Marine Division]] commander MG [[Rathvon M. Tompkins]] at Khe Sanh, 1 February 1968  \n| nickname = \n| birth_date = {{birth date|1920|10|4}}\n| birth_place = \n| death_date = {{death-date and age|August 31, 2011|October 4, 1920}}\n| death_place = [[Naples, Florida]]\n| placeofburial = [[Quantico National Cemetery]]\n| placeofburial_label = Place of burial\n| allegiance = [[United States of America]]\n| branch = [[File:USMC logo.svg|25px]]&nbsp;[[United States Marine Corps]]\n| serviceyears = 1942\u20131991\n| rank = [[File:US-O6 insignia.svg|28px]] [[Colonel (United States)|Colonel]]\n| unit = \n| commands = [[26th Marine Regiment (United States)|26th Marine Regiment]]\n| battles = '''[[World War II]]'''<br>'''[[Korean War]]'''<br>'''[[Dominican Civil War]]'''<br>'''[[Vietnam War]]'''\n*[[Battle of Khe Sanh]]\n| awards = [[Navy Cross]]<br>[[Bronze Star]]<br>[[Purple Heart]] (2)\n| relations = [[George R. Christmas]] (son-in-law)\n| laterwork = \n}}\n\n'''David Edward Lownds''' (October 4, 1920 \u2013 August 31, 2011) was a [[United States Marine Corps]] [[Colonel (United States)|colonel]] who served in the [[Vietnam War]], notably as ground commander at [[Khe Sanh Combat Base]] during the [[Battle of Khe Sanh]] in 1968.\n\n==Early life and education==\n{{empty section|date=January 2019}}\n\n==Military career==\n===World War II===\nLownds joined the Marine Corps on 3 March 1942. He was a first lieutenant with Company B, [[1st Battalion, 24th Marines]] during the [[Battle of Kwajalein|Battle of Roi-Namur]].<ref name=24th>{{cite web|url=https://1stbattalion24thmarines.com/the-companies/baker/l/david-e-lownds/|title=David E. Lownds|publisher=1st Battalion, 24th Marines|date=|accessdate=5 November 2018}}</ref>\n\nLownds was wounded while leading Company B, 1/24 Marines during the [[Battle of Saipan]].<ref name=24th/>\n\nDuring the [[Battle of Iwo Jima]] Lownds was attached to Headquarters Company, 1/24 Marines and was again wounded in the battle.<ref name=24th/>\n\nLownds returned to the US following the end of the war, and joined the Marine Reserves on 25 October 1945.<ref name=24th/>\n\n===Korean War===\nLownds returned to active duty during the [[Korean War]].\n\nLownds was serving with the [[I Marine Expeditionary Force]] when they were deployed to the [[Dominican Republic]] aboard {{USS|Boxer|CV-21|6}} during [[Dominican Civil War#U.S. intervention|Operation Powerpack]] in April 1965.\n\n===Vietnam War===\nOn 14 August 1967, Col. Lownds assumed command of the [[26th Marine Regiment (United States)|26th Marine Regiment]] which was conducting [[Operation Ardmore]], continued as [[Operation Scotland]], around [[Khe Sanh Combat Base]] in northwest [[Qu\u1ea3ng Tr\u1ecb Province]].<ref>{{cite book|last=Telfer|first=Gary|title=U.S. Marines in Vietnam: Fighting the North Vietnamese 1967|publisher=History and Museums Division, Headquarters, U.S. Marine Corps|year=1984|url=https://archive.org/details/FightingTheNorthVietnamese|isbn=978-1494285449|page=[https://archive.org/details/FightingTheNorthVietnamese/page/n153 142]}}</ref><ref name=Shulimson>{{cite book|last=Shulimson|first=Jack|title=U.S. Marines in Vietnam: 1968 The Defining Year|publisher=History and Museums Division, Headquarters, U.S. Marine Corps|year=1997|url=https://archive.org/stream/USMarinesInVietnamTheDefiningYear1968#page/n0/mode/2up|isbn=0-16-049125-8|page=62}}</ref>\n\nLownds led the defense of Khe Sanh throughout the [[Battle of Khe Sanh]], ultimately commanding over 6000 Marines at the base. Lownds was criticised by some for failing to send reinforcements to [[Battle of Lang Vei|Lang Vei]] when it came under attack on the night of 6/7 February 1968, but he defended his decision on the basis that Khe Sanh itself was under artillery attack with a ground assault believed to be imminent and that any attempt to reinforce Lang Vei at night would be suicidal. Lownds' decision was accepted by the US command.<ref name=Shulimson/>{{rp|275}} Lownds received further criticism when he refused to allow the approximately 6000 Laotian survivors and dependents of the Lang Vei garrison into the base on the basis that it would compromise base security. These refugees were initially housed outside the base perimeter with most eventually seeking refuge further east.<ref name=Shulimson/>{{rp|276\u20137}}\n[[File:A416482.tif|thumb|right|President Lyndon B. Johnson attaches the Presidential Unit Citation Streamer to the colors of the 26th Marine Regiment as Lownds looks on]]\nLownds was described by [[Michael Herr]] in his book [[Dispatches (book)|''Dispatches'']] as follows: \"Lownds was a deceptively complicated man with a gift (as one of his staff officers put it) for \"jerking off the press\". He could appear as a meek, low-keyed, distracted, and even stupid man (some reporters referred to him privately as \"The lion of Khe Sanh\"), as though he had been carefully picked for just these qualities by a cynical command as a front for its decisions... He was a small man with vague, watery eyes, slightly reminiscent of a rodent in a fable, with one striking feature: a full, scrupulously attended regimental moustache... His professed ignorance of [[Battle of Dien Bien Phu|Dien Bien Phu]] drove correspondents crazy, but it was a dodge. Lownds knew very well about Dien Bien Phu and what had happened there, knew more about it than most of the interviewers.\"<ref>{{cite book|last=Herr|first=Michael|title=Dispatches|publisher=Picador|year=1977|isbn=9781447275077|page=}}</ref>\n\nIn early April 1968 Lownds was relieved by Col Bruce F. Meyers.<ref name=Shulimson/>{{rp|287}}\n\nOn 23 May 1968 President [[Lyndon B. Johnson]] presented the [[Presidential Unit Citation (United States)|Presidential Unit Citation]] to the 26th Marines in a ceremony at the [[White House]] attended by Lownds and the 26th Marines Regimental Sergeant-Major.<ref>{{cite book|last=Jones|first=Gregg|title=Last Stand at Khe Sanh: The U.S. Marines' Finest Hour in Vietnam|publisher=Hachette|year=2014|isbn=9780306821400|page=}}</ref><ref name=Shulimson/>{{rp|288}}\n\nLownds was awarded the [[Navy Cross]] for his service at Khe Sanh.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://valor.militarytimes.com/hero/4124|title=David E. Lownds Navy Cross|publisher=Military Times|date=|accessdate=5 November 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Later life==\nLownds died at his home in [[Naples, Florida]], on 31 August 2011.\n\n==References==\n{{Marine Corps}}\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Lownds, David}}\n[[Category:1920 births]]\n[[Category:2011 deaths]]\n[[Category:American Marine Corps personnel of World War II]]\n[[Category:American Marine Corps personnel of the Korean War]]\n[[Category:United States Marine Corps personnel of the Vietnam War]]\n[[Category:Burials at Quantico National Cemetery]]\n", "name_user": "Mztourist", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eVietnam War", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/David_E._Lownds"}
{"title_page": "Everett, Washington", "text_new": "{{Use mdy dates|date=February 2019}}\n{{pp-move-indef}}\n{{Infobox settlement\n|name                     = Everett\n|official_name            = City of Everett\n|other_name = [[Lushootseed]]: ''{{lang|lut|d\u1dbb\u0259\u026cig\u02b7\u0259d}}''<ref name=\"BatesHess1994\">{{cite book |author1=Dawn Bates |author2=Thom Hess |author3=Hilbert, Vi |title=d\u1dbb\u0259\u026big\u02b7\u0259d |page=90 |work=Lushootseed Dictionary |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=ekq921r1kV0C |year=1994 |publisher=University of Washington Press |isbn=0-295-97323-4}}</ref>\n|settlement_type          = [[City]]\n|image_skyline            = Everett Station - Everett skyline, 2014.jpg\n|image_seal               = Everett logo.svg\n|image_map                = Snohomish_County_Washington_Incorporated_and_Unincorporated_areas_Everett_Highlighted.svg\n|mapsize                  = 250px\n|map_caption              = Location of Everett, Washington\n|pushpin_map              = USA\n|pushpin_map_caption      = Location in the United States\n|subdivision_type         = Country\n|subdivision_type1        = [[U.S. state|State]]\n|subdivision_type2        = [[List of counties in Washington|County]]\n|subdivision_name         = [[United States]]\n|subdivision_name1        = [[Washington (state)|Washington]]\n|subdivision_name2        = [[Snohomish County, Washington|Snohomish]]\n|established_title        = Established\n|established_date         = 1890\n|established_title2       = [[Municipal corporation|Incorporated]]\n|established_date2        = May 4, 1893\n|government_type          = [[Mayor\u2013council government|Mayor\u2013council]]\n|leader_title             = [[Mayor]]\n|leader_name              = Cassie Franklin\n|unit_pref                = Imperial\n|area_footnotes           = <ref name=\"CenPopGazetteer2016\">{{cite web |title=2018 U.S. Gazetteer Files |url=https://www2.census.gov/geo/docs/maps-data/data/gazetteer/2018_Gazetteer/2018_gaz_place_53.txt |publisher=United States Census Bureau |accessdate=February 16, 2020}}</ref>\n|area_magnitude           = \n|area_total_sq_mi         = 47.91\n|area_land_sq_mi          = 33.20\n|area_water_sq_mi         = 14.71\n|population_as_of         = [[2010 United States Census|2010]]\n|population_est           = 111262\n|pop_est_as_of            = 2018\n|pop_est_footnotes        = <ref name=\"USCensusEst2018CenPopScriptOnlyDirtyFixDoNotUse\"/>\n|population_footnotes     = <ref name=\"FactFinder\"/>\n|population_total         = 103019\n|population_density_sq_mi = 3351.47\n|population_metro         = 3,939,363 (US: [[List of Metropolitan Statistical Areas|15th]])\n|population_rank          = US: [[List of United States cities by population|270th]]<br />WA: 7th\n|population_demonym       = Everettite\n|timezone                 = [[Pacific Time Zone|PST]]\n|utc_offset               = &minus;8\n|timezone_DST             = [[Pacific Daylight Time|PDT]]\n|utc_offset_DST           = &minus;7\n|coordinates              = {{coord|47|57|48|N|122|12|2|W|region:US-WA_type:city|display=inline,title}}\n|postal_code_type         = Zip codes\n|postal_code = 98201, 98203, 98204, 98206, 98207, 98208, 98213<ref>{{cite web |url=http://zip4.usps.com/zip4/citytown.jsp |title=ZIP code lookup |publisher=[[United States Postal Service]] |accessdate=December 23, 2008 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20101104123722/http://zip4.usps.com/zip4/citytown.jsp |archivedate=November 4, 2010 }}</ref>\n|area_code                = [[Area code 425|425]]\n|blank_name               = [[Federal Information Processing Standard|FIPS code]]\n|blank_info               = 53-22640\n|blank1_name              = [[Geographic Names Information System|GNIS]] feature ID\n|blank1_info              = 1512198<ref name=\"GR3\">{{cite web |url=http://geonames.usgs.gov |accessdate=January 31, 2008 |title=US Board on Geographic Names |publisher=[[United States Geological Survey]] |date=October 25, 2007}}</ref>\n|website                  = {{URL|everettwa.gov}}\n|footnotes                = \n|area_total_km2           = 124.09\n|area_land_km2            = 85.98\n|area_water_km2           = 38.11\n|population_density_km2   = 1294.01\n}}\n\n'''Everett''' is the [[county seat]] of and the largest city in [[Snohomish County, Washington|Snohomish County]], Washington, United States. It is located {{convert|25|mi|km|0}} north of [[Seattle]] and is one of the main cities in the [[Seattle metropolitan area|metropolitan area]] and [[Puget Sound region]]. Everett is the [[List of cities and towns in Washington|seventh-largest]] city in Washington state and had a total population of 103,019 at the [[2010 United States Census|2010 census]]. The city is located at the mouth of the [[Snohomish River]] along [[Port Gardner Bay]], an inlet of [[Possession Sound]] (itself part of [[Puget Sound]]).\n\nAmerican settlement on the Everett peninsula began in the 1860s, with several [[sawmill]]s built to serve the area's growing timber industry. Everett was [[plat]]ted by a group of investors seeking to build an industrial city and named for the son of co-founder Charles L. Colby. The city was [[municipal incorporation|incorporated]] in 1893, shortly after the arrival of the [[Great Northern Railway (U.S.)|Great Northern Railway]], and prospered as a major industrial center. Everett's economy transitioned away from lumber and towards aviation after [[World War II]], with the construction of [[Boeing]]'s [[Boeing Everett Factory|aircraft assembly plant]] at [[Paine Field]] in 1967. Boeing remains the city's largest employer, alongside the [[U.S. Navy]], which has operated [[Naval Station Everett]] since 1992. Everett received an [[All-America City Award]] in 2002.\n\nEverett remains a major employment center for Snohomish County, but has also become a [[bedroom community]] for Seattle in recent decades. It is connected to Seattle by [[Interstate 5 in Washington|Interstate 5]] and various public transit services at [[Everett Station]], including the [[Sounder commuter rail|Sounder commuter train]], [[Amtrak]], and commuter buses.\n\n==History==\n[[File:everettwaterfront.jpg|thumb| [[Weyerhaeuser]] Lumber Mill, Everett Waterfront, c. early 1900s]]\n\nThe [[Port Gardner]] peninsula was originally inhabited by local [[Coast Salish]] tribes who arrived in the region 10,000 years [[before present]] and settled near modern-day Everett approximately 2,000 years [[before present]].{{sfnp|O'Donnell|1993|p=2}} The [[Snohomish people]] lived around local waterways in the [[Possession Sound]] estuary and had a fortified winter village at Hibulb (also called Hebolb) at the mouth of the [[Snohomish River]].{{sfnp|O'Donnell|1993|p=2}}<ref>{{cite news |last=Whitely |first=Peyton |date=March 16, 2005 |title=Aerial photos show 2 very different cities |page=H8 |url=https://www.seattletimes.com/seattle-news/aerial-photos-show-2-very-different-cities/ |work=[[The Seattle Times]] |accessdate=June 30, 2018}}</ref> The first Europeans in the area were explorers from the 1792 [[Vancouver Expedition]], landing on a beach on the modern Everett waterfront on June 4 and claiming the land for [[England]] on the birthday of King [[George III of the United Kingdom|George III]].<ref>{{cite book |author=[[Federal Writers' Project]] |year=1941 |title=The WPA Guide to Washington: The Evergreen State |pages=186\u2013200 |series=[[American Guide Series]] |publisher=[[Works Progress Administration]] |oclc=881468746 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=07PpCAAAQBAJ |via=Google Books |accessdate=June 30, 2018}}</ref> [[Puget Sound]] was further explored and charted ny the [[Hudson's Bay Company]] in 1824 and the [[United States Exploring Expedition]] under [[Charles Wilkes]] in 1841, ahead of a larger American presence in the area.{{sfnp|O'Donnell|1993|p=4}}<ref name=\"HistoryLink\">{{cite web |last=Oakley |first=Janet |date=July 26, 2005 |title=Everett \u2014 Thumbnail History |url=https://www.historylink.org/file/7397 |work=[[HistoryLink]] |accessdate=June 30, 2018}}</ref>\n\nThe Snohomish and other Coast Salish tribes signed the [[Treaty of Point Elliott]] in 1855, which relinquished their lands to the [[Washington Territory|territorial government]] and established the nearby [[Tulalip Indian Reservation]], where they would be relocated.<ref name=\"Herald-125th\">{{cite news |last=Muhlstein |first=Julie |date=May 9, 2018 |title=City of Everett to celebrate 125th birthday with big party |url=https://www.heraldnet.com/news/city-of-everett-celebrates-125-years-and-counting/ |work=[[The Everett Herald]] |accessdate=June 30, 2018}}</ref> The first permanent American settler to arrive on the peninsula was Dennis Brigham, a carpenter from [[Worcester, Massachusetts]], who claimed a {{convert|160|acre|km2|1|adj=on}} [[Homestead Acts|homestead]] and built a cabin for himself. He was joined by several other families on their own homesteads, which included the establishment of a general store and a [[sawmill]] that quickly went out of business.<ref name=\"HistoryLink\"/> Over the next several years a handful of loggers moved to the area, but plans for a settlement were not conceived until 1890.{{sfnp|O'Donnell|1993|p=7}}\n\nDuring an Alaskan cruise via the [[Inside Passage]] aboard the steamship ''[[Queen of the Pacific]]'' in July 1890, plans were drawn up for an industrial city on Port Gardner Bay by lumberman [[Henry Hewitt Jr.]] and railroad executive [[Charles L. Colby]]. Hewitt and Colby had previously met in [[Wisconsin]], where they operated lumber and maritime businesses, respectively, and in [[Tacoma, Washington]], from which the voyage began. The pair sought to build an industrial center at a site they speculated would be the first ocean port for [[Great Northern Railway (U.S.)|Great Northern Railway]], to be constructed by [[James J. Hill]], and turn it into a \"[[Pittsburgh]] of the West\".{{sfnp|O'Donnell|1993|p=12}}<ref name=\"Times-HewittColby93\">{{cite news |last=Dilgard |first=David |date=April 22, 1993 |title=Odd couple of Hewitt and Colby hatched ambitious plan for Everett |page=F5 |url=https://archive.seattletimes.com/archive/?date=19930422&slug=1697251 |work=The Seattle Times |accessdate=April 3, 2020}}</ref> On August 22, 1890, the [[plat]] for a {{convert|50|acre|m2|adj=on}} townsite on the peninsula was filed by the [[Rucker Brothers]], who had moved north from Tacoma and had more modest plans for the area.{{sfnp|O'Donnell|1993|p=12}}\n\nBy September, Colby had secured $800,000 in funding from oil magnate [[John D. Rockefeller]] and his railroad associate [[Colgate Hoyt]] to begin acquiring land while avoiding property speculators.{{sfnp|O'Donnell|1993|p=12}} The Hewitt\u2013Colby syndicate decided to use a name without an identifiable location, naming their planned city after [[Everett Colby]], the fifteen-year-old son of investor Charles L. Colby, who had displayed a \"prodigious appetite\" at a group dinner.<ref name=\"Times-HewittColby93\"/> The Everett Land Company was incorporated in [[Pierce County, Washington|Pierce County]] on November 19, 1890, and acquired {{convert|434.15|acre|sqkm}} of property from the Rucker Brothers a week later.{{sfnp|O'Donnell|1993|p=15}} The Rucker plat was withdrawn after an agreement was reached with Hewitt promising certain industrial developments under the \"Remarkable Document\", which was also used to acquire property from other landowners in the area.{{sfnp|Cameron|LeWarne|May|O'Donnell|2005|p=103}}\n\nEverett gained its first businesses in early 1891, as the new settlement attracted land speculators and commitments to build lumber mills and other industrial enterprises.{{sfnp|O'Donnell|1993|p=16}} The Everett Land Company bought much of the Ruckers' land, taking them in as junior partners. Everett was officially incorporated on May 4, 1893, the year the [[Great Northern Railway (U.S.)|Great Northern Railway]] came to the town. Both Hewitt and the Ruckers had speculated that [[James J. Hill]] would make the town the terminus of his railroad. However Hill continued the railroad along the shore of [[Puget Sound]] to [[Seattle]]. Although it succeeded in building the city, the Everett Land Company was a failure for its investors. The outside investors withdrew, and the Company's holdings were transferred to a new company controlled by Hill. The Ruckers, who helped broker the deal, stayed in Everett and became leading citizens of the young city.\n\nRailroads and mines played a part in Everett's future. The mining community of [[Monte Cristo, Washington|Monte Cristo]] depended on a railway for supplies. It was hoped that the railroad would cross the mountains and bring in traffic. For a while ore was smelted in Everett, then sawmilling and port activity commenced. A dozen steam riverboats were built in Everett for the [[Klondike Gold Rush|Yukon gold rush]].\n\nSeveral survivors of the [[Bellingham riots]] settled in Everett for two months, until they were beaten and forcefully evicted by a mob on November 5, 1907. Everett also was the site of the [[Everett Massacre]] of 1916 in which a posse led by local Sheriff Donald McRae shot and killed five [[Industrial Workers of the World]] members. The IWW members on the [[Verona (steamship)|steamer ''Verona'']] travelled from Seattle to support strikers in Everett and sought to land, but McRae and his posse of deputized civilians blocked the harbor. Shooting broke out and at least five IWW members were killed, along with two in the posse who were deemed to have been killed by friendly fire.\n\nEverett streets are named after each of the three founders. Adjacent streets Colby Avenue and Hoyt Avenue run north and south and are intersected by Hewitt Avenue running east and west just south of the [[BNSF Railway]] tracks cutting across Everett. There are several other streets named for their associates such as Bond Street named for Judge [[Hiram Bond]], President of the Everett & Monte Cristo Railroad. Parallel to Colby and Hoyt are avenues named for other investors, [[John D. Rockefeller]], railroad executive [[Thomas Fletcher Oakes|T.F. Oakes]], shipbuilder [[Alexander McDougall (1845-1923)|Alexander McDougall]], and McDougall's associate [[Charles W. Wetmore]].\n\nDuring the [[Great Depression]], the [[Works Progress Administration]] was tasked with construction of several public works projects in the Everett area, including a new county airport that later became [[Paine Field]]. The airport was appropriated for military use during [[World War II]], but was later turned over to county ownership.<ref name=\"HistoryLink\"/> The [[Boeing Company]] selected a {{convert|780|acre|ha|adj=mid}} plot of land north of the airport in June 1966 to build a [[Boeing Everett Factory|new airplane factory]] for its [[Boeing 747]] passenger jetliner, which would become the world's first \"jumbo jet\". The first 747, named the \"City of Everett\", was unveiled in September 1968 and made its maiden flight on February 9, 1969.<ref name=\"Herald-Boeing50\">{{cite news |last=Catchpole |first=Dan |date=May 22, 2017 |title=50 history-making years of building Boeing jets in Everett |url=https://www.heraldnet.com/business/boeing-has-built-planes-in-everett-for-50-history-making-years/ |work=The Everett Herald |accessdate=February 18, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Podsada |first=Janice |date=September 30, 2018 |title=50 years ago, they rolled it out: the first Boeing 747 |url=https://www.heraldnet.com/business/50-years-ago-they-rolled-it-out-the-first-boeing-747/ |work=The Everett Herald |accessdate=February 18, 2019}}</ref> The Everett factory was expanded several times to accommodate later Boeing programs, including the [[Boeing 767|767]], [[Boeing 777|777]], and [[Boeing 787|787 Dreamliner]].<ref name=\"Herald-Boeing50\"/>\n\nEverett was selected by the [[U.S. Navy]] in 1984 as the site of a new military base under the [[Strategic Homeport]] program.<ref>{{cite news |last=Cowley |first=Geoffrey |date=November 7, 1984 |title=Everett says 'yes' to Navy by a margin of more than 2-to-1 |page=B10 |work=The Seattle Times}}</ref> [[Naval Station Everett]] was constructed between 1987 and 1994 on a site near the [[Port of Everett]] on Port Gardner Bay,<ref>{{cite news |last=Brooks |first=Diane |date=June 5, 1992 |title=The Navy's in port: three ships greeted at Everett's new base |page=E1 |work=The Seattle Times}}</ref> with auxiliary facilities in [[Smokey Point, Washington|Smokey Point]].<ref>{{cite news |last=Hendricks |first=Tyche |date=June 5, 1995 |title=Eagerly awaiting stores' opening\u2014Navy exchange, commissary ready |page=B1 |url=http://community.seattletimes.nwsource.com/archive/?date=19950605&slug=2124724 |work=The Seattle Times |accessdate=February 18, 2019}}</ref> The first ships arrived in September 1994, and Naval Station Everett was the long-term home of several [[aircraft carrier]]s, including the {{USS|Abraham Lincoln|CVN-72|6}}.<ref>{{cite news |last=Clutter |first=Stephen |date=January 9, 1997 |title=Bringing home the future: The Lincoln, with crew of 3,200 is first carrier permanently assigned to Everett |page=B1 |work=The Seattle Times}}</ref> The city underwent an urban revival in the 1990s, with new construction in many neighborhoods and improved city facilities.<ref>{{cite news |last=Carter |first=Don |date=July 12, 1997 |title=New life breathes in old mill town |page=D1 |work=Seattle Post-Intelligencer}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=King |first=Harriet |date=May 13, 1990 |title=Focus: The I-5 Corridor; A Lively New Washington Growth Area |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1990/05/13/realestate/focus-the-i-5-corridor-a-lively-new-washington-growth-area.html |work=The New York Times |accessdate=March 29, 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe first [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in the United States|U.S. case]] of [[coronavirus disease 2019]] was identified at Providence Regional Medical Center in Everett on January 20, 2020.<ref>{{cite news |last=Blethen |first=Ryan |date=February 14, 2020 |title=What it was like for doctors and nurses at an Everett hospital to treat the nation's first novel coronavirus patient |page=A1 |url=https://www.seattletimes.com/seattle-news/health/what-it-was-like-for-doctors-and-nurses-at-an-everett-hospital-to-treat-the-nations-first-novel-coronavirus-patient/ |work=The Seattle Times |accessdate=March 21, 2020}}</ref> As the coronavirus pandemic worsened in the state, mayor Cassie Franklin declared the first shelter-in-place order for Washington state on March 21, 2020.<ref>{{cite news |last=Gutman |first=David |date=March 21, 2020 |title=Everett orders residents to stay home to slow coronavirus, others call on Inslee to follow suit |page=A1 |url=https://www.seattletimes.com/seattle-news/health/everett-orders-residents-to-stay-home-to-slow-coronavirus-others-call-on-inslee-to-follow-suit/ |accessdate=March 21, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Geography==\n\nEverett is one of the core cities comprising the [[Seattle metropolitan area]] and is located {{convert|25|mi|km}} north of [[Seattle]].<ref>{{cite news |last=Johnson |first=Kirk |date=December 10, 2013 |title=Boeing Looks Around, and a State Worries |page=A16 |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2013/12/11/us/washington-state-not-ready-to-ponder-future-without-boeing.html |work=[[The New York Times]] |accessdate=February 18, 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"GR1\">{{cite web |url=https://www.census.gov/geo/www/gazetteer/gazette.html |publisher=[[United States Census Bureau]] |accessdate=April 23, 2011 |date=February 12, 2011 |title=US Gazetteer files: 2010, 2000, and 1990}}</ref> It is located primarily on Port Gardner Peninsula, bordered to the west by [[Port Gardner Bay]] (part of the [[Puget Sound]] estuary), and to the north and east by the [[Snohomish River]] delta. The city also encompasses areas to the south and southwest of the peninsula, which were annexed during the 20th century. [[Mukilteo, Washington|Mukilteo]] is located west of the city, while [[Lynnwood, Washington|Lynnwood]] and [[Mill Creek, Washington|Mill Creek]] sit further south.<ref name=\"HistoryLink\"/> Everett is connected to the north towards [[Marysville, Washington|Marysville]] and east towards [[Lake Stevens, Washington|Lake Stevens]] by a series of highway and railway bridges that cross the Snohomish River delta.{{cn|date=March 2020}} The city also owns {{convert|3,729|acre|ha}} around [[Lake Chaplain]], a reservoir in the Cascade Mountains that provides part of the municipal water supply.<ref>{{cite news |last=Winters |first=Chris |date=May 10, 2015 |title=Trade-off would allow timber harvest at Lake Chaplain |url=https://www.heraldnet.com/news/trade-off-would-allow-timber-harvest-at-lake-chaplain/ |work=The Everett Herald |accessdate=March 21, 2020}}</ref>\n\nAccording to the [[United States Census Bureau]], the city has a total area of {{convert|48.49|sqmi|sqkm|2}}, of which, {{convert|33.45|sqmi|sqkm|2}} is land and {{convert|15.04|sqmi|sqkm|2}} is water.<ref name=\"Gazetteer files\">{{cite web |title=US Gazetteer files 2010 |url=https://www.census.gov/geo/www/gazetteer/files/Gaz_places_national.txt |publisher=[[United States Census Bureau]] |accessdate=December 19, 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120112090031/http://www.census.gov/geo/www/gazetteer/files/Gaz_places_national.txt |archivedate=January 12, 2012 }}</ref> The city has {{convert|11|mi|km}} of freshwater shoreline and {{convert|11|mi|km}} of saltwater shoreline.<ref name=\"CAFR2018\"/>{{rp|2}}\n\nThe Port Gardner Peninsula was formed during the northward retreat of [[Vashon Glaciation]] during an [[ice age]] 14,000 years before present.{{sfnp|O'Donnell|1993|p=2}}\n\n===Cityscape and neighborhoods===\n\nThe city of Everett maintains an Office of Neighborhoods which facilitate communication between the city and 19 recognized neighborhood associations. The neighborhood associations are independent from the city and have elected leaders who communicate with the city government.<ref>{{cite web |title=Neighborhood Associations |url=https://everettwa.gov/334/Neighborhood-Associations |publisher=City of Everett |accessdate=March 27, 2020}}</ref> The neighborhood associations are:<ref>{{cite map |date=April 2019 |title=Everett Neighborhoods |url=https://everettwa.gov/DocumentCenter/View/17789/4-16-19-Everett-Neighborhoods-Map-11x17 |publisher=City of Everett |accessdate=March 27, 2020}}</ref>\n\n* Bayside \u2013 comprising much of the central business district, the waterfront, and the surrounding residential areas.\n* Boulevard Bluffs \u2013 primarily residential area of the city bordering [[Mukilteo]].\n* Cascade View \u2013 residential area in South Everett, north of Everett Mall\n* Delta \u2013 primarily residential area north of downtown Everett\n* Evergreen \u2013 primarily residential area in South Everett.\n* Glacier View \u2013 older residential area south of downtown.\n* Harborview-Seahurst-Glenhaven \u2013 older residential areas south of downtown.\n* Holly \u2013 a mix of residential, commercial, and industrial areas on the southern edge of the city.\n* Lowell \u2013 formerly an independent town, Lowell is a primarily residential area southeast of downtown.\n* Northwest \u2013 older residential areas northwest of downtown.\n* Pinehurst-Beverly Park \u2013 mix of residential and commercial developments in South Everett.\n* Port Gardner \u2013 residential neighborhoods south of downtown.\n* Riverside \u2013 areas just northeast of downtown.\n* Silver Lake \u2013 residential and commercial areas surrounding Silver Lake in the extreme southeastern part of the city.\n* South Forest Park \u2013 residential neighborhood near downtown.\n* Twin Creeks \u2013 the area surrounding Everett Mall, a mix of residential and commercial areas.<ref>{{cite news |last=Muhlstein |first=Julie |date=August 28, 2012 |title=Everett's Twin Creeks neighborhood gets its renaissance |url=https://www.heraldnet.com/news/everetts-twin-creeks-neighborhood-gets-its-renaissance/ |work=The Everett Herald |accessdate=March 10, 2019}}</ref>\n* Valley View-Sylvan Crest-Larimer Ridge \u2013 residential areas in southeast Everett.\n* View Ridge-Madison \u2013 residential areas west and southwest of Forest Park.\n* Westmont \u2013 primarily multi-family housing in the southwestern part of the city.\n\n====Downtown====\n[[File:Everett Mutual Tower (18345199053).jpg|thumb|[[Everett Mutual Tower|Key Bank Tower]], the tallest building in Everett, Washington]]\n\nDowntown Everett is generally defined by the area north of Pacific Avenue, east of West Marine View Drive, south of Everett Avenue, and west of Broadway.<ref>{{cite web |date=July 2006 |title=Everett  Downtown Plan |url=https://everettwa.gov/DocumentCenter/Home/View/784 |publisher=City of Everett |accessdate=February 2, 2017}}</ref>{{rp|4}} Downtown is home to the government campuses of Snohomish County and the City of Everett, multiple high-rise office and residential buildings, as well as the [[Xfinity Arena|Angel of the Winds Arena]], [[Everett Public Library]] and other city amenities.\n\nThe tallest building in Everett, [[Everett Mutual Tower|Key Bank Tower]], is located in Downtown.\n\nSeveral downtown streets are named for the founders of the Everett Land Company and their associates.<ref>{{cite news |last=Rathbun |first=Andy |date=September 7, 2012 |title=We have mnemonic winner for Everett's streets |url=https://www.heraldnet.com/life/we-have-mnemonic-winner-for-everetts-streets/ |work=The Everett Herald |accessdate=April 3, 2020}}</ref>\n\n====Waterfront====\n[[File:Port Gardner Wharf.jpg|thumb|View from Everett Yacht Club on Port Gardner Wharf]]\nSituated at the mouth of the [[Snohomish River]] on [[Possession Sound]], the Everett waterfront is home to [[Naval Station Everett]] and the Port of Everett (est. 1918).  The Port of Everett includes both a deep-water commercial seaport and a marina with over 2,000 slips, which it claims to be the largest on the west coast of the United States.<ref>[http://www.portofeverett.com/home/index.asp?page=4 Port of Everett - Marina<!-- Bot generated title -->] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070629215830/http://www.portofeverett.com/home/index.asp?page=4 |date=June 29, 2007 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |date=July 3, 2018 |title=Everett's economic anchor: Big ships, big marina, big impact |url=https://www.heraldnet.com/business/everetts-economic-anchor-big-ships-big-marina-big-impact/ |work=The Everett Herald |accessdate=March 27, 2020}}</ref> Ambitious redevelopment began in 2006 to convert the north end of the waterfront into a community of maritime businesses, retail shops and condominiums, beginning with the Port of Everett's Port Gardner Wharf.  In 2006, the seaport received 119 ships and 59 barges, totaling some 192,000 short tons of cargo.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.portofeverett.com/home/index.asp?page=167 |title=Port of Everett - Cargo Statistics<!-- Bot generated title --> |accessdate=February 19, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070927235529/http://www.portofeverett.com/home/index.asp?page=167 |archive-date=September 27, 2007 |url-status=dead |df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n\nThe waterfront is also home to the Everett Yacht Club, which was founded in 1907, although it existed in some form as early as 1895.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.everettyachtclub.com/New_History_Page.html |title=Home \u2013 Everett Yacht Club |publisher= |access-date=July 14, 2007 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070630003547/http://www.everettyachtclub.com/New_History_Page.html |archive-date=June 30, 2007 |url-status=dead }}</ref>  During summer months, the marina is home to the Everett Farmer's Market (Sundays) and the Waterfront Concert Series (Thursday nights), part of a citywide free concert series which, in 2006, attracted over 26,000 visitors.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.everettwa.org/default.aspx?ID=1152 |title=Sunday Afternoon Waterfront Series in Everett<!-- Bot generated title --> |publisher= |accessdate=February 19, 2018}}</ref>  Each September, Tenth Street Park on the waterfront is home to the annual Everett Coho Derby,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.everettcohoderby.com/ |title=Home |first= |last=Administrator |publisher=}}</ref> while each August the marina promenade is gowned in local art during the Fresh Paint Festival of Artists.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.freshpaint.org/ |title=FRESH PAINT |publisher=}}</ref>\n\n===Climate===\n\nThe climate of Everett is generally similar to most of the [[Puget Sound region|Puget Sound lowlands]], with year-round moderate temperatures influenced by marine air masses. The variation of normal weather between seasons is less extreme than inland areas, with dry summers and mild, rainy winters due to the proximity of the [[Pacific Ocean]].{{sfnp|O'Donnell|1993|p=253}} Under the [[K\u00f6ppen climate classification]] system, Everett has a [[warm-summer Mediterranean climate]] (Csb), though it is also described as having an [[oceanic climate]] (Cfb).{{sfnp|O'Donnell|1993|p=253}}<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Peel |first1=M. C. |last2=Finlayson |first2=B. L. |last3=McMahon |first3=T. A. |year=2007 |title=Updated world map of the K\u00f6ppen-Geiger climate classification |journal=[[Hydrology and Earth System Sciences]] |doi=10.5194/hess-11-1633-2007 |issn=1027-5606 |volume=11 |issue=5 |pages=1633\u20131644 |publisher=[[European Geosciences Union]] |url=http://www.hydrol-earth-syst-sci.net/11/1633/2007/hess-11-1633-2007.html |accessdate=October 14, 2019}}</ref> The city marks the north end of the [[Puget Sound Convergence Zone]], a local weather phenomenon caused by colliding air currents from the region's mountain ranges that produces heavier rain and stronger winds than the rest of the region.<ref>{{cite book |last=Mass |first=Cliff |year=2008 |title=The Weather of the Pacific Northwest |page=149 |publisher=[[University of Washington Press]] |isbn=978-0-295-98847-4 |oclc=416457886 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=xPiACgAAQBAJ&pg=PA149 |via=Google Books |accessdate=March 26, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last=Sistek |first=Scott |date=December 17, 2015 |title=What Is A Puget Sound Convergence Zone? |url=https://komonews.com/weather/faq/what-is-a-puget-sound-convergence-zone |publisher=[[KOMO-TV|KOMO 4 News]] |accessdate=March 26, 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe warmest month for Everett is August, with average high temperatures of {{convert|72.7|F|C|lk=on}}, while January is the coolest, at an average high of {{convert|44.9|F|C}}.<ref name=\"WRCC\"/> The highest recorded temperature, {{convert|98|F|C}}, occurred on June 9, 1955, and the lowest, {{convert|0|F|C}}, occurred on November 11, 1993.<ref name=\"WRCC\"/> The city receives {{convert|35.71|in|mm}} of annual rainfall, which mostly falls from October to March and peaks in December.{{sfnp|O'Donnell|1993|p=253}}<ref name=\"WRCC\"/> Everett's highest recorded snowfall, {{convert|26.6|in|cm}}, occurred in 1965.<ref name=\"WRCC\"/>\n\n{{Weather box \n|location = Everett\n|single line = Y\n| Jan record high F = 72\n| Feb record high F = 74\n| Mar record high F = 82\n| Apr record high F = 85\n| May record high F = 93\n| Jun record high F = 98\n| Jul record high F = 93\n| Aug record high F = 94\n| Sep record high F = 89\n| Oct record high F = 83\n| Nov record high F = 74\n| Dec record high F = 66\n| year record high F = 98\n| Jan high F = 44.9\n| Feb high F = 48.8\n| Mar high F = 52.8\n| Apr high F = 58.1\n| May high F = 63.6\n| Jun high F = 68.3\n| Jul high F = 72.6\n| Aug high F = 72.7\n| Sep high F = 67.8\n| Oct high F = 59.5\n| Nov high F = 50.9\n| Dec high F = 45.7\n| year high F = 58.8\n| Jan low F = 33.1\n| Feb low F = 34.4\n| Mar low F = 36.8\n| Apr low F = 40.4\n| May low F = 45.3\n| Jun low F = 50.2\n| Jul low F = 52.9\n| Aug low F = 52.8\n| Sep low F = 48.3\n| Oct low F = 43\n| Nov low F = 37.6\n| Dec low F = 34.3\n| year low F = 42.4\n| Jan record low F = 1\n| Feb record low F = 2\n| Mar record low F = 10\n| Apr record low F = 23\n| May record low F = 29\n| Jun record low F = 36\n| Jul record low F = 37\n| Aug record low F = 38\n| Sep record low F = 30\n| Oct record low F = 22\n| Nov record low F = 0\n| Dec record low F = 5\n| year record low F = 0\n| precipitation colour = green\n| Jan precipitation inch = 4.51\n| Feb precipitation inch = 3.25\n| Mar precipitation inch = 3.57\n| Apr precipitation inch = 2.7\n| May precipitation inch = 2.34\n| Jun precipitation inch = 2.12\n| Jul precipitation inch = 1.04\n| Aug precipitation inch = 1.2\n| Sep precipitation inch = 1.98\n| Oct precipitation inch = 3.39\n| Nov precipitation inch = 4.65\n| Dec precipitation inch = 4.96\n| year precipitation inch = 35.71\n| Jan precipitation days = 19\n| Feb precipitation days = 16\n| Mar precipitation days = 18\n| Apr precipitation days = 15\n| May precipitation days = 12\n| Jun precipitation days = 10\n| Jul precipitation days = 6\n| Aug precipitation days = 6\n| Sep precipitation days = 9\n| Oct precipitation days = 15\n| Nov precipitation days = 18\n| Dec precipitation days = 19\n| Jan snow inch = 3.3\n| Feb snow inch = 1.2\n| Mar snow inch = 0.6\n| Apr snow inch = 0.2\n| May snow inch = 0\n| Jun snow inch = 0\n| Jul snow inch = 0\n| Aug snow inch = 0\n| Sep snow inch = 0\n| Oct snow inch = 0\n| Nov snow inch = 0.6\n| Dec snow inch = 1.4\n| year snow inch = 7.3\n\n|source 1 = [[Western Regional Climate Center]] (1894\u20132015)<ref name=\"WRCC\">{{cite web |title=Period of Record Monthly Climate Summary: Everett, Washington (452675) |url=http://www.wrcc.dri.edu/cgi-bin/cliMAIN.pl?wa2675 |publisher=[[Western Regional Climate Center]] |accessdate=November 16, 2015}}</ref>\n|date=November 2015\n}}\n\n==Economy==\n\nEverett has a workforce population of 88,146 people, as of a 2018 U.S. Census estimate, of whom 59,599 are employed.<ref name=\"ACS\">{{cite web |year=2019 |title=Selected Economic Characteristics: Everett, Washington |url=https://data.census.gov/cedsci/table?q=DP03&g=1600000US5322640&tid=ACSDP5Y2018.DP03&hidePreview=true |work=[[American Community Survey]] |publisher=United States Census Bureau |accessdate=April 2, 2020}}</ref> The city had an estimated 7,335 registered businesses in 2012.<ref>{{cite web |title=Profile: Everett, Washington |url=https://data.census.gov/cedsci/profile?g=1600000US5322640&q=Everett |publisher=United States Census Bureau |accessdate=April 2, 2020}}</ref>\n\nEverett's early economy was tied to the lumber trade. The city's last remaining wood [[pulp mill]], owned by [[Kimberly-Clark]], shut down in April 2012 and was demolished a year later, marking the end of Everett's lumber economy.<ref>{{cite news |last=Smith |first=Debra |date=March 30, 2012 |title=Kimberly-Clark mill is part of the Everett we've lost |url=https://www.heraldnet.com/news/kimberly-clark-mill-is-part-of-the-everett-weve-lost/ |work=The Everett Herald |accessdate=March 31, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Haglund |first=Noah |date=August 18, 2013 |title=Kimberly-Clark says former mill site better without grass |url=https://www.heraldnet.com/news/kimberly-clark-says-former-mill-site-better-without-grass/ |work=The Everett Herald |accessdate=March 31, 2020}}</ref> The city's 2006 labor workforce comprised more than 80,000, predominantly employed in technology, aerospace, and service-based industries.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://everettwa.usachamber.com/custom2.asp?pageid=2570 |title=Archived copy |accessdate=July 14, 2007 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070928231215/http://everettwa.usachamber.com/custom2.asp?pageid=2570 |archivedate=September 28, 2007 }}</ref>\n\nAirplane manufacturer [[Boeing]] has a significant presence in Everett, with 31 percent of all jobs,<ref name=\"CAFR2018\"/> including a [[Boeing Everett Factory|large manufacturing plant]] that is the world's largest building by volume.<ref>{{cite web |title=Boeing in Everett |url=http://www.boeing.com/company/about-bca/everett-production-facility.page |publisher=[[Boeing]] |accessdate=September 27, 2016}}</ref> Electronics manufacturer [[Fluke Corporation]] (now part of [[Fortive]]) is based in Everett and has 1,000 employees in Washington state.<ref>{{cite news |last=Lerman |first=Rachel |date=October 28, 2016 |title=Quiet industrial giant emerges in Everett |url=https://www.seattletimes.com/business/technology/everetts-fortive-shapes-strategy-for-successful-companies/ |work=The Seattle Times |accessdate=April 1, 2020}}</ref> Toymaker [[Funko]] is also headquartered in Downtown Everett and has a major distribution center in the city.<ref>{{cite news |last=Catchpole |first=Dan |date=September 9, 2016 |title=Toymaker Funko moving to downtown Everett |url=http://www.heraldnet.com/news/toymaker-funko-moving-to-downtown-everett/ |work=The Everett Herald |accessdate=September 27, 2016}}</ref>\n\nThe city's retail is concentrated along two major corridors, Evergreen Way and Everett Mall Way, and around the [[Everett Mall]], which opened in 1974 and has over 100 stores.<ref>{{cite news |last=Haglund |first=Noah |date=September 6, 2013 |title=New tenant seen as key to Everett Mall revival |url=https://www.heraldnet.com/business/new-tenant-seen-as-key-to-everett-mall-revival-2/ |work=The Everett Herald |accessdate=January 1, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Chapter V. Retail Demand |url=https://everettwa.gov/DocumentCenter/View/986/Retail-Demand-PDF?bidId= |work=Everett Downtown Plan Market Study |publisher=City of Everett |accessdate=January 1, 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Top employers===\n\nAccording to the City's 2018 Comprehensive Annual Financial Report,<ref name=\"CAFR2018\">{{cite web |date=June 26, 2019 |title=City of Everett, Washington 2018 Comrpehensive Annual Financial Report For the Year Ended December 31, 2018 |page=175 |url=https://everettwa.gov/ArchiveCenter/ViewFile/Item/1156 |publisher=City of Everett |accessdate=April 1, 2020}}</ref> the top employers in the city are:\n\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\" border=\"1\"\n|-\n! #\n! Employer\n! # of Employees\n|-\n|1\n|[[Boeing]]\n|35,000\n|-\n|2\n|[[Providence Regional Medical Center Everett]]\n|4,906\n|-\n|3\n|[[Washington (state)|State of Washington]]\n|3,000\n|-\n|4\n|[[Naval Station Everett]]\n|2,900\n|-\n|5\n|[[The Everett Clinic]]\n|2,871\n|-\n|6\n|[[Snohomish County, Washington|Snohomish County]]\n|2,759\n|-\n|7\n|[[Everett Public Schools (Washington)|Everett Public Schools]]\n|2,443\n|-\n|8\n|[[Fluke Corporation]] ([[Fortive]])\n|1,200\n|-\n|9\n|City of Everett\n|1,198\n|-\n|10\n|[[Snohomish County Public Utility District]]\n|1,004\n|}\n\n==Demographics==\n{{US Census population\n|1900= 7838\n|1910= 24814\n|1920= 27644\n|1930= 30567\n|1940= 30224\n|1950= 33849\n|1960= 40304\n|1970= 53622\n|1980= 54413\n|1990= 69961\n|2000= 91488\n|2010= 103019\n|estyear=2018\n|estimate=111262\n|estref=<ref name=\"USCensusEst2018CenPopScriptOnlyDirtyFixDoNotUse\">{{cite web |date=June 27, 2019 |title=Population and Housing Unit Estimates |url=https://www.census.gov/programs-surveys/popest/data/tables.2018.html |publisher=United States Census Bureau |accessdate=February 16, 2020}}</ref>\n|footnote=Source:<ref>Moffatt, Riley.  ''Population History of Western U.S. Cities & Towns, 1850-1990''.  [[Lanham, Maryland|Lanham]]: Scarecrow, 1996, 320.</ref><center>U.S. Decennial Census<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.census.gov/prod/www/decennial.html|title=U.S. Decennial Census|publisher=Census.gov|accessdate=June 6, 2013|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150426102944/http://www.census.gov/prod/www/decennial.html|archivedate=April 26, 2015}}</ref><br>2018 Estimate<ref name=\"2018 Pop Estimate\">{{cite web|title=Population Estimates|url=https://census.gov/data/tables/2018/demo/popest/total-cities-and-towns.html|publisher=[[United States Census Bureau]]|accessdate=June 5, 2019}}</ref>\n}}\n\n===2010 census===\n\nAs of the [[2010 United States Census|2010 U.S. census]], there were 103,019 people, 41,312 households, and 23,282 families residing in the city. The [[population density]] was {{convert|3079.8|PD/sqmi|PD/km2|1}}. There were 44,609 housing units at an average density of {{convert|1333.6|/sqmi|/km2|1}}. The [[Race and ethnicity in the United States Census|racial makeup]] of the city was 74.6% White, 4.1% African American, 1.4% Native American, 7.8% Asian, 0.7% Pacific Islander, 6.1% from other races, and 5.3% from two or more races. Hispanic or Latino of any race were 14.2% of the population.<ref name=\"FactFinder\">{{cite web |title=American FactFinder |url=http://factfinder2.census.gov/faces/nav/jsf/pages/index.xhtml |publisher=[[United States Census Bureau]] |accessdate=December 19, 2012}}</ref>\n\nThere were 41,312 households of which 30.5% had children under the age of 18 living with them, 38.2% were [[Marriage|married couples]] living together, 12.5% had a female householder with no husband present, 5.7% had a male householder with no wife present, and 43.6% were non-families. 34.1% of all households were made up of individuals and 9.3% had someone living alone who was 65 years of age or older. The average household size was 2.39 and the average family size was 3.09.<ref name=\"FactFinder\"/>\n\nThe median age in the city was 34.4 years. 22.7% of residents were under the age of 18; 11.3% were between the ages of 18 and 24; 30.6% were from 25 to 44; 25% were from 45 to 64; and 10.3% were 65 years of age or older. The gender makeup of the city was 50.9% male and 49.1% female.<ref name=\"FactFinder\"/>\n\n===2000 census===\n\nAs of the [[2000 United States Census|2000 U.S. census]], there were 91,488 people, 36,325 households and 21,613 families residing in the city.  The population density was 2,814.6 people per square mile (1,086.9/km\u00b2).  There were 38,512 housing units at an average density of 1,184.8 per square mile (457.5/km\u00b2).  The racial makeup of the city was 56% White, 9% African American, 1.56% Native American, 10% Asian, 4% Pacific Islander, 3.13% from other races and 4.25% from two or more races.  Hispanic or Latino of any race were 13% of the population.<ref name=\"Census2000\">{{cite web |year=2000 |title=Profile of General Demographic Characteristics: Everett city, Washington |url=https://www.psrc.org/sites/default/files/everett.pdf |publisher=United States Census Bureau |via=[[Puget Sound Regional Council]] |accessdate=April 1, 2020}}</ref>\n\nThere were 36,325 households, out of which 31.9% had children under the age of 18 living with them, 42.1% were married couples living together, 12.5% had a female householder with no husband present, and 40.5% were non-families. 31.7% of all households were made up of individuals and 8.5% had someone living alone who was 65 years of age or older.  The average household size was 2.40 and the average family size was 3.04.\n\nIn the city, the population was spread out with 25.1% under the age of 18, 12.3% from 18 to 24, 33.3% from 25 to 44, 18.9% from 45 to 64, and 10.3% who were 65 years of age or older.  The median age was 32 years.  For every 100 females, there were 103.5 males.  For every 100 females age 18 and over, there were 102.8 males.\n\nThe median income for a household in the city was $40,100 and the median income for a family was $46,743.  Males had a median income of $35,852 versus $28,841 for females.  The [[per capita income]] for the city was $20,577.  About 10.1% of families and 19.5% of the population were below the [[poverty line]], including 16% of those under the age of 18 and 12.1% of those ages 65 and older.\n\n===Crime===\n{{Infobox UCR\n|city_name= Everett\n|year= 2015\n|murder and manslaughter= 5\n|rape= 42\n|robbery= 140\n|aggravated_assault= 214\n|burglary= 924\n|larceny_theft= 4096\n|motor_vehicle_theft= 862\n|arson= 31\n|source_url= https://www.fbi.gov/contact-us/field-offices/seattle/news/press-releases/the-fbi-releases-2015-crime-statistics-for-washington-state\n|source_name= 2015 FBI Crime Statistics\n|notes= 2013 population: 105,370\n}}\nWhile in 2012, Everett was ranked with the 104th highest crime rate in the United States,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://os.cqpress.com/citycrime/2012/CityCrime2013_CityCrimeRateRankings.pdf |title=2012 City Crime Rate Rankings* |publisher=[[CQ Press]]}}</ref> it has since seen significant improvement in several key areas. For example, between 2012 and 2015, Everett's robbery rate decreased from 182 to 148 (-18.7%). Aggravated assault decreased from 252 to 225 (-10.7%), and burglary from 4,281 to 974 (-77.2%).<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.fbi.gov/contact-us/field-offices/seattle/news/press-releases/the-fbi-releases-2015-crime-statistics-for-washington-state |title=FBI Releases 2015 Crime Statistics for Washington State}}</ref> Everett's burglary rate in 2012 was unusually high, and that a more fair comparison would have been the decrease from 2013's burglary rate of 1,129 to 2015's 974 (-13.7%).<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.fbi.gov/contact-us/field-offices/seattle/news/press-releases/the-fbi-releases-2013-crime-statistics-for-washington-state |title=FBI Releases 2013 Crime Statistics for Washington State}}</ref>\n\nIn January 2017, Everett, with a high rate of [[opioid abuse]], sued [[Purdue Pharma]], claiming that the company's [[gross negligence]] in the distribution of [[OxyContin]] harmed its citizens. One aspect of the complex suit is a Los Angeles drug ring, which employed corrupt doctors issuing huge prescriptions to homeless people, diverting the drug to Washington and other states.<ref>{{citation |title=City devastated by OxyContin use sues Purdue Pharma, claims drugmaker put profits over citizens' welfare |author=Harriet Ryan |date=January 19, 2017 |newspaper=The Los Angeles Times |url=http://www.latimes.com/local/lanow/la-me-oxycontin-lawsuit-20170118-story.html}}</ref><ref>{{citation |newspaper=Everett Herald |title=Everett's suit against OxyContin maker moves to federal court |author=Scott North |date=February 20, 2017 |url=http://www.heraldnet.com/news/everetts-suit-against-oxycontin-maker-moves-to-federal-court/}}</ref><ref>{{citation |url=https://www.npr.org/2017/02/03/513196772/u-s-city-sues-oxycontin-maker-for-contributing-to-opiod-crisis |title=U.S. City Sues OxyContin Maker For Contributing To Opioid Crisis |work=[[Morning Edition]] |publisher=NPR |date=February 3, 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Government and politics==\n\nEverett is a first-class city with an organized [[city charter|charter]] and a [[mayor\u2013council government|mayor\u2013council]] form of government.<ref name=\"MRSC-First\">{{cite web |date=March 10, 2020 |title=First Class Cities |url=http://mrsc.org/getdoc/490c32b2-2cd8-480a-92bc-a4ec66fbeb1c/First-Class-Cities-by-Form-of-Government.aspx |publisher=[[Municipal Research and Services Center]] |accessdate=March 26, 2020}}</ref> The city's [[mayor]] and seven councilmembers are elected [[at-large]] to four-year terms in staggered elections that take place during odd-numbered years. Beginning in 2021, the Everett city council will elect five members from districts and two from at-large seats.<ref>{{cite news |last=Giordano |first=Lizz |date=November 19, 2018 |title=Significant changes coming to Everett's City Council |url=https://www.heraldnet.com/news/significant-changes-coming-to-everetts-city-council/ |work=The Everett Herald |accessdate=March 26, 2020}}</ref> The city council meets weekly on Wednesdays and offers live television and web broadcasts via the [[Everett Channel]].<ref>{{cite web |title=City Council |url=https://everettwa.gov/409/City-Council |publisher=City of Everett |accessdate=March 26, 2020}}</ref> The city government is based out of the Wall Street Building in Downtown Everett, a 10-story office tower adjacent to the historic [[Everett City Hall]]\u2014now home to the city police department and city council chambers.<ref>{{cite news |last=Winters |first=Chris |date=December 6, 2016 |title=City of Everett tightens Wall Street building security |url=https://www.heraldnet.com/news/everett-hires-security-for-building-housing-mayor-city-offices/ |work=The Everett Herald |accessdate=March 26, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Smith |first=Debra |date=February 26, 2012 |title=Plan could allow new name for old Everett city hall |url=https://www.heraldnet.com/news/plan-could-allow-new-name-for-old-everett-city-hall/ |work=The Everett Herald |accessdate=March 26, 2020}}</ref>\n\n[[Cassie Franklin]], a former city councilmember, was elected as mayor in 2017 and is the second woman and first non-appointee to hold the office.<ref>{{cite news |last=King |first=Rikki |date=November 16, 2017 |title=Franklin becomes first woman to be elected mayor of Everett |url=https://www.heraldnet.com/news/cassie-franklin-becomes-first-woman-to-be-elected-mayor-of-everett/ |work=The Everett Herald |accessdate=March 26, 2020}}</ref> The mayor of Everett is responsible for appointing the heads of various city departments, the city clerk, the city treasurer, the [[police chief|police]] and [[fire chief|fire]] chiefs, and members of service commissions and boards.<ref name=\"MRSC-First\"/> The city government has 1,200 employees and an operating budget of $148.7&nbsp;million for 2020.<ref>{{cite news |last=Giordano |first=Lizz |date=January 11, 2019 |title=City of Everett offers buyouts to 330 senior employees |url=https://www.heraldnet.com/news/city-of-everett-offers-buyouts-to-330-senior-employees/ |work=The Everett Herald |accessdate=March 26, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Giordano |first=Lizz |date=November 15, 2019 |title=Everett balances 2020 budget with no new fees or taxes |url=https://www.heraldnet.com/news/everett-balances-2020-budget-with-no-new-fees-or-taxes/ |work=The Everett Herald |accessdate=March 26, 2020}}</ref> It provides a range of municipal services, including police, fire, [[emergency medical services]], public works, a [[housing authority]], zoning and planning, parks and recreation, and some utilities.<ref name=\"CAFR2018\"/>{{rp|2}}<ref name=\"About\">{{cite web |title=About Everett |url=https://everettwa.gov/272/About-Everett |publisher=City of Everett |accessdate=March 26, 2020}}</ref> Everett also has a [[municipal court]] that was established in 1987 and has two judges who are elected to four-year terms.<ref>{{cite news |last=Haglund |first=Noah |date=December 20, 2013 |title=First woman to serve on Everett Municipal Court |url=https://www.heraldnet.com/news/first-woman-to-serve-on-everett-municipal-court/ |work=The Everett Herald |accessdate=March 29, 2020}}</ref> The city government runs its own [[Everett Transit|public transit]] and [[Everett Public Library|library]] systems, which are separate from the countywide [[Community Transit]] and [[Sno-Isle Libraries]].<ref>{{cite news |last=Giordano |first=Lizz |date=November 8, 2019 |title=Everett entertains pitch for joining county-wide bus system |url=https://www.heraldnet.com/news/everett-entertains-pitch-for-joining-county-wide-bus-system/ |work=The Everett Herald |accessdate=March 26, 2020}}</ref>\n\nEverett is also the [[county seat]] of [[Snohomish County, Washington|Snohomish County]] and houses several major government facilities on a campus in Downtown Everett. The campus includes the [[Snohomish County Courthouse|county courthouse]], county jail, administrative offices, and the main precinct of the [[Snohomish County Sheriff|county sheriff]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Departments-Offices-Campus Map |url=https://snohomishcountywa.gov/2902/Departments-Offices-CampusMap |publisher=Snohomish County |accessdate=March 26, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Kelly |first=Brian |date=June 1, 2005 |title=$175 million later... |url=https://www.heraldnet.com/news/175-million-later/ |work=The Everett Herald |accessdate=March 26, 2020}}</ref>\n\nAt the federal level, Everett is part of the [[Washington's 2nd congressional district|2nd congressional district]], represented by Democrat [[Rick Larsen]] since 2001.<ref name=\"DistrictMap\">{{cite map |date=February 7, 2012 |title=Washington State Legislative & Congressional District Map |url=http://www.redistricting.wa.gov/assets/maps/FoldedMap_State.pdf |inset=[http://www.redistricting.wa.gov/assets/maps/FoldedMap_Insets.pdf Puget Sound & Other Areas] |publisher=[[Washington State Redistricting Commission]] |accessdate=March 26, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Cornfield |first=Jerry |date=January 7, 2019 |title=Now in majority, state\u2019s Democrats ready to use new clout |url=https://www.heraldnet.com/news/now-in-majority-states-democrats-ready-to-use-new-clout/ |work=The Everett Herald |accessdate=March 26, 2020}}</ref> At the state level, most of the city is in the [[Washington's 38th legislative district|38th legislative district]] alongside Marysville and the Tulalip Indian Reservation. The southern neighborhoods of the city, including Silver Lake, are part of the [[Washington's 21st legislative district|21st legislative district]], shared with Edmonds and Mukilteo.<ref name=\"DistrictMap\"/> Everett is also part of the [[Snohomish County Council]]'s 2nd district, which also includes Mukilteo and the Tulalip Indian Reservation.<ref>{{cite map |title=Snohomish County Council Districts |url=http://snohomishcountywa.gov/DocumentCenter/Home/View/49 |publisher=Snohomish County Elections |accessdate=March 26, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Culture==\n\n===Arts and tourism===\n[[File:Everett Theater 02.jpg|thumb|Historic Everett Theatre]]\n\nEverett is described as a \"largely [[blue-collar]] city\", but is home to a regional arts scene that includes galleries, community theaters, music, and artwork.<ref>{{cite news |last=Winters |first=Chris |date=August 27, 2014 |title=With a change of tune, Snohomish County Music Project thrives |url=https://www.heraldnet.com/news/with-a-change-of-tune-snohomish-county-music-project-thrives/ |work=The Everett Herald |accessdate=March 29, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Wood |first=Kyle R. |date=August 16, 1996 |title=Selling Snohomish County |page=B1 |url=https://archive.seattletimes.com/archive/?date=19960816&slug=2344504 |work=The Seattle Times |accessdate=March 29, 2020}}</ref>\n\nDowntown Everett is also home to the Everett Performing Arts Center (home to the [[Village Theatre]] theatre company), The Historic Everett Theatre<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.historiceveretttheatre.org |title=Home |publisher=}}</ref> (built in 1901 and is one of the oldest active theatre West of the Rockies), the [[Imagine Children's Museum]], the Arts Council of Snohomish County, and an array of street sculptures. The Everett Symphony (established 1935) performs at the Everett Civic Auditorium. The city is also home to the Everett Chorale, which holds their concerts at the Everett Performing Arts Center.\n\nFounded as the Arts Council of Snohomish County, the [[Schack Art Center]] opened in downtown Everett in April 2011 and was named for John and Idamae Schack, in honor of their steadfast support of Everett's cultural institutions.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.schack.org |title=Welcome |publisher=}}</ref> It is the place to look at, learn about, and create art in the region. Village Theatre has produced musical theatre since 1979. Through its Village Originals program, Village Theatre contributes to the development of new musicals, having launched over 145 new works to date. Its youth education programs, Pied Piper and KIDSTAGE, serving over 55,000 young people, families, and schools annually.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.villagetheatre.org/everett/about.php |title=Village Theatre \u2013 About Us |publisher=}}</ref>\n{{Expand section|date=June 2008}}\n\nSince the end of the Great Recession (2009), Seattle has seen its cost of living rise exponentially, largely due to large-scale economic development and the growth of the tech industry.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://smartasset.com/mortgage/what-is-the-cost-of-living-in-seattle |title=What Is the True Cost of Living in Seattle? |publisher=}}</ref> As its perception as a working class community has diminished,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://grist.org/cities/in-seattle-the-rent-is-too-damn-high |title=In Seattle, the rent is too damn high |publisher=}}</ref> many musicians and artists have found it increasingly difficult to live within Seattle proper.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://kuow.org/post/seattle-too-expensive-artists-who-help-it-boom |title=Seattle Is Too Expensive For Artists Who Help It Boom |publisher=}}</ref> This has led to an \"artistic flight\" toward neighboring communities, most notably Everett which is often cited as possessing the \"true grit and soul of the 90's.\" <ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.cityonthesound.com/#!blank-1/sz453 |title=Everett Today |publisher=}}</ref>\n\nThe Everett area has several tourist attractions, particularly those themed around aviation. The [[Future of Flight Aviation Center & Boeing Tour|Future of Flight Aviation Center]] at Paine Field, owned by the county government and operated by Boeing, has several aviation exhibits and includes a tour of the Boeing assembly plant. It is the most popular tourist attraction in Snohomish County, with 495,000 total visitors in 2017.<ref>{{cite news |last=Gates |first=Dominic |date=February 28, 2018 |title=Boeing, Snohomish County hold key to Future of Flight as aviation center faces turbulent times |url=https://www.seattletimes.com/business/boeing-aerospace/boeing-snohomish-county-hold-key-to-future-of-flight-aviation-centers-future/ |work=The Seattle Times |accessdate=March 30, 2020}}</ref> The [[Flying Heritage & Combat Armor Museum]] opened in 2008 at a renovated Paine Field hangar and houses a collection of restored 20th century military planes and vehicles.<ref>{{cite news |last=Catchpole |first=Dan |date=April 11, 2017 |title=Growing Flying Heritage Collection now has a new name |url=https://www.heraldnet.com/news/growing-flying-heritage-collection-now-has-a-new-name/ |work=The Everett Herald |accessdate=March 30, 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Events===\n\nThe city hosts several annual events and festivals for local arts and celebrations, usually during the summer months. The Fisherman's Village Music Festival, established in 2014, takes place annually over a three-day weekend in May at four stages in Downtown Everett. The music festival includes performances from 50 local and national artists as well as art exhibitions.<ref>{{cite news |last=Rietmulder |first=Michael |date=March 29, 2018 |title=With Fisherman's Village Music Festival, Everett out-rocks Seattle one weekend a year |url=https://www.seattletimes.com/entertainment/music/with-fishermans-village-music-festival-everett-out-rocks-seattle-one-weekend-a-year/ |work=The Seattle Times |accessdate=March 29, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Thompson |first=Evan |date=May 9, 2019 |title=Fisherman's Village Music Festival expands to Everett Station |url=https://www.heraldnet.com/life/fishermans-village-music-festival-expands-to-everett-station/ |work=The Everett Herald |accessdate=March 29, 2020}}</ref> The city's waterfront hosts an annual parade and [[fireworks]] display on [[Independence Day (United States)|Independence Day]].<ref>{{cite news |last=Davey |first=Stephanie |date=July 5, 2019 |title=July 4th parade is a 'special tradition' for local families |url=https://www.heraldnet.com/news/july-4th-parade-is-a-special-tradition-for-local-families/ |work=The Everett Herald |accessdate=March 29, 2020}}</ref> Several annual festivals were established in the 1990s, including a [[film festival]] in February,<ref>{{cite news |last=Salyer |first=Sharon |date=February 7, 2019 |title=Everett Film Festival marks its 20th year with 10 screenings |url=https://www.heraldnet.com/life/see-10-short-films-and-documentaries-at-everett-film-festival/ |work=The Everett Herald |accessdate=March 29, 2020}}</ref> the Sorticulture garden festival in June,<ref>{{cite news |last=Thompson |first=Evan |date=June 1, 2019 |title=Sprinklers with style, and much more at Everett's Sorticulture |url=https://www.heraldnet.com/life/sprinklers-with-style-and-much-more-at-everetts-sorticulture/ |work=The Everett Herald |accessdate=March 29, 2020}}</ref> and the Fresh Paint [[art show]] in August.<ref>{{cite news |last=Salyer |first=Sharon |date=August 16, 2018 |title=Fresh Paint to bring artists, art lovers to waterfront |url=https://www.heraldnet.com/life/fresh-paint-to-bring-artists-art-lovers-to-waterfront/ |work=The Everett Herald |accessdate=March 29, 2020}}</ref> The cit's largest annual summer festival, the Salty Sea Days, was established in 1970 and included a parade, [[hydroplane race]]s, a classic auto show, and other events. It was originally subsidized using city [[lodging tax]]es until 2003, and shut down three years later.<ref>{{cite news |last=Langston |first=Jennifer |date=August 26, 2003 |title=Puget Sound Journal: Everett's summer fest not worth its salt, some say |page=B3 |url=https://www.seattlepi.com/news/article/Puget-Sound-Journal-Everett-s-summer-fest-not-1122698.php |work=Seattle Post-Intelligencer |accessdate=March 30, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Warnick |first=Jennifer |date=March 1, 2005 |title=Group scuttles Salty Sea Days |url=https://www.heraldnet.com/news/group-scuttles-salty-sea-days/ |work=The Everett Herald |accessdate=March 30, 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe Everett [[farmers market]] began in 1994 and operates on Sundays from May to October with 200 vendors and about 5,000 weekly visitors.<ref>{{cite news |last=Giordano |first=Lizz |date=July 20, 2019 |title=Farmers Market is leaving Boxcar, moving to downtown Everett |url=https://www.heraldnet.com/news/farmers-market-is-leaving-boxcar-moving-to-downtown-everett/ |work=The Everett Herald |accessdate=March 29, 2020}}</ref> It was originally located at the Port of Everett but moved in 2019 to Wetmore Avenue in downtown because of parking and accessibility issues at the waterfront site.<ref>{{cite news |last=Smith |first=Debra |date=June 6, 2011 |title=Future murky for Everett waterfront farmers market |url=http://www.heraldnet.com/article/20110606/NEWS01/706069912 |work=The Everett Herald |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110728064906/http://www.heraldnet.com/article/20110606/NEWS01/706069912 |archivedate=July 28, 2011 |accessdate=March 29, 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"Herald-FM19\">{{cite news |last=Giordano |first=Lizz |date=August 13, 2019 |title=Long parking lines, costs led Everett Farmers Market to move |url=https://www.heraldnet.com/news/parking-lines-costs-led-to-move-by-everett-farmers-market/ |work=The Everett Herald |accessdate=March 29, 2020}}</ref> The farmers market also operates popup [[bazaar]]s during the off-season and a Wednesday market at [[Everett Station]] during the summer.<ref>{{cite news |last=Watanabe |first=Ben |date=February 10, 2020 |title=First popup Everett Farmers Market draws hundreds of people |url=https://www.heraldnet.com/news/first-popup-everett-farmers-market-draws-hundreds-of-people/ |work=The Everett Herald |accessdate=March 29, 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Media===\n\nThe ''[[Everett Herald]]'' is the city's daily newspaper, providing local and national news for 40,000 subscribers in Snohomish County. It began publication on February 11, 1901, emerging as the city's lone daily newspaper from a field of three competitors established in the early 1890s, including the ''Everett News'', ''Everett Times'', and ''Everett Tribune''.<ref name=\"Editions\">{{cite book |last1=Bagwell |first1=Steve |last2=Stapilus |first2=Randy |year=2013 |title=New Editions: The Northwest's newspapers as they were, are, and will be |pages=212\u2013213 |publisher=Ridenbaugh Press |location=Carlton, Oregon |isbn=978-0-945648-10-9 |oclc=861618089}}</ref> The newspaper remained under local ownership until it was purchased by [[The Washington Post Company]] in 1978 and it was sold to [[Sound Publishing]] in 2013.<ref name=\"Editions\"/><ref>{{cite news |date=March 4, 2013 |title=Herald sale to Sound Publishing completed |url=https://www.heraldnet.com/business/herald-sale-to-sound-publishing-completed/ |work=The Everett Herald |accessdate=March 29, 2020}}</ref> The ''Herald'' launched its online website on January 5, 1997, the monthly ''Herald Business Journal'' in 1998,<ref>{{cite web |title=The Herald Business Journal |url=http://www.soundpublishing.com/titles/the-herald-business-journal/ |publisher=[[Sound Publishing]] |accessdate=March 30, 2020}}</ref> and began publishing a weekly Spanish-language newspaper, ''La Raza del Noroeste'', in April 2006.<ref>{{cite web |title=About the Daily Herald and Heraldnet |url=http://www.heraldnet.com/article/99999999/EXTRAS02/676034648 |publisher=The Everett Herald |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100716223513/http://www.heraldnet.com/article/99999999/EXTRAS02/676034648 |archivedate=July 16, 2010 |accessdate=March 30, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Arriola |first=Cindy |date=February 14, 2013 |title=El futuro de \"La Raza\" |language=Spanish |trans-title=The future of \"La Raza\" |url=https://www.larazanw.com/noticias/el-futuro-de-la-raza/ |work=La Raza del Noroeste |accessdate=March 30, 2020}}</ref> My Everett News is an independent online news outlet for Everett that was established in 2011 and is affiliated with ''[[The Seattle Times]]''.<ref>{{cite news |date=July 13, 2011 |title=Seattle Times announces more local news partners |url=https://www.seattletimes.com/seattle-news/seattle-times-announces-more-local-news-partners-1/ |work=The Seattle Times |accessdate=March 30, 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe city is part of the [[Media in Seattle|Seattle\u2013Tacoma media market]], ranked 13th among U.S. metro areas, which includes several major television and radio stations.<ref>{{cite web |date=September 28, 2019 |title=Local Television Market Universe Estimates |page=1 |url=https://www.nielsen.com/wp-content/uploads/sites/3/2019/09/2019-20-dma-ranker.pdf |publisher=[[Nielsen Media Research]] |accessdate=March 30, 2020}}</ref> [[KONG-TV]], a Seattle-based broadcast channel that is affiliated with [[KING-TV]], has been licensed to Everett sine 1984 and debuted in 1997.<ref>{{cite news |last=Levesque |first=John |date=July 2, 1997 |title=KING grooms KONG for a Monday debut and a spot on cable |page=D10 |work=Seattle Post-Intelligencer}}</ref> The City of Everett also runs The Everett Channel, a [[government-access television]] station that broadcasts local events and city meetings.<ref>{{cite web |title=The Everett Channel |url=https://everettwa.gov/408/Everett-Channel |publisher=City of Everett |accessdate=March 30, 2020}}</ref> Everett itself has four radio stations.<ref>{{cite news |last=Guiney |first=Kelley |date=January 2, 2010 |title=Neighborhood of the week: North Everett |url=http://seattletimes.nwsource.com/html/realestate/2010652800_realneighborhood03.html |work=The Seattle Times |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100107053938/http://seattletimes.nwsource.com/html/realestate/2010652800_realneighborhood03.html |archivedate=January 7, 2010 |accessdate=March 30, 2020}}</ref> The Skotdal family owns two stations in Everett that share facilities with the Everett Post: [[KRKO|KRKO-AM]], which began broadcasting in 1922 and primary plays [[Classic hits]] along with local sports;<ref>{{cite web |last=Blecha |first=Peter |date=December 6, 2010 |title=KRKO: Everett's Historic Radio Station |url=https://www.historylink.org/File/9620 |work=HistoryLink |accessdate=March 30, 2020}}</ref> and [[KKXA|KKXA-AM]], a country music station launched in 2011.<ref>{{cite news |last=Davis |first=Jim |date=October 7, 2016 |title=Two Everett AM radio stations approved to broadcast on FM |url=https://www.heraldnet.com/news/two-everett-am-radio-stations-approved-to-broadcast-on-fm/ |work=The Everett Herald |accessdate=March 30, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Brown |first=Andrea |date=April 10, 2018 |title=An Everett 'potcast' explains what all the buzz is about |url=https://www.heraldnet.com/news/what-all-the-buzz-is-about/ |work=The Everett Herald |accessdate=March 30, 2020}}</ref> [[KSER|KSER-FM]] is an independent [[public radio]] station founded in 1991 to serve Snohomish County, carrying local news, music programming, and nationally syndicated news.<ref>{{cite news |last=Muhlstein |first=Julie |date=March 12, 2016 |title=At 25, Everett's KSER still entertains, informs community |url=https://www.heraldnet.com/news/at-25-everetts-kser-still-entertains-informs-community/ |work=The Everett Herald |accessdate=March 30, 2020}}</ref> Everett is also the home to [[KWYZ|KWYZ-AM]] (Radio Hankook), a [[Korean language]] news and entertainment station that launched in 1997 and is broadcast from [[Federal Way, Washington|Federal Way]].<ref>{{cite news |last=Virgin |first=Bill |date=June 10, 1999 |title=Korean-language stations a resource for immigrants |page=C6 |work=Seattle Post-Intelligencer}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Kugiya |first=Hugo |date=July 8, 2014 |title=Radio Hankook: The heart of Korea on Washington radio |url=https://crosscut.com/2014/07/korean-radio-hankook-federal-way-seattle |work=[[Crosscut.com]] |accessdate=March 30, 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Libraries===\n\nThe [[Everett Public Library]] system has two locations with 258,133 total items and serves 45,205 registered members in the city and surrounding communities {{as of|2018|lc=y}}.<ref>{{cite web |date=September 2019 |title=2018 Washington Public Library Statistical Report |pages=50\u201356 |url=https://www.sos.wa.gov/_assets/library/libraries/libdev/2018stats.pdf |publisher=[[Washington State Library]] |accessdate=March 21, 2020}}</ref> The library was founded in 1894 and moved into a [[Everett Carnegie Library|permanent building]] in 1905. The current downtown library opened in 1934 and was expanded in 1991;<ref>{{cite web |last=Van Wingen |first=Melinda |date=December 3, 2019 |title=Everett Public Library |url=https://www.historylink.org/File/20926 |work=HistoryLink |accessdate=March 21, 2020}}</ref> a branch library in South Everett opened in 1985 and was renovated in 2019.<ref>{{cite news |last=Muhlstein |first=Julie |date=December 11, 2019 |title=It's a launch for Everett library's renovated Evergreen Branch |url=https://www.heraldnet.com/news/its-a-launch-for-everett-librarys-renovated-evergreen-branch/ |work=The Everett Herald |accessdate=March 21, 2020}}</ref> In 2017, [[Sno-Isle Libraries]], the countywide library system, opened a demonstration branch at a [[strip mall]] in South Everett to serve the Mariner area.<ref>{{cite news |last=Bray |first=Kari |date=February 9, 2017 |title=Everett community finally gets long-awaited library |url=https://www.heraldnet.com/news/everett-community-finally-gets-long-awaited-library/ |work=The Everett Herald |accessdate=March 27, 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Historic preservation===\n[[File:Henry M. Jackson's Home-1.jpg|thumb|Senator [[Henry M. Jackson]]'s home in North Everett]]\n\nEverett is home to 14 properties listed on the [[National Register of Historic Places]].<ref name=\"LandmarkMap\">{{cite map |date=April 23, 2019 |title=Historic Register Properties & Areas |url=https://everettwa.gov/DocumentCenter/View/19452/Historic-Register-Properties-and-Areas |publisher=City of Everett |accessdate=February 15, 2020}}</ref> The city also maintains its own register of historic places that has 35 properties.<ref>{{cite news |date=April 7, 2017 |title=Groups work to preserve Everett's rich history |url=https://www.heraldnet.com/advertising/groups-work-to-preserve-everetts-rich-history/ |work=The Everett Herald |accessdate=June 29, 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn addition to historic properties, the city has several designated [[Historic districts in the United States|historic districts]]: [[Hewitt Avenue Historic District]] in Downtown Everett; the [[Rucker Hill Historic District]]; and the [[Swalwell Block]]. Several historic overlay districts are designated by the city government, including the Riverside Overlay, the Norton\u2013Grand Overlay, and the Rucker\u2013Grand Overlay, which includes the home of the former U.S. Senator [[Henry M. Jackson]].<ref name=\"LandmarkMap\"/>\n\nThe Everett Museum of History was established in 1953 as a countywide historical association and maintained its own museum until 2007. The organization's collections moved between several historic buildings, including the former [[Everett Carnegie Library]] and part of the [[Everett Mall]], while a new location was sought.<ref>{{cite news |last=Muhlstein |first=Julie |date=August 28, 2016 |title=Everett Museum of History seeks a forever home |url=https://www.heraldnet.com/news/everett-museum-of-history-seeks-a-forever-home/ |work=The Everett Herald |accessdate=February 15, 2020}}</ref> A permanent museum at the former downtown offices of the ''Everett Herald'' is planned to open in 2021.<ref>{{cite news |last=Muhlstein |first=Julie |date=December 21, 2017 |title=A Christmas present for the keepers of Everett's past |url=https://www.heraldnet.com/news/a-present-for-the-past/ |work=The Everett Herald |accessdate=February 15, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=About Us |url=https://everett-museum.org/everett-museum-of-history/ |publisher=Everett Museum of History |accessdate=February 15, 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Sports===\n\nEverett is home to two sports venues that are used by professional [[minor league]] teams and for other events.<ref name=\"Times-Sports05\">{{cite news |last=Alexander |first=Brian |date=October 19, 2005 |title=Snohomish County minor league teams are a major success |page=H16 |url=https://archive.seattletimes.com/archive/?date=20051019&slug=minorleagues19n |work=The Seattle Times |accessdate=March 28, 2020}}</ref> The [[Angel of the Winds Arena]], an indoor arena in downtown which seats 8,149, is home to [[Everett Silvertips]] of the [[Western Hockey League]].<ref>{{cite news |last=Watanabe |first=Ben |date=May 4, 2018 |title=Silvertips fans: Meet the enemy stronghold of Swift Current |url=https://www.heraldnet.com/news/silvertips-fans-meet-the-enemy-stronghold-of-swift-current/ |work=The Everett Herald |accessdate=March 28, 2020}}</ref> It opened in 2003 at a cost of $83&nbsp;million and includes a community [[ice rink]] and a [[convention center]] for use by other events.<ref>{{cite news |last=Tuinstra |first=Rachel |date=September 24, 2003 |title=A $71.5 million venue represents 'a big leap of faith' for the city |page=H28 |url=http://community.seattletimes.nwsource.com/archive/?date=20030924&slug=center24n |work=The Seattle Times |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121004084051/http://community.seattletimes.nwsource.com/archive/?date=20030924&slug=center24n |archivedate=October 4, 2012 |accessdate=March 25, 2012}}</ref> The arena has also hosted basketball games for the [[Seattle Storm]] of the [[WNBA]],<ref>{{cite news |last=Patterson |first=Nick |date=January 16, 2020 |title=Storm returning to Everett for 8 games in 2020 |url=https://www.heraldnet.com/sports/storm-returning-to-everett-for-8-games-in-2020/ |work=The Everett Herald |accessdate=March 28, 2020}}</ref> indoor tennis events including the [[2020 Fed Cup]],<ref>{{cite news |last=Patterson |first=Nick |date=February 17, 2020 |title=USTA: Everett aces first time hosting Fed Cup qualifier |url=https://www.heraldnet.com/sports/usta-everett-aces-first-time-hosting-fed-cup-qualifier/ |work=The Everett Herald |accessdate=March 28, 2020}}</ref> and two editions of the [[Skate America]] figure skating championships in 2008 and 2018.<ref>{{cite news |last=Patterson |first=Nick |date=October 30, 2018 |title=Can Everett become a regular on the figure-skating circuit? |url=https://www.heraldnet.com/sports/skate-americas-encore-in-everett-deemed-a-success/ |work=The Everett Herald |accessdate=March 28, 2020}}</ref> The [[Everett AquaSox]] of the [[Northwest League]] play at Funko Field, a 3,682-seat baseball stadium that is part of the [[Everett Memorial Stadium]] complex.<ref>{{cite news |last=Calkins |first=Matt |date=August 2, 2019 |title=As he tries to revive MLB career, Felix Hernandez remains King in Everett |page=C1 |url=https://www.seattletimes.com/sports/mariners/felix-hernandez-after-rehab-start-in-everett-it-feels-good-to-be-back-on-the-mound/ |work=The Seattle Times |accessdate=March 28, 2020}}</ref> The Memorial Stadium complex was built in 1947 and also includes a 12,000-seat football and track stadium that is used by the city's various high school teams.{{sfnp|O'Donnell|1993|p=157}}<ref>{{cite news |date=September 6, 2001 |title=Ticket prices and more for region's football stadiums |url=https://archive.seattletimes.com/archive/?date=20010906&slug=stadiumweb06 |work=The Seattle Times |accessdate=March 28, 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe city formerly had additional indoor sports teams who played in minor leagues: the [[Snohomish County Explosion]], which played from 2008 to 2010 in the defunct [[International Basketball League]];<ref>{{cite news |last=Lommers |first=Aaron |date=April 8, 2011 |title=New owners bring Explosion back to Everett |url=https://www.heraldnet.com/sports/new-owners-bring-explosion-back-to-everett/ |work=The Everett Herald |accessdate=February 18, 2019}}</ref> the [[Everett Hawks]] of the [[National Indoor Football League]] and [[AF2]], who folded in 2007; the [[Everett Raptors]] of the [[Indoor Football League]], who played for one season in 2012;<ref>{{cite news |last=Boyle |first=John |date=February 24, 2012 |title=Everett Raptors make their debut Saturday night |url=https://www.heraldnet.com/sports/everett-raptors-make-their-debut-saturday-night/ |work=The Everett Herald |accessdate=February 18, 2019}}</ref> and the [[Washington Stealth]] of the [[National Lacrosse League]], who moved to British Columbia in 2014.<ref>{{cite news |date=June 27, 2013 |title=Stealth moving to Langley, B.C. |url=https://www.heraldnet.com/sports/stealth-moving-to-langley-b-c/ |work=The Everett Herald |accessdate=February 18, 2019}}</ref>\n\nEverett also hosted several minor league soccer teams, including the [[Seattle BigFoot|Everett BigFoot]] of the third-division [[USISL Pro League]], who began play in 1995 and moved to [[West Seattle]] in 1997.<ref>{{cite news |last=Peoples |first=John |date=February 2, 1995 |title=Bigfoot hoping to leave mark on Everett, soccer landscape |page=C9 |url=https://archive.seattletimes.com/archive/?date=19950202&slug=2102732 |work=The Seattle Times |accessdate=March 28, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |date=March 17, 1997 |title=Around the Northwest |page=D8 |work=The Seattle Times}}</ref> The [[North Sound SeaWolves]] of the [[USL Premier Development League]] began play at [[Mariner High School (Everett, Washington)|Mariner High School]] in 2011 and moved to [[Edmonds, Washington|Edmonds]] the following season.<ref>{{cite news |last=Allende |first=Mike |date=October 13, 2011 |title=SeaWolves fans pick team's new logo |url=https://www.heraldnet.com/sports/seawolves-fans-pick-teams-new-logo/ |work=The Everett Herald |accessdate=February 18, 2019}}</ref> Everett Jets FC, an ameatur team based at Memorial Stadium, are set to begin their inaugural 2020 season in the [[Evergreen Premier League]].<ref>{{cite news |last=Patterson |first=Nick |date=January 27, 2020 |title=Community sports roundup: Everett Jets FC to join men's league |url=https://www.heraldnet.com/sports/community-sports-roundup-everett-jets-fc-to-join-mens-league/ |work=The Everett Herald |accessdate=March 28, 2020}}</ref>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Club\n! Sport\n! League\n! Founded\n! Venue\n! Championships\n|-\n| [[Everett AquaSox]]\n| align=center | [[Baseball]]\n| [[Northwest League]]\n| align=center | 1984\n| [[Everett Memorial Stadium|Funko Field]]\n| 1985, 2010\n|-\n| [[Everett Jets FC]]\n| align=center | [[Association football|Soccer]]\n| [[Evergreen Premier League]]\n| align=center | 2020\n| [[Everett Memorial Stadium]]\n| \n|-\n| [[Everett Silvertips]]\n| align=center | [[Ice hockey|Hockey]]\n| [[Western Hockey League]]\n| align=center | 2003\n| [[Angel of the Winds Arena]]\n|\n|}\n\n==Parks and recreation==\n[[File:Everett - Grand Ave Park.jpg|thumb|Grand Ave. Park]]\n\nEverett is home to 40 parks. The biggest parks are Walter E. Hall Park at {{convert|137|acre|km2|1}}, Forest Park at {{convert|111|acre|km2|1}}, Langus Riverfront Park at {{convert|96|acre|km2}}, Kasch Park at {{convert|60|acre|km2}}, Howarth Park at {{convert|28|acre|km2}}, and Thornton A. Sullivan Park at {{convert|27|acre|km2}}.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.everettwa.org/default.aspx?ID=11 |title=Everett Parks in Everett<!-- Bot generated title --> |publisher= |accessdate=February 19, 2018}}</ref> Walter E. Hall Park, near the Boeing plant, sports a golf course and a skate park; Forest Park, a swimming pool, hockey, horseshoes, miles of trails and an animal farm; Langus Park, a boat launch; Kasch Park, four softball fields; Howarth Park, a sandy beach on Puget Sound; and Thornton A. Sullivan Park hosts a sandy swimming beach on Silver Lake as well as public docks for fishing.\n\n===Forest Park===\nForest Park is the oldest public park in Everett. As its name suggests, the park is heavily wooded. It is  home to miles of trails, a playground, and a popular public swimming pool.\n\n===Jetty Island===\n{{main|Jetty Island}}\n\n[[Jetty Island]] is a man-made island and park located in the [[Puget Sound]], just off the Everett, Washington waterfront. The island is two miles long and half a mile wide, approximately 1,800 acres. The island has no plumbing, electricity or structures. During the summer months, a ferry becomes operational, allowing transportation to and from the island. A floating restroom also becomes operational off the island's shore. Jetty Island's unique features provide excellent habitat for birds and juvenile salmon. The island is home to more than 45 bird species including osprey, shorebirds, hawks, eagles, cormorants and ducks. Visitors may see seals surfacing or lounging near the water's edge, or even witness gray whales swimming past during spring migration.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.portofeverett.com/recreation/beaches-kiteboarding/jetty-island-290 |title=Port of Everett : Jetty Island |publisher=}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.historiceverettwaterfront.com/waterfront-special-features/jetty-island |title=Jetty Island \u2013 Everett Waterfront Historical Interpretive Program |first= |last=Everett |publisher=}}</ref>\n\n===Nishiyama Garden===\nNishiyama Garden is a traditional Japanese garden located at the Nippon Business Institute at [[Everett Community College]].  It features Sukiya-style wooden gates, gravel paths, stones, trees, a small stream and a portion of the famous Kintai Bridge from [[Iwakuni|Iwakuni, Japan]], one of Everett's sister cities.<ref>[http://www.everettcc.edu/programs/socsci/nbi/index.cfm?id=5040 Nishiyama Japanese Garden<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref>\n\n===Evergreen Arboretum and Gardens===\nEvergreen Arboretum and Gardens ({{convert|2.4|acre|m2}}) is an [[arboretum]] and park located at the south end of [[American Legion Memorial Park|Legion Park]], at the intersection of Alverson and Marine View Drive.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.evergreenarboretum.com/ |title=Evergreen Arboretum and Gardens |publisher=}}</ref>  Gardens include sculpture and vistas of [[Puget Sound]], as well as:\n\n* Conifer garden \u2013 includes ''[[Chamaecyparis lawsoniana]]'', ''[[Chamaecyparis nootkatensis]]'', ''[[Pfitzeriana]] Aurea'', ''[[Picea glauca]]'', and ''[[Strobus]] 'Nana{{'}}''.\n* Dahlia garden \u2013 a variety of [[dahlia]]s.\n* Japanese Maple grove \u2013 17 varieties of maples, with [[fern]]s and [[hydrangea]]s.\n* Perennial border \u2013 includes artichoke (''[[Cynara scolymus]]''), Japanese forest grass (''[[Hakonechloa macra]]''), giant hyssop (''[[Hyssopus officinalis]]''), dwarf waterlily (''[[Nymphaea]]''), and New Zealand flax (''[[Phormium cookianum]]'').\n* Small Urban Tree Walk\n* White border \u2013 flowers and foliage in white, silver, and blue.\n* Woodland garden \u2013 grotto with Knadhill and [[Exbury Gardens|Exbury]] [[azalea]]s, lace-cap hydrangeas (''[[Hydrangea macrophylla]]''), and ''[[Pieris japonica]]''.\n\n==Education==\n[[File:Everett High School-1.jpg|thumb|[[Everett High School (Washington)|Everett High School]] (part of Everett Public Schools)]]\n\nThe city's public education system is managed by [[Everett Public Schools]] (officially the Everett School District), which has 26 schools, 2,000 staff members, and an enrollment of 20,000 students.<ref>{{cite news |last=Cornfield |first=Jerry |date=October 29, 2019 |title=In Everett school races, they agree more than they don't |url=https://www.heraldnet.com/news/in-everett-school-races-they-agree-more-than-they-dont/ |work=The Everett Herald |accessdate=March 28, 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"Times-Cohn\">{{cite news |date=November 18, 2016 |title=Everett schools chief honored as state Superintendent of Year |url=https://www.seattletimes.com/seattle-news/education/everett-schools-chief-named-state-supe-of-2017/ |work=The Seattle Times |accessdate=November 21, 2016}}</ref> The school district covers {{convert|52|sqmi|sqkm}}, including most of Everett, the city of [[Mill Creek, Washington|Mill Creek]], and the unincorporated area of [[Silver Firs, Washington|Silver Firs]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Census 2010: Everett School District |url=http://data.spokesman.com/census/2010/washington/school-districts/everett-school-district-wa/ |work=[[Spokesman-Review]] |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110304004210/http://data.spokesman.com/census/2010/washington/school-districts/everett-school-district-wa/ |archivedate=March 4, 2011 |accessdate=March 28, 2020}}</ref> The southern and western neighborhoods of Everett are served by the [[Mukilteo School District]], which also has its own high school ([[Mariner High School (Everett, Washington)|Mariner]]) in the area.<ref>{{cite map |date=December 21, 2017 |title=Snohomish County School Districts Map |url=http://www.snoco.org/docs/scd/PDF/PDS_CFP/Snohomish%20County%20School%20District.pdf |publisher=Snohomish County |accessdate=March 28, 2020}}</ref>\n\nEverett Public Schools has three high school campuses: [[Everett High School (Washington)|Everett High School]] near downtown, [[Cascade High School (Everett, Washington)|Cascade High School]] near Casino Corner, and [[Henry M. Jackson High School]] in Mill Creek.<ref name=\"Herald-HighSchool19\">{{cite news |last=Bryan |first=Zachariah |date=May 22, 2019 |title=After year of debate, Everett has new high school boundaries |url=https://www.heraldnet.com/news/after-year-of-debate-everett-has-new-high-school-boundaries/ |work=The Everett Herald |accessdate=March 28, 2020}}</ref> The school district was recognized in 2016 for its high [[graduation]] rates of 90 percent for four-year students and 94.5 percent for five-year students.<ref name=\"Times-Cohn\"/> A fourth high school campus, planned to cost $220&nbsp;million to build, was part of a [[bond measure]] in February 2018 that was rejected by voters, resulting in boundary changes for the existing schools.<ref name=\"Herald-HighSchool19\"/><ref>{{cite news |last=Cornfield |first=Jerry |date=September 22, 2019 |title=Trying again. Everett schools eye a $317M bond in 2020 |url=https://www.heraldnet.com/news/trying-again-everett-schools-eye-a-317m-bond-in-2020/ |work=The Everett Herald |accessdate=March 28, 2020}}</ref> The school district also has five [[middle school]]s and 18 [[elementary school]]s in Everett and Mill Creek.<ref>{{cite web |title=2019-20 Boundary Map |url=https://www.everettsd.org/Page/29519 |publisher=[[Everett Public Schools]] |accessdate=March 28, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Stevick |first=Eric |date=December 8, 2018 |title=Meet Tambark Creek. Everett has a new kid on the block |url=https://www.heraldnet.com/news/meet-tambark-creek-everett-has-a-new-kid-on-the-block/ |work=The Everett Herald |accessdate=March 28, 2020}}</ref> The city is also home to two [[alternative school]]s: Sequoia High School, operated by Everett Public Schools;<ref>{{cite news |last1=Mulligan |first1=Mark |last2=Mulligan |first2=Annie |date=June 28, 2013 |title=If students have the will, Sequoia High has the way |url=https://www.heraldnet.com/news/if-students-have-the-will-sequoia-high-has-the-way/ |work=The Everett Herald |accessdate=March 28, 2020}}</ref> and ACES High School, operated by the Mukilteo School District.<ref>{{cite news |last=Hutton |first=Caleb |date=December 6, 2018 |title=Teen guilty of plotting a massive school shooting in Everett |url=https://www.heraldnet.com/news/everett-teen-with-gun-guilty-of-plotting-school-shooting/ |work=The Everett Herald |accessdate=March 28, 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe Everett area is also home to several [[private school]] systems operated by religious organizations and independent educators, including those that cater to commuters from around the county. The largest private high school in the county is [[Archbishop Murphy High School]], a Catholic school located in southeastern Everett, with an enrollment of 500 students.<ref>{{cite news |last=Slager |first=Melissa |date=December 9, 2006 |title=Private school enrollment rises |url=http://www.heraldnet.com/stories/06/12/09/100loc_b1schools001.cfm |work=The Everett Herald |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20061214170329/http://www.heraldnet.com/stories/06/12/09/100loc_b1schools001.cfm |archivedate=December 14, 2006 |accessdate=March 28, 2020}}</ref> Other major private religious schools include the [[Everett Christian School]], Cedar Park Christian School, and Northshore Christian Academy.<ref>{{cite news |last=Koenig |first=Sarah |date=January 10, 2008 |title=Cedar Park takes over North Sound Christian Schools |url=https://www.heraldnet.com/uncategorized/cedar-park-takes-over-north-sound-christian-schools/ |work=The Everett Herald |accessdate=March 28, 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Higher education===\n\n[[Everett Community College]] (EVCC) is a two-year public [[community college]] that has enrolled 19,000 students from around Snohomish County and 463 total faculty.<ref>{{cite news |last=Davis |first=Jim |date=October 14, 2015 |title=Developer to build dormitory near Everett Community College |url=https://www.heraldnet.com/business/developer-to-build-dormitory-near-everett-community-college/ |work=The Everett Herald Business Journal |accessdate=March 29, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=College Navigator: Everett Community College |url=https://nces.ed.gov/collegenavigator/?id=235149 |work=[[National Center for Education Statistics]] |publisher=[[Institute of Education Sciences]] |accessdate=March 29, 2020}}</ref> The college's main campus is located <!--spans {{convert||acre|ha}}--> in North Everett on the south side of Legion Memorial Golf Course.<ref name=\"Times-WSU11\">{{cite news |last=Long |first=Katherine |date=May 23, 2011 |title=Steps taken toward creating WSU branch campus in Everett |url=http://old.seattletimes.com/html/localnews/2015129940_wsu24m.html |work=The Seattle Times |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170202073035/http://old.seattletimes.com/html/localnews/2015129940_wsu24m.html |archivedate=February 2, 2017 |accessdate=March 29, 2020}}</ref> It was established in 1941 at a former downtown elementary school and moved to its North Everett location in 1958, where it has since expanded several times.{{sfnp|O'Donnell|1993|pages=210\u2013211}}<ref>{{cite news |last1=Slager |first1=Melissa |last2=Warnick |first2=Jennifer |date=August 13, 2005 |title=EvCC carving a place to grow |url=https://www.heraldnet.com/news/evcc-carving-a-place-to-grow/ |work=The Everett Herald |accessdate=March 29, 2020}}</ref>\n\nCivic and business leaders from the Everett area began lobbying the state legislature for a four-year college in the 1990s, proposing a branch of an existing state college to serve Snohomish, Island, and Skagit counties.<ref>{{cite news |last=Brooks |first=Diane |date=December 2, 1994 |title=Bid for college alive in Everett |page=B1 |work=The Seattle Times}}</ref> A site in [[Bothell, Washington|Bothell]] was instead chosen for a [[University of Washington Bothell|northern branch campus]] for the [[University of Washington]] (UW), but only 27 percent of its students were from Snohomish County.<ref>{{cite news |last=Thompson |first=Lynn |date=August 17, 2005 |title=Push for 4-year college revs up |page=H18 |url=http://old.seattletimes.com/html/education/2002442337_4year17n.html |work=The Seattle Times |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180306202952/http://old.seattletimes.com/html/education/2002442337_4year17n.html |archivedate=March 6, 2018 |accessdate=March 29, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Stevick |first=Eric |date=August 22, 2005 |title=Ideas floated for new university |url=https://www.heraldnet.com/news/ideas-floated-for-new-university/ |work=The Everett Herald |accessdate=March 29, 2020}}</ref> In 2007, the state legislature authorized planning funds for a UW branch campus in Snohomish County and a site near [[Everett Station]] was named as a finalist alongside candidates in Lake Stevens and Marysville.<ref name=\"Times-WSU11\"/><ref>{{cite news |last=Perry |first=Nick |date=January 6, 2008 |title=UW Everett: ambitious, but dogged by doubts |page=A1 |url=https://www.seattletimes.com/seattle-news/uw-everett-ambitious-but-dogged-by-doubts/ |work=The Seattle Times |accessdate=March 29, 2020}}</ref> The [[University of Washington North Sound|branch campus project]] was shelved by the state legislature in 2008 amid a funding shortfall for the education system.<ref name=\"Herald-Degrees08\">{{cite news |last=Stevick |first=Eric |date=November 23, 2008 |title=College degrees available in Everett |url=https://www.heraldnet.com/news/college-degrees-available-in-everett/ |work=The Everett Herald |accessdate=March 29, 2020}}</ref>\n\n[[Washington State University Everett]] opened in 2017 as a branch campus of WSU and is located adjacent to the EVCC campus in North Everett.<ref name=\"Times-WSU17\">{{cite news |last=Long |first=Katherine |date=August 11, 2017 |title=WSU's new building: 'the biggest thing Everett has ever done in terms of its future' |url=https://www.seattletimes.com/seattle-news/education/wsus-new-building-the-biggest-thing-everett-has-ever-done-in-terms-of-its-future/ |work=The Seattle Times |accessdate=March 29, 2020}}</ref> The branch campus was conceived as a replacement for the UW proposal and included a WSU takeover of the [[University Center of North Puget Sound]], an alternative degrees program at EVCC, in 2014.<ref name=\"Times-WSU11\"/><ref>{{cite news |last=Harper |first=Christina |date=June 30, 2014 |title=WSU taking over University Center at EvCC |url=https://www.heraldnet.com/news/wsu-taking-over-university-center-at-evcc/ |work=The Everett Herald Business Journal |accessdate=March 29, 2020}}</ref> The EVCC campus also houses a branch of [[Western Washington University]], which it established in 1986.<ref>{{cite web |title=Everett |url=https://www.wwu.edu/everett |publisher=[[Western Washington University]] |accessdate=March 29, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Haglund |first1=Noah |last2=Stevick |first2=Eric |date=August 16, 2017 |title=At long last, WSU Everett's new building is open for business |url=https://www.heraldnet.com/news/at-long-last-wsu-everetts-new-building-open-for-business/ |work=The Everett Herald |accessdate=March 29, 2020}}</ref>\n\nEverett is also home to several private and specialized colleges, including [[City University of Seattle|City University]] and [[Everest College]] near the Everett Mall.<ref>{{cite news |date=December 27, 2011 |title=Snohomish County colleges |url=https://www.heraldnet.com/business/snohomish-county-colleges/ |work=The Everett Herald Business Journal |accessdate=March 29, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |date=November 13, 2017 |title=Altierus to close Everett college, layoff 29 |url=https://www.heraldnet.com/business/altierus-to-close-everett-college-layoff-29/ |work=The Everett Herald Business Journal |accessdate=March 29, 2020}}</ref> The city also has branch campuses for [[Embry\u2013Riddle Aeronautical University]] near the Boeing assembly plant and [[Columbia College (Missouri)|Columbia College]] at Naval Station Everett.<ref>{{cite web |title=Locations: Everett, WA |url=https://worldwide.erau.edu/locations/everett |publisher=[[Embry\u2013Riddle Aeronautical University]] |accessdate=March 29, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Davis |first=Jim |date=August 26, 2015 |title=Columbia College celebrates 20 years in Snohomish County |url=https://www.heraldnet.com/business/columbia-college-celebrates-20-years-in-snohomish-county/ |work=The Everett Herald Business Journal |accessdate=March 29, 2020}}</ref> Everett's two major [[Lutheran]] churches operated a pair of short-lived private colleges in the early 20th century, Bethania College and Columbia College.{{sfnp|O'Donnell|1993|pages=210\u2013211}} [[Henry Cogswell College]], a private institution, moved from Kirkland to Everett in 1996 and closed in 2006.<ref>{{cite news |last=Brooks |first=Diane |date=March 21, 1996 |title=4-year school to locate in Everett |page=B3 |url=https://archive.seattletimes.com/archive/?date=19960321&slug=2320138 |work=The Seattle Times |accessdate=March 29, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Stevick |first1=Eric |last2=Chircop |first2=David |date=June 29, 2006 |title=Cogswell College will close |url=https://www.heraldnet.com/news/cogswell-college-will-close/ |work=The Everett Herald |accessdate=March 29, 2020}}</ref> In the 2010s, [[Bryman College]] and [[Trinity Lutheran College (Washington)|Trinity Lutheran College]] both closed their Everett campuses.<ref>{{cite news |last=Winters |first=Chris |date=January 12, 2016 |title=Trinity Lutheran College in downtown Everett to close |url=https://www.heraldnet.com/news/trinity-lutheran-college-in-downtown-everett-to-close/ |work=The Everett Herald |accessdate=March 29, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Infrastructure==\n\n===Transportation===\n[[File:Everett Station building.jpg|thumb|[[Everett Station]], the city's [[Amtrak]] and [[Sounder commuter rail]] station that also serves local and express buses]]\n\nThe city is located along [[Interstate 5 in Washington|Interstate 5]] (I-5), a major north\u2013south freeway that connects Everett to [[Seattle]] and [[Vancouver]], British Columbia. The Everett\u2013Seattle section of I-5 is rated as one of the most congested in the United States during commuting hours, with an average of 94 minutes to travel {{convert|24|mi|km}} and 182,000 daily vehicles in South Everett.<ref>{{cite news |last=Lindblom |first=Mike |date=February 5, 2018 |title=It's worse than you think: Everett leads the nation in traffic congestion, report says |page=A1 |url=https://www.seattletimes.com/seattle-news/transportation/its-worse-than-you-think-everett-leads-the-nation-in-traffic-congestion-report-says/ |work=The Seattle Times |accessdate=March 29, 2020}}</ref> The city also has several major highways with intercity connections, including [[U.S. Route 2 in Washington|U.S. Route 2]] to [[Wenatchee, Washington|Wenatchee]] via [[Stevens Pass]]; [[Washington State Route 99|State Route 99]] from the Everett Mall to Seattle; [[Washington State Route 526|State Route 526]] to Mukilteo; [[Washington State Route 527|State Route 527]] from the Everett Mall to Mill Creek; and [[Washington State Route 529|State Route 529]] from the waterfront to Marysville.<ref>{{cite map |year=2014 |title=Washington State Highways, 2014\u20132015 |url=https://www.wsdot.wa.gov/sites/default/files/2006/06/13/TouristMapFront_withoutHillshade.pdf |inset=[https://www.wsdot.wa.gov/sites/default/files/2017/08/31/highway-map-PugetSound_Full.pdf Puget Sound] |publisher=Washington State Department of Transportation |accessdate=March 23, 2020}}</ref>\n\nEverett has several public transit and intercity transport services that intersect at [[Everett Station]], a multimodal train and bus station that opened in 2002.<ref>{{cite news |last=Whitley |first=Peyton |date=January 1, 2003 |title=City's new terminal has amassed transit depots in single location |page=I17 |url=http://community.seattletimes.nwsource.com/archive/?date=20030101&slug=station01n |work=The Seattle Times |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140808042501/http://community.seattletimes.nwsource.com/archive/?date=20030101&slug=station01n |archivedate=August 8, 2014 |accessdate=March 29, 2020}}</ref> The station is served by two [[Amtrak]] routes: [[Amtrak Cascades|''Cascades'']], which connects Vancouver to Seattle and [[Portland, Oregon]]; and the ''[[Empire Builder]]'', which travels from Seattle to [[Chicago]].<ref>{{cite news |last=Cantwell |first=Brian J. |date=December 10, 2015 |title=Amtrak restores train service through Washington state |url=https://www.seattletimes.com/life/travel/amtrak-restores-service-through-washington-state/ |work=The Seattle Times |accessdate=March 29, 2020}}</ref> Everett is also the northern terminus of the [[Sounder commuter rail]] system, which is operated by [[Sound Transit]] and travels south to Seattle during [[peak hour]]s with stops in Mukilteo and Edmonds.<ref>{{cite news |last=Lindblom |first=Mike |date=October 16, 2012 |title=Too many empty seats on Sounder north line |page=A1 |url=http://seattletimes.com/html/localnews/2019441910_sounder16m.html |work=The Seattle Times |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130514123023/http://seattletimes.com/html/localnews/2019441910_sounder16m.html |archivedate=May 14, 2013 |accessdate=March 29, 2020}}</ref> The station is served by intercity buses from [[Greyhound Lines]], [[BoltBus]], and [[Northwestern Trailways]], which connect Everett to cities in the Pacific Northwest.<ref>{{cite news |last=Sheets |first=Bill |date=February 6, 2012 |title=Everett Station celebrates 10 years and 17 million visits |url=https://www.heraldnet.com/news/everett-station-celebrates-10-years-and-17-million-visits/ |work=The Everett Herald |accessdate=March 29, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Podsada |first=Janice |date=March 8, 2019 |title=BoltBus links Everett to Seattle and other big I-5 cities |url=https://www.heraldnet.com/news/discount-bus-service-launches-from-everett-station/ |work=The Everett Herald |accessdate=March 29, 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe city-run [[Everett Transit]] system was established in 1969, replacing a private operator that had opened the first [[streetcar]] lines in the city in 1893.<ref>{{cite news |date=November 30, 2008 |title=Everett Transit rolls back fares for 115th birthday |url=https://www.heraldnet.com/news/around-the-county-346/ |work=The Everett Herald |accessdate=March 29, 2020}}</ref> The countywide [[Community Transit]] system, based in Everett, connects to surrounding cities and operates a commuter bus network.<ref>{{cite map |date=September 2019 |title=Community Transit System Map |url=https://www.communitytransit.org/docs/default-source/mappdfs/19septmaps/systemmappdfs/mapsystemsept2019.pdf |publisher=[[Community Transit]] |accessdate=March 29, 2020}}</ref> Its [[bus rapid transit]] system, [[Swift Bus Rapid Transit|Swift]] has two lines that travel through the city: the [[Swift Blue Line|Blue Line]] from Downtown Everett to [[Shoreline, Washington|Shoreline]] via State Route 99; and the [[Swift Green Line|Green Line]], which connects the Boeing plant to Mill Creek and northern Bothell.<ref>{{cite news |last=Giordano |first=Lizz |date=March 21, 2019 |title=From Bothell to Boeing: Green Line bus route begins Sunday |url=https://www.heraldnet.com/news/major-changes-coming-to-community-transit-in-march/ |work=The Everett Herald |accessdate=March 29, 2020}}</ref> Sound Transit also provides [[Sound Transit Express|express bus service]] to [[Bellevue, Washington|Bellevue]] during peak hours and Downtown Seattle at all hours.<ref>{{cite web |date=December 2017 |title=2017 Service Implementation Plan |pages=116\u2013117, 140\u2013141 |url=https://www.soundtransit.org/sites/default/files/2018-service-implementation-plan.pdf |publisher=[[Sound Transit]] |accessdate=March 29, 2020}}</ref> The agency plans to extend its [[Link light rail]] service to Downtown Everett in 2036, as part of the [[Sound Transit 3]] plan passed by voters in 2016.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Haglund |first1=Noah |last2=Giordano |first2=Lizz |date=June 25, 2018 |title=It's getting real: Light rail is coming to the 'burbs |url=https://www.heraldnet.com/news/its-getting-real-light-rail-is-coming-to-the-burbs/ |work=The Everett Herald |accessdate=March 29, 2020}}</ref> From 1910\u20131939, Everett was connected with Seattle by an [[interurban]] railway, which was later replaced by the [[Interurban Trail (Snohomish County)|Interurban Trail]].<ref>{{cite news |last=Giordano |first=Lizz |date=December 2, 2019 |title=The Interurban Railway: Everett's first rapid transit line |url=https://www.heraldnet.com/news/the-interurban-railway-everetts-first-rapid-transit-line/ |work=The Everett Herald |accessdate=March 29, 2020}}</ref>\n\nEverett's airport, [[Paine Field]], is operated by Snohomish County primarily for aerospace businesses and general aviation. The airport was opened in 1936 and was used as a military base and commercial airport until 1966, when Boeing selected it for the site of a major assembly plant.<ref>{{cite news |date=August 7, 2004 |title=Paine Field's journey to flight |url=https://www.heraldnet.com/news/paine-fields-journey-to-flight/ |work=The Everett Herald |accessdate=March 30, 2020}}</ref> Commercial passenger service to Paine Field resumed on March 4, 2019, after the construction of a new terminal operated by a private company.<ref name=\"Times-Paine\">{{cite news |last=Blethen |first=Ryan |date=March 5, 2019 |title=How the first day of commercial flights from Paine Field went |page=A1 |url=https://www.seattletimes.com/life/travel/first-commercial-flight-to-take-off-from-everetts-paine-field-today/ |work=The Seattle Times |accessdate=March 8, 2019}}</ref> The nearest major airports are [[Boeing Field]] in Seattle and [[Seattle-Tacoma International Airport]] in southern King County.<ref name=\"Times-Paine\"/> A private passenger ferry from the Port of Everett provides access to [[Gedney Island|Hat Island]] in Possession Sound.<ref>{{cite news |last=Muhlstein |first=Julie |date=July 31, 2018 |title=Hat Island: The somewhat secret, other-worldy Northwest gem |url=https://www.heraldnet.com/news/close-yet-another-world-its-quite-a-voyage-to-hat-island/ |work=The Everett Herald |accessdate=March 23, 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Utilities===\n\n[[Electric power]] for Everett buildings is provided by the [[Snohomish County Public Utility District]] (PUD), a consumer-owned [[public utility]] that serves all of Snohomish County.<ref>{{cite web |date=October 2018 |title=Quick Facts for Snohomish County PUD |url=https://www.snopud.com/Site/Content/Documents/custpubs/MiniQF_1018.pdf |publisher=[[Snohomish County Public Utility District]] |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20181129142056/https://www.snopud.com/Site/Content/Documents/custpubs/MiniQF_1018.pdf |archivedate=November 29, 2018 |accessdate=March 25, 2020}}</ref> The privately run [[Puget Sound Energy]] provides [[natural gas]] service to the city's residents and businesses.<ref>{{cite web |year=2013 |title=Puget Sound Energy service area |url=http://pse.com/aboutpse/PseNewsroom/MediaKit/1213_ServiceAreaMap_web.pdf |publisher=[[Puget Sound Energy]] |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170128213047/https://pse.com/aboutpse/PseNewsroom/MediaKit/1213_ServiceAreaMap_web.pdf |archivedate=January 28, 2017 |accessdate=March 25, 2020}}</ref> The city government contracts with Rubatino Refuse Removal and [[Waste Management (corporation)|Waste Management]] for curbside [[municipal solid waste|garbage]], [[single-stream recycling|recycling]], and [[yard waste]] collection and disposal.<ref>{{cite web |title=Garbage, Recycling & Compost |url=https://everettwa.gov/637/Garbage-Recycling-Compost |publisher=City of Everett |accessdate=March 25, 2020}}</ref> Everett's municipal [[wastewater]] and [[sewage]] system, which is combined with [[stormwater]] treatment, includes {{convert|145|mi|km}} and primarily empties into the [[Everett Water Pollution Control Facility]] on Smith Island in the Snohomish River delta.<ref>{{cite news |last=Winters |first=Chris |date=December 4, 2014 |title=$320M fix prescribed for Everett's aging sewers |url=https://www.heraldnet.com/news/320m-fix-prescribed-for-everett%C2%92s-aging-sewers/ |work=The Everett Herald |accessdate=March 27, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Sanders |first=Julia-Grace |date=September 12, 2019 |title=Stench wrinkles noses in some north Everett neighborhoods |url=https://www.heraldnet.com/news/odor-overwhelms-some-north-everett-neighborhoods/ |work=The Everett Herald |accessdate=March 27, 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe City of Everett maintains a [[tap water]] system that supplies 80 percent of Snohomish County through interlocal agreements with other municipalities and [[water district]]s.<ref>{{cite news |last=Sheets |first=Bill |date=October 13, 2011 |title=Environmental plan earns Sultan River dam a new 45-year license |url=https://www.heraldnet.com/news/environmental-plan-earns-sultan-river-dam-a-new-45-year-license/ |work=The Everett Herald |accessdate=March 27, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |date=November 2004 |title=Where Does Your Water Come From? |url=https://everettwa.gov/DocumentCenter/View/824/Where-Does-Your-Water-Come-From-PDF |publisher=City of Everett |accessdate=March 27, 2020}}</ref> The system primarily sources its water from [[Spada Lake]], an artificial reservoir on the [[Sultan River]] created by the [[Culmback Dam]] located {{convert|25|mi|km}} east of Everett in the Cascade Mountains. The water is treated at a [[water purification|filtration plant]] at Lake Chaplain, the system's secondary water source, which has a capacity of {{convert|134|e6USgal|kl}} per day and typically handles {{convert|50|e6gal|kl|abbr=unit}} per day.<ref>{{cite news |last=Winters |first=Chris |date=September 8, 2016 |title=Anticipating growth, Everett looks to boost water flow |url=https://www.heraldnet.com/news/everett-to-test-increasing-water-flow-to-customers/ |work=The Everett Herald |accessdate=March 27, 2020}}</ref> The Sultan River basin has been used as the main source of the city's water since 1917; the modern Spada Lake reservoir was formed in 1965 by the construction of the Culmback Dam, co-owned by Everett and the Snohomish County PUD.{{sfnp|O'Donnell|1993|p=187}}\n\nThe city is covered by several telecommunications companies that provide [[telephone]], [[broadband internet]], and other services. [[Frontier Communications Northwest|Frontier Communications]] is the largest telecommunications provider in the city and inherited its legacy system from [[GTE|GTE Northwest]] and [[Verizon]].<ref>{{cite news |last=Podsada |first=Janice |date=June 3, 2019 |title=A new-wave broadband firm dials up Frontier Communications |url=https://www.heraldnet.com/business/a-new-wave-broadband-firm-dials-up-frontier-communications/ |work=The Everett Herald |accessdate=March 27, 2020}}</ref> Other major providers in the Everett area include [[Xfinity|Comcast Xfinity]], [[CenturyLink]], and [[Wave Broadband]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Everett Comprehensive Plan Capital Facilities and Utilities Element |page=36 |url=https://everettwa.gov/DocumentCenter/View/4861/Chapter-06-Capital-Facilities-and-Utilities-PDF |publisher=City of Everett |accessdate=March 27, 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Healthcare===\n\nEverett is home to [[Providence Regional Medical Center Everett]], a system of two general hospitals operated by [[Providence Health & Services]]. The hospital system was formed in 1994 by the merger of two existing hospitals in Everett: the Everett General Hospital, opened in January 1894 as the city's first hospital;{{sfnp|O'Donnell|1993|p=211}} and Providence Hospital, established in 1905 near Downtown Everett.<ref>{{cite web |title=The Providence Story |url=https://washington.providence.org/locations-directory/r/regional-medical-center/about/history |publisher=[[Providence Health & Services]] |accessdate=March 25, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Muhlstein |first=Julie |date=August 27, 2014 |title=Spirit of giving is a cornerstone of Snohomish County history |url=https://www.heraldnet.com/news/spirit-of-giving-is-a-cornerstone-of-snohomish-county-history/ |work=The Everett Herald |accessdate=March 25, 2020}}</ref> The existing Providence Hospital was renamed the Providence Pacific Campus, while the former General Hospital became the Colby Campus, which was expanded in 2011 with a 12-story medical tower.<ref name=\"Herald-Providence11\">{{cite news |last=Salyer |first=Sharon |date=May 15, 2011 |title=A $460 million gamble |url=https://www.heraldnet.com/news/a-460-million-gamble/ |work=The Everett Herald |accessdate=March 25, 2020}}</ref> The Providence campuses have a combined capacity of 571 beds and 3,300 employees.<ref name=\"Herald-Providence11\"/><ref>{{cite news |last=Salyer |first=Sharon |date=January 16, 2017 |title=Everett Providence hospital seeks state OK for 70 more beds |url=https://www.heraldnet.com/news/everett-providence-hospital-seeks-state-ok-for-70-more-beds/ |work=The Everett Herald |accessdate=March 25, 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe city also has several medical services with [[clinic]]s and specialized facilities operated by Providence and other providers. [[Kaiser Permanente]] has a five-story medical tower in Downtown Everett with a walk-in clinic, specialty services, and an [[urgent care]] clinic.<ref>{{cite web |title=Everett Medical Center |url=https://wa.kaiserpermanente.org/html/public/locations/everett |publisher=[[Kaiser Permanente]] |accessdate=March 25, 2020}}</ref> The building originally opened for [[Group Health Cooperative|Group Health]] in 1994 to consolidate its three clinics in Everett and is planned to be expanded in 2020.<ref>{{cite news |last=Alexander |first=Karen |date=April 30, 1993 |title=Group Health sets Everett groundbreaker |page=D8 |work=The Seattle Times}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Giordano |first=Lizz |date=October 2, 2019 |title=Kaiser Permanente plans big growth spurt in Everett |url=https://www.heraldnet.com/news/kaiser-permanente-plans-big-growth-spurt-in-everett/ |work=The Everett Herald |accessdate=March 25, 2020}}</ref> [[The Everett Clinic]] is based in the city and operates medical facilities across Snohomish County, serving 320,000 patients.<ref>{{cite news |last=Salyer |first=Sharon |date=February 29, 2016 |title=DaVita HealthCare Partners completes Everett Clinic purchase |url=https://www.heraldnet.com/news/davita-healthcare-partners-completes-everett-clinic-purchase/ |work=The Everett Herald |accessdate=March 25, 2020}}</ref> The system was founded in 1924 and acquired in 2016 by [[DaVita Inc.]]; it was then sold to [[UnitedHealth Group]]'s [[Optum]] a year later.<ref>{{cite news |last=Davis |first=Jim |date=December 6, 2017 |title=DaVita to sell off medical groups including The Everett Clinic |url=https://www.heraldnet.com/business/davita-to-sell-off-medical-groups-including-the-everett-clinic/ |work=The Everett Herald |accessdate=March 25, 2020}}</ref> The non-profit Community Health Center of Snohomish County operates four medical clinics in Everett, providing services to primarily low-income and uninsured patients.<ref>{{cite news |last=Salyer |first=Sharon |date=January 16, 2018 |title=New Everett clinic to ease long wait times for appointments |url=https://www.heraldnet.com/news/community-health-center-opening-its-seventh-clinic/ |work=The Everett Herald |accessdate=March 25, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Notable people==\n{{main|List of people from Everett, Washington}}\n\n==Sister cities==\n\nEverett has the following [[Town twinning|sister city]] relationships:<ref>{{cite web |title=Washington's Sister Cities Relationships |url=https://www.ltgov.wa.gov/washington-sister-cities |publisher=[[Lieutenant Governor of Washington]] |accessdate=March 21, 2020}}</ref>\n\n* {{flagdeco|JPN}} [[Iwakuni]], [[Yamaguchi Prefecture|Yamaguchi]], Japan (since 1962)<ref>{{cite news |last=Fiege |first=Gale |date=July 23, 2012 |title=Everett celebrates 50 years with Japanese sister city |url=https://www.heraldnet.com/news/everett-celebrates-50-years-with-japanese-sister-city/ |work=The Everett Herald |accessdate=March 21, 2020}}</ref>\n* {{flagdeco|IRL}} [[Sligo]], [[County Sligo]], Ireland\n* {{flagdeco|RUS}} [[Sovetskaya Gavan]], [[Khabarovsk Krai]], Russia\n\n==Gallery==\n<gallery>\nFile:Everett - County Campus.jpg|Snohomish County Government Campus\nFile:Everett Events Center.jpg|Everett Events Centre (now Angel of the Winds Arena)\nFile:Everett - Hewitt Ave.jpg|Downtown\nFile:Everett Theater 01.jpg| Historic Everett Theatre\nFile:Everett Library 01.jpg| Everett Public Library\nFile:Everett Library 02.jpg| Everett Public Library\nFile:Everett - Bethel Baptist.jpg| Bethel Baptist Church\nFile:Everett - Trinity Episcopal.jpg|Trinity Episcopal Church (1920)\nFile:Everett - First Presbyterian.jpg|First Presbyterian Church\nFile:Everett - FPC Stained Glass.jpg|First Presbyterian Church\nFile:Everett - Public Art.JPG|Public Art\nFile:Everett - Old Courthouse.jpg|Old County Courthouse\nFile:Everett - War Memorial.jpg|War Memorial\nFile:Everett - Armed Forces.jpg|Armed Forces Memorial\nFile:Everett - Colby Ave.jpg|Downtown\nFile:Everett - Kimberly Clark.jpg|Kimberly-Clark Paper Plant\nFile:Naval Station Everett.jpg|Naval Station Everett\nFile:Everett Marina.jpg|Everett Marina\n</gallery>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==Bibliography==\n{{refbegin}}\n* {{cite book |ref=harv |last1=Cameron |first1=David A. |last2=LeWarne |first2=Charles P. |last3=May |first3=M. Allan |last4=O'Donnell |first4=Jack C. |last5=O'Donnell |first5=Lawrence E. |year=2005 |title=Snohomish County: An Illustrated History |publisher=Kelcema Books LLC |location=Index, Washington |isbn=978-0-9766700-0-1 |oclc=62728798}}\n* {{cite book |ref=harv |last=Clark |first=Norman H. |year=1970 |title=Mill Town: A Social History of Everett, Washington, From Its Earliest Beginnings on the Shores of Puget Sound to the Tragic and Infamous Event Known as the Everett Massacre |publisher=[[University of Washington Press]] |isbn=978-0-295-95241-3 |oclc=28005191}}\n* {{cite book |ref=harv |last=O'Donnell |first=Lawrence E. |year=1993 |title=Everett Past and Present: A Centennial History of Everett |page=253 |publisher=K&H Printers |isbn=978-0-89716-275-3 |oclc=436832753}}\n{{refend}}\n\n==Archives==\n{{refbegin}}\n* [http://digital.lib.washington.edu/findingaids/view?docId=EverettEducationAssociation3849.xml Everett Education Association Records.] 1937\u20132002. 28.06 cubic feet. At the [http://www.lib.washington.edu/specialcoll/laws Labor Archives of Washington, University of Washington Libraries Special Collections.]\n{{refend}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category}}\n{{EB1911 Poster|Everett, Washington}}\n* {{wikivoyage-inline|Everett (Washington)|Everett, Washington}}\n* {{official website|https://www.everettwa.gov/}}\n* {{dmoz|Regional/North_America/United_States/Washington/Localities/E/Everett}}\n\n{{Everett, Washington}}\n{{Snohomish County, Washington}}\n{{Washington}}\n{{Seattle Metro}}\n{{Geographic Location (8-way)\n|Northwest = [[Port Gardner Bay]]\n|North     = [[Tulalip Indian Reservation]]/[[Marysville, Washington|Marysville]]\n|Northeast = [[Marysville, Washington|Marysville]]/[[Lake Stevens, Washington|Lake Stevens]]\n|West      = [[Gedney Island (Washington)|Hat Island]]/[[Possession Sound]]\n|Center    = Everett\n|South     = [[Mill Creek, Washington|Mill Creek]]/[[Lynnwood, Washington|Lynnwood]]\n|Southwest = [[Mukilteo, Washington|Mukilteo]]\n|Southeast = [[Snohomish, Washington|Snohomish]]\n|East      = [[Lake Stevens, Washington|Lake Stevens]]\n}}\n{{Washington cities and mayors of 100,000 population}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Everett, Washington]]\n[[Category:Cities in Washington (state)]]\n[[Category:Cities in Snohomish County, Washington]]\n[[Category:County seats in Washington (state)]]\n[[Category:Industrial Workers of the World]]\n[[Category:Populated places established in 1890]]\n[[Category:Populated places on Puget Sound]]\n[[Category:Port settlements in Washington (state)]]\n[[Category:1890 establishments in Washington (state)]]\n[[Category:Cities in the Seattle metropolitan area]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use mdy dates|date=February 2019}}\n{{pp-move-indef}}\n{{Infobox settlement\n|name                     = Everett\n|official_name            = City of Everett\n|other_name = [[Lushootseed]]: ''{{lang|lut|d\u1dbb\u0259\u026cig\u02b7\u0259d}}''<ref name=\"BatesHess1994\">{{cite book |author1=Dawn Bates |author2=Thom Hess |author3=Hilbert, Vi |title=d\u1dbb\u0259\u026big\u02b7\u0259d |page=90 |work=Lushootseed Dictionary |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=ekq921r1kV0C |year=1994 |publisher=University of Washington Press |isbn=0-295-97323-4}}</ref>\n|settlement_type          = [[City]]\n|image_skyline            = Everett Station - Everett skyline, 2014.jpg\n|image_seal               = Everett logo.svg\n|image_map                = Snohomish_County_Washington_Incorporated_and_Unincorporated_areas_Everett_Highlighted.svg\n|mapsize                  = 250px\n|map_caption              = Location of Everett, Washington\n|pushpin_map              = USA\n|pushpin_map_caption      = Location in the United States\n|subdivision_type         = Country\n|subdivision_type1        = [[U.S. state|State]]\n|subdivision_type2        = [[List of counties in Washington|County]]\n|subdivision_name         = [[United States]]\n|subdivision_name1        = [[Washington (state)|Washington]]\n|subdivision_name2        = [[Snohomish County, Washington|Snohomish]]\n|established_title        = Established\n|established_date         = 1890\n|established_title2       = [[Municipal corporation|Incorporated]]\n|established_date2        = May 4, 1893\n|government_type          = [[Mayor\u2013council government|Mayor\u2013council]]\n|leader_title             = [[Mayor]]\n|leader_name              = Cassie Franklin\n|unit_pref                = Imperial\n|area_footnotes           = <ref name=\"CenPopGazetteer2016\">{{cite web |title=2018 U.S. Gazetteer Files |url=https://www2.census.gov/geo/docs/maps-data/data/gazetteer/2018_Gazetteer/2018_gaz_place_53.txt |publisher=United States Census Bureau |accessdate=February 16, 2020}}</ref>\n|area_magnitude           = \n|area_total_sq_mi         = 47.91\n|area_land_sq_mi          = 33.20\n|area_water_sq_mi         = 14.71\n|population_as_of         = [[2010 United States Census|2010]]\n|population_est           = 111262\n|pop_est_as_of            = 2018\n|pop_est_footnotes        = <ref name=\"USCensusEst2018CenPopScriptOnlyDirtyFixDoNotUse\"/>\n|population_footnotes     = <ref name=\"FactFinder\"/>\n|population_total         = 103019\n|population_density_sq_mi = 3351.47\n|population_metro         = 3,939,363 (US: [[List of Metropolitan Statistical Areas|15th]])\n|population_rank          = US: [[List of United States cities by population|270th]]<br />WA: 7th\n|population_demonym       = Everettite\n|timezone                 = [[Pacific Time Zone|PST]]\n|utc_offset               = &minus;8\n|timezone_DST             = [[Pacific Daylight Time|PDT]]\n|utc_offset_DST           = &minus;7\n|coordinates              = {{coord|47|57|48|N|122|12|2|W|region:US-WA_type:city|display=inline,title}}\n|postal_code_type         = Zip codes\n|postal_code = 98201, 98203, 98204, 98206, 98207, 98208, 98213<ref>{{cite web |url=http://zip4.usps.com/zip4/citytown.jsp |title=ZIP code lookup |publisher=[[United States Postal Service]] |accessdate=December 23, 2008 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20101104123722/http://zip4.usps.com/zip4/citytown.jsp |archivedate=November 4, 2010 }}</ref>\n|area_code                = [[Area code 425|425]]\n|blank_name               = [[Federal Information Processing Standard|FIPS code]]\n|blank_info               = 53-22640\n|blank1_name              = [[Geographic Names Information System|GNIS]] feature ID\n|blank1_info              = 1512198<ref name=\"GR3\">{{cite web |url=http://geonames.usgs.gov |accessdate=January 31, 2008 |title=US Board on Geographic Names |publisher=[[United States Geological Survey]] |date=October 25, 2007}}</ref>\n|website                  = {{URL|everettwa.gov}}\n|footnotes                = \n|area_total_km2           = 124.09\n|area_land_km2            = 85.98\n|area_water_km2           = 38.11\n|population_density_km2   = 1294.01\n}}\n\n'''Everett''' is the [[county seat]] of and the largest city in [[Snohomish County, Washington|Snohomish County]], Washington, United States. It is located {{convert|25|mi|km|0}} north of [[Seattle]] and is one of the main cities in the [[Seattle metropolitan area|metropolitan area]] and [[Puget Sound region]]. Everett is the [[List of cities and towns in Washington|seventh-largest]] city in Washington state and had a total population of 103,019 at the [[2010 United States Census|2010 census]]. The city is located at the mouth of the [[Snohomish River]] along [[Port Gardner Bay]], an inlet of [[Possession Sound]] (itself part of [[Puget Sound]]).\n\nAmerican settlement on the Everett peninsula began in the 1860s, with several [[sawmill]]s built to serve the area's growing timber industry. Everett was [[plat]]ted by a group of investors seeking to build an industrial city and named for the son of co-founder Charles L. Colby. The city was [[municipal incorporation|incorporated]] in 1893, shortly after the arrival of the [[Great Northern Railway (U.S.)|Great Northern Railway]], and prospered as a major industrial center. Everett's economy transitioned away from lumber and towards aviation after [[World War II]], with the construction of [[Boeing]]'s [[Boeing Everett Factory|aircraft assembly plant]] at [[Paine Field]] in 1967. Boeing remains the city's largest employer, alongside the [[U.S. Navy]], which has operated [[Naval Station Everett]] since 1992. Everett received an [[All-America City Award]] in 2002.\n\nEverett remains a major employment center for Snohomish County, but has also become a [[bedroom community]] for Seattle in recent decades. It is connected to Seattle by [[Interstate 5 in Washington|Interstate 5]] and various public transit services at [[Everett Station]], including the [[Sounder commuter rail|Sounder commuter train]], [[Amtrak]], and commuter buses.\n\n==History==\n[[File:everettwaterfront.jpg|thumb| [[Weyerhaeuser]] Lumber Mill, Everett Waterfront, c. early 1900s]]\n\nThe [[Port Gardner]] peninsula was originally inhabited by local [[Coast Salish]] tribes who arrived in the region 10,000 years [[before present]] and settled near modern-day Everett approximately 2,000 years [[before present]].{{sfnp|O'Donnell|1993|p=2}} The [[Snohomish people]] lived around local waterways in the [[Possession Sound]] estuary and had a fortified winter village at Hibulb (also called Hebolb) at the mouth of the [[Snohomish River]].{{sfnp|O'Donnell|1993|p=2}}<ref>{{cite news |last=Whitely |first=Peyton |date=March 16, 2005 |title=Aerial photos show 2 very different cities |page=H8 |url=https://www.seattletimes.com/seattle-news/aerial-photos-show-2-very-different-cities/ |work=[[The Seattle Times]] |accessdate=June 30, 2018}}</ref> The first Europeans in the area were explorers from the 1792 [[Vancouver Expedition]], landing on a beach on the modern Everett waterfront on June 4 and claiming the land for [[England]] on the birthday of King [[George III of the United Kingdom|George III]].<ref>{{cite book |author=[[Federal Writers' Project]] |year=1941 |title=The WPA Guide to Washington: The Evergreen State |pages=186\u2013200 |series=[[American Guide Series]] |publisher=[[Works Progress Administration]] |oclc=881468746 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=07PpCAAAQBAJ |via=Google Books |accessdate=June 30, 2018}}</ref> [[Puget Sound]] was further explored and charted ny the [[Hudson's Bay Company]] in 1824 and the [[United States Exploring Expedition]] under [[Charles Wilkes]] in 1841, ahead of a larger American presence in the area.{{sfnp|O'Donnell|1993|p=4}}<ref name=\"HistoryLink\">{{cite web |last=Oakley |first=Janet |date=July 26, 2005 |title=Everett \u2014 Thumbnail History |url=https://www.historylink.org/file/7397 |work=[[HistoryLink]] |accessdate=June 30, 2018}}</ref>\n\nThe Snohomish and other Coast Salish tribes signed the [[Treaty of Point Elliott]] in 1855, which relinquished their lands to the [[Washington Territory|territorial government]] and established the nearby [[Tulalip Indian Reservation]], where they would be relocated.<ref name=\"Herald-125th\">{{cite news |last=Muhlstein |first=Julie |date=May 9, 2018 |title=City of Everett to celebrate 125th birthday with big party |url=https://www.heraldnet.com/news/city-of-everett-celebrates-125-years-and-counting/ |work=[[The Everett Herald]] |accessdate=June 30, 2018}}</ref> The first permanent American settler to arrive on the peninsula was Dennis Brigham, a carpenter from [[Worcester, Massachusetts]], who claimed a {{convert|160|acre|km2|1|adj=on}} [[Homestead Acts|homestead]] and built a cabin for himself. He was joined by several other families on their own homesteads, which included the establishment of a general store and a [[sawmill]] that quickly went out of business.<ref name=\"HistoryLink\"/> Over the next several years a handful of loggers moved to the area, but plans for a settlement were not conceived until 1890.{{sfnp|O'Donnell|1993|p=7}}\n\nDuring an Alaskan cruise via the [[Inside Passage]] aboard the steamship ''[[Queen of the Pacific]]'' in July 1890, plans were drawn up for an industrial city on Port Gardner Bay by lumberman [[Henry Hewitt Jr.]] and railroad executive [[Charles L. Colby]]. Hewitt and Colby had previously met in [[Wisconsin]], where they operated lumber and maritime businesses, respectively, and in [[Tacoma, Washington]], from which the voyage began. The pair sought to build an industrial center at a site they speculated would be the first ocean port for [[Great Northern Railway (U.S.)|Great Northern Railway]], to be constructed by [[James J. Hill]], and turn it into a \"[[Pittsburgh]] of the West\".{{sfnp|O'Donnell|1993|p=12}}<ref name=\"Times-HewittColby93\">{{cite news |last=Dilgard |first=David |date=April 22, 1993 |title=Odd couple of Hewitt and Colby hatched ambitious plan for Everett |page=F5 |url=https://archive.seattletimes.com/archive/?date=19930422&slug=1697251 |work=The Seattle Times |accessdate=April 3, 2020}}</ref> On August 22, 1890, the [[plat]] for a {{convert|50|acre|m2|adj=on}} townsite on the peninsula was filed by the [[Rucker Brothers]], who had moved north from Tacoma and had more modest plans for the area.{{sfnp|O'Donnell|1993|p=12}}\n\nBy September, Colby had secured $800,000 in funding from oil magnate [[John D. Rockefeller]] and his railroad associate [[Colgate Hoyt]] to begin acquiring land while avoiding property speculators.{{sfnp|O'Donnell|1993|p=12}} The Hewitt\u2013Colby syndicate decided to use a name without an identifiable location, naming their planned city after [[Everett Colby]], the fifteen-year-old son of investor Charles L. Colby, who had displayed a \"prodigious appetite\" at a group dinner.<ref name=\"Times-HewittColby93\"/> The Everett Land Company was incorporated in [[Pierce County, Washington|Pierce County]] on November 19, 1890, and acquired {{convert|434.15|acre|sqkm}} of property from the Rucker Brothers a week later.{{sfnp|O'Donnell|1993|p=15}} The Rucker plat was withdrawn after an agreement was reached with Hewitt promising certain industrial developments under the \"Remarkable Document\", which was also used to acquire property from other landowners in the area.{{sfnp|Cameron|LeWarne|May|O'Donnell|2005|p=103}}\n\nThe Company bought much of the Ruckers' land, taking them in as junior partners. Everett was officially incorporated on May 4, 1893, the year the [[Great Northern Railway (U.S.)|Great Northern Railway]] came to the town. Both Hewitt and the Ruckers had speculated that [[James J. Hill]] would make the town the terminus of his railroad. However Hill continued the railroad along the shore of [[Puget Sound]] to [[Seattle]]. Although it succeeded in building the city, the Everett Land Company was a failure for its investors. The outside investors withdrew, and the Company's holdings were transferred to a new company controlled by Hill. The Ruckers, who helped broker the deal, stayed in Everett and became leading citizens of the young city.\n\nRailroads and mines played a part in Everett's future. The mining community of [[Monte Cristo, Washington|Monte Cristo]] depended on a railway for supplies. It was hoped that the railroad would cross the mountains and bring in traffic. For a while ore was smelted in Everett, then sawmilling and port activity commenced. A dozen steam riverboats were built in Everett for the [[Klondike Gold Rush|Yukon gold rush]].\n\nSeveral survivors of the [[Bellingham riots]] settled in Everett for two months, until they were beaten and forcefully evicted by a mob on November 5, 1907. Everett also was the site of the [[Everett Massacre]] of 1916 in which a posse led by local Sheriff Donald McRae shot and killed five [[Industrial Workers of the World]] members. The IWW members on the [[Verona (steamship)|steamer ''Verona'']] travelled from Seattle to support strikers in Everett and sought to land, but McRae and his posse of deputized civilians blocked the harbor. Shooting broke out and at least five IWW members were killed, along with two in the posse who were deemed to have been killed by friendly fire.\n\nEverett streets are named after each of the three founders. Adjacent streets Colby Avenue and Hoyt Avenue run north and south and are intersected by Hewitt Avenue running east and west just south of the [[BNSF Railway]] tracks cutting across Everett. There are several other streets named for their associates such as Bond Street named for Judge [[Hiram Bond]], President of the Everett & Monte Cristo Railroad. Parallel to Colby and Hoyt are avenues named for other investors, [[John D. Rockefeller]], railroad executive [[Thomas Fletcher Oakes|T.F. Oakes]], shipbuilder [[Alexander McDougall (1845-1923)|Alexander McDougall]], and McDougall's associate [[Charles W. Wetmore]].\n\nDuring the [[Great Depression]], the [[Works Progress Administration]] was tasked with construction of several public works projects in the Everett area, including a new county airport that later became [[Paine Field]]. The airport was appropriated for military use during [[World War II]], but was later turned over to county ownership.<ref name=\"HistoryLink\"/> The [[Boeing Company]] selected a {{convert|780|acre|ha|adj=mid}} plot of land north of the airport in June 1966 to build a [[Boeing Everett Factory|new airplane factory]] for its [[Boeing 747]] passenger jetliner, which would become the world's first \"jumbo jet\". The first 747, named the \"City of Everett\", was unveiled in September 1968 and made its maiden flight on February 9, 1969.<ref name=\"Herald-Boeing50\">{{cite news |last=Catchpole |first=Dan |date=May 22, 2017 |title=50 history-making years of building Boeing jets in Everett |url=https://www.heraldnet.com/business/boeing-has-built-planes-in-everett-for-50-history-making-years/ |work=The Everett Herald |accessdate=February 18, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Podsada |first=Janice |date=September 30, 2018 |title=50 years ago, they rolled it out: the first Boeing 747 |url=https://www.heraldnet.com/business/50-years-ago-they-rolled-it-out-the-first-boeing-747/ |work=The Everett Herald |accessdate=February 18, 2019}}</ref> The Everett factory was expanded several times to accommodate later Boeing programs, including the [[Boeing 767|767]], [[Boeing 777|777]], and [[Boeing 787|787 Dreamliner]].<ref name=\"Herald-Boeing50\"/>\n\nEverett was selected by the [[U.S. Navy]] in 1984 as the site of a new military base under the [[Strategic Homeport]] program.<ref>{{cite news |last=Cowley |first=Geoffrey |date=November 7, 1984 |title=Everett says 'yes' to Navy by a margin of more than 2-to-1 |page=B10 |work=The Seattle Times}}</ref> [[Naval Station Everett]] was constructed between 1987 and 1994 on a site near the [[Port of Everett]] on Port Gardner Bay,<ref>{{cite news |last=Brooks |first=Diane |date=June 5, 1992 |title=The Navy's in port: three ships greeted at Everett's new base |page=E1 |work=The Seattle Times}}</ref> with auxiliary facilities in [[Smokey Point, Washington|Smokey Point]].<ref>{{cite news |last=Hendricks |first=Tyche |date=June 5, 1995 |title=Eagerly awaiting stores' opening\u2014Navy exchange, commissary ready |page=B1 |url=http://community.seattletimes.nwsource.com/archive/?date=19950605&slug=2124724 |work=The Seattle Times |accessdate=February 18, 2019}}</ref> The first ships arrived in September 1994, and Naval Station Everett was the long-term home of several [[aircraft carrier]]s, including the {{USS|Abraham Lincoln|CVN-72|6}}.<ref>{{cite news |last=Clutter |first=Stephen |date=January 9, 1997 |title=Bringing home the future: The Lincoln, with crew of 3,200 is first carrier permanently assigned to Everett |page=B1 |work=The Seattle Times}}</ref> The city underwent an urban revival in the 1990s, with new construction in many neighborhoods and improved city facilities.<ref>{{cite news |last=Carter |first=Don |date=July 12, 1997 |title=New life breathes in old mill town |page=D1 |work=Seattle Post-Intelligencer}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=King |first=Harriet |date=May 13, 1990 |title=Focus: The I-5 Corridor; A Lively New Washington Growth Area |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1990/05/13/realestate/focus-the-i-5-corridor-a-lively-new-washington-growth-area.html |work=The New York Times |accessdate=March 29, 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe first [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in the United States|U.S. case]] of [[coronavirus disease 2019]] was identified at Providence Regional Medical Center in Everett on January 20, 2020.<ref>{{cite news |last=Blethen |first=Ryan |date=February 14, 2020 |title=What it was like for doctors and nurses at an Everett hospital to treat the nation's first novel coronavirus patient |page=A1 |url=https://www.seattletimes.com/seattle-news/health/what-it-was-like-for-doctors-and-nurses-at-an-everett-hospital-to-treat-the-nations-first-novel-coronavirus-patient/ |work=The Seattle Times |accessdate=March 21, 2020}}</ref> As the coronavirus pandemic worsened in the state, mayor Cassie Franklin declared the first shelter-in-place order for Washington state on March 21, 2020.<ref>{{cite news |last=Gutman |first=David |date=March 21, 2020 |title=Everett orders residents to stay home to slow coronavirus, others call on Inslee to follow suit |page=A1 |url=https://www.seattletimes.com/seattle-news/health/everett-orders-residents-to-stay-home-to-slow-coronavirus-others-call-on-inslee-to-follow-suit/ |accessdate=March 21, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Geography==\n\nEverett is one of the core cities comprising the [[Seattle metropolitan area]] and is located {{convert|25|mi|km}} north of [[Seattle]].<ref>{{cite news |last=Johnson |first=Kirk |date=December 10, 2013 |title=Boeing Looks Around, and a State Worries |page=A16 |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2013/12/11/us/washington-state-not-ready-to-ponder-future-without-boeing.html |work=[[The New York Times]] |accessdate=February 18, 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"GR1\">{{cite web |url=https://www.census.gov/geo/www/gazetteer/gazette.html |publisher=[[United States Census Bureau]] |accessdate=April 23, 2011 |date=February 12, 2011 |title=US Gazetteer files: 2010, 2000, and 1990}}</ref> It is located primarily on Port Gardner Peninsula, bordered to the west by [[Port Gardner Bay]] (part of the [[Puget Sound]] estuary), and to the north and east by the [[Snohomish River]] delta. The city also encompasses areas to the south and southwest of the peninsula, which were annexed during the 20th century. [[Mukilteo, Washington|Mukilteo]] is located west of the city, while [[Lynnwood, Washington|Lynnwood]] and [[Mill Creek, Washington|Mill Creek]] sit further south.<ref name=\"HistoryLink\"/> Everett is connected to the north towards [[Marysville, Washington|Marysville]] and east towards [[Lake Stevens, Washington|Lake Stevens]] by a series of highway and railway bridges that cross the Snohomish River delta.{{cn|date=March 2020}} The city also owns {{convert|3,729|acre|ha}} around [[Lake Chaplain]], a reservoir in the Cascade Mountains that provides part of the municipal water supply.<ref>{{cite news |last=Winters |first=Chris |date=May 10, 2015 |title=Trade-off would allow timber harvest at Lake Chaplain |url=https://www.heraldnet.com/news/trade-off-would-allow-timber-harvest-at-lake-chaplain/ |work=The Everett Herald |accessdate=March 21, 2020}}</ref>\n\nAccording to the [[United States Census Bureau]], the city has a total area of {{convert|48.49|sqmi|sqkm|2}}, of which, {{convert|33.45|sqmi|sqkm|2}} is land and {{convert|15.04|sqmi|sqkm|2}} is water.<ref name=\"Gazetteer files\">{{cite web |title=US Gazetteer files 2010 |url=https://www.census.gov/geo/www/gazetteer/files/Gaz_places_national.txt |publisher=[[United States Census Bureau]] |accessdate=December 19, 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120112090031/http://www.census.gov/geo/www/gazetteer/files/Gaz_places_national.txt |archivedate=January 12, 2012 }}</ref> The city has {{convert|11|mi|km}} of freshwater shoreline and {{convert|11|mi|km}} of saltwater shoreline.<ref name=\"CAFR2018\"/>{{rp|2}}\n\nThe Port Gardner Peninsula was formed during the northward retreat of [[Vashon Glaciation]] during an [[ice age]] 14,000 years before present.{{sfnp|O'Donnell|1993|p=2}}\n\n===Cityscape and neighborhoods===\n\nThe city of Everett maintains an Office of Neighborhoods which facilitate communication between the city and 19 recognized neighborhood associations. The neighborhood associations are independent from the city and have elected leaders who communicate with the city government.<ref>{{cite web |title=Neighborhood Associations |url=https://everettwa.gov/334/Neighborhood-Associations |publisher=City of Everett |accessdate=March 27, 2020}}</ref> The neighborhood associations are:<ref>{{cite map |date=April 2019 |title=Everett Neighborhoods |url=https://everettwa.gov/DocumentCenter/View/17789/4-16-19-Everett-Neighborhoods-Map-11x17 |publisher=City of Everett |accessdate=March 27, 2020}}</ref>\n\n* Bayside \u2013 comprising much of the central business district, the waterfront, and the surrounding residential areas.\n* Boulevard Bluffs \u2013 primarily residential area of the city bordering [[Mukilteo]].\n* Cascade View \u2013 residential area in South Everett, north of Everett Mall\n* Delta \u2013 primarily residential area north of downtown Everett\n* Evergreen \u2013 primarily residential area in South Everett.\n* Glacier View \u2013 older residential area south of downtown.\n* Harborview-Seahurst-Glenhaven \u2013 older residential areas south of downtown.\n* Holly \u2013 a mix of residential, commercial, and industrial areas on the southern edge of the city.\n* Lowell \u2013 formerly an independent town, Lowell is a primarily residential area southeast of downtown.\n* Northwest \u2013 older residential areas northwest of downtown.\n* Pinehurst-Beverly Park \u2013 mix of residential and commercial developments in South Everett.\n* Port Gardner \u2013 residential neighborhoods south of downtown.\n* Riverside \u2013 areas just northeast of downtown.\n* Silver Lake \u2013 residential and commercial areas surrounding Silver Lake in the extreme southeastern part of the city.\n* South Forest Park \u2013 residential neighborhood near downtown.\n* Twin Creeks \u2013 the area surrounding Everett Mall, a mix of residential and commercial areas.<ref>{{cite news |last=Muhlstein |first=Julie |date=August 28, 2012 |title=Everett's Twin Creeks neighborhood gets its renaissance |url=https://www.heraldnet.com/news/everetts-twin-creeks-neighborhood-gets-its-renaissance/ |work=The Everett Herald |accessdate=March 10, 2019}}</ref>\n* Valley View-Sylvan Crest-Larimer Ridge \u2013 residential areas in southeast Everett.\n* View Ridge-Madison \u2013 residential areas west and southwest of Forest Park.\n* Westmont \u2013 primarily multi-family housing in the southwestern part of the city.\n\n====Downtown====\n[[File:Everett Mutual Tower (18345199053).jpg|thumb|[[Everett Mutual Tower|Key Bank Tower]], the tallest building in Everett, Washington]]\n\nDowntown Everett is generally defined by the area north of Pacific Avenue, east of West Marine View Drive, south of Everett Avenue, and west of Broadway.<ref>{{cite web |date=July 2006 |title=Everett  Downtown Plan |url=https://everettwa.gov/DocumentCenter/Home/View/784 |publisher=City of Everett |accessdate=February 2, 2017}}</ref>{{rp|4}} Downtown is home to the government campuses of Snohomish County and the City of Everett, multiple high-rise office and residential buildings, as well as the [[Xfinity Arena|Angel of the Winds Arena]], [[Everett Public Library]] and other city amenities.\n\nThe tallest building in Everett, [[Everett Mutual Tower|Key Bank Tower]], is located in Downtown.\n\nSeveral downtown streets are named for the founders of the Everett Land Company and their associates.<ref>{{cite news |last=Rathbun |first=Andy |date=September 7, 2012 |title=We have mnemonic winner for Everett's streets |url=https://www.heraldnet.com/life/we-have-mnemonic-winner-for-everetts-streets/ |work=The Everett Herald |accessdate=April 3, 2020}}</ref>\n\n====Waterfront====\n[[File:Port Gardner Wharf.jpg|thumb|View from Everett Yacht Club on Port Gardner Wharf]]\nSituated at the mouth of the [[Snohomish River]] on [[Possession Sound]], the Everett waterfront is home to [[Naval Station Everett]] and the Port of Everett (est. 1918).  The Port of Everett includes both a deep-water commercial seaport and a marina with over 2,000 slips, which it claims to be the largest on the west coast of the United States.<ref>[http://www.portofeverett.com/home/index.asp?page=4 Port of Everett - Marina<!-- Bot generated title -->] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070629215830/http://www.portofeverett.com/home/index.asp?page=4 |date=June 29, 2007 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |date=July 3, 2018 |title=Everett's economic anchor: Big ships, big marina, big impact |url=https://www.heraldnet.com/business/everetts-economic-anchor-big-ships-big-marina-big-impact/ |work=The Everett Herald |accessdate=March 27, 2020}}</ref> Ambitious redevelopment began in 2006 to convert the north end of the waterfront into a community of maritime businesses, retail shops and condominiums, beginning with the Port of Everett's Port Gardner Wharf.  In 2006, the seaport received 119 ships and 59 barges, totaling some 192,000 short tons of cargo.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.portofeverett.com/home/index.asp?page=167 |title=Port of Everett - Cargo Statistics<!-- Bot generated title --> |accessdate=February 19, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070927235529/http://www.portofeverett.com/home/index.asp?page=167 |archive-date=September 27, 2007 |url-status=dead |df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n\nThe waterfront is also home to the Everett Yacht Club, which was founded in 1907, although it existed in some form as early as 1895.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.everettyachtclub.com/New_History_Page.html |title=Home \u2013 Everett Yacht Club |publisher= |access-date=July 14, 2007 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070630003547/http://www.everettyachtclub.com/New_History_Page.html |archive-date=June 30, 2007 |url-status=dead }}</ref>  During summer months, the marina is home to the Everett Farmer's Market (Sundays) and the Waterfront Concert Series (Thursday nights), part of a citywide free concert series which, in 2006, attracted over 26,000 visitors.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.everettwa.org/default.aspx?ID=1152 |title=Sunday Afternoon Waterfront Series in Everett<!-- Bot generated title --> |publisher= |accessdate=February 19, 2018}}</ref>  Each September, Tenth Street Park on the waterfront is home to the annual Everett Coho Derby,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.everettcohoderby.com/ |title=Home |first= |last=Administrator |publisher=}}</ref> while each August the marina promenade is gowned in local art during the Fresh Paint Festival of Artists.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.freshpaint.org/ |title=FRESH PAINT |publisher=}}</ref>\n\n===Climate===\n\nThe climate of Everett is generally similar to most of the [[Puget Sound region|Puget Sound lowlands]], with year-round moderate temperatures influenced by marine air masses. The variation of normal weather between seasons is less extreme than inland areas, with dry summers and mild, rainy winters due to the proximity of the [[Pacific Ocean]].{{sfnp|O'Donnell|1993|p=253}} Under the [[K\u00f6ppen climate classification]] system, Everett has a [[warm-summer Mediterranean climate]] (Csb), though it is also described as having an [[oceanic climate]] (Cfb).{{sfnp|O'Donnell|1993|p=253}}<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Peel |first1=M. C. |last2=Finlayson |first2=B. L. |last3=McMahon |first3=T. A. |year=2007 |title=Updated world map of the K\u00f6ppen-Geiger climate classification |journal=[[Hydrology and Earth System Sciences]] |doi=10.5194/hess-11-1633-2007 |issn=1027-5606 |volume=11 |issue=5 |pages=1633\u20131644 |publisher=[[European Geosciences Union]] |url=http://www.hydrol-earth-syst-sci.net/11/1633/2007/hess-11-1633-2007.html |accessdate=October 14, 2019}}</ref> The city marks the north end of the [[Puget Sound Convergence Zone]], a local weather phenomenon caused by colliding air currents from the region's mountain ranges that produces heavier rain and stronger winds than the rest of the region.<ref>{{cite book |last=Mass |first=Cliff |year=2008 |title=The Weather of the Pacific Northwest |page=149 |publisher=[[University of Washington Press]] |isbn=978-0-295-98847-4 |oclc=416457886 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=xPiACgAAQBAJ&pg=PA149 |via=Google Books |accessdate=March 26, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last=Sistek |first=Scott |date=December 17, 2015 |title=What Is A Puget Sound Convergence Zone? |url=https://komonews.com/weather/faq/what-is-a-puget-sound-convergence-zone |publisher=[[KOMO-TV|KOMO 4 News]] |accessdate=March 26, 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe warmest month for Everett is August, with average high temperatures of {{convert|72.7|F|C|lk=on}}, while January is the coolest, at an average high of {{convert|44.9|F|C}}.<ref name=\"WRCC\"/> The highest recorded temperature, {{convert|98|F|C}}, occurred on June 9, 1955, and the lowest, {{convert|0|F|C}}, occurred on November 11, 1993.<ref name=\"WRCC\"/> The city receives {{convert|35.71|in|mm}} of annual rainfall, which mostly falls from October to March and peaks in December.{{sfnp|O'Donnell|1993|p=253}}<ref name=\"WRCC\"/> Everett's highest recorded snowfall, {{convert|26.6|in|cm}}, occurred in 1965.<ref name=\"WRCC\"/>\n\n{{Weather box \n|location = Everett\n|single line = Y\n| Jan record high F = 72\n| Feb record high F = 74\n| Mar record high F = 82\n| Apr record high F = 85\n| May record high F = 93\n| Jun record high F = 98\n| Jul record high F = 93\n| Aug record high F = 94\n| Sep record high F = 89\n| Oct record high F = 83\n| Nov record high F = 74\n| Dec record high F = 66\n| year record high F = 98\n| Jan high F = 44.9\n| Feb high F = 48.8\n| Mar high F = 52.8\n| Apr high F = 58.1\n| May high F = 63.6\n| Jun high F = 68.3\n| Jul high F = 72.6\n| Aug high F = 72.7\n| Sep high F = 67.8\n| Oct high F = 59.5\n| Nov high F = 50.9\n| Dec high F = 45.7\n| year high F = 58.8\n| Jan low F = 33.1\n| Feb low F = 34.4\n| Mar low F = 36.8\n| Apr low F = 40.4\n| May low F = 45.3\n| Jun low F = 50.2\n| Jul low F = 52.9\n| Aug low F = 52.8\n| Sep low F = 48.3\n| Oct low F = 43\n| Nov low F = 37.6\n| Dec low F = 34.3\n| year low F = 42.4\n| Jan record low F = 1\n| Feb record low F = 2\n| Mar record low F = 10\n| Apr record low F = 23\n| May record low F = 29\n| Jun record low F = 36\n| Jul record low F = 37\n| Aug record low F = 38\n| Sep record low F = 30\n| Oct record low F = 22\n| Nov record low F = 0\n| Dec record low F = 5\n| year record low F = 0\n| precipitation colour = green\n| Jan precipitation inch = 4.51\n| Feb precipitation inch = 3.25\n| Mar precipitation inch = 3.57\n| Apr precipitation inch = 2.7\n| May precipitation inch = 2.34\n| Jun precipitation inch = 2.12\n| Jul precipitation inch = 1.04\n| Aug precipitation inch = 1.2\n| Sep precipitation inch = 1.98\n| Oct precipitation inch = 3.39\n| Nov precipitation inch = 4.65\n| Dec precipitation inch = 4.96\n| year precipitation inch = 35.71\n| Jan precipitation days = 19\n| Feb precipitation days = 16\n| Mar precipitation days = 18\n| Apr precipitation days = 15\n| May precipitation days = 12\n| Jun precipitation days = 10\n| Jul precipitation days = 6\n| Aug precipitation days = 6\n| Sep precipitation days = 9\n| Oct precipitation days = 15\n| Nov precipitation days = 18\n| Dec precipitation days = 19\n| Jan snow inch = 3.3\n| Feb snow inch = 1.2\n| Mar snow inch = 0.6\n| Apr snow inch = 0.2\n| May snow inch = 0\n| Jun snow inch = 0\n| Jul snow inch = 0\n| Aug snow inch = 0\n| Sep snow inch = 0\n| Oct snow inch = 0\n| Nov snow inch = 0.6\n| Dec snow inch = 1.4\n| year snow inch = 7.3\n\n|source 1 = [[Western Regional Climate Center]] (1894\u20132015)<ref name=\"WRCC\">{{cite web |title=Period of Record Monthly Climate Summary: Everett, Washington (452675) |url=http://www.wrcc.dri.edu/cgi-bin/cliMAIN.pl?wa2675 |publisher=[[Western Regional Climate Center]] |accessdate=November 16, 2015}}</ref>\n|date=November 2015\n}}\n\n==Economy==\n\nEverett has a workforce population of 88,146 people, as of a 2018 U.S. Census estimate, of whom 59,599 are employed.<ref name=\"ACS\">{{cite web |year=2019 |title=Selected Economic Characteristics: Everett, Washington |url=https://data.census.gov/cedsci/table?q=DP03&g=1600000US5322640&tid=ACSDP5Y2018.DP03&hidePreview=true |work=[[American Community Survey]] |publisher=United States Census Bureau |accessdate=April 2, 2020}}</ref> The city had an estimated 7,335 registered businesses in 2012.<ref>{{cite web |title=Profile: Everett, Washington |url=https://data.census.gov/cedsci/profile?g=1600000US5322640&q=Everett |publisher=United States Census Bureau |accessdate=April 2, 2020}}</ref>\n\nEverett's early economy was tied to the lumber trade. The city's last remaining wood [[pulp mill]], owned by [[Kimberly-Clark]], shut down in April 2012 and was demolished a year later, marking the end of Everett's lumber economy.<ref>{{cite news |last=Smith |first=Debra |date=March 30, 2012 |title=Kimberly-Clark mill is part of the Everett we've lost |url=https://www.heraldnet.com/news/kimberly-clark-mill-is-part-of-the-everett-weve-lost/ |work=The Everett Herald |accessdate=March 31, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Haglund |first=Noah |date=August 18, 2013 |title=Kimberly-Clark says former mill site better without grass |url=https://www.heraldnet.com/news/kimberly-clark-says-former-mill-site-better-without-grass/ |work=The Everett Herald |accessdate=March 31, 2020}}</ref> The city's 2006 labor workforce comprised more than 80,000, predominantly employed in technology, aerospace, and service-based industries.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://everettwa.usachamber.com/custom2.asp?pageid=2570 |title=Archived copy |accessdate=July 14, 2007 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070928231215/http://everettwa.usachamber.com/custom2.asp?pageid=2570 |archivedate=September 28, 2007 }}</ref>\n\nAirplane manufacturer [[Boeing]] has a significant presence in Everett, with 31 percent of all jobs,<ref name=\"CAFR2018\"/> including a [[Boeing Everett Factory|large manufacturing plant]] that is the world's largest building by volume.<ref>{{cite web |title=Boeing in Everett |url=http://www.boeing.com/company/about-bca/everett-production-facility.page |publisher=[[Boeing]] |accessdate=September 27, 2016}}</ref> Electronics manufacturer [[Fluke Corporation]] (now part of [[Fortive]]) is based in Everett and has 1,000 employees in Washington state.<ref>{{cite news |last=Lerman |first=Rachel |date=October 28, 2016 |title=Quiet industrial giant emerges in Everett |url=https://www.seattletimes.com/business/technology/everetts-fortive-shapes-strategy-for-successful-companies/ |work=The Seattle Times |accessdate=April 1, 2020}}</ref> Toymaker [[Funko]] is also headquartered in Downtown Everett and has a major distribution center in the city.<ref>{{cite news |last=Catchpole |first=Dan |date=September 9, 2016 |title=Toymaker Funko moving to downtown Everett |url=http://www.heraldnet.com/news/toymaker-funko-moving-to-downtown-everett/ |work=The Everett Herald |accessdate=September 27, 2016}}</ref>\n\nThe city's retail is concentrated along two major corridors, Evergreen Way and Everett Mall Way, and around the [[Everett Mall]], which opened in 1974 and has over 100 stores.<ref>{{cite news |last=Haglund |first=Noah |date=September 6, 2013 |title=New tenant seen as key to Everett Mall revival |url=https://www.heraldnet.com/business/new-tenant-seen-as-key-to-everett-mall-revival-2/ |work=The Everett Herald |accessdate=January 1, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Chapter V. Retail Demand |url=https://everettwa.gov/DocumentCenter/View/986/Retail-Demand-PDF?bidId= |work=Everett Downtown Plan Market Study |publisher=City of Everett |accessdate=January 1, 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Top employers===\n\nAccording to the City's 2018 Comprehensive Annual Financial Report,<ref name=\"CAFR2018\">{{cite web |date=June 26, 2019 |title=City of Everett, Washington 2018 Comrpehensive Annual Financial Report For the Year Ended December 31, 2018 |page=175 |url=https://everettwa.gov/ArchiveCenter/ViewFile/Item/1156 |publisher=City of Everett |accessdate=April 1, 2020}}</ref> the top employers in the city are:\n\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\" border=\"1\"\n|-\n! #\n! Employer\n! # of Employees\n|-\n|1\n|[[Boeing]]\n|35,000\n|-\n|2\n|[[Providence Regional Medical Center Everett]]\n|4,906\n|-\n|3\n|[[Washington (state)|State of Washington]]\n|3,000\n|-\n|4\n|[[Naval Station Everett]]\n|2,900\n|-\n|5\n|[[The Everett Clinic]]\n|2,871\n|-\n|6\n|[[Snohomish County, Washington|Snohomish County]]\n|2,759\n|-\n|7\n|[[Everett Public Schools (Washington)|Everett Public Schools]]\n|2,443\n|-\n|8\n|[[Fluke Corporation]] ([[Fortive]])\n|1,200\n|-\n|9\n|City of Everett\n|1,198\n|-\n|10\n|[[Snohomish County Public Utility District]]\n|1,004\n|}\n\n==Demographics==\n{{US Census population\n|1900= 7838\n|1910= 24814\n|1920= 27644\n|1930= 30567\n|1940= 30224\n|1950= 33849\n|1960= 40304\n|1970= 53622\n|1980= 54413\n|1990= 69961\n|2000= 91488\n|2010= 103019\n|estyear=2018\n|estimate=111262\n|estref=<ref name=\"USCensusEst2018CenPopScriptOnlyDirtyFixDoNotUse\">{{cite web |date=June 27, 2019 |title=Population and Housing Unit Estimates |url=https://www.census.gov/programs-surveys/popest/data/tables.2018.html |publisher=United States Census Bureau |accessdate=February 16, 2020}}</ref>\n|footnote=Source:<ref>Moffatt, Riley.  ''Population History of Western U.S. Cities & Towns, 1850-1990''.  [[Lanham, Maryland|Lanham]]: Scarecrow, 1996, 320.</ref><center>U.S. Decennial Census<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.census.gov/prod/www/decennial.html|title=U.S. Decennial Census|publisher=Census.gov|accessdate=June 6, 2013|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150426102944/http://www.census.gov/prod/www/decennial.html|archivedate=April 26, 2015}}</ref><br>2018 Estimate<ref name=\"2018 Pop Estimate\">{{cite web|title=Population Estimates|url=https://census.gov/data/tables/2018/demo/popest/total-cities-and-towns.html|publisher=[[United States Census Bureau]]|accessdate=June 5, 2019}}</ref>\n}}\n\n===2010 census===\n\nAs of the [[2010 United States Census|2010 U.S. census]], there were 103,019 people, 41,312 households, and 23,282 families residing in the city. The [[population density]] was {{convert|3079.8|PD/sqmi|PD/km2|1}}. There were 44,609 housing units at an average density of {{convert|1333.6|/sqmi|/km2|1}}. The [[Race and ethnicity in the United States Census|racial makeup]] of the city was 74.6% White, 4.1% African American, 1.4% Native American, 7.8% Asian, 0.7% Pacific Islander, 6.1% from other races, and 5.3% from two or more races. Hispanic or Latino of any race were 14.2% of the population.<ref name=\"FactFinder\">{{cite web |title=American FactFinder |url=http://factfinder2.census.gov/faces/nav/jsf/pages/index.xhtml |publisher=[[United States Census Bureau]] |accessdate=December 19, 2012}}</ref>\n\nThere were 41,312 households of which 30.5% had children under the age of 18 living with them, 38.2% were [[Marriage|married couples]] living together, 12.5% had a female householder with no husband present, 5.7% had a male householder with no wife present, and 43.6% were non-families. 34.1% of all households were made up of individuals and 9.3% had someone living alone who was 65 years of age or older. The average household size was 2.39 and the average family size was 3.09.<ref name=\"FactFinder\"/>\n\nThe median age in the city was 34.4 years. 22.7% of residents were under the age of 18; 11.3% were between the ages of 18 and 24; 30.6% were from 25 to 44; 25% were from 45 to 64; and 10.3% were 65 years of age or older. The gender makeup of the city was 50.9% male and 49.1% female.<ref name=\"FactFinder\"/>\n\n===2000 census===\n\nAs of the [[2000 United States Census|2000 U.S. census]], there were 91,488 people, 36,325 households and 21,613 families residing in the city.  The population density was 2,814.6 people per square mile (1,086.9/km\u00b2).  There were 38,512 housing units at an average density of 1,184.8 per square mile (457.5/km\u00b2).  The racial makeup of the city was 56% White, 9% African American, 1.56% Native American, 10% Asian, 4% Pacific Islander, 3.13% from other races and 4.25% from two or more races.  Hispanic or Latino of any race were 13% of the population.<ref name=\"Census2000\">{{cite web |year=2000 |title=Profile of General Demographic Characteristics: Everett city, Washington |url=https://www.psrc.org/sites/default/files/everett.pdf |publisher=United States Census Bureau |via=[[Puget Sound Regional Council]] |accessdate=April 1, 2020}}</ref>\n\nThere were 36,325 households, out of which 31.9% had children under the age of 18 living with them, 42.1% were married couples living together, 12.5% had a female householder with no husband present, and 40.5% were non-families. 31.7% of all households were made up of individuals and 8.5% had someone living alone who was 65 years of age or older.  The average household size was 2.40 and the average family size was 3.04.\n\nIn the city, the population was spread out with 25.1% under the age of 18, 12.3% from 18 to 24, 33.3% from 25 to 44, 18.9% from 45 to 64, and 10.3% who were 65 years of age or older.  The median age was 32 years.  For every 100 females, there were 103.5 males.  For every 100 females age 18 and over, there were 102.8 males.\n\nThe median income for a household in the city was $40,100 and the median income for a family was $46,743.  Males had a median income of $35,852 versus $28,841 for females.  The [[per capita income]] for the city was $20,577.  About 10.1% of families and 19.5% of the population were below the [[poverty line]], including 16% of those under the age of 18 and 12.1% of those ages 65 and older.\n\n===Crime===\n{{Infobox UCR\n|city_name= Everett\n|year= 2015\n|murder and manslaughter= 5\n|rape= 42\n|robbery= 140\n|aggravated_assault= 214\n|burglary= 924\n|larceny_theft= 4096\n|motor_vehicle_theft= 862\n|arson= 31\n|source_url= https://www.fbi.gov/contact-us/field-offices/seattle/news/press-releases/the-fbi-releases-2015-crime-statistics-for-washington-state\n|source_name= 2015 FBI Crime Statistics\n|notes= 2013 population: 105,370\n}}\nWhile in 2012, Everett was ranked with the 104th highest crime rate in the United States,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://os.cqpress.com/citycrime/2012/CityCrime2013_CityCrimeRateRankings.pdf |title=2012 City Crime Rate Rankings* |publisher=[[CQ Press]]}}</ref> it has since seen significant improvement in several key areas. For example, between 2012 and 2015, Everett's robbery rate decreased from 182 to 148 (-18.7%). Aggravated assault decreased from 252 to 225 (-10.7%), and burglary from 4,281 to 974 (-77.2%).<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.fbi.gov/contact-us/field-offices/seattle/news/press-releases/the-fbi-releases-2015-crime-statistics-for-washington-state |title=FBI Releases 2015 Crime Statistics for Washington State}}</ref> Everett's burglary rate in 2012 was unusually high, and that a more fair comparison would have been the decrease from 2013's burglary rate of 1,129 to 2015's 974 (-13.7%).<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.fbi.gov/contact-us/field-offices/seattle/news/press-releases/the-fbi-releases-2013-crime-statistics-for-washington-state |title=FBI Releases 2013 Crime Statistics for Washington State}}</ref>\n\nIn January 2017, Everett, with a high rate of [[opioid abuse]], sued [[Purdue Pharma]], claiming that the company's [[gross negligence]] in the distribution of [[OxyContin]] harmed its citizens. One aspect of the complex suit is a Los Angeles drug ring, which employed corrupt doctors issuing huge prescriptions to homeless people, diverting the drug to Washington and other states.<ref>{{citation |title=City devastated by OxyContin use sues Purdue Pharma, claims drugmaker put profits over citizens' welfare |author=Harriet Ryan |date=January 19, 2017 |newspaper=The Los Angeles Times |url=http://www.latimes.com/local/lanow/la-me-oxycontin-lawsuit-20170118-story.html}}</ref><ref>{{citation |newspaper=Everett Herald |title=Everett's suit against OxyContin maker moves to federal court |author=Scott North |date=February 20, 2017 |url=http://www.heraldnet.com/news/everetts-suit-against-oxycontin-maker-moves-to-federal-court/}}</ref><ref>{{citation |url=https://www.npr.org/2017/02/03/513196772/u-s-city-sues-oxycontin-maker-for-contributing-to-opiod-crisis |title=U.S. City Sues OxyContin Maker For Contributing To Opioid Crisis |work=[[Morning Edition]] |publisher=NPR |date=February 3, 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Government and politics==\n\nEverett is a first-class city with an organized [[city charter|charter]] and a [[mayor\u2013council government|mayor\u2013council]] form of government.<ref name=\"MRSC-First\">{{cite web |date=March 10, 2020 |title=First Class Cities |url=http://mrsc.org/getdoc/490c32b2-2cd8-480a-92bc-a4ec66fbeb1c/First-Class-Cities-by-Form-of-Government.aspx |publisher=[[Municipal Research and Services Center]] |accessdate=March 26, 2020}}</ref> The city's [[mayor]] and seven councilmembers are elected [[at-large]] to four-year terms in staggered elections that take place during odd-numbered years. Beginning in 2021, the Everett city council will elect five members from districts and two from at-large seats.<ref>{{cite news |last=Giordano |first=Lizz |date=November 19, 2018 |title=Significant changes coming to Everett's City Council |url=https://www.heraldnet.com/news/significant-changes-coming-to-everetts-city-council/ |work=The Everett Herald |accessdate=March 26, 2020}}</ref> The city council meets weekly on Wednesdays and offers live television and web broadcasts via the [[Everett Channel]].<ref>{{cite web |title=City Council |url=https://everettwa.gov/409/City-Council |publisher=City of Everett |accessdate=March 26, 2020}}</ref> The city government is based out of the Wall Street Building in Downtown Everett, a 10-story office tower adjacent to the historic [[Everett City Hall]]\u2014now home to the city police department and city council chambers.<ref>{{cite news |last=Winters |first=Chris |date=December 6, 2016 |title=City of Everett tightens Wall Street building security |url=https://www.heraldnet.com/news/everett-hires-security-for-building-housing-mayor-city-offices/ |work=The Everett Herald |accessdate=March 26, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Smith |first=Debra |date=February 26, 2012 |title=Plan could allow new name for old Everett city hall |url=https://www.heraldnet.com/news/plan-could-allow-new-name-for-old-everett-city-hall/ |work=The Everett Herald |accessdate=March 26, 2020}}</ref>\n\n[[Cassie Franklin]], a former city councilmember, was elected as mayor in 2017 and is the second woman and first non-appointee to hold the office.<ref>{{cite news |last=King |first=Rikki |date=November 16, 2017 |title=Franklin becomes first woman to be elected mayor of Everett |url=https://www.heraldnet.com/news/cassie-franklin-becomes-first-woman-to-be-elected-mayor-of-everett/ |work=The Everett Herald |accessdate=March 26, 2020}}</ref> The mayor of Everett is responsible for appointing the heads of various city departments, the city clerk, the city treasurer, the [[police chief|police]] and [[fire chief|fire]] chiefs, and members of service commissions and boards.<ref name=\"MRSC-First\"/> The city government has 1,200 employees and an operating budget of $148.7&nbsp;million for 2020.<ref>{{cite news |last=Giordano |first=Lizz |date=January 11, 2019 |title=City of Everett offers buyouts to 330 senior employees |url=https://www.heraldnet.com/news/city-of-everett-offers-buyouts-to-330-senior-employees/ |work=The Everett Herald |accessdate=March 26, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Giordano |first=Lizz |date=November 15, 2019 |title=Everett balances 2020 budget with no new fees or taxes |url=https://www.heraldnet.com/news/everett-balances-2020-budget-with-no-new-fees-or-taxes/ |work=The Everett Herald |accessdate=March 26, 2020}}</ref> It provides a range of municipal services, including police, fire, [[emergency medical services]], public works, a [[housing authority]], zoning and planning, parks and recreation, and some utilities.<ref name=\"CAFR2018\"/>{{rp|2}}<ref name=\"About\">{{cite web |title=About Everett |url=https://everettwa.gov/272/About-Everett |publisher=City of Everett |accessdate=March 26, 2020}}</ref> Everett also has a [[municipal court]] that was established in 1987 and has two judges who are elected to four-year terms.<ref>{{cite news |last=Haglund |first=Noah |date=December 20, 2013 |title=First woman to serve on Everett Municipal Court |url=https://www.heraldnet.com/news/first-woman-to-serve-on-everett-municipal-court/ |work=The Everett Herald |accessdate=March 29, 2020}}</ref> The city government runs its own [[Everett Transit|public transit]] and [[Everett Public Library|library]] systems, which are separate from the countywide [[Community Transit]] and [[Sno-Isle Libraries]].<ref>{{cite news |last=Giordano |first=Lizz |date=November 8, 2019 |title=Everett entertains pitch for joining county-wide bus system |url=https://www.heraldnet.com/news/everett-entertains-pitch-for-joining-county-wide-bus-system/ |work=The Everett Herald |accessdate=March 26, 2020}}</ref>\n\nEverett is also the [[county seat]] of [[Snohomish County, Washington|Snohomish County]] and houses several major government facilities on a campus in Downtown Everett. The campus includes the [[Snohomish County Courthouse|county courthouse]], county jail, administrative offices, and the main precinct of the [[Snohomish County Sheriff|county sheriff]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Departments-Offices-Campus Map |url=https://snohomishcountywa.gov/2902/Departments-Offices-CampusMap |publisher=Snohomish County |accessdate=March 26, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Kelly |first=Brian |date=June 1, 2005 |title=$175 million later... |url=https://www.heraldnet.com/news/175-million-later/ |work=The Everett Herald |accessdate=March 26, 2020}}</ref>\n\nAt the federal level, Everett is part of the [[Washington's 2nd congressional district|2nd congressional district]], represented by Democrat [[Rick Larsen]] since 2001.<ref name=\"DistrictMap\">{{cite map |date=February 7, 2012 |title=Washington State Legislative & Congressional District Map |url=http://www.redistricting.wa.gov/assets/maps/FoldedMap_State.pdf |inset=[http://www.redistricting.wa.gov/assets/maps/FoldedMap_Insets.pdf Puget Sound & Other Areas] |publisher=[[Washington State Redistricting Commission]] |accessdate=March 26, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Cornfield |first=Jerry |date=January 7, 2019 |title=Now in majority, state\u2019s Democrats ready to use new clout |url=https://www.heraldnet.com/news/now-in-majority-states-democrats-ready-to-use-new-clout/ |work=The Everett Herald |accessdate=March 26, 2020}}</ref> At the state level, most of the city is in the [[Washington's 38th legislative district|38th legislative district]] alongside Marysville and the Tulalip Indian Reservation. The southern neighborhoods of the city, including Silver Lake, are part of the [[Washington's 21st legislative district|21st legislative district]], shared with Edmonds and Mukilteo.<ref name=\"DistrictMap\"/> Everett is also part of the [[Snohomish County Council]]'s 2nd district, which also includes Mukilteo and the Tulalip Indian Reservation.<ref>{{cite map |title=Snohomish County Council Districts |url=http://snohomishcountywa.gov/DocumentCenter/Home/View/49 |publisher=Snohomish County Elections |accessdate=March 26, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Culture==\n\n===Arts and tourism===\n[[File:Everett Theater 02.jpg|thumb|Historic Everett Theatre]]\n\nEverett is described as a \"largely [[blue-collar]] city\", but is home to a regional arts scene that includes galleries, community theaters, music, and artwork.<ref>{{cite news |last=Winters |first=Chris |date=August 27, 2014 |title=With a change of tune, Snohomish County Music Project thrives |url=https://www.heraldnet.com/news/with-a-change-of-tune-snohomish-county-music-project-thrives/ |work=The Everett Herald |accessdate=March 29, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Wood |first=Kyle R. |date=August 16, 1996 |title=Selling Snohomish County |page=B1 |url=https://archive.seattletimes.com/archive/?date=19960816&slug=2344504 |work=The Seattle Times |accessdate=March 29, 2020}}</ref>\n\nDowntown Everett is also home to the Everett Performing Arts Center (home to the [[Village Theatre]] theatre company), The Historic Everett Theatre<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.historiceveretttheatre.org |title=Home |publisher=}}</ref> (built in 1901 and is one of the oldest active theatre West of the Rockies), the [[Imagine Children's Museum]], the Arts Council of Snohomish County, and an array of street sculptures. The Everett Symphony (established 1935) performs at the Everett Civic Auditorium. The city is also home to the Everett Chorale, which holds their concerts at the Everett Performing Arts Center.\n\nFounded as the Arts Council of Snohomish County, the [[Schack Art Center]] opened in downtown Everett in April 2011 and was named for John and Idamae Schack, in honor of their steadfast support of Everett's cultural institutions.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.schack.org |title=Welcome |publisher=}}</ref> It is the place to look at, learn about, and create art in the region. Village Theatre has produced musical theatre since 1979. Through its Village Originals program, Village Theatre contributes to the development of new musicals, having launched over 145 new works to date. Its youth education programs, Pied Piper and KIDSTAGE, serving over 55,000 young people, families, and schools annually.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.villagetheatre.org/everett/about.php |title=Village Theatre \u2013 About Us |publisher=}}</ref>\n{{Expand section|date=June 2008}}\n\nSince the end of the Great Recession (2009), Seattle has seen its cost of living rise exponentially, largely due to large-scale economic development and the growth of the tech industry.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://smartasset.com/mortgage/what-is-the-cost-of-living-in-seattle |title=What Is the True Cost of Living in Seattle? |publisher=}}</ref> As its perception as a working class community has diminished,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://grist.org/cities/in-seattle-the-rent-is-too-damn-high |title=In Seattle, the rent is too damn high |publisher=}}</ref> many musicians and artists have found it increasingly difficult to live within Seattle proper.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://kuow.org/post/seattle-too-expensive-artists-who-help-it-boom |title=Seattle Is Too Expensive For Artists Who Help It Boom |publisher=}}</ref> This has led to an \"artistic flight\" toward neighboring communities, most notably Everett which is often cited as possessing the \"true grit and soul of the 90's.\" <ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.cityonthesound.com/#!blank-1/sz453 |title=Everett Today |publisher=}}</ref>\n\nThe Everett area has several tourist attractions, particularly those themed around aviation. The [[Future of Flight Aviation Center & Boeing Tour|Future of Flight Aviation Center]] at Paine Field, owned by the county government and operated by Boeing, has several aviation exhibits and includes a tour of the Boeing assembly plant. It is the most popular tourist attraction in Snohomish County, with 495,000 total visitors in 2017.<ref>{{cite news |last=Gates |first=Dominic |date=February 28, 2018 |title=Boeing, Snohomish County hold key to Future of Flight as aviation center faces turbulent times |url=https://www.seattletimes.com/business/boeing-aerospace/boeing-snohomish-county-hold-key-to-future-of-flight-aviation-centers-future/ |work=The Seattle Times |accessdate=March 30, 2020}}</ref> The [[Flying Heritage & Combat Armor Museum]] opened in 2008 at a renovated Paine Field hangar and houses a collection of restored 20th century military planes and vehicles.<ref>{{cite news |last=Catchpole |first=Dan |date=April 11, 2017 |title=Growing Flying Heritage Collection now has a new name |url=https://www.heraldnet.com/news/growing-flying-heritage-collection-now-has-a-new-name/ |work=The Everett Herald |accessdate=March 30, 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Events===\n\nThe city hosts several annual events and festivals for local arts and celebrations, usually during the summer months. The Fisherman's Village Music Festival, established in 2014, takes place annually over a three-day weekend in May at four stages in Downtown Everett. The music festival includes performances from 50 local and national artists as well as art exhibitions.<ref>{{cite news |last=Rietmulder |first=Michael |date=March 29, 2018 |title=With Fisherman's Village Music Festival, Everett out-rocks Seattle one weekend a year |url=https://www.seattletimes.com/entertainment/music/with-fishermans-village-music-festival-everett-out-rocks-seattle-one-weekend-a-year/ |work=The Seattle Times |accessdate=March 29, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Thompson |first=Evan |date=May 9, 2019 |title=Fisherman's Village Music Festival expands to Everett Station |url=https://www.heraldnet.com/life/fishermans-village-music-festival-expands-to-everett-station/ |work=The Everett Herald |accessdate=March 29, 2020}}</ref> The city's waterfront hosts an annual parade and [[fireworks]] display on [[Independence Day (United States)|Independence Day]].<ref>{{cite news |last=Davey |first=Stephanie |date=July 5, 2019 |title=July 4th parade is a 'special tradition' for local families |url=https://www.heraldnet.com/news/july-4th-parade-is-a-special-tradition-for-local-families/ |work=The Everett Herald |accessdate=March 29, 2020}}</ref> Several annual festivals were established in the 1990s, including a [[film festival]] in February,<ref>{{cite news |last=Salyer |first=Sharon |date=February 7, 2019 |title=Everett Film Festival marks its 20th year with 10 screenings |url=https://www.heraldnet.com/life/see-10-short-films-and-documentaries-at-everett-film-festival/ |work=The Everett Herald |accessdate=March 29, 2020}}</ref> the Sorticulture garden festival in June,<ref>{{cite news |last=Thompson |first=Evan |date=June 1, 2019 |title=Sprinklers with style, and much more at Everett's Sorticulture |url=https://www.heraldnet.com/life/sprinklers-with-style-and-much-more-at-everetts-sorticulture/ |work=The Everett Herald |accessdate=March 29, 2020}}</ref> and the Fresh Paint [[art show]] in August.<ref>{{cite news |last=Salyer |first=Sharon |date=August 16, 2018 |title=Fresh Paint to bring artists, art lovers to waterfront |url=https://www.heraldnet.com/life/fresh-paint-to-bring-artists-art-lovers-to-waterfront/ |work=The Everett Herald |accessdate=March 29, 2020}}</ref> The cit's largest annual summer festival, the Salty Sea Days, was established in 1970 and included a parade, [[hydroplane race]]s, a classic auto show, and other events. It was originally subsidized using city [[lodging tax]]es until 2003, and shut down three years later.<ref>{{cite news |last=Langston |first=Jennifer |date=August 26, 2003 |title=Puget Sound Journal: Everett's summer fest not worth its salt, some say |page=B3 |url=https://www.seattlepi.com/news/article/Puget-Sound-Journal-Everett-s-summer-fest-not-1122698.php |work=Seattle Post-Intelligencer |accessdate=March 30, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Warnick |first=Jennifer |date=March 1, 2005 |title=Group scuttles Salty Sea Days |url=https://www.heraldnet.com/news/group-scuttles-salty-sea-days/ |work=The Everett Herald |accessdate=March 30, 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe Everett [[farmers market]] began in 1994 and operates on Sundays from May to October with 200 vendors and about 5,000 weekly visitors.<ref>{{cite news |last=Giordano |first=Lizz |date=July 20, 2019 |title=Farmers Market is leaving Boxcar, moving to downtown Everett |url=https://www.heraldnet.com/news/farmers-market-is-leaving-boxcar-moving-to-downtown-everett/ |work=The Everett Herald |accessdate=March 29, 2020}}</ref> It was originally located at the Port of Everett but moved in 2019 to Wetmore Avenue in downtown because of parking and accessibility issues at the waterfront site.<ref>{{cite news |last=Smith |first=Debra |date=June 6, 2011 |title=Future murky for Everett waterfront farmers market |url=http://www.heraldnet.com/article/20110606/NEWS01/706069912 |work=The Everett Herald |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110728064906/http://www.heraldnet.com/article/20110606/NEWS01/706069912 |archivedate=July 28, 2011 |accessdate=March 29, 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"Herald-FM19\">{{cite news |last=Giordano |first=Lizz |date=August 13, 2019 |title=Long parking lines, costs led Everett Farmers Market to move |url=https://www.heraldnet.com/news/parking-lines-costs-led-to-move-by-everett-farmers-market/ |work=The Everett Herald |accessdate=March 29, 2020}}</ref> The farmers market also operates popup [[bazaar]]s during the off-season and a Wednesday market at [[Everett Station]] during the summer.<ref>{{cite news |last=Watanabe |first=Ben |date=February 10, 2020 |title=First popup Everett Farmers Market draws hundreds of people |url=https://www.heraldnet.com/news/first-popup-everett-farmers-market-draws-hundreds-of-people/ |work=The Everett Herald |accessdate=March 29, 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Media===\n\nThe ''[[Everett Herald]]'' is the city's daily newspaper, providing local and national news for 40,000 subscribers in Snohomish County. It began publication on February 11, 1901, emerging as the city's lone daily newspaper from a field of three competitors established in the early 1890s, including the ''Everett News'', ''Everett Times'', and ''Everett Tribune''.<ref name=\"Editions\">{{cite book |last1=Bagwell |first1=Steve |last2=Stapilus |first2=Randy |year=2013 |title=New Editions: The Northwest's newspapers as they were, are, and will be |pages=212\u2013213 |publisher=Ridenbaugh Press |location=Carlton, Oregon |isbn=978-0-945648-10-9 |oclc=861618089}}</ref> The newspaper remained under local ownership until it was purchased by [[The Washington Post Company]] in 1978 and it was sold to [[Sound Publishing]] in 2013.<ref name=\"Editions\"/><ref>{{cite news |date=March 4, 2013 |title=Herald sale to Sound Publishing completed |url=https://www.heraldnet.com/business/herald-sale-to-sound-publishing-completed/ |work=The Everett Herald |accessdate=March 29, 2020}}</ref> The ''Herald'' launched its online website on January 5, 1997, the monthly ''Herald Business Journal'' in 1998,<ref>{{cite web |title=The Herald Business Journal |url=http://www.soundpublishing.com/titles/the-herald-business-journal/ |publisher=[[Sound Publishing]] |accessdate=March 30, 2020}}</ref> and began publishing a weekly Spanish-language newspaper, ''La Raza del Noroeste'', in April 2006.<ref>{{cite web |title=About the Daily Herald and Heraldnet |url=http://www.heraldnet.com/article/99999999/EXTRAS02/676034648 |publisher=The Everett Herald |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100716223513/http://www.heraldnet.com/article/99999999/EXTRAS02/676034648 |archivedate=July 16, 2010 |accessdate=March 30, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Arriola |first=Cindy |date=February 14, 2013 |title=El futuro de \"La Raza\" |language=Spanish |trans-title=The future of \"La Raza\" |url=https://www.larazanw.com/noticias/el-futuro-de-la-raza/ |work=La Raza del Noroeste |accessdate=March 30, 2020}}</ref> My Everett News is an independent online news outlet for Everett that was established in 2011 and is affiliated with ''[[The Seattle Times]]''.<ref>{{cite news |date=July 13, 2011 |title=Seattle Times announces more local news partners |url=https://www.seattletimes.com/seattle-news/seattle-times-announces-more-local-news-partners-1/ |work=The Seattle Times |accessdate=March 30, 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe city is part of the [[Media in Seattle|Seattle\u2013Tacoma media market]], ranked 13th among U.S. metro areas, which includes several major television and radio stations.<ref>{{cite web |date=September 28, 2019 |title=Local Television Market Universe Estimates |page=1 |url=https://www.nielsen.com/wp-content/uploads/sites/3/2019/09/2019-20-dma-ranker.pdf |publisher=[[Nielsen Media Research]] |accessdate=March 30, 2020}}</ref> [[KONG-TV]], a Seattle-based broadcast channel that is affiliated with [[KING-TV]], has been licensed to Everett sine 1984 and debuted in 1997.<ref>{{cite news |last=Levesque |first=John |date=July 2, 1997 |title=KING grooms KONG for a Monday debut and a spot on cable |page=D10 |work=Seattle Post-Intelligencer}}</ref> The City of Everett also runs The Everett Channel, a [[government-access television]] station that broadcasts local events and city meetings.<ref>{{cite web |title=The Everett Channel |url=https://everettwa.gov/408/Everett-Channel |publisher=City of Everett |accessdate=March 30, 2020}}</ref> Everett itself has four radio stations.<ref>{{cite news |last=Guiney |first=Kelley |date=January 2, 2010 |title=Neighborhood of the week: North Everett |url=http://seattletimes.nwsource.com/html/realestate/2010652800_realneighborhood03.html |work=The Seattle Times |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100107053938/http://seattletimes.nwsource.com/html/realestate/2010652800_realneighborhood03.html |archivedate=January 7, 2010 |accessdate=March 30, 2020}}</ref> The Skotdal family owns two stations in Everett that share facilities with the Everett Post: [[KRKO|KRKO-AM]], which began broadcasting in 1922 and primary plays [[Classic hits]] along with local sports;<ref>{{cite web |last=Blecha |first=Peter |date=December 6, 2010 |title=KRKO: Everett's Historic Radio Station |url=https://www.historylink.org/File/9620 |work=HistoryLink |accessdate=March 30, 2020}}</ref> and [[KKXA|KKXA-AM]], a country music station launched in 2011.<ref>{{cite news |last=Davis |first=Jim |date=October 7, 2016 |title=Two Everett AM radio stations approved to broadcast on FM |url=https://www.heraldnet.com/news/two-everett-am-radio-stations-approved-to-broadcast-on-fm/ |work=The Everett Herald |accessdate=March 30, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Brown |first=Andrea |date=April 10, 2018 |title=An Everett 'potcast' explains what all the buzz is about |url=https://www.heraldnet.com/news/what-all-the-buzz-is-about/ |work=The Everett Herald |accessdate=March 30, 2020}}</ref> [[KSER|KSER-FM]] is an independent [[public radio]] station founded in 1991 to serve Snohomish County, carrying local news, music programming, and nationally syndicated news.<ref>{{cite news |last=Muhlstein |first=Julie |date=March 12, 2016 |title=At 25, Everett's KSER still entertains, informs community |url=https://www.heraldnet.com/news/at-25-everetts-kser-still-entertains-informs-community/ |work=The Everett Herald |accessdate=March 30, 2020}}</ref> Everett is also the home to [[KWYZ|KWYZ-AM]] (Radio Hankook), a [[Korean language]] news and entertainment station that launched in 1997 and is broadcast from [[Federal Way, Washington|Federal Way]].<ref>{{cite news |last=Virgin |first=Bill |date=June 10, 1999 |title=Korean-language stations a resource for immigrants |page=C6 |work=Seattle Post-Intelligencer}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Kugiya |first=Hugo |date=July 8, 2014 |title=Radio Hankook: The heart of Korea on Washington radio |url=https://crosscut.com/2014/07/korean-radio-hankook-federal-way-seattle |work=[[Crosscut.com]] |accessdate=March 30, 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Libraries===\n\nThe [[Everett Public Library]] system has two locations with 258,133 total items and serves 45,205 registered members in the city and surrounding communities {{as of|2018|lc=y}}.<ref>{{cite web |date=September 2019 |title=2018 Washington Public Library Statistical Report |pages=50\u201356 |url=https://www.sos.wa.gov/_assets/library/libraries/libdev/2018stats.pdf |publisher=[[Washington State Library]] |accessdate=March 21, 2020}}</ref> The library was founded in 1894 and moved into a [[Everett Carnegie Library|permanent building]] in 1905. The current downtown library opened in 1934 and was expanded in 1991;<ref>{{cite web |last=Van Wingen |first=Melinda |date=December 3, 2019 |title=Everett Public Library |url=https://www.historylink.org/File/20926 |work=HistoryLink |accessdate=March 21, 2020}}</ref> a branch library in South Everett opened in 1985 and was renovated in 2019.<ref>{{cite news |last=Muhlstein |first=Julie |date=December 11, 2019 |title=It's a launch for Everett library's renovated Evergreen Branch |url=https://www.heraldnet.com/news/its-a-launch-for-everett-librarys-renovated-evergreen-branch/ |work=The Everett Herald |accessdate=March 21, 2020}}</ref> In 2017, [[Sno-Isle Libraries]], the countywide library system, opened a demonstration branch at a [[strip mall]] in South Everett to serve the Mariner area.<ref>{{cite news |last=Bray |first=Kari |date=February 9, 2017 |title=Everett community finally gets long-awaited library |url=https://www.heraldnet.com/news/everett-community-finally-gets-long-awaited-library/ |work=The Everett Herald |accessdate=March 27, 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Historic preservation===\n[[File:Henry M. Jackson's Home-1.jpg|thumb|Senator [[Henry M. Jackson]]'s home in North Everett]]\n\nEverett is home to 14 properties listed on the [[National Register of Historic Places]].<ref name=\"LandmarkMap\">{{cite map |date=April 23, 2019 |title=Historic Register Properties & Areas |url=https://everettwa.gov/DocumentCenter/View/19452/Historic-Register-Properties-and-Areas |publisher=City of Everett |accessdate=February 15, 2020}}</ref> The city also maintains its own register of historic places that has 35 properties.<ref>{{cite news |date=April 7, 2017 |title=Groups work to preserve Everett's rich history |url=https://www.heraldnet.com/advertising/groups-work-to-preserve-everetts-rich-history/ |work=The Everett Herald |accessdate=June 29, 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn addition to historic properties, the city has several designated [[Historic districts in the United States|historic districts]]: [[Hewitt Avenue Historic District]] in Downtown Everett; the [[Rucker Hill Historic District]]; and the [[Swalwell Block]]. Several historic overlay districts are designated by the city government, including the Riverside Overlay, the Norton\u2013Grand Overlay, and the Rucker\u2013Grand Overlay, which includes the home of the former U.S. Senator [[Henry M. Jackson]].<ref name=\"LandmarkMap\"/>\n\nThe Everett Museum of History was established in 1953 as a countywide historical association and maintained its own museum until 2007. The organization's collections moved between several historic buildings, including the former [[Everett Carnegie Library]] and part of the [[Everett Mall]], while a new location was sought.<ref>{{cite news |last=Muhlstein |first=Julie |date=August 28, 2016 |title=Everett Museum of History seeks a forever home |url=https://www.heraldnet.com/news/everett-museum-of-history-seeks-a-forever-home/ |work=The Everett Herald |accessdate=February 15, 2020}}</ref> A permanent museum at the former downtown offices of the ''Everett Herald'' is planned to open in 2021.<ref>{{cite news |last=Muhlstein |first=Julie |date=December 21, 2017 |title=A Christmas present for the keepers of Everett's past |url=https://www.heraldnet.com/news/a-present-for-the-past/ |work=The Everett Herald |accessdate=February 15, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=About Us |url=https://everett-museum.org/everett-museum-of-history/ |publisher=Everett Museum of History |accessdate=February 15, 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Sports===\n\nEverett is home to two sports venues that are used by professional [[minor league]] teams and for other events.<ref name=\"Times-Sports05\">{{cite news |last=Alexander |first=Brian |date=October 19, 2005 |title=Snohomish County minor league teams are a major success |page=H16 |url=https://archive.seattletimes.com/archive/?date=20051019&slug=minorleagues19n |work=The Seattle Times |accessdate=March 28, 2020}}</ref> The [[Angel of the Winds Arena]], an indoor arena in downtown which seats 8,149, is home to [[Everett Silvertips]] of the [[Western Hockey League]].<ref>{{cite news |last=Watanabe |first=Ben |date=May 4, 2018 |title=Silvertips fans: Meet the enemy stronghold of Swift Current |url=https://www.heraldnet.com/news/silvertips-fans-meet-the-enemy-stronghold-of-swift-current/ |work=The Everett Herald |accessdate=March 28, 2020}}</ref> It opened in 2003 at a cost of $83&nbsp;million and includes a community [[ice rink]] and a [[convention center]] for use by other events.<ref>{{cite news |last=Tuinstra |first=Rachel |date=September 24, 2003 |title=A $71.5 million venue represents 'a big leap of faith' for the city |page=H28 |url=http://community.seattletimes.nwsource.com/archive/?date=20030924&slug=center24n |work=The Seattle Times |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121004084051/http://community.seattletimes.nwsource.com/archive/?date=20030924&slug=center24n |archivedate=October 4, 2012 |accessdate=March 25, 2012}}</ref> The arena has also hosted basketball games for the [[Seattle Storm]] of the [[WNBA]],<ref>{{cite news |last=Patterson |first=Nick |date=January 16, 2020 |title=Storm returning to Everett for 8 games in 2020 |url=https://www.heraldnet.com/sports/storm-returning-to-everett-for-8-games-in-2020/ |work=The Everett Herald |accessdate=March 28, 2020}}</ref> indoor tennis events including the [[2020 Fed Cup]],<ref>{{cite news |last=Patterson |first=Nick |date=February 17, 2020 |title=USTA: Everett aces first time hosting Fed Cup qualifier |url=https://www.heraldnet.com/sports/usta-everett-aces-first-time-hosting-fed-cup-qualifier/ |work=The Everett Herald |accessdate=March 28, 2020}}</ref> and two editions of the [[Skate America]] figure skating championships in 2008 and 2018.<ref>{{cite news |last=Patterson |first=Nick |date=October 30, 2018 |title=Can Everett become a regular on the figure-skating circuit? |url=https://www.heraldnet.com/sports/skate-americas-encore-in-everett-deemed-a-success/ |work=The Everett Herald |accessdate=March 28, 2020}}</ref> The [[Everett AquaSox]] of the [[Northwest League]] play at Funko Field, a 3,682-seat baseball stadium that is part of the [[Everett Memorial Stadium]] complex.<ref>{{cite news |last=Calkins |first=Matt |date=August 2, 2019 |title=As he tries to revive MLB career, Felix Hernandez remains King in Everett |page=C1 |url=https://www.seattletimes.com/sports/mariners/felix-hernandez-after-rehab-start-in-everett-it-feels-good-to-be-back-on-the-mound/ |work=The Seattle Times |accessdate=March 28, 2020}}</ref> The Memorial Stadium complex was built in 1947 and also includes a 12,000-seat football and track stadium that is used by the city's various high school teams.{{sfnp|O'Donnell|1993|p=157}}<ref>{{cite news |date=September 6, 2001 |title=Ticket prices and more for region's football stadiums |url=https://archive.seattletimes.com/archive/?date=20010906&slug=stadiumweb06 |work=The Seattle Times |accessdate=March 28, 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe city formerly had additional indoor sports teams who played in minor leagues: the [[Snohomish County Explosion]], which played from 2008 to 2010 in the defunct [[International Basketball League]];<ref>{{cite news |last=Lommers |first=Aaron |date=April 8, 2011 |title=New owners bring Explosion back to Everett |url=https://www.heraldnet.com/sports/new-owners-bring-explosion-back-to-everett/ |work=The Everett Herald |accessdate=February 18, 2019}}</ref> the [[Everett Hawks]] of the [[National Indoor Football League]] and [[AF2]], who folded in 2007; the [[Everett Raptors]] of the [[Indoor Football League]], who played for one season in 2012;<ref>{{cite news |last=Boyle |first=John |date=February 24, 2012 |title=Everett Raptors make their debut Saturday night |url=https://www.heraldnet.com/sports/everett-raptors-make-their-debut-saturday-night/ |work=The Everett Herald |accessdate=February 18, 2019}}</ref> and the [[Washington Stealth]] of the [[National Lacrosse League]], who moved to British Columbia in 2014.<ref>{{cite news |date=June 27, 2013 |title=Stealth moving to Langley, B.C. |url=https://www.heraldnet.com/sports/stealth-moving-to-langley-b-c/ |work=The Everett Herald |accessdate=February 18, 2019}}</ref>\n\nEverett also hosted several minor league soccer teams, including the [[Seattle BigFoot|Everett BigFoot]] of the third-division [[USISL Pro League]], who began play in 1995 and moved to [[West Seattle]] in 1997.<ref>{{cite news |last=Peoples |first=John |date=February 2, 1995 |title=Bigfoot hoping to leave mark on Everett, soccer landscape |page=C9 |url=https://archive.seattletimes.com/archive/?date=19950202&slug=2102732 |work=The Seattle Times |accessdate=March 28, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |date=March 17, 1997 |title=Around the Northwest |page=D8 |work=The Seattle Times}}</ref> The [[North Sound SeaWolves]] of the [[USL Premier Development League]] began play at [[Mariner High School (Everett, Washington)|Mariner High School]] in 2011 and moved to [[Edmonds, Washington|Edmonds]] the following season.<ref>{{cite news |last=Allende |first=Mike |date=October 13, 2011 |title=SeaWolves fans pick team's new logo |url=https://www.heraldnet.com/sports/seawolves-fans-pick-teams-new-logo/ |work=The Everett Herald |accessdate=February 18, 2019}}</ref> Everett Jets FC, an ameatur team based at Memorial Stadium, are set to begin their inaugural 2020 season in the [[Evergreen Premier League]].<ref>{{cite news |last=Patterson |first=Nick |date=January 27, 2020 |title=Community sports roundup: Everett Jets FC to join men's league |url=https://www.heraldnet.com/sports/community-sports-roundup-everett-jets-fc-to-join-mens-league/ |work=The Everett Herald |accessdate=March 28, 2020}}</ref>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Club\n! Sport\n! League\n! Founded\n! Venue\n! Championships\n|-\n| [[Everett AquaSox]]\n| align=center | [[Baseball]]\n| [[Northwest League]]\n| align=center | 1984\n| [[Everett Memorial Stadium|Funko Field]]\n| 1985, 2010\n|-\n| [[Everett Jets FC]]\n| align=center | [[Association football|Soccer]]\n| [[Evergreen Premier League]]\n| align=center | 2020\n| [[Everett Memorial Stadium]]\n| \n|-\n| [[Everett Silvertips]]\n| align=center | [[Ice hockey|Hockey]]\n| [[Western Hockey League]]\n| align=center | 2003\n| [[Angel of the Winds Arena]]\n|\n|}\n\n==Parks and recreation==\n[[File:Everett - Grand Ave Park.jpg|thumb|Grand Ave. Park]]\n\nEverett is home to 40 parks. The biggest parks are Walter E. Hall Park at {{convert|137|acre|km2|1}}, Forest Park at {{convert|111|acre|km2|1}}, Langus Riverfront Park at {{convert|96|acre|km2}}, Kasch Park at {{convert|60|acre|km2}}, Howarth Park at {{convert|28|acre|km2}}, and Thornton A. Sullivan Park at {{convert|27|acre|km2}}.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.everettwa.org/default.aspx?ID=11 |title=Everett Parks in Everett<!-- Bot generated title --> |publisher= |accessdate=February 19, 2018}}</ref> Walter E. Hall Park, near the Boeing plant, sports a golf course and a skate park; Forest Park, a swimming pool, hockey, horseshoes, miles of trails and an animal farm; Langus Park, a boat launch; Kasch Park, four softball fields; Howarth Park, a sandy beach on Puget Sound; and Thornton A. Sullivan Park hosts a sandy swimming beach on Silver Lake as well as public docks for fishing.\n\n===Forest Park===\nForest Park is the oldest public park in Everett. As its name suggests, the park is heavily wooded. It is  home to miles of trails, a playground, and a popular public swimming pool.\n\n===Jetty Island===\n{{main|Jetty Island}}\n\n[[Jetty Island]] is a man-made island and park located in the [[Puget Sound]], just off the Everett, Washington waterfront. The island is two miles long and half a mile wide, approximately 1,800 acres. The island has no plumbing, electricity or structures. During the summer months, a ferry becomes operational, allowing transportation to and from the island. A floating restroom also becomes operational off the island's shore. Jetty Island's unique features provide excellent habitat for birds and juvenile salmon. The island is home to more than 45 bird species including osprey, shorebirds, hawks, eagles, cormorants and ducks. Visitors may see seals surfacing or lounging near the water's edge, or even witness gray whales swimming past during spring migration.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.portofeverett.com/recreation/beaches-kiteboarding/jetty-island-290 |title=Port of Everett : Jetty Island |publisher=}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.historiceverettwaterfront.com/waterfront-special-features/jetty-island |title=Jetty Island \u2013 Everett Waterfront Historical Interpretive Program |first= |last=Everett |publisher=}}</ref>\n\n===Nishiyama Garden===\nNishiyama Garden is a traditional Japanese garden located at the Nippon Business Institute at [[Everett Community College]].  It features Sukiya-style wooden gates, gravel paths, stones, trees, a small stream and a portion of the famous Kintai Bridge from [[Iwakuni|Iwakuni, Japan]], one of Everett's sister cities.<ref>[http://www.everettcc.edu/programs/socsci/nbi/index.cfm?id=5040 Nishiyama Japanese Garden<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref>\n\n===Evergreen Arboretum and Gardens===\nEvergreen Arboretum and Gardens ({{convert|2.4|acre|m2}}) is an [[arboretum]] and park located at the south end of [[American Legion Memorial Park|Legion Park]], at the intersection of Alverson and Marine View Drive.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.evergreenarboretum.com/ |title=Evergreen Arboretum and Gardens |publisher=}}</ref>  Gardens include sculpture and vistas of [[Puget Sound]], as well as:\n\n* Conifer garden \u2013 includes ''[[Chamaecyparis lawsoniana]]'', ''[[Chamaecyparis nootkatensis]]'', ''[[Pfitzeriana]] Aurea'', ''[[Picea glauca]]'', and ''[[Strobus]] 'Nana{{'}}''.\n* Dahlia garden \u2013 a variety of [[dahlia]]s.\n* Japanese Maple grove \u2013 17 varieties of maples, with [[fern]]s and [[hydrangea]]s.\n* Perennial border \u2013 includes artichoke (''[[Cynara scolymus]]''), Japanese forest grass (''[[Hakonechloa macra]]''), giant hyssop (''[[Hyssopus officinalis]]''), dwarf waterlily (''[[Nymphaea]]''), and New Zealand flax (''[[Phormium cookianum]]'').\n* Small Urban Tree Walk\n* White border \u2013 flowers and foliage in white, silver, and blue.\n* Woodland garden \u2013 grotto with Knadhill and [[Exbury Gardens|Exbury]] [[azalea]]s, lace-cap hydrangeas (''[[Hydrangea macrophylla]]''), and ''[[Pieris japonica]]''.\n\n==Education==\n[[File:Everett High School-1.jpg|thumb|[[Everett High School (Washington)|Everett High School]] (part of Everett Public Schools)]]\n\nThe city's public education system is managed by [[Everett Public Schools]] (officially the Everett School District), which has 26 schools, 2,000 staff members, and an enrollment of 20,000 students.<ref>{{cite news |last=Cornfield |first=Jerry |date=October 29, 2019 |title=In Everett school races, they agree more than they don't |url=https://www.heraldnet.com/news/in-everett-school-races-they-agree-more-than-they-dont/ |work=The Everett Herald |accessdate=March 28, 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"Times-Cohn\">{{cite news |date=November 18, 2016 |title=Everett schools chief honored as state Superintendent of Year |url=https://www.seattletimes.com/seattle-news/education/everett-schools-chief-named-state-supe-of-2017/ |work=The Seattle Times |accessdate=November 21, 2016}}</ref> The school district covers {{convert|52|sqmi|sqkm}}, including most of Everett, the city of [[Mill Creek, Washington|Mill Creek]], and the unincorporated area of [[Silver Firs, Washington|Silver Firs]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Census 2010: Everett School District |url=http://data.spokesman.com/census/2010/washington/school-districts/everett-school-district-wa/ |work=[[Spokesman-Review]] |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110304004210/http://data.spokesman.com/census/2010/washington/school-districts/everett-school-district-wa/ |archivedate=March 4, 2011 |accessdate=March 28, 2020}}</ref> The southern and western neighborhoods of Everett are served by the [[Mukilteo School District]], which also has its own high school ([[Mariner High School (Everett, Washington)|Mariner]]) in the area.<ref>{{cite map |date=December 21, 2017 |title=Snohomish County School Districts Map |url=http://www.snoco.org/docs/scd/PDF/PDS_CFP/Snohomish%20County%20School%20District.pdf |publisher=Snohomish County |accessdate=March 28, 2020}}</ref>\n\nEverett Public Schools has three high school campuses: [[Everett High School (Washington)|Everett High School]] near downtown, [[Cascade High School (Everett, Washington)|Cascade High School]] near Casino Corner, and [[Henry M. Jackson High School]] in Mill Creek.<ref name=\"Herald-HighSchool19\">{{cite news |last=Bryan |first=Zachariah |date=May 22, 2019 |title=After year of debate, Everett has new high school boundaries |url=https://www.heraldnet.com/news/after-year-of-debate-everett-has-new-high-school-boundaries/ |work=The Everett Herald |accessdate=March 28, 2020}}</ref> The school district was recognized in 2016 for its high [[graduation]] rates of 90 percent for four-year students and 94.5 percent for five-year students.<ref name=\"Times-Cohn\"/> A fourth high school campus, planned to cost $220&nbsp;million to build, was part of a [[bond measure]] in February 2018 that was rejected by voters, resulting in boundary changes for the existing schools.<ref name=\"Herald-HighSchool19\"/><ref>{{cite news |last=Cornfield |first=Jerry |date=September 22, 2019 |title=Trying again. Everett schools eye a $317M bond in 2020 |url=https://www.heraldnet.com/news/trying-again-everett-schools-eye-a-317m-bond-in-2020/ |work=The Everett Herald |accessdate=March 28, 2020}}</ref> The school district also has five [[middle school]]s and 18 [[elementary school]]s in Everett and Mill Creek.<ref>{{cite web |title=2019-20 Boundary Map |url=https://www.everettsd.org/Page/29519 |publisher=[[Everett Public Schools]] |accessdate=March 28, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Stevick |first=Eric |date=December 8, 2018 |title=Meet Tambark Creek. Everett has a new kid on the block |url=https://www.heraldnet.com/news/meet-tambark-creek-everett-has-a-new-kid-on-the-block/ |work=The Everett Herald |accessdate=March 28, 2020}}</ref> The city is also home to two [[alternative school]]s: Sequoia High School, operated by Everett Public Schools;<ref>{{cite news |last1=Mulligan |first1=Mark |last2=Mulligan |first2=Annie |date=June 28, 2013 |title=If students have the will, Sequoia High has the way |url=https://www.heraldnet.com/news/if-students-have-the-will-sequoia-high-has-the-way/ |work=The Everett Herald |accessdate=March 28, 2020}}</ref> and ACES High School, operated by the Mukilteo School District.<ref>{{cite news |last=Hutton |first=Caleb |date=December 6, 2018 |title=Teen guilty of plotting a massive school shooting in Everett |url=https://www.heraldnet.com/news/everett-teen-with-gun-guilty-of-plotting-school-shooting/ |work=The Everett Herald |accessdate=March 28, 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe Everett area is also home to several [[private school]] systems operated by religious organizations and independent educators, including those that cater to commuters from around the county. The largest private high school in the county is [[Archbishop Murphy High School]], a Catholic school located in southeastern Everett, with an enrollment of 500 students.<ref>{{cite news |last=Slager |first=Melissa |date=December 9, 2006 |title=Private school enrollment rises |url=http://www.heraldnet.com/stories/06/12/09/100loc_b1schools001.cfm |work=The Everett Herald |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20061214170329/http://www.heraldnet.com/stories/06/12/09/100loc_b1schools001.cfm |archivedate=December 14, 2006 |accessdate=March 28, 2020}}</ref> Other major private religious schools include the [[Everett Christian School]], Cedar Park Christian School, and Northshore Christian Academy.<ref>{{cite news |last=Koenig |first=Sarah |date=January 10, 2008 |title=Cedar Park takes over North Sound Christian Schools |url=https://www.heraldnet.com/uncategorized/cedar-park-takes-over-north-sound-christian-schools/ |work=The Everett Herald |accessdate=March 28, 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Higher education===\n\n[[Everett Community College]] (EVCC) is a two-year public [[community college]] that has enrolled 19,000 students from around Snohomish County and 463 total faculty.<ref>{{cite news |last=Davis |first=Jim |date=October 14, 2015 |title=Developer to build dormitory near Everett Community College |url=https://www.heraldnet.com/business/developer-to-build-dormitory-near-everett-community-college/ |work=The Everett Herald Business Journal |accessdate=March 29, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=College Navigator: Everett Community College |url=https://nces.ed.gov/collegenavigator/?id=235149 |work=[[National Center for Education Statistics]] |publisher=[[Institute of Education Sciences]] |accessdate=March 29, 2020}}</ref> The college's main campus is located <!--spans {{convert||acre|ha}}--> in North Everett on the south side of Legion Memorial Golf Course.<ref name=\"Times-WSU11\">{{cite news |last=Long |first=Katherine |date=May 23, 2011 |title=Steps taken toward creating WSU branch campus in Everett |url=http://old.seattletimes.com/html/localnews/2015129940_wsu24m.html |work=The Seattle Times |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170202073035/http://old.seattletimes.com/html/localnews/2015129940_wsu24m.html |archivedate=February 2, 2017 |accessdate=March 29, 2020}}</ref> It was established in 1941 at a former downtown elementary school and moved to its North Everett location in 1958, where it has since expanded several times.{{sfnp|O'Donnell|1993|pages=210\u2013211}}<ref>{{cite news |last1=Slager |first1=Melissa |last2=Warnick |first2=Jennifer |date=August 13, 2005 |title=EvCC carving a place to grow |url=https://www.heraldnet.com/news/evcc-carving-a-place-to-grow/ |work=The Everett Herald |accessdate=March 29, 2020}}</ref>\n\nCivic and business leaders from the Everett area began lobbying the state legislature for a four-year college in the 1990s, proposing a branch of an existing state college to serve Snohomish, Island, and Skagit counties.<ref>{{cite news |last=Brooks |first=Diane |date=December 2, 1994 |title=Bid for college alive in Everett |page=B1 |work=The Seattle Times}}</ref> A site in [[Bothell, Washington|Bothell]] was instead chosen for a [[University of Washington Bothell|northern branch campus]] for the [[University of Washington]] (UW), but only 27 percent of its students were from Snohomish County.<ref>{{cite news |last=Thompson |first=Lynn |date=August 17, 2005 |title=Push for 4-year college revs up |page=H18 |url=http://old.seattletimes.com/html/education/2002442337_4year17n.html |work=The Seattle Times |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180306202952/http://old.seattletimes.com/html/education/2002442337_4year17n.html |archivedate=March 6, 2018 |accessdate=March 29, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Stevick |first=Eric |date=August 22, 2005 |title=Ideas floated for new university |url=https://www.heraldnet.com/news/ideas-floated-for-new-university/ |work=The Everett Herald |accessdate=March 29, 2020}}</ref> In 2007, the state legislature authorized planning funds for a UW branch campus in Snohomish County and a site near [[Everett Station]] was named as a finalist alongside candidates in Lake Stevens and Marysville.<ref name=\"Times-WSU11\"/><ref>{{cite news |last=Perry |first=Nick |date=January 6, 2008 |title=UW Everett: ambitious, but dogged by doubts |page=A1 |url=https://www.seattletimes.com/seattle-news/uw-everett-ambitious-but-dogged-by-doubts/ |work=The Seattle Times |accessdate=March 29, 2020}}</ref> The [[University of Washington North Sound|branch campus project]] was shelved by the state legislature in 2008 amid a funding shortfall for the education system.<ref name=\"Herald-Degrees08\">{{cite news |last=Stevick |first=Eric |date=November 23, 2008 |title=College degrees available in Everett |url=https://www.heraldnet.com/news/college-degrees-available-in-everett/ |work=The Everett Herald |accessdate=March 29, 2020}}</ref>\n\n[[Washington State University Everett]] opened in 2017 as a branch campus of WSU and is located adjacent to the EVCC campus in North Everett.<ref name=\"Times-WSU17\">{{cite news |last=Long |first=Katherine |date=August 11, 2017 |title=WSU's new building: 'the biggest thing Everett has ever done in terms of its future' |url=https://www.seattletimes.com/seattle-news/education/wsus-new-building-the-biggest-thing-everett-has-ever-done-in-terms-of-its-future/ |work=The Seattle Times |accessdate=March 29, 2020}}</ref> The branch campus was conceived as a replacement for the UW proposal and included a WSU takeover of the [[University Center of North Puget Sound]], an alternative degrees program at EVCC, in 2014.<ref name=\"Times-WSU11\"/><ref>{{cite news |last=Harper |first=Christina |date=June 30, 2014 |title=WSU taking over University Center at EvCC |url=https://www.heraldnet.com/news/wsu-taking-over-university-center-at-evcc/ |work=The Everett Herald Business Journal |accessdate=March 29, 2020}}</ref> The EVCC campus also houses a branch of [[Western Washington University]], which it established in 1986.<ref>{{cite web |title=Everett |url=https://www.wwu.edu/everett |publisher=[[Western Washington University]] |accessdate=March 29, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Haglund |first1=Noah |last2=Stevick |first2=Eric |date=August 16, 2017 |title=At long last, WSU Everett's new building is open for business |url=https://www.heraldnet.com/news/at-long-last-wsu-everetts-new-building-open-for-business/ |work=The Everett Herald |accessdate=March 29, 2020}}</ref>\n\nEverett is also home to several private and specialized colleges, including [[City University of Seattle|City University]] and [[Everest College]] near the Everett Mall.<ref>{{cite news |date=December 27, 2011 |title=Snohomish County colleges |url=https://www.heraldnet.com/business/snohomish-county-colleges/ |work=The Everett Herald Business Journal |accessdate=March 29, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |date=November 13, 2017 |title=Altierus to close Everett college, layoff 29 |url=https://www.heraldnet.com/business/altierus-to-close-everett-college-layoff-29/ |work=The Everett Herald Business Journal |accessdate=March 29, 2020}}</ref> The city also has branch campuses for [[Embry\u2013Riddle Aeronautical University]] near the Boeing assembly plant and [[Columbia College (Missouri)|Columbia College]] at Naval Station Everett.<ref>{{cite web |title=Locations: Everett, WA |url=https://worldwide.erau.edu/locations/everett |publisher=[[Embry\u2013Riddle Aeronautical University]] |accessdate=March 29, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Davis |first=Jim |date=August 26, 2015 |title=Columbia College celebrates 20 years in Snohomish County |url=https://www.heraldnet.com/business/columbia-college-celebrates-20-years-in-snohomish-county/ |work=The Everett Herald Business Journal |accessdate=March 29, 2020}}</ref> Everett's two major [[Lutheran]] churches operated a pair of short-lived private colleges in the early 20th century, Bethania College and Columbia College.{{sfnp|O'Donnell|1993|pages=210\u2013211}} [[Henry Cogswell College]], a private institution, moved from Kirkland to Everett in 1996 and closed in 2006.<ref>{{cite news |last=Brooks |first=Diane |date=March 21, 1996 |title=4-year school to locate in Everett |page=B3 |url=https://archive.seattletimes.com/archive/?date=19960321&slug=2320138 |work=The Seattle Times |accessdate=March 29, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Stevick |first1=Eric |last2=Chircop |first2=David |date=June 29, 2006 |title=Cogswell College will close |url=https://www.heraldnet.com/news/cogswell-college-will-close/ |work=The Everett Herald |accessdate=March 29, 2020}}</ref> In the 2010s, [[Bryman College]] and [[Trinity Lutheran College (Washington)|Trinity Lutheran College]] both closed their Everett campuses.<ref>{{cite news |last=Winters |first=Chris |date=January 12, 2016 |title=Trinity Lutheran College in downtown Everett to close |url=https://www.heraldnet.com/news/trinity-lutheran-college-in-downtown-everett-to-close/ |work=The Everett Herald |accessdate=March 29, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Infrastructure==\n\n===Transportation===\n[[File:Everett Station building.jpg|thumb|[[Everett Station]], the city's [[Amtrak]] and [[Sounder commuter rail]] station that also serves local and express buses]]\n\nThe city is located along [[Interstate 5 in Washington|Interstate 5]] (I-5), a major north\u2013south freeway that connects Everett to [[Seattle]] and [[Vancouver]], British Columbia. The Everett\u2013Seattle section of I-5 is rated as one of the most congested in the United States during commuting hours, with an average of 94 minutes to travel {{convert|24|mi|km}} and 182,000 daily vehicles in South Everett.<ref>{{cite news |last=Lindblom |first=Mike |date=February 5, 2018 |title=It's worse than you think: Everett leads the nation in traffic congestion, report says |page=A1 |url=https://www.seattletimes.com/seattle-news/transportation/its-worse-than-you-think-everett-leads-the-nation-in-traffic-congestion-report-says/ |work=The Seattle Times |accessdate=March 29, 2020}}</ref> The city also has several major highways with intercity connections, including [[U.S. Route 2 in Washington|U.S. Route 2]] to [[Wenatchee, Washington|Wenatchee]] via [[Stevens Pass]]; [[Washington State Route 99|State Route 99]] from the Everett Mall to Seattle; [[Washington State Route 526|State Route 526]] to Mukilteo; [[Washington State Route 527|State Route 527]] from the Everett Mall to Mill Creek; and [[Washington State Route 529|State Route 529]] from the waterfront to Marysville.<ref>{{cite map |year=2014 |title=Washington State Highways, 2014\u20132015 |url=https://www.wsdot.wa.gov/sites/default/files/2006/06/13/TouristMapFront_withoutHillshade.pdf |inset=[https://www.wsdot.wa.gov/sites/default/files/2017/08/31/highway-map-PugetSound_Full.pdf Puget Sound] |publisher=Washington State Department of Transportation |accessdate=March 23, 2020}}</ref>\n\nEverett has several public transit and intercity transport services that intersect at [[Everett Station]], a multimodal train and bus station that opened in 2002.<ref>{{cite news |last=Whitley |first=Peyton |date=January 1, 2003 |title=City's new terminal has amassed transit depots in single location |page=I17 |url=http://community.seattletimes.nwsource.com/archive/?date=20030101&slug=station01n |work=The Seattle Times |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140808042501/http://community.seattletimes.nwsource.com/archive/?date=20030101&slug=station01n |archivedate=August 8, 2014 |accessdate=March 29, 2020}}</ref> The station is served by two [[Amtrak]] routes: [[Amtrak Cascades|''Cascades'']], which connects Vancouver to Seattle and [[Portland, Oregon]]; and the ''[[Empire Builder]]'', which travels from Seattle to [[Chicago]].<ref>{{cite news |last=Cantwell |first=Brian J. |date=December 10, 2015 |title=Amtrak restores train service through Washington state |url=https://www.seattletimes.com/life/travel/amtrak-restores-service-through-washington-state/ |work=The Seattle Times |accessdate=March 29, 2020}}</ref> Everett is also the northern terminus of the [[Sounder commuter rail]] system, which is operated by [[Sound Transit]] and travels south to Seattle during [[peak hour]]s with stops in Mukilteo and Edmonds.<ref>{{cite news |last=Lindblom |first=Mike |date=October 16, 2012 |title=Too many empty seats on Sounder north line |page=A1 |url=http://seattletimes.com/html/localnews/2019441910_sounder16m.html |work=The Seattle Times |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130514123023/http://seattletimes.com/html/localnews/2019441910_sounder16m.html |archivedate=May 14, 2013 |accessdate=March 29, 2020}}</ref> The station is served by intercity buses from [[Greyhound Lines]], [[BoltBus]], and [[Northwestern Trailways]], which connect Everett to cities in the Pacific Northwest.<ref>{{cite news |last=Sheets |first=Bill |date=February 6, 2012 |title=Everett Station celebrates 10 years and 17 million visits |url=https://www.heraldnet.com/news/everett-station-celebrates-10-years-and-17-million-visits/ |work=The Everett Herald |accessdate=March 29, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Podsada |first=Janice |date=March 8, 2019 |title=BoltBus links Everett to Seattle and other big I-5 cities |url=https://www.heraldnet.com/news/discount-bus-service-launches-from-everett-station/ |work=The Everett Herald |accessdate=March 29, 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe city-run [[Everett Transit]] system was established in 1969, replacing a private operator that had opened the first [[streetcar]] lines in the city in 1893.<ref>{{cite news |date=November 30, 2008 |title=Everett Transit rolls back fares for 115th birthday |url=https://www.heraldnet.com/news/around-the-county-346/ |work=The Everett Herald |accessdate=March 29, 2020}}</ref> The countywide [[Community Transit]] system, based in Everett, connects to surrounding cities and operates a commuter bus network.<ref>{{cite map |date=September 2019 |title=Community Transit System Map |url=https://www.communitytransit.org/docs/default-source/mappdfs/19septmaps/systemmappdfs/mapsystemsept2019.pdf |publisher=[[Community Transit]] |accessdate=March 29, 2020}}</ref> Its [[bus rapid transit]] system, [[Swift Bus Rapid Transit|Swift]] has two lines that travel through the city: the [[Swift Blue Line|Blue Line]] from Downtown Everett to [[Shoreline, Washington|Shoreline]] via State Route 99; and the [[Swift Green Line|Green Line]], which connects the Boeing plant to Mill Creek and northern Bothell.<ref>{{cite news |last=Giordano |first=Lizz |date=March 21, 2019 |title=From Bothell to Boeing: Green Line bus route begins Sunday |url=https://www.heraldnet.com/news/major-changes-coming-to-community-transit-in-march/ |work=The Everett Herald |accessdate=March 29, 2020}}</ref> Sound Transit also provides [[Sound Transit Express|express bus service]] to [[Bellevue, Washington|Bellevue]] during peak hours and Downtown Seattle at all hours.<ref>{{cite web |date=December 2017 |title=2017 Service Implementation Plan |pages=116\u2013117, 140\u2013141 |url=https://www.soundtransit.org/sites/default/files/2018-service-implementation-plan.pdf |publisher=[[Sound Transit]] |accessdate=March 29, 2020}}</ref> The agency plans to extend its [[Link light rail]] service to Downtown Everett in 2036, as part of the [[Sound Transit 3]] plan passed by voters in 2016.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Haglund |first1=Noah |last2=Giordano |first2=Lizz |date=June 25, 2018 |title=It's getting real: Light rail is coming to the 'burbs |url=https://www.heraldnet.com/news/its-getting-real-light-rail-is-coming-to-the-burbs/ |work=The Everett Herald |accessdate=March 29, 2020}}</ref> From 1910\u20131939, Everett was connected with Seattle by an [[interurban]] railway, which was later replaced by the [[Interurban Trail (Snohomish County)|Interurban Trail]].<ref>{{cite news |last=Giordano |first=Lizz |date=December 2, 2019 |title=The Interurban Railway: Everett's first rapid transit line |url=https://www.heraldnet.com/news/the-interurban-railway-everetts-first-rapid-transit-line/ |work=The Everett Herald |accessdate=March 29, 2020}}</ref>\n\nEverett's airport, [[Paine Field]], is operated by Snohomish County primarily for aerospace businesses and general aviation. The airport was opened in 1936 and was used as a military base and commercial airport until 1966, when Boeing selected it for the site of a major assembly plant.<ref>{{cite news |date=August 7, 2004 |title=Paine Field's journey to flight |url=https://www.heraldnet.com/news/paine-fields-journey-to-flight/ |work=The Everett Herald |accessdate=March 30, 2020}}</ref> Commercial passenger service to Paine Field resumed on March 4, 2019, after the construction of a new terminal operated by a private company.<ref name=\"Times-Paine\">{{cite news |last=Blethen |first=Ryan |date=March 5, 2019 |title=How the first day of commercial flights from Paine Field went |page=A1 |url=https://www.seattletimes.com/life/travel/first-commercial-flight-to-take-off-from-everetts-paine-field-today/ |work=The Seattle Times |accessdate=March 8, 2019}}</ref> The nearest major airports are [[Boeing Field]] in Seattle and [[Seattle-Tacoma International Airport]] in southern King County.<ref name=\"Times-Paine\"/> A private passenger ferry from the Port of Everett provides access to [[Gedney Island|Hat Island]] in Possession Sound.<ref>{{cite news |last=Muhlstein |first=Julie |date=July 31, 2018 |title=Hat Island: The somewhat secret, other-worldy Northwest gem |url=https://www.heraldnet.com/news/close-yet-another-world-its-quite-a-voyage-to-hat-island/ |work=The Everett Herald |accessdate=March 23, 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Utilities===\n\n[[Electric power]] for Everett buildings is provided by the [[Snohomish County Public Utility District]] (PUD), a consumer-owned [[public utility]] that serves all of Snohomish County.<ref>{{cite web |date=October 2018 |title=Quick Facts for Snohomish County PUD |url=https://www.snopud.com/Site/Content/Documents/custpubs/MiniQF_1018.pdf |publisher=[[Snohomish County Public Utility District]] |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20181129142056/https://www.snopud.com/Site/Content/Documents/custpubs/MiniQF_1018.pdf |archivedate=November 29, 2018 |accessdate=March 25, 2020}}</ref> The privately run [[Puget Sound Energy]] provides [[natural gas]] service to the city's residents and businesses.<ref>{{cite web |year=2013 |title=Puget Sound Energy service area |url=http://pse.com/aboutpse/PseNewsroom/MediaKit/1213_ServiceAreaMap_web.pdf |publisher=[[Puget Sound Energy]] |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170128213047/https://pse.com/aboutpse/PseNewsroom/MediaKit/1213_ServiceAreaMap_web.pdf |archivedate=January 28, 2017 |accessdate=March 25, 2020}}</ref> The city government contracts with Rubatino Refuse Removal and [[Waste Management (corporation)|Waste Management]] for curbside [[municipal solid waste|garbage]], [[single-stream recycling|recycling]], and [[yard waste]] collection and disposal.<ref>{{cite web |title=Garbage, Recycling & Compost |url=https://everettwa.gov/637/Garbage-Recycling-Compost |publisher=City of Everett |accessdate=March 25, 2020}}</ref> Everett's municipal [[wastewater]] and [[sewage]] system, which is combined with [[stormwater]] treatment, includes {{convert|145|mi|km}} and primarily empties into the [[Everett Water Pollution Control Facility]] on Smith Island in the Snohomish River delta.<ref>{{cite news |last=Winters |first=Chris |date=December 4, 2014 |title=$320M fix prescribed for Everett's aging sewers |url=https://www.heraldnet.com/news/320m-fix-prescribed-for-everett%C2%92s-aging-sewers/ |work=The Everett Herald |accessdate=March 27, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Sanders |first=Julia-Grace |date=September 12, 2019 |title=Stench wrinkles noses in some north Everett neighborhoods |url=https://www.heraldnet.com/news/odor-overwhelms-some-north-everett-neighborhoods/ |work=The Everett Herald |accessdate=March 27, 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe City of Everett maintains a [[tap water]] system that supplies 80 percent of Snohomish County through interlocal agreements with other municipalities and [[water district]]s.<ref>{{cite news |last=Sheets |first=Bill |date=October 13, 2011 |title=Environmental plan earns Sultan River dam a new 45-year license |url=https://www.heraldnet.com/news/environmental-plan-earns-sultan-river-dam-a-new-45-year-license/ |work=The Everett Herald |accessdate=March 27, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |date=November 2004 |title=Where Does Your Water Come From? |url=https://everettwa.gov/DocumentCenter/View/824/Where-Does-Your-Water-Come-From-PDF |publisher=City of Everett |accessdate=March 27, 2020}}</ref> The system primarily sources its water from [[Spada Lake]], an artificial reservoir on the [[Sultan River]] created by the [[Culmback Dam]] located {{convert|25|mi|km}} east of Everett in the Cascade Mountains. The water is treated at a [[water purification|filtration plant]] at Lake Chaplain, the system's secondary water source, which has a capacity of {{convert|134|e6USgal|kl}} per day and typically handles {{convert|50|e6gal|kl|abbr=unit}} per day.<ref>{{cite news |last=Winters |first=Chris |date=September 8, 2016 |title=Anticipating growth, Everett looks to boost water flow |url=https://www.heraldnet.com/news/everett-to-test-increasing-water-flow-to-customers/ |work=The Everett Herald |accessdate=March 27, 2020}}</ref> The Sultan River basin has been used as the main source of the city's water since 1917; the modern Spada Lake reservoir was formed in 1965 by the construction of the Culmback Dam, co-owned by Everett and the Snohomish County PUD.{{sfnp|O'Donnell|1993|p=187}}\n\nThe city is covered by several telecommunications companies that provide [[telephone]], [[broadband internet]], and other services. [[Frontier Communications Northwest|Frontier Communications]] is the largest telecommunications provider in the city and inherited its legacy system from [[GTE|GTE Northwest]] and [[Verizon]].<ref>{{cite news |last=Podsada |first=Janice |date=June 3, 2019 |title=A new-wave broadband firm dials up Frontier Communications |url=https://www.heraldnet.com/business/a-new-wave-broadband-firm-dials-up-frontier-communications/ |work=The Everett Herald |accessdate=March 27, 2020}}</ref> Other major providers in the Everett area include [[Xfinity|Comcast Xfinity]], [[CenturyLink]], and [[Wave Broadband]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Everett Comprehensive Plan Capital Facilities and Utilities Element |page=36 |url=https://everettwa.gov/DocumentCenter/View/4861/Chapter-06-Capital-Facilities-and-Utilities-PDF |publisher=City of Everett |accessdate=March 27, 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Healthcare===\n\nEverett is home to [[Providence Regional Medical Center Everett]], a system of two general hospitals operated by [[Providence Health & Services]]. The hospital system was formed in 1994 by the merger of two existing hospitals in Everett: the Everett General Hospital, opened in January 1894 as the city's first hospital;{{sfnp|O'Donnell|1993|p=211}} and Providence Hospital, established in 1905 near Downtown Everett.<ref>{{cite web |title=The Providence Story |url=https://washington.providence.org/locations-directory/r/regional-medical-center/about/history |publisher=[[Providence Health & Services]] |accessdate=March 25, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Muhlstein |first=Julie |date=August 27, 2014 |title=Spirit of giving is a cornerstone of Snohomish County history |url=https://www.heraldnet.com/news/spirit-of-giving-is-a-cornerstone-of-snohomish-county-history/ |work=The Everett Herald |accessdate=March 25, 2020}}</ref> The existing Providence Hospital was renamed the Providence Pacific Campus, while the former General Hospital became the Colby Campus, which was expanded in 2011 with a 12-story medical tower.<ref name=\"Herald-Providence11\">{{cite news |last=Salyer |first=Sharon |date=May 15, 2011 |title=A $460 million gamble |url=https://www.heraldnet.com/news/a-460-million-gamble/ |work=The Everett Herald |accessdate=March 25, 2020}}</ref> The Providence campuses have a combined capacity of 571 beds and 3,300 employees.<ref name=\"Herald-Providence11\"/><ref>{{cite news |last=Salyer |first=Sharon |date=January 16, 2017 |title=Everett Providence hospital seeks state OK for 70 more beds |url=https://www.heraldnet.com/news/everett-providence-hospital-seeks-state-ok-for-70-more-beds/ |work=The Everett Herald |accessdate=March 25, 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe city also has several medical services with [[clinic]]s and specialized facilities operated by Providence and other providers. [[Kaiser Permanente]] has a five-story medical tower in Downtown Everett with a walk-in clinic, specialty services, and an [[urgent care]] clinic.<ref>{{cite web |title=Everett Medical Center |url=https://wa.kaiserpermanente.org/html/public/locations/everett |publisher=[[Kaiser Permanente]] |accessdate=March 25, 2020}}</ref> The building originally opened for [[Group Health Cooperative|Group Health]] in 1994 to consolidate its three clinics in Everett and is planned to be expanded in 2020.<ref>{{cite news |last=Alexander |first=Karen |date=April 30, 1993 |title=Group Health sets Everett groundbreaker |page=D8 |work=The Seattle Times}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Giordano |first=Lizz |date=October 2, 2019 |title=Kaiser Permanente plans big growth spurt in Everett |url=https://www.heraldnet.com/news/kaiser-permanente-plans-big-growth-spurt-in-everett/ |work=The Everett Herald |accessdate=March 25, 2020}}</ref> [[The Everett Clinic]] is based in the city and operates medical facilities across Snohomish County, serving 320,000 patients.<ref>{{cite news |last=Salyer |first=Sharon |date=February 29, 2016 |title=DaVita HealthCare Partners completes Everett Clinic purchase |url=https://www.heraldnet.com/news/davita-healthcare-partners-completes-everett-clinic-purchase/ |work=The Everett Herald |accessdate=March 25, 2020}}</ref> The system was founded in 1924 and acquired in 2016 by [[DaVita Inc.]]; it was then sold to [[UnitedHealth Group]]'s [[Optum]] a year later.<ref>{{cite news |last=Davis |first=Jim |date=December 6, 2017 |title=DaVita to sell off medical groups including The Everett Clinic |url=https://www.heraldnet.com/business/davita-to-sell-off-medical-groups-including-the-everett-clinic/ |work=The Everett Herald |accessdate=March 25, 2020}}</ref> The non-profit Community Health Center of Snohomish County operates four medical clinics in Everett, providing services to primarily low-income and uninsured patients.<ref>{{cite news |last=Salyer |first=Sharon |date=January 16, 2018 |title=New Everett clinic to ease long wait times for appointments |url=https://www.heraldnet.com/news/community-health-center-opening-its-seventh-clinic/ |work=The Everett Herald |accessdate=March 25, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Notable people==\n{{main|List of people from Everett, Washington}}\n\n==Sister cities==\n\nEverett has the following [[Town twinning|sister city]] relationships:<ref>{{cite web |title=Washington's Sister Cities Relationships |url=https://www.ltgov.wa.gov/washington-sister-cities |publisher=[[Lieutenant Governor of Washington]] |accessdate=March 21, 2020}}</ref>\n\n* {{flagdeco|JPN}} [[Iwakuni]], [[Yamaguchi Prefecture|Yamaguchi]], Japan (since 1962)<ref>{{cite news |last=Fiege |first=Gale |date=July 23, 2012 |title=Everett celebrates 50 years with Japanese sister city |url=https://www.heraldnet.com/news/everett-celebrates-50-years-with-japanese-sister-city/ |work=The Everett Herald |accessdate=March 21, 2020}}</ref>\n* {{flagdeco|IRL}} [[Sligo]], [[County Sligo]], Ireland\n* {{flagdeco|RUS}} [[Sovetskaya Gavan]], [[Khabarovsk Krai]], Russia\n\n==Gallery==\n<gallery>\nFile:Everett - County Campus.jpg|Snohomish County Government Campus\nFile:Everett Events Center.jpg|Everett Events Centre (now Angel of the Winds Arena)\nFile:Everett - Hewitt Ave.jpg|Downtown\nFile:Everett Theater 01.jpg| Historic Everett Theatre\nFile:Everett Library 01.jpg| Everett Public Library\nFile:Everett Library 02.jpg| Everett Public Library\nFile:Everett - Bethel Baptist.jpg| Bethel Baptist Church\nFile:Everett - Trinity Episcopal.jpg|Trinity Episcopal Church (1920)\nFile:Everett - First Presbyterian.jpg|First Presbyterian Church\nFile:Everett - FPC Stained Glass.jpg|First Presbyterian Church\nFile:Everett - Public Art.JPG|Public Art\nFile:Everett - Old Courthouse.jpg|Old County Courthouse\nFile:Everett - War Memorial.jpg|War Memorial\nFile:Everett - Armed Forces.jpg|Armed Forces Memorial\nFile:Everett - Colby Ave.jpg|Downtown\nFile:Everett - Kimberly Clark.jpg|Kimberly-Clark Paper Plant\nFile:Naval Station Everett.jpg|Naval Station Everett\nFile:Everett Marina.jpg|Everett Marina\n</gallery>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==Bibliography==\n{{refbegin}}\n* {{cite book |ref=harv |last1=Cameron |first1=David A. |last2=LeWarne |first2=Charles P. |last3=May |first3=M. Allan |last4=O'Donnell |first4=Jack C. |last5=O'Donnell |first5=Lawrence E. |year=2005 |title=Snohomish County: An Illustrated History |publisher=Kelcema Books LLC |location=Index, Washington |isbn=978-0-9766700-0-1 |oclc=62728798}}\n* {{cite book |ref=harv |last=Clark |first=Norman H. |year=1970 |title=Mill Town: A Social History of Everett, Washington, From Its Earliest Beginnings on the Shores of Puget Sound to the Tragic and Infamous Event Known as the Everett Massacre |publisher=[[University of Washington Press]] |isbn=978-0-295-95241-3 |oclc=28005191}}\n* {{cite book |ref=harv |last=O'Donnell |first=Lawrence E. |year=1993 |title=Everett Past and Present: A Centennial History of Everett |page=253 |publisher=K&H Printers |isbn=978-0-89716-275-3 |oclc=436832753}}\n{{refend}}\n\n==Archives==\n{{refbegin}}\n* [http://digital.lib.washington.edu/findingaids/view?docId=EverettEducationAssociation3849.xml Everett Education Association Records.] 1937\u20132002. 28.06 cubic feet. At the [http://www.lib.washington.edu/specialcoll/laws Labor Archives of Washington, University of Washington Libraries Special Collections.]\n{{refend}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category}}\n{{EB1911 Poster|Everett, Washington}}\n* {{wikivoyage-inline|Everett (Washington)|Everett, Washington}}\n* {{official website|https://www.everettwa.gov/}}\n* {{dmoz|Regional/North_America/United_States/Washington/Localities/E/Everett}}\n\n{{Everett, Washington}}\n{{Snohomish County, Washington}}\n{{Washington}}\n{{Seattle Metro}}\n{{Geographic Location (8-way)\n|Northwest = [[Port Gardner Bay]]\n|North     = [[Tulalip Indian Reservation]]/[[Marysville, Washington|Marysville]]\n|Northeast = [[Marysville, Washington|Marysville]]/[[Lake Stevens, Washington|Lake Stevens]]\n|West      = [[Gedney Island (Washington)|Hat Island]]/[[Possession Sound]]\n|Center    = Everett\n|South     = [[Mill Creek, Washington|Mill Creek]]/[[Lynnwood, Washington|Lynnwood]]\n|Southwest = [[Mukilteo, Washington|Mukilteo]]\n|Southeast = [[Snohomish, Washington|Snohomish]]\n|East      = [[Lake Stevens, Washington|Lake Stevens]]\n}}\n{{Washington cities and mayors of 100,000 population}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Everett, Washington]]\n[[Category:Cities in Washington (state)]]\n[[Category:Cities in Snohomish County, Washington]]\n[[Category:County seats in Washington (state)]]\n[[Category:Industrial Workers of the World]]\n[[Category:Populated places established in 1890]]\n[[Category:Populated places on Puget Sound]]\n[[Category:Port settlements in Washington (state)]]\n[[Category:1890 establishments in Washington (state)]]\n[[Category:Cities in the Seattle metropolitan area]]\n", "name_user": "SounderBruce", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eHistory:starting 1891", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Everett,_Washington"}
{"title_page": "Australian Classification Board", "text_new": "{{Use Australian English|date=October 2013}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2013}}\n{{Infobox Government agency\n|agency_name     = Classification Board\n|formed          = {{start date and age|1970}} (as Australian Classification Board)\n|logo            = File:Australian Classification Board crest.gif\n|jurisdiction    = Commonwealth of Australia\n|superseding     =\n|minister1_name  = [[Paul Fletcher (politician)|Paul Fletcher]]\n|minister1_pfo   = [[Minister for Communications (Australia)|Minister for Communications]]\n|parent_agency   = [[Department of Communications and the Arts]] (current parent agency), OFLC (Original parent agency), [[Australian Classification Review Board]] (sister agency)\n|website         = {{url|http://www.classification.gov.au}}\n}}\nThe '''Australian Classification Board''' ('''ACB''' or '''CB''') is an [[Australian]] [[Government of Australia|Government]] [[Statute|statutory]] body responsible for the classification and censorship of films, video games and publications for [[exhibition]], sale or hire in Australia. The ACB was established in 1970 and was once part of the '''Office of Film and Literature Classification''' ('''OFLC'''), which was dissolved in 2006. The Department of Communications and the Arts now provides administrative support to the ACB and decisions made by the ACB may be reviewed by the [[Australian Classification Review Board]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.classification.gov.au/About/Pages/Review-Board.aspx|title=Review Board {{!}} Australian Classification|website=www.classification.gov.au|access-date=2016-04-30}}</ref> The ACB now operates under the ''Commonwealth Classification Act 1995''.\n\nThe ACB does not directly censor material by ordering cuts or changes. However, it is able to effectively censor media by refusing classification and making the media illegal for hire, exhibition and importation to Australia. \n\nThe classification system has several levels of \"restricted\" categories, prohibiting sale, exhibition or use of some materials to those who are under a prescribed age. In 2005, video and computer games became subject to the same classification ratings and restrictions as films (with the exception of the R18+ and X18+ ratings), in response to confusion by parents.<ref>{{Cite news|edition=1 \u2013 State |page=11 |title=Games get film ratings |work=The Daily Telegraph |date=6 July 2005 |url=http://www.news.com.au/story/0,10117,15534581-421,00.html |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20050609030406/http://www.news.com.au/story/0%2C10117%2C15534581-421%2C00.html |archivedate=9 June 2005 |url-status=dead }}</ref> Despite a line in the ''National Classification Code'' stating that \"adults should be able to read, hear and see what they want\", the adult R18+ classification was not applied to video games in Australia until 1 January 2013.<ref>[http://www.comlaw.gov.au/Details/F2013C00006 The Classification Code; May 2005]</ref>\n\n==History==\nThe Australian Classification Board was created in 1970 to classify or rate all films (and later in 1994, [[video games]]) that came into Australia. In the early years of the system, beginning in November 1971, there were four ratings:\n\n*''G'' for \"general exhibition\", carried over from the previous ratings system\n*''NRC'' for \"not recommended for children under 12\" (previously ''X, A'' or ''not suitable for children.'' This later became ''PG'' for \"parental guidance\")\n*''M'' for \"mature audiences\" (later became ''M 15+'' from the late 1980s until 2005)\n*''R'' for \"restricted exhibition\"<ref>{{cite news|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=uLIpAAAAIBAJ&sjid=JuUDAAAAIBAJ&pg=4106,478776&dq=fritz+the+cat&hl=en|title=Censorship Classifications|date=1 July 1973|accessdate=18 September 2010|work=[[Sydney Morning Herald]]|page=87}}</ref> (previously ''SOA'' or ''suitable only for adults''.  This later became ''R 18+'' in the late 1980s)\n\nThe ''MA 15+'' rating was introduced in 1993, to flag content that was too strong for the ''M'' classification, but not so much so that the content should be restricted only to persons over the age of 18.<ref>Cole, R., Driscoll, C., & Grealy, L. (2018). Classifying adulthood: A history of governing minority in media classi\ufb01cation. In Youth, Technology, Governance, Experience (p. 74). Routledge.</ref>\n\nThe Office of Film and Literature Classification (OFLC) was reorganised in 1994, and oversaw the ACB. In 2005 the OFLC was dissolved and supervision of the ACB transferred to the [[Attorney-General's Department (Australia)|Attorney-General's Department]].\n\nThe current colour-coded classification markings for films and computer games were introduced in May 2005.<ref>[http://www.classification.gov.au/About/AnnualReports/Documents/673.pdf Annual Report 2004\u20132005]</ref>\n\nIn August 2014, the ACB introduced amendments to allow for the automated classification process employed by the [[International Age Rating Coalition]]. This new process reduces the costs of video game developers as they seek to obtain ratings for their products that are distributed digitally online.<ref>http://au.ign.com/articles/2014/09/01/getting-digitally-distributed-games-classified-in-australia-to-be-cost-free</ref>\n\n==Overview==\nThe board operates on a procedure that primarily involves [[decision-making]]. The members must communicate their views clearly and appreciate the views of others. Board members would be exposed to a wide range of material, including content that is confronting and offensive. Every film and computer game has to be classified before it can be legally made available to the public. Some [[publications]] also need to be classified. Failure to give classification (especially for unclassified material that is likely to be classified RC) is an implicit [[ban (law)|ban]] (except for exempt films, games, and publications). It is an offence \"to display, demonstrate, sell, hire, publicly exhibit or advertise a film or computer game\" without having it classified. Some films and documentaries (such as [[current affairs (news format)|current affairs]] and those created for business, scientific and [[Video lesson|education]] purposes) are exempt from classification unless, if classified, they would be ''M'' or above.<ref>http://www.artslaw.com.au/info-sheets/info-sheet/classification-and-censorship/</ref>\n\nThere are legal age restrictions for the ratings of ''MA 15+'' and ''R 18+''. ''X 18+'' is a special restriction rating for adult content. The other classification categories (''G'', ''PG'' and ''M'') are merely recommendations and they are not submitted to legal age restrictions. ''RC'' (banned) material cannot be sold, hired or distributed to any persons. A film or video game's context is crucial in determining whether a classifiable element is justified by the story-line or themes.\n\nThe ACB decides what consumer advice accompanies each classification. They indicate the elements in films and computer games which caused the classification and help consumers make choices about what they read, view or play. There are six classifiable elements for films: ''themes'' (rape, suicide, racism, etc.), ''violence'' (the level of violence and how threatening it is in its context), ''sex'' (intercourse and references to sex), ''language'' (the level of coarse language), ''drug use'' (the use of, and references to, drugs) and ''nudity'' (the explicitness of nudity). Consumer advice appears with the classification symbol on products, packaging and in advertisements. Consumer advice is not given if the element in question would be acceptable at a lower classification.<ref>http://www.classification.gov.au/Public/Resources/Pages/Parents.aspx</ref>\n\nThe ACB also classifies material submitted by the police, the [[Australian Customs and Border Protection Service]] and the [[Australian Communications and Media Authority]]. The board does not classify live performances, audio CDs and television shows. Television is regulated by the Australian Communications and Media Authority.<ref>{{Cite news | page= 7 | last = Canna | first = Xavier La | title = New classifications pave way for R-rated games |work=The Age |location=Australia | accessdate = 2012-08-05 | date = 6 June 2005 | url = http://www.theage.com.au/news/National/New-classifications-pave-way-for-Rrated-games/2005/06/05/1117910187614.html }}</ref> Film classification also normally applies to Internet streaming services. In January 2019, for the first time, [[Netflix]] was given the go-ahead to self-regulate film and television classification on its streaming platform, allowing the company to rank content between ''G'' and ''R18+''.<ref>[https://www.smh.com.au/business/companies/netflix-gets-approval-to-classify-own-shows-after-two-year-trial-20190120-p50sim.html Netflix gets approval to classify own shows after two-year trial]</ref>\n\n== Film and video game classifications ==\n<!-- PLEASE STOP COMPARING THE RATINGS TO OTHER COUNTRIES' RATING SYSTEMS.-->\n<!-- PLEASE DO NOT LIST THE \"MA15+\" RATING AS \"UNRESTRICTED\". Only E, G, PG and M are legally unrestricted.-->\n<!-- PLEASE DO NOT LIST THE \"M\" RATING AS \"RESTRICTED\". SEE TALK PAGE. Only MA15+, R18+ and X18+ are legally restricted in accordance to the ACB classification website: http://www.classification.gov.au/Classificationmarkings/Pages/Classificationmarkingsonfilmandcomputergames.aspx -->\n\n===Unrestricted/advisory===\nThe classifications below are ''unrestricted'' and may require parental ''advisory'',  but do not impose any legal restrictions on access to or distribution of material.<ref name=\"cats explained\">{{cite web |title=Information for Parents: Classification categories explained |publisher=Australian Classification Board |url=http://www.classification.gov.au/Public/Resources/Pages/Parents.aspx |accessdate=9 May 2015}}</ref><ref name=\"Fact Sheets\">{{cite web |last=Clare |first=Jason (Minister for Justice) |title=Guidelines for the Classification of Films 2012 |date=10 December 2012 |publisher=Commonwealth of Australia |url=http://www.comlaw.gov.au/Details/F2012L02541 |accessdate=10 May 2015}}</ref>\n\n[[File:OFLC small E.svg|90px]] [[File:Exempt for classification.png|280px]]\n\n* ''Exempt (E)'' \u2013 Only very specific types of material (including educational material and artistic performances) can be exempt from classification, and the material cannot contain anything that exceeds the constraints of the PG classification.<ref>{{cite web |title=Is it exempt? |publisher=Australian Classification Board |url=http://www.classification.gov.au/Industry/Journey/Pages/Exemptions/Step1.aspx |accessdate=9 May 2015}}</ref> The assessment of exemption may be made by the distributor or exhibitor (self-assessed) without needing to submit the product for certification by the ACB. Self-assessed exempt films cannot use the official marking although it is advised that films and computer games that are self-assessed as exempt display, \"This film/computer game is exempt from classification\".\n\n[[File:G tag.svg|90px]] [[File:OFLC large G.svg|280px]]\n\n* ''General (G)'' \u2013 Contains material available for general viewing. This category does not necessarily designate a children's film or game. Although not mandatory at this category, the board may provide consumer information. Consumer advice at ''G'' classification usually relates to impacts on very young children. The content is very mild in impact.\n**''Themes'' should have a very low sense of threat or menace, and be justified by context.\n**''Violence'' should have only a low sense of threat or menace, and be justified by context.\n**''Sexual activity'' should be very mild and very discreetly implied, and be justified by context.\n**''Coarse language'' should be very mild and infrequent and justified by context.\n**''Drug use'' should be implied only very discreetly, and be justified by context.\n**''Nudity'' should be justified by context.\n\n[[File:PG.svg|90px]] [[File:OFLC large PG.svg|280px]]\n\n* ''Parental guidance (PG)'' \u2013 Not recommended for viewing or playing by people under 15 without guidance from parents or guardians. Contains material that young viewers may find confusing or upsetting. The content is mild in impact.\n**''Themes'' should have a very low sense of threat or menace, and be justified by context.\n**''Violence'' should be mild and infrequent, and be justified by context. Sexual violence is not permitted.\n**''Sexual activity'' should be mild and discreetly implied, and be justified by context.\n**''Coarse language'' should be mild and infrequent, and be justified by context.\n**''Sex, nudity and drug use'' should be mild, infrequent, \"discreetly implied\" and \"justified by context\".\n**''Drug use''' and '''nudity'' should be justified by context.\n\n[[File:M.svg|90px]] [[File:OFLC large M.svg|280px]]\n\n* ''Mature (M)'' \u2013 Recommended for people aged 15 years and over. People under 15 may legally access this material because it is an advisory category. This category contains material that may require a mature perspective, but is not deemed too strong for younger viewers. The content is moderate in impact, although in recent years, the \"moderate\" indicator prefix is omitted from the consumer advice, eg. \"moderate violence\" is referred to as \"violence\".\n**''Themes'' may have a moderate sense of threat or menace, if justified by context.\n**''Moderate violence'' is permitted, if \"justified by context\". Sexual violence should be very limited and justified by context.\n**''Sexual activity'' should be discreetly implied, if \"justified by context\".\n**''Coarse Language'' may be used. Aggressive or strong coarse language should be infrequent and justified by context.\n**''Drug use''' and ''nudity''' should be justified by context.\n\n===Restricted===\nBy contrast, the classifications below are legally ''restricted'': it is illegal to sell or exhibit material so classified to anyone younger than the mentioned minimum age.<ref name=\"cats explained\"/><ref name=\"Fact Sheets\"/>\n\n[[File:MA 15+ classification tag from OFLC.svg|90px]] [[File:OFLC large MA15+.svg|280px]]\n\n* ''Mature accompanied (MA 15+)'' \u2013  Contains material that is considered unsuitable for exhibition by persons under the age of 15. People under 15 may legally purchase, rent, exhibit or view such content only under the supervision of a parent or adult guardian. A person may be asked to show proof of age before renting or purchasing an ''MA 15+'' film or computer game. The content is strong in impact.\n**''Realistic violence'' of medium intensity is permitted. Violent depictions with a \"high degree or realism\" is accepted only if \"justified by context\". Stylised violence, however, can be \"more detailed\".\n**''Strong Violence'' is permitted, although if it is bloody and strong it should be \"infrequent\" or \"justified by context\".\n**''Sexual violence'' is permitted only if it is \"not frequent, gratuitous or exploitative\".\n**''Sexual activity'' may be \"discreetly implied\" or \"simulated\".\n**''Nudity'' is permitted, but in a sexual context it should \"not be exploitative\".\n**''Frightening or intense scenes'' should \"not disturb a reasonable adult\".\n**''Aggressive and very strong coarse language'' may be used but it should \"not be exploitative\".\n**''Drug use'' may be depicted, but not in an \"advocatory manner\".\n**''Themes'', if strong, should be justified by context.\n\n[[File:OFLC small R18+.svg|90px]] [[File:OFLC large R18+.svg|280px]]\n\n* ''Restricted (R 18+)'' \u2013 Contains material that is considered unsuitable for exhibition to persons under the age of 18. People under 18 may not legally buy, rent, exhibit or view ''R 18+'' classified content. A person may be asked for proof of their age before purchasing, hiring or viewing an ''R 18+'' film or computer game at a retail store or cinema. Some material classified ''R 18+'' may be offensive to sections of the adult community. The content is high in impact.\n**''Realistic and explicit depictions of violence'' is permitted, but violence that is \"frequently gratuitous, cruel, exploitative and offensive to a reasonable adult\" is not permitted.\n**''Themes'' can have a \"very high degree of intensity\" but should not be \"exploitative\".\n**''Sexual violence'' is permitted only to the extent that they are \"necessary to the narrative\" and \"not exploitative\" or \"not shown in detail\".\n**''Sexual activity'' can be \"realistically simulated\", but depiction of \"[[Unsimulated sex|actual sexual activity]]\" is not permitted.\n**''Drug use'' can be shown but \"not gratuitously detailed\" and should also \"not be promoted or encouraged\". For computer games, drug use related to \"incentives and rewards\" is not permitted.\n**''Nudity'' in a sexual context should \"not include obvious genital contact\".\n**''Coarse language'' is virtually unrestricted.\n\n[[File:OFLC X 18 classification tag.svg|90px]] [[File:OFLC large X18+.svg|280px]]\n\n* ''Restricted (X 18+)'' \u2013 Contains material that is [[pornographic]] in nature. People under 18 may not legally buy, rent, possess, exhibit or view these films. The exhibition or sale of these films to people under the age of 18 years is a criminal offence carrying a maximum fine of $5,500. Films classified as ''X 18+'' are banned (via state government legislation) from being sold or rented in all Australian states (but are legal to possess except in certain parts of the [[Northern Territory]]) and are legally available to purchase only in the [[Australian Capital Territory]] and the Northern Territory. Importing ''X 18+'' material from these territories to any other state is legal (as the [[Australian Constitution]] forbids any restrictions on trade between the states and territories). The content is sexually explicit, and the rating does not exist for video games.\n**This rating applies to films that \"depict unsimulated sexual content only\". Depictions of sexual violence, coercion and \"sexually assaultive\" language are not allowed in the category. Fetishes such as body piercing, \"[[golden showers]]\", [[Bondage (BDSM)|bondage]], [[BDSM|spanking or fisting]] are also not permitted.\n\n===Other labels===\n\n[[File:Refused Classification Rating.svg|90px]]\n\n* ''{{vanchor|RC}} (Refused classification)'' \u2013 Contains material that, while being, in most cases, legal to possess, is considered offensive to the standards of morality, decency and propriety generally accepted by a \"reasonable adult\" to the extent that it should not be classified. Classification is mandatory, and films that are refused classification by the ACB are legally banned for sale, hire or public exhibition, carrying a maximum [[fine (penalty)|fine]] of $275,000 and/or 10 years in prison if an individual or organisation is found to be in breach of this. It is, however, legal to possess ''RC'' films and games for people over 18 (except in [[Western Australia]] and certain parts of the Northern Territory) unless they contain illegal content (such as [[child pornography]]). The content is very high in impact.\n** Films and games that exceed the ''X 18+'' and ''R 18+'' ratings (respectively) are refused classification by the ACB. Content that may be refused classification includes, but is not limited to:\n*** Detailed instruction or promotion in matters of crime or violence.\n*** The promotion or provision of instruction in paedophile activity.\n*** Descriptions or depictions of child sexual abuse or any other exploitative or offensive descriptions or depictions involving a person who is, or appears to be, a child under 18 years.\n*** Gratuitous, exploitative or offensive depictions of:\n****  violence with a very high degree of impact or which are excessively frequent, prolonged or detailed;\n**** ( cruelty or real violence which are very detailed or which have an extremely high impact;\n****  sexual violence.\n*** Depictions of practices such as bestiality, necrophilia or other practices that are considered revolting or abhorrent. \n*** Gratuitous, exploitative or offensive depictions of:\n****  activity accompanied by fetishes or practices that are offensive or abhorrent;\n****  incest fantasies or other fantasies that are offensive or abhorrent.\n\n[[File:Check the Classification Australia.jpg|150px]] \n* ''Check the classification (CTC)'' \u2013 The content has been assessed and approved for advertising unclassified films and computer games. \"This film has advertising approval. Check the classification closer to the released date\" is usually written on the marking.\n**Any advertising of unclassified films and games must display the ''CTC'' message on posters, trailers, on the internet, and any other types of advertising.\n**Once the content is classified, the classification marking replaces the ''CTC'' marking on all advertising material.\n\n== Literature ratings ==\nPublications such as books and magazines (though they would also include other printed media such as calendars, cards and catalogues) are required to be classified if they contain depictions or descriptions of sexuality, drugs, nudity or violence that are unsuitable for a [[minor (law)|minor]] or an adult who would take offence if sold as an unrestricted publication.\n\nPublication classifications are most commonly applied to magazines with visual depictions of nudity or sexual activity, such as many [[men's magazines]]. It is uncommon for these ratings to appear on books, even those dealing with adult themes, except in the most controversial cases.\n\n[[File:OFCL Australia Lit Rating- U.png|Unrestricted]] or [[File:OFCL Australia Lit Rating - UM.png|Unrestricted M (mature)]]\n*''Unrestricted''{{spaced ndash}}These publications are unrestricted, although they may not be recommended for readers under 15 years.\n\n[[File:OFCL Australia Lit Rating - R1.png|Category 1 restricted]]\n*''Category 1 restricted''{{Spaced ndash}}These publications are not available to persons under 18 years. These may contain images of sexualised nudity. They must be distributed in a sealed wrapper. Their covers must be suitable for public display.\n\n[[File:OFCL Australia Lit Rating - R2.png|Category 2 restricted]]\n*''Category 2 restricted''{{Spaced ndash}}Just like ''category 1 restricted'' publications, they are not available to persons under 18 years. However, they contain explicit images of actual sexual activity which are not permissible under ''category 1'', and may only be displayed in sites that are restricted to adults. Therefore, no publications that are likely to be classified ''category 2 restricted'' may be displayed in public registered events.\n\n[[File:Refused Classification Rating.svg|90px]]\n*''RC''{{Spaced ndash}}''RC'' publications are banned and cannot be sold or displayed anywhere in Australia.\n\nThe ''restricted'' publications are for adults and they are not to be sold to people under 18 (and in [[Queensland]] under state law). They have content, such as nudity or explicit sexual content, that could offend some sections of the adult community. The ''restricted'' categories are subject to various restrictions in different states; for example, one or both categories may only be sold in adults-only premises in certain states. For this reason, some adult magazines are published in two editions in Australia, or just one edited edition which can be sold anywhere with a warning, as ''unrestricted mature''.\n\n==Controversies==\n\n===Film===\n{{See also|List of films banned in Australia}}\n\n*[[Pasolini]]'s ''[[Sal\u00f2, or the 120 Days of Sodom]]'' has twice been banned in Australia. The Home Affairs Minister, [[Brendan O'Connor (politician)|Brendan O'Connor]], asked the Classification Review Board to reassess the decision;<ref>[http://www.smh.com.au/nsw/minister-asks-censors-to-reassess-approval-of-sadistic-film-20100416-skg2.html Minister asks censors to reassess approval of sadistic film]. SMH (17 April 2010).</ref> however, the review failed to find any fault in the classification. The film was banned in 1997, and was released after two failed attempts in September 2010, when the ''ACB'' classified an uncut version of ''Sal\u00f2'' R18+, mainly due to extra material providing greater context.\n*In 1992, Island World Communications Ltd and [[Manga Entertainment]] Australia Ltd had ''[[Urotsukidoji]]: Legend of the Overfiend'' submitted to the ''OFLC''. It was the first animated feature to be banned in Australia and the feature was banned outright, similar to ''[[Violence Jack]]''. ''Urotsukidoji'' was then censored to meet the OFLC's standards. The Australian version is the most censored in the [[western world]]. Many fans of [[anime]] imported uncensored versions of ''Urotsukidoji: Legend of the Overfiend'' from the [[United Kingdom|UK]]. The rest of the ''Urotsukidoji'' series was censored in Australia, with many still importing or downloading the American versions.\n*''[[Ninja Scroll]]'' was originally released in 1994 in Australia by ''Manga Entertainment Ltd''. It originally had the MA15+ rating on the VHS originally, but this was overturned in 1997 when [[Phillip Ruddock]] had the anime reviewed after an uncut screening of the movie on [[Special Broadcasting Service|SBS]]. A few months later it was given the R18+ rating and was uncut, then edited again, eventually using the [[BBFC]] cut of it. This was overturned in 2003 when [[Madman Entertainment]] and Manga Entertainment Ltd. released the uncut version.\n*''[[Romance (1999 film)|Romance]]'', a new crop within the ''[[arthouse]]'' genre, which features short scenes of [[Unsimulated sex|actual sex]] began to attract closer scrutiny. The film was initially refused classification in Australia, before it was awarded an R18+ on appeal.<ref name=\"aus\">{{cite web|url=http://refused-classification.com/censorship/films/romance-1999.html|title=Romance (1999)|publisher=Refused-Classification.com|accessdate=9 December 2011}}</ref> It single-handedly paved the way for actual sex to be accommodated in the R18+ classification in Australia.<ref name=\"aus\"/>\n* ''[[Baise-moi]]'', a French film about two prostitutes who take violent revenge after being raped.<ref>[http://www.oflc.gov.au/resource.html?resource=92&filename=92.pdf OFLC Classification Review Board Report re Baisez-Moi.] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070416025140/http://www.oflc.gov.au/resource.html?resource=92&filename=92.pdf |date=16 April 2007 }}</ref> In 2000, the film was classified as R18+. On 25 April 2002, The film was subsequently banned and pulled from cinemas and still remains prohibited in Australia due to exploitative and offensive depictions of sexual violence, extreme violence and depictions of behavior and fetishes that are considered offensive/abhorrent.<ref>[http://www.oflc.gov.au/special.html?n=46&p=156&sTitle=baise-moi&sMature=1&sMediaFilm=1&sMediaPublications=1&sMediaGames=1&sDateFromM=1&sDateFromY=1970&sDateToM=1&sDateToY=2007&record=176380 OFLC Classifies Baise-Moi R18+.]{{dead link|date=July 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n* ''[[Ken Park]]'', an American film about teenagers that features a scene of [[autoerotic asphyxiation]], amongst other sexually explicit scenes.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.oflc.gov.au/resource.html?resource=219&filename=219.pdf |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2016-02-08 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20061008233651/http://www.oflc.gov.au/resource.html?resource=219&filename=219.pdf |archivedate=8 October 2006 }}</ref> The ban, however, is actually due to exploitative sexual depiction of minors, which is a criminal offence in Australia. In response to the ban, a protest screening was held which was shut down by the police.<ref>{{Cite news | page = 5 | last = Needham | first = Kirsty | title =  Police quiz critic after raid |work=Sydney Morning Herald | accessdate = 2007-05-30 | date = 7 April 2003 | url =http://www.theage.com.au/articles/2003/07/03/1057179099732.html }}</ref> \n**Prominent movie reviewer [[Margaret Pomeranz]], former host of ''[[The Movie Show]]'' on SBS and now host of [[At the Movies (Australian TV series)|''At the Movies'']] on [[Australian Broadcasting Corporation|ABC]], was arrested (and later cautioned and released) along with several others after attempting to screen at a hall what she described as \"a wonderful film\".<ref>[http://www.wsws.org/articles/2003/jul2003/balm-j10.shtml World Socialist Web Site report into the screening of Ken Park]. Wsws.org (10 July 2003)</ref> [[Tom Gleisner]], host of ''[[The Panel (Australian TV series)|The Panel]]'' (a prime-time comedy show), openly stated on the show that he had downloaded and watched the film.\n**Former [[New South Wales]] Premier [[Bob Carr]] stated that he thought the banning of ''Ken Park'' and other films is inappropriate, and that his Attorney-General [[Bob Debus]] would discuss changing the laws with other state Attorneys-General at a then upcoming meeting.<ref>{{Cite news | issn = 0312-6315 | page = 9 | last = Maddox | first = Garry | title = Debus wants festival film rethink |work=The Sydney Morning Herald | accessdate = 2012-08-05 | date = 18 June 2003 | url = http://www.smh.com.au/articles/2003/06/17/1055828326284.html }}</ref>\n. In October 2017 the board was branded as homophobic by the Luke Buckmaster on flicks.com.au for classifying the film ''[[Tom of Finland (film)|Tom of Finland]]'' as R18+ for high impact sexualised imagery and nudity. Luke made multiple falsified claims including that the movie was given this rating due to \"level of offence\" and the [[Netflix]] and other streaming platforms go completely unchecked in regards to content they distribute which was untrue as at the time the board was in the pilot of a classification tool to streamline the classification of [[Netflix]] content in Australia.<ref>http://www.classification.gov.au/Public/Resources/Documents/2017-media-releases/19october2017--classification-of-film-tom-of-finland-and-allegations-that-classification-board-is-homophobic.pdf</ref>\n\n===Video games===\n{{See also|List of banned video games in Australia}}\nVideo gaming censorship in Australia is considered to be one of the strictest in the western world.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://opennet.net/research/australia-and-new-zealand |work=OpenNet |title=Australia & New Zealand}}</ref>\n\n*''[[Grand Theft Auto III]]'' was withdrawn from sale for allowing players to have sexual intercourse with virtual prostitutes; the game was later reinstated when this action was removed. Specifically, the player could solicit intercourse from a virtual prostitute, and then kill her. The ability to solicit sex from prostitutes in the game was the action that was removed, but in-game characters and pedestrians could still violently murder them. ''[[Grand Theft Auto: Vice City]]'' was also pre-censored for the same reasons.  Though, in 2010 Vice City was classified uncut again receiving a MA15+.{{Cn|date=September 2018}}\n*''[[Grand Theft Auto: San Andreas]]'' was withdrawn from sale in July 2005 following the revelation that interactive sex scenes were included in the content files on the game's disc; one could not ordinarily access these scenes, but a third party modification, known as the [[Hot Coffee minigame controversy|Hot Coffee mod]], allowed the player to access these scenes within the game itself, and the inclusion of the scenes on the game disc took the game outside the MA15+ category. The MA15+ rating was re-instated after a modified version was released worldwide by [[Rockstar Games]], removing the content files for the sex scenes.\n*''[[Grand Theft Auto IV]]'' also prompted editing in the Australian ([[PAL]]) version, as Rockstar was worried it might get a RC rating. In the American release, sexual encounters with prostitutes occur inside the player's vehicle and the player has the ability to rotate the camera for a clearer view of what transpires. In the censored Australian version, the camera is fixed behind the vehicle, which rocks from side to side with accompanying audio effects. It is impossible for the player to view the inside of the car.<ref>[http://au.xbox360.ign.com/articles/869/869828p1.html IGN: Aussie GTA IV Censorship Update]. Au.xbox360.ign.com.</ref> Rockstar later decided to rate the uncut version of the game, which went on to receive a MA15+ rating, and a patch was later released for the PS3, PC and Xbox 360 to uncensor the game.\n*''[[50 Cent: Bulletproof]]'' was banned for encouraging gang violence. A version removing the game's Arcade Mode, cutting down on gore, and with an automatic Game Over for killing innocents was given an MA15+ rating.\n*''[[Fallout 3]]'' was refused classification by the [[Office of Film and Literature Classification (Australia)|OFLC]]<ref name=\"No AUS Release\">[http://www.classification.gov.au/special.html?n=46&p=156&sTitle=fallout+3&sMature=1&sMediaGames=1&sDateFromM=1&sDateFromY=2008&sDateToM=12&sDateToY=2008&record=228415 OFLC listing] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090302235433/http://www.classification.gov.au/special.html?n=46&p=156&sTitle=fallout+3&sMature=1&sMediaGames=1&sDateFromM=1&sDateFromY=2008&sDateToM=12&sDateToY=2008&record=228415 |date=2 March 2009 }} for ''Fallout 3''. Retrieved 12 July 2008.</ref><ref>[http://xbox360.ign.com/articles/887/887547p1.html '&#39;Fallout 3'&#39; Officially Refused Classification in Australia]. Xbox360.ign.com.</ref> due to the \"realistic visual representations of drugs and their delivery method (bringing) the 'science-fiction' drugs in line with 'real-world' drugs.\" A revised version of the game was resubmitted to the OFLC and reclassified as MA15+ on 7 August 2008 after drug names were changed.<ref name=\"AUS Revised\">{{cite web|title=Fallout 3 Censorship Report|url=http://au.ign.com/articles/2008/08/13/fallout-3-censorship-report|publisher=IGN|accessdate=6 May 2015}}</ref> It was later clarified that the only change done to the final version of the game was the name Morphine changed to Med-x. This change was done to all versions worldwide; thus, Australia got the same version of the game as other countries uncut with a MA15+.\n\n===Adult (18+) ratings for video games===\nMany games were banned before 2011 on the basis that the R18+ rating did not apply to video games at the time. This was the subject of complaint in the gaming community, who argued that there is no reason why adults should be prevented from seeing content in games that they could see in a film. One of the main opponents to the introduction of a R18+ rating for video games was the former South Australian Attorney-General [[Michael Atkinson (politician)|Michael Atkinson]] who vetoed every attempt to induce one.<ref>{{cite news |first=Chloe |last=Lake |title=Attorney-general opposes R rating for games |url=http://www.news.com.au/technology/story/0,25642,23282288-5014239,00.html |work=News.com.au |publisher=News Limited |date=27 February 2008 |accessdate=27 February 2008}}</ref>\n\nOn 11 August 2010, at a public forum, then opposition leader [[Tony Abbott]] was asked a question about his views on the absence of an R18+ rating for video games and whether he had any policies relating to the subject, saying, \"if what happens with video games is not roughly analogous to what happens in other areas, that seems silly...Instinctively I'm with you, and it's something I'd be happy to look at, if we are in Government.\"<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.couriermail.com.au/news/national/tony-abbott-qa-from-rooty-hill/story-fn5z3z83-1225904099798 |title=Tony Abbott Q&A from Rooty Hill |newspaper=The Courier Mail |publisher=News Limited |date=11 August 2010 |first1=Michael |last1=Madigan |first2=Ben |last2=Packham}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.kotaku.com.au/2010/08/tony-abbott-happy-to-look-at-r18-rating/ |title=Tony Abbott: \"Happy To Look At\" R18+ Rating |work=Kotaku |first=David |last=Wildgoose |date=12 August 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.itwire.com/it-industry-news/strategy/41091-abbott-pledges-r18-gaming-review |title=Abbott pledges R18+ gaming review |first=Renai |last=LeMay |date=11 August 2010 |work=iTWire |access-date=23 May 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160303195526/http://www.itwire.com/it-industry-news/strategy/41091-abbott-pledges-r18-gaming-review |archive-date=3 March 2016 |url-status=dead |df=dmy-all }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://delimiter.com.au/2010/08/11/abbott-pledges-r18-gaming-review/ |title=Abbott pledges R18+ gaming review |first=Renai |last=LeMay |date=11 August 2010 |work=Delimiter |publisher= LeMay & Galt Media}}</ref> In December 2010, Attorney General Robert McClelland appeared to be moving on this issue following the release of telephone poll results conducted by the Minister for Home Affairs Brendan O'Connor, showing roughly 80% in support of a R18+ classification.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.ag.gov.au/www/agd/agd.nsf/Page/Consultationsreformsandreviews_AnR18+ClassificationforComputerGames-PublicConsultation?open&query=game |title=An R 18+ Classification for Computer Games |publisher=Commonwealth of Australia |work=Attorney-General's Department |date=8 December 2010 |access-date=23 May 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110403033305/http://www.ag.gov.au/www/agd/agd.nsf/Page/Consultationsreformsandreviews_AnR18+ClassificationforComputerGames-PublicConsultation?open&query=game |archive-date=3 April 2011 |url-status=dead |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\nOn 22 July 2011, at a meeting of State and Territories' Attorneys General, an agreement was reached for the introduction of an R18+ classification. It was planned to introduce the rating towards the end of 2011.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.smh.com.au/digital-life/games/historic-agreement-on-r18-video-games-20110722-1hs78.html|title='Historic agreement' on R18+ video games|work=The Sydney Morning Herald|publisher=Fairfax Media|date=22 July 2011|accessdate=24 February 2012}}</ref>\nOn 22 July 2011, a meeting of Attorneys-General produced an in-principle agreement to introduce the R18+ classification for video games; however, NSW Attorney-General Greg Smith abstained from the vote. The Home Affairs Minister, [[Brendan O'Connor (politician)|Brendan O'Connor]], said the federal government would over-ride NSW and implement the R18+ rating regardless of its decision and would be officially available before the end of 2011.<ref name=\"R18\">{{cite news |author=Asher Moses, Ben Grubb |title='Historic agreement' on R18+ video games |url=http://www.smh.com.au/digital-life/games/historic-agreement-on-r18-video-games-20110722-1hs78.html#ixzz1C7Pkl0Tl |date=22 July 2011 |accessdate=22 July 2011 |work=The Sydney Morning Herald}}</ref> On 10 August the NSW Attorney General agreed on the R18+; thus, the rating would be accepted and available to all states before the end of 2011.<ref>[http://au.gamespot.com/news/6328240/nsw-backs-r18-for-games NSW backs R18+ for games], By Laura Parker, 9 August 2011 \u2013 GameSpot.com</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.abc.net.au/news/2011-07-22/games-rating-agreement/2806200|title=Governments agree on R18+ games rating|work=ABC News|publisher=Australian Broadcasting Company|accessdate=3 November 2011|date=22 July 2011}}</ref>\n\nAs of 1 January 2013, the R18+ rating has been officially implemented for video games although it is apparently not being used to full effect as many games are still being [[List of banned video games in Australia|refused classification]].<ref>{{cite news| url=http://www.news.com.au/breaking-news/gamers-get-adults-only-r18-classification/story-e6frfku0-1226399228661 | agency=AAP | title=Gamers get adults-only R18+ classification | date=18 June 2012}}</ref> [[Michael Atkinson (politician)|Michael Atkinson]], who was the South Australian [[Attorney-General]] until 2010, was a continuous opponent against the introduction of the R18+ classification, and actively blocked the release of a discussion paper until just before his retirement from cabinet that canvassed the opinion of the Australian public on whether or not an R18+ classification should be introduced.{{cn|date=September 2018}}\n\nThe first game to be released with an R18+ rating was ''[[Ninja Gaiden Sigma 2 Plus]]''. The game ''[[Saints Row IV]]'' became the first game to be refused classification under the new standard on 25 June 2013.<ref name=\"IGN: banned\">{{cite news|last=Reilly|first=Luke|date=June 25, 2013|url=http://www.ign.com/articles/2013/06/25/saints-row-iv-banned-in-australia|title=Saints Row IV banned in Australia|work=[[IGN]]|publisher=[[Ziff Davis]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150403134526/http://www.ign.com/articles/2013/06/25/saints-row-iv-banned-in-australia|archive-date=April 3, 2015|url-status=dead|access-date=March 15, 2015}}</ref><ref>[http://www.classification.gov.au/News/Pages/25June2013SaintsRowIVfirstcomputergameRefusedClassification.aspx 25 June 2013: \u2018''Saints Row IV''\u2019 first computer game Refused Classification]. Australian Classification Board, 25 June 2013. Retrieved 26 June 2013.</ref> ''[[State of Decay (video game)|State of Decay]]'' became the second game to be refused classification less than 24 hours after the first (''Saints Row IV'') was banned.<ref>[http://www.news.com.au/technology/gaming/second-video-game-state-of-decay-banned-in-australia/story-e6frfrt9-1226670282295 26 June 2013: \"Second video game \u2013 State of Decay \u2013 banned in Australia\"]. News.com.au, 26 June 2013. Retrieved 26 June 2013.</ref>\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Australia}}\n* [[Censorship in Australia]]\n* [[Internet censorship in Australia]]\n* [[Pornography by region|List of pornography laws by region]] \u2013 Australian hardcore pornography laws\n* [[Television content rating systems#Australia|Television content rating]] \u2013 includes the rating system of Australian TV\n* [[Video game controversy]] \u2013 includes the history of games censorship in Australia\n* [[List of banned video games in Australia]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n== External links==\n* [http://www.classification.gov.au/ The Australian Government Classification Website] Includes info about classification system, Board member profiles and a public searchable database of classification decisions\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20120125050930/http://www.ag.gov.au/gamesclassification The R18+ Discussion Paper] Submissions due 28 February 2010.\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20091012083157/http://cenere.com.au/files/articles/pdf/Exratings.pdf Inside Film Magazine's Phillip Cenere reports on the ACB International Ratings Conference]\n* [http://www.refused-classification.com Refused-Classification.com] Database of films, games, and books that have had problems with the ACB.\n* [http://libertu.net/censor/ Libertus Australia]{{Dead link|date=May 2019 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }} Website maintained by Irene Graham, the executive director of EFA.\n* [http://www.facebook.com/MediaCensorshipInAustralia Media Censorship in Australia] A Facebook censorship news page started in 2013 with several updates a week.\n\n{{CinemaofAustralia}}\n\n{{Video game controversy}}\n{{Pornography legality|state=collapsed}}\n\n[[Category:1970 establishments in Australia]]\n[[Category:Australian classification system]]\n[[Category:Censorship in Australia]]\n[[Category:Cinema of Australia]]\n[[Category:Commonwealth Government agencies of Australia]]\n[[Category:Video game content ratings systems]]\n[[Category:Video game organizations]]\n[[Category:Motion picture rating systems]]\n[[Category:Entertainment rating organizations]]\n\n[[fr:Australian Classification Board]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use Australian English|date=October 2013}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2013}}\n{{Infobox Government agency\n|agency_name     = Classification Board\n|formed          = {{start date and age|1970}} (as Australian Classification Board)\n|logo            = File:Australian Classification Board crest.gif\n|jurisdiction    = Commonwealth of Australia\n|superseding     =\n|minister1_name  = [[Paul Fletcher (politician)|Paul Fletcher]]\n|minister1_pfo   = [[Minister for Communications (Australia)|Minister for Communications]]\n|parent_agency   = [[Department of Communications and the Arts]] (current parent agency), OFLC (Original parent agency), [[Australian Classification Review Board]] (sister agency)\n|website         = {{url|http://www.classification.gov.au}}\n}}\nThe '''Australian Classification Board''' ('''ACB''' or '''CB''') is an [[Australian]] [[Government of Australia|Government]] [[Statute|statutory]] body responsible for the classification and censorship of films, video games and publications for [[exhibition]], sale or hire in Australia. The ACB was established in 1970 and was once part of the '''Office of Film and Literature Classification''' ('''OFLC'''), which was dissolved in 2006. The Department of Communications and the Arts now provides administrative support to the ACB and decisions made by the ACB may be reviewed by the [[Australian Classification Review Board]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.classification.gov.au/About/Pages/Review-Board.aspx|title=Review Board {{!}} Australian Classification|website=www.classification.gov.au|access-date=2016-04-30}}</ref> The ACB now operates under the ''Commonwealth Classification Act 1995''.\n\nThe ACB does not directly censor material by ordering cuts or changes. However, it is able to effectively censor media by refusing classification and making the media illegal for hire, exhibition and importation to Australia. \n\nThe classification system has several levels of \"restricted\" categories, prohibiting sale, exhibition or use of some materials to those who are under a prescribed age. In 2005, video and computer games became subject to the same classification ratings and restrictions as films (with the exception of the R18+ and X18+ ratings), in response to confusion by parents.<ref>{{Cite news|edition=1 \u2013 State |page=11 |title=Games get film ratings |work=The Daily Telegraph |date=6 July 2005 |url=http://www.news.com.au/story/0,10117,15534581-421,00.html |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20050609030406/http://www.news.com.au/story/0%2C10117%2C15534581-421%2C00.html |archivedate=9 June 2005 |url-status=dead }}</ref> Despite a line in the ''National Classification Code'' stating that \"adults should be able to read, hear and see what they want\", the adult R18+ classification was not applied to video games in Australia until 1 January 2013.<ref>[http://www.comlaw.gov.au/Details/F2013C00006 The Classification Code; May 2005]</ref>\n\n==History==\nThe Australian Classification Board was created in 1970 to classify or rate all films (and later in 1994, [[video games]]) that came into Australia. In the early years of the system, beginning in November 1971, there were four ratings:\n\n*''G'' for \"general exhibition\", carried over from the previous ratings system\n*''NRC'' for \"not recommended for children under 12\" (previously ''X, A'' or ''not suitable for children.'' This later became ''PG'' for \"parental guidance\")\n*''M'' for \"mature audiences\" (later became ''M 15+'' from the late 1980s until 2005)\n*''R'' for \"restricted exhibition\"<ref>{{cite news|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=uLIpAAAAIBAJ&sjid=JuUDAAAAIBAJ&pg=4106,478776&dq=fritz+the+cat&hl=en|title=Censorship Classifications|date=1 July 1973|accessdate=18 September 2010|work=[[Sydney Morning Herald]]|page=87}}</ref> (previously ''SOA'' or ''suitable only for adults''.  This later became ''R 18+'' in the late 1980s)\n\nThe ''MA 15+'' rating was introduced in 1993, to flag content that was too strong for the ''M'' classification, but not so much so that the content should be restricted only to persons over the age of 18.<ref>Cole, R., Driscoll, C., & Grealy, L. (2018). Classifying adulthood: A history of governing minority in media classi\ufb01cation. In Youth, Technology, Governance, Experience (pp. 74). Routledge.</ref>\n\nThe Office of Film and Literature Classification (OFLC) was reorganised in 1994, and oversaw the ACB. In 2005 the OFLC was dissolved and supervision of the ACB transferred to the [[Attorney-General's Department (Australia)|Attorney-General's Department]].\n\nThe current colour-coded classification markings for films and computer games were introduced in May 2005.<ref>[http://www.classification.gov.au/About/AnnualReports/Documents/673.pdf Annual Report 2004\u20132005]</ref>\n\nIn August 2014, the ACB introduced amendments to allow for the automated classification process employed by the [[International Age Rating Coalition]]. This new process reduces the costs of video game developers as they seek to obtain ratings for their products that are distributed digitally online.<ref>http://au.ign.com/articles/2014/09/01/getting-digitally-distributed-games-classified-in-australia-to-be-cost-free</ref>\n\n==Overview==\nThe board operates on a procedure that primarily involves [[decision-making]]. The members must communicate their views clearly and appreciate the views of others. Board members would be exposed to a wide range of material, including content that is confronting and offensive. Every film and computer game has to be classified before it can be legally made available to the public. Some [[publications]] also need to be classified. Failure to give classification (especially for unclassified material that is likely to be classified RC) is an implicit [[ban (law)|ban]] (except for exempt films, games, and publications). It is an offence \"to display, demonstrate, sell, hire, publicly exhibit or advertise a film or computer game\" without having it classified. Some films and documentaries (such as [[current affairs (news format)|current affairs]] and those created for business, scientific and [[Video lesson|education]] purposes) are exempt from classification unless, if classified, they would be ''M'' or above.<ref>http://www.artslaw.com.au/info-sheets/info-sheet/classification-and-censorship/</ref>\n\nThere are legal age restrictions for the ratings of ''MA 15+'' and ''R 18+''. ''X 18+'' is a special restriction rating for adult content. The other classification categories (''G'', ''PG'' and ''M'') are merely recommendations and they are not submitted to legal age restrictions. ''RC'' (banned) material cannot be sold, hired or distributed to any persons. A film or video game's context is crucial in determining whether a classifiable element is justified by the story-line or themes.\n\nThe ACB decides what consumer advice accompanies each classification. They indicate the elements in films and computer games which caused the classification and help consumers make choices about what they read, view or play. There are six classifiable elements for films: ''themes'' (rape, suicide, racism, etc.), ''violence'' (the level of violence and how threatening it is in its context), ''sex'' (intercourse and references to sex), ''language'' (the level of coarse language), ''drug use'' (the use of, and references to, drugs) and ''nudity'' (the explicitness of nudity). Consumer advice appears with the classification symbol on products, packaging and in advertisements. Consumer advice is not given if the element in question would be acceptable at a lower classification.<ref>http://www.classification.gov.au/Public/Resources/Pages/Parents.aspx</ref>\n\nThe ACB also classifies material submitted by the police, the [[Australian Customs and Border Protection Service]] and the [[Australian Communications and Media Authority]]. The board does not classify live performances, audio CDs and television shows. Television is regulated by the Australian Communications and Media Authority.<ref>{{Cite news | page= 7 | last = Canna | first = Xavier La | title = New classifications pave way for R-rated games |work=The Age |location=Australia | accessdate = 2012-08-05 | date = 6 June 2005 | url = http://www.theage.com.au/news/National/New-classifications-pave-way-for-Rrated-games/2005/06/05/1117910187614.html }}</ref> Film classification also normally applies to Internet streaming services. In January 2019, for the first time, [[Netflix]] was given the go-ahead to self-regulate film and television classification on its streaming platform, allowing the company to rank content between ''G'' and ''R18+''.<ref>[https://www.smh.com.au/business/companies/netflix-gets-approval-to-classify-own-shows-after-two-year-trial-20190120-p50sim.html Netflix gets approval to classify own shows after two-year trial]</ref>\n\n== Film and video game classifications ==\n<!-- PLEASE STOP COMPARING THE RATINGS TO OTHER COUNTRIES' RATING SYSTEMS.-->\n<!-- PLEASE DO NOT LIST THE \"MA15+\" RATING AS \"UNRESTRICTED\". Only E, G, PG and M are legally unrestricted.-->\n<!-- PLEASE DO NOT LIST THE \"M\" RATING AS \"RESTRICTED\". SEE TALK PAGE. Only MA15+, R18+ and X18+ are legally restricted in accordance to the ACB classification website: http://www.classification.gov.au/Classificationmarkings/Pages/Classificationmarkingsonfilmandcomputergames.aspx -->\n\n===Unrestricted/advisory===\nThe classifications below are ''unrestricted'' and may require parental ''advisory'',  but do not impose any legal restrictions on access to or distribution of material.<ref name=\"cats explained\">{{cite web |title=Information for Parents: Classification categories explained |publisher=Australian Classification Board |url=http://www.classification.gov.au/Public/Resources/Pages/Parents.aspx |accessdate=9 May 2015}}</ref><ref name=\"Fact Sheets\">{{cite web |last=Clare |first=Jason (Minister for Justice) |title=Guidelines for the Classification of Films 2012 |date=10 December 2012 |publisher=Commonwealth of Australia |url=http://www.comlaw.gov.au/Details/F2012L02541 |accessdate=10 May 2015}}</ref>\n\n[[File:OFLC small E.svg|90px]] [[File:Exempt for classification.png|280px]]\n\n* ''Exempt (E)'' \u2013 Only very specific types of material (including educational material and artistic performances) can be exempt from classification, and the material cannot contain anything that exceeds the constraints of the PG classification.<ref>{{cite web |title=Is it exempt? |publisher=Australian Classification Board |url=http://www.classification.gov.au/Industry/Journey/Pages/Exemptions/Step1.aspx |accessdate=9 May 2015}}</ref> The assessment of exemption may be made by the distributor or exhibitor (self-assessed) without needing to submit the product for certification by the ACB. Self-assessed exempt films cannot use the official marking although it is advised that films and computer games that are self-assessed as exempt display, \"This film/computer game is exempt from classification\".\n\n[[File:G tag.svg|90px]] [[File:OFLC large G.svg|280px]]\n\n* ''General (G)'' \u2013 Contains material available for general viewing. This category does not necessarily designate a children's film or game. Although not mandatory at this category, the board may provide consumer information. Consumer advice at ''G'' classification usually relates to impacts on very young children. The content is very mild in impact.\n**''Themes'' should have a very low sense of threat or menace, and be justified by context.\n**''Violence'' should have only a low sense of threat or menace, and be justified by context.\n**''Sexual activity'' should be very mild and very discreetly implied, and be justified by context.\n**''Coarse language'' should be very mild and infrequent and justified by context.\n**''Drug use'' should be implied only very discreetly, and be justified by context.\n**''Nudity'' should be justified by context.\n\n[[File:PG.svg|90px]] [[File:OFLC large PG.svg|280px]]\n\n* ''Parental guidance (PG)'' \u2013 Not recommended for viewing or playing by people under 15 without guidance from parents or guardians. Contains material that young viewers may find confusing or upsetting. The content is mild in impact.\n**''Themes'' should have a very low sense of threat or menace, and be justified by context.\n**''Violence'' should be mild and infrequent, and be justified by context. Sexual violence is not permitted.\n**''Sexual activity'' should be mild and discreetly implied, and be justified by context.\n**''Coarse language'' should be mild and infrequent, and be justified by context.\n**''Sex, nudity and drug use'' should be mild, infrequent, \"discreetly implied\" and \"justified by context\".\n**''Drug use''' and '''nudity'' should be justified by context.\n\n[[File:M.svg|90px]] [[File:OFLC large M.svg|280px]]\n\n* ''Mature (M)'' \u2013 Recommended for people aged 15 years and over. People under 15 may legally access this material because it is an advisory category. This category contains material that may require a mature perspective, but is not deemed too strong for younger viewers. The content is moderate in impact, although in recent years, the \"moderate\" indicator prefix is omitted from the consumer advice, eg. \"moderate violence\" is referred to as \"violence\".\n**''Themes'' may have a moderate sense of threat or menace, if justified by context.\n**''Moderate violence'' is permitted, if \"justified by context\". Sexual violence should be very limited and justified by context.\n**''Sexual activity'' should be discreetly implied, if \"justified by context\".\n**''Coarse Language'' may be used. Aggressive or strong coarse language should be infrequent and justified by context.\n**''Drug use''' and ''nudity''' should be justified by context.\n\n===Restricted===\nBy contrast, the classifications below are legally ''restricted'': it is illegal to sell or exhibit material so classified to anyone younger than the mentioned minimum age.<ref name=\"cats explained\"/><ref name=\"Fact Sheets\"/>\n\n[[File:MA 15+ classification tag from OFLC.svg|90px]] [[File:OFLC large MA15+.svg|280px]]\n\n* ''Mature accompanied (MA 15+)'' \u2013  Contains material that is considered unsuitable for exhibition by persons under the age of 15. People under 15 may legally purchase, rent, exhibit or view such content only under the supervision of a parent or adult guardian. A person may be asked to show proof of age before renting or purchasing an ''MA 15+'' film or computer game. The content is strong in impact.\n**''Realistic violence'' of medium intensity is permitted. Violent depictions with a \"high degree or realism\" is accepted only if \"justified by context\". Stylised violence, however, can be \"more detailed\".\n**''Strong Violence'' is permitted, although if it is bloody and strong it should be \"infrequent\" or \"justified by context\".\n**''Sexual violence'' is permitted only if it is \"not frequent, gratuitous or exploitative\".\n**''Sexual activity'' may be \"discreetly implied\" or \"simulated\".\n**''Nudity'' is permitted, but in a sexual context it should \"not be exploitative\".\n**''Frightening or intense scenes'' should \"not disturb a reasonable adult\".\n**''Aggressive and very strong coarse language'' may be used but it should \"not be exploitative\".\n**''Drug use'' may be depicted, but not in an \"advocatory manner\".\n**''Themes'', if strong, should be justified by context.\n\n[[File:OFLC small R18+.svg|90px]] [[File:OFLC large R18+.svg|280px]]\n\n* ''Restricted (R 18+)'' \u2013 Contains material that is considered unsuitable for exhibition to persons under the age of 18. People under 18 may not legally buy, rent, exhibit or view ''R 18+'' classified content. A person may be asked for proof of their age before purchasing, hiring or viewing an ''R 18+'' film or computer game at a retail store or cinema. Some material classified ''R 18+'' may be offensive to sections of the adult community. The content is high in impact.\n**''Realistic and explicit depictions of violence'' is permitted, but violence that is \"frequently gratuitous, cruel, exploitative and offensive to a reasonable adult\" is not permitted.\n**''Themes'' can have a \"very high degree of intensity\" but should not be \"exploitative\".\n**''Sexual violence'' is permitted only to the extent that they are \"necessary to the narrative\" and \"not exploitative\" or \"not shown in detail\".\n**''Sexual activity'' can be \"realistically simulated\", but depiction of \"[[Unsimulated sex|actual sexual activity]]\" is not permitted.\n**''Drug use'' can be shown but \"not gratuitously detailed\" and should also \"not be promoted or encouraged\". For computer games, drug use related to \"incentives and rewards\" is not permitted.\n**''Nudity'' in a sexual context should \"not include obvious genital contact\".\n**''Coarse language'' is virtually unrestricted.\n\n[[File:OFLC X 18 classification tag.svg|90px]] [[File:OFLC large X18+.svg|280px]]\n\n* ''Restricted (X 18+)'' \u2013 Contains material that is [[pornographic]] in nature. People under 18 may not legally buy, rent, possess, exhibit or view these films. The exhibition or sale of these films to people under the age of 18 years is a criminal offence carrying a maximum fine of $5,500. Films classified as ''X 18+'' are banned (via state government legislation) from being sold or rented in all Australian states (but are legal to possess except in certain parts of the [[Northern Territory]]) and are legally available to purchase only in the [[Australian Capital Territory]] and the Northern Territory. Importing ''X 18+'' material from these territories to any other state is legal (as the [[Australian Constitution]] forbids any restrictions on trade between the states and territories). The content is sexually explicit, and the rating does not exist for video games.\n**This rating applies to films that \"depict unsimulated sexual content only\". Depictions of sexual violence, coercion and \"sexually assaultive\" language are not allowed in the category. Fetishes such as body piercing, \"[[golden showers]]\", [[Bondage (BDSM)|bondage]], [[BDSM|spanking or fisting]] are also not permitted.\n\n===Other labels===\n\n[[File:Refused Classification Rating.svg|90px]]\n\n* ''{{vanchor|RC}} (Refused classification)'' \u2013 Contains material that, while being, in most cases, legal to possess, is considered offensive to the standards of morality, decency and propriety generally accepted by a \"reasonable adult\" to the extent that it should not be classified. Classification is mandatory, and films that are refused classification by the ACB are legally banned for sale, hire or public exhibition, carrying a maximum [[fine (penalty)|fine]] of $275,000 and/or 10 years in prison if an individual or organisation is found to be in breach of this. It is, however, legal to possess ''RC'' films and games for people over 18 (except in [[Western Australia]] and certain parts of the Northern Territory) unless they contain illegal content (such as [[child pornography]]). The content is very high in impact.\n** Films and games that exceed the ''X 18+'' and ''R 18+'' ratings (respectively) are refused classification by the ACB. Content that may be refused classification includes, but is not limited to:\n*** Detailed instruction or promotion in matters of crime or violence.\n*** The promotion or provision of instruction in paedophile activity.\n*** Descriptions or depictions of child sexual abuse or any other exploitative or offensive descriptions or depictions involving a person who is, or appears to be, a child under 18 years.\n*** Gratuitous, exploitative or offensive depictions of:\n****  violence with a very high degree of impact or which are excessively frequent, prolonged or detailed;\n**** ( cruelty or real violence which are very detailed or which have an extremely high impact;\n****  sexual violence.\n*** Depictions of practices such as bestiality, necrophilia or other practices that are considered revolting or abhorrent. \n*** Gratuitous, exploitative or offensive depictions of:\n****  activity accompanied by fetishes or practices that are offensive or abhorrent;\n****  incest fantasies or other fantasies that are offensive or abhorrent.\n\n[[File:Check the Classification Australia.jpg|150px]] \n* ''Check the classification (CTC)'' \u2013 The content has been assessed and approved for advertising unclassified films and computer games. \"This film has advertising approval. Check the classification closer to the released date\" is usually written on the marking.\n**Any advertising of unclassified films and games must display the ''CTC'' message on posters, trailers, on the internet, and any other types of advertising.\n**Once the content is classified, the classification marking replaces the ''CTC'' marking on all advertising material.\n\n== Literature ratings ==\nPublications such as books and magazines (though they would also include other printed media such as calendars, cards and catalogues) are required to be classified if they contain depictions or descriptions of sexuality, drugs, nudity or violence that are unsuitable for a [[minor (law)|minor]] or an adult who would take offence if sold as an unrestricted publication.\n\nPublication classifications are most commonly applied to magazines with visual depictions of nudity or sexual activity, such as many [[men's magazines]]. It is uncommon for these ratings to appear on books, even those dealing with adult themes, except in the most controversial cases.\n\n[[File:OFCL Australia Lit Rating- U.png|Unrestricted]] or [[File:OFCL Australia Lit Rating - UM.png|Unrestricted M (mature)]]\n*''Unrestricted''{{spaced ndash}}These publications are unrestricted, although they may not be recommended for readers under 15 years.\n\n[[File:OFCL Australia Lit Rating - R1.png|Category 1 restricted]]\n*''Category 1 restricted''{{Spaced ndash}}These publications are not available to persons under 18 years. These may contain images of sexualised nudity. They must be distributed in a sealed wrapper. Their covers must be suitable for public display.\n\n[[File:OFCL Australia Lit Rating - R2.png|Category 2 restricted]]\n*''Category 2 restricted''{{Spaced ndash}}Just like ''category 1 restricted'' publications, they are not available to persons under 18 years. However, they contain explicit images of actual sexual activity which are not permissible under ''category 1'', and may only be displayed in sites that are restricted to adults. Therefore, no publications that are likely to be classified ''category 2 restricted'' may be displayed in public registered events.\n\n[[File:Refused Classification Rating.svg|90px]]\n*''RC''{{Spaced ndash}}''RC'' publications are banned and cannot be sold or displayed anywhere in Australia.\n\nThe ''restricted'' publications are for adults and they are not to be sold to people under 18 (and in [[Queensland]] under state law). They have content, such as nudity or explicit sexual content, that could offend some sections of the adult community. The ''restricted'' categories are subject to various restrictions in different states; for example, one or both categories may only be sold in adults-only premises in certain states. For this reason, some adult magazines are published in two editions in Australia, or just one edited edition which can be sold anywhere with a warning, as ''unrestricted mature''.\n\n==Controversies==\n\n===Film===\n{{See also|List of films banned in Australia}}\n\n*[[Pasolini]]'s ''[[Sal\u00f2, or the 120 Days of Sodom]]'' has twice been banned in Australia. The Home Affairs Minister, [[Brendan O'Connor (politician)|Brendan O'Connor]], asked the Classification Review Board to reassess the decision;<ref>[http://www.smh.com.au/nsw/minister-asks-censors-to-reassess-approval-of-sadistic-film-20100416-skg2.html Minister asks censors to reassess approval of sadistic film]. SMH (17 April 2010).</ref> however, the review failed to find any fault in the classification. The film was banned in 1997, and was released after two failed attempts in September 2010, when the ''ACB'' classified an uncut version of ''Sal\u00f2'' R18+, mainly due to extra material providing greater context.\n*In 1992, Island World Communications Ltd and [[Manga Entertainment]] Australia Ltd had ''[[Urotsukidoji]]: Legend of the Overfiend'' submitted to the ''OFLC''. It was the first animated feature to be banned in Australia and the feature was banned outright, similar to ''[[Violence Jack]]''. ''Urotsukidoji'' was then censored to meet the OFLC's standards. The Australian version is the most censored in the [[western world]]. Many fans of [[anime]] imported uncensored versions of ''Urotsukidoji: Legend of the Overfiend'' from the [[United Kingdom|UK]]. The rest of the ''Urotsukidoji'' series was censored in Australia, with many still importing or downloading the American versions.\n*''[[Ninja Scroll]]'' was originally released in 1994 in Australia by ''Manga Entertainment Ltd''. It originally had the MA15+ rating on the VHS originally, but this was overturned in 1997 when [[Phillip Ruddock]] had the anime reviewed after an uncut screening of the movie on [[Special Broadcasting Service|SBS]]. A few months later it was given the R18+ rating and was uncut, then edited again, eventually using the [[BBFC]] cut of it. This was overturned in 2003 when [[Madman Entertainment]] and Manga Entertainment Ltd. released the uncut version.\n*''[[Romance (1999 film)|Romance]]'', a new crop within the ''[[arthouse]]'' genre, which features short scenes of [[Unsimulated sex|actual sex]] began to attract closer scrutiny. The film was initially refused classification in Australia, before it was awarded an R18+ on appeal.<ref name=\"aus\">{{cite web|url=http://refused-classification.com/censorship/films/romance-1999.html|title=Romance (1999)|publisher=Refused-Classification.com|accessdate=9 December 2011}}</ref> It single-handedly paved the way for actual sex to be accommodated in the R18+ classification in Australia.<ref name=\"aus\"/>\n* ''[[Baise-moi]]'', a French film about two prostitutes who take violent revenge after being raped.<ref>[http://www.oflc.gov.au/resource.html?resource=92&filename=92.pdf OFLC Classification Review Board Report re Baisez-Moi.] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070416025140/http://www.oflc.gov.au/resource.html?resource=92&filename=92.pdf |date=16 April 2007 }}</ref> In 2000, the film was classified as R18+. On 25 April 2002, The film was subsequently banned and pulled from cinemas and still remains prohibited in Australia due to exploitative and offensive depictions of sexual violence, extreme violence and depictions of behavior and fetishes that are considered offensive/abhorrent.<ref>[http://www.oflc.gov.au/special.html?n=46&p=156&sTitle=baise-moi&sMature=1&sMediaFilm=1&sMediaPublications=1&sMediaGames=1&sDateFromM=1&sDateFromY=1970&sDateToM=1&sDateToY=2007&record=176380 OFLC Classifies Baise-Moi R18+.]{{dead link|date=July 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n* ''[[Ken Park]]'', an American film about teenagers that features a scene of [[autoerotic asphyxiation]], amongst other sexually explicit scenes.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.oflc.gov.au/resource.html?resource=219&filename=219.pdf |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2016-02-08 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20061008233651/http://www.oflc.gov.au/resource.html?resource=219&filename=219.pdf |archivedate=8 October 2006 }}</ref> The ban, however, is actually due to exploitative sexual depiction of minors, which is a criminal offence in Australia. In response to the ban, a protest screening was held which was shut down by the police.<ref>{{Cite news | page = 5 | last = Needham | first = Kirsty | title =  Police quiz critic after raid |work=Sydney Morning Herald | accessdate = 2007-05-30 | date = 7 April 2003 | url =http://www.theage.com.au/articles/2003/07/03/1057179099732.html }}</ref> \n**Prominent movie reviewer [[Margaret Pomeranz]], former host of ''[[The Movie Show]]'' on SBS and now host of [[At the Movies (Australian TV series)|''At the Movies'']] on [[Australian Broadcasting Corporation|ABC]], was arrested (and later cautioned and released) along with several others after attempting to screen at a hall what she described as \"a wonderful film\".<ref>[http://www.wsws.org/articles/2003/jul2003/balm-j10.shtml World Socialist Web Site report into the screening of Ken Park]. Wsws.org (10 July 2003)</ref> [[Tom Gleisner]], host of ''[[The Panel (Australian TV series)|The Panel]]'' (a prime-time comedy show), openly stated on the show that he had downloaded and watched the film.\n**Former [[New South Wales]] Premier [[Bob Carr]] stated that he thought the banning of ''Ken Park'' and other films is inappropriate, and that his Attorney-General [[Bob Debus]] would discuss changing the laws with other state Attorneys-General at a then upcoming meeting.<ref>{{Cite news | issn = 0312-6315 | page = 9 | last = Maddox | first = Garry | title = Debus wants festival film rethink |work=The Sydney Morning Herald | accessdate = 2012-08-05 | date = 18 June 2003 | url = http://www.smh.com.au/articles/2003/06/17/1055828326284.html }}</ref>\n. In October 2017 the board was branded as homophobic by the Luke Buckmaster on flicks.com.au for classifying the film ''[[Tom of Finland (film)|Tom of Finland]]'' as R18+ for high impact sexualised imagery and nudity. Luke made multiple falsified claims including that the movie was given this rating due to \"level of offence\" and the [[Netflix]] and other streaming platforms go completely unchecked in regards to content they distribute which was untrue as at the time the board was in the pilot of a classification tool to streamline the classification of [[Netflix]] content in Australia.<ref>http://www.classification.gov.au/Public/Resources/Documents/2017-media-releases/19october2017--classification-of-film-tom-of-finland-and-allegations-that-classification-board-is-homophobic.pdf</ref>\n\n===Video games===\n{{See also|List of banned video games in Australia}}\nVideo gaming censorship in Australia is considered to be one of the strictest in the western world.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://opennet.net/research/australia-and-new-zealand |work=OpenNet |title=Australia & New Zealand}}</ref>\n\n*''[[Grand Theft Auto III]]'' was withdrawn from sale for allowing players to have sexual intercourse with virtual prostitutes; the game was later reinstated when this action was removed. Specifically, the player could solicit intercourse from a virtual prostitute, and then kill her. The ability to solicit sex from prostitutes in the game was the action that was removed, but in-game characters and pedestrians could still violently murder them. ''[[Grand Theft Auto: Vice City]]'' was also pre-censored for the same reasons.  Though, in 2010 Vice City was classified uncut again receiving a MA15+.{{Cn|date=September 2018}}\n*''[[Grand Theft Auto: San Andreas]]'' was withdrawn from sale in July 2005 following the revelation that interactive sex scenes were included in the content files on the game's disc; one could not ordinarily access these scenes, but a third party modification, known as the [[Hot Coffee minigame controversy|Hot Coffee mod]], allowed the player to access these scenes within the game itself, and the inclusion of the scenes on the game disc took the game outside the MA15+ category. The MA15+ rating was re-instated after a modified version was released worldwide by [[Rockstar Games]], removing the content files for the sex scenes.\n*''[[Grand Theft Auto IV]]'' also prompted editing in the Australian ([[PAL]]) version, as Rockstar was worried it might get a RC rating. In the American release, sexual encounters with prostitutes occur inside the player's vehicle and the player has the ability to rotate the camera for a clearer view of what transpires. In the censored Australian version, the camera is fixed behind the vehicle, which rocks from side to side with accompanying audio effects. It is impossible for the player to view the inside of the car.<ref>[http://au.xbox360.ign.com/articles/869/869828p1.html IGN: Aussie GTA IV Censorship Update]. Au.xbox360.ign.com.</ref> Rockstar later decided to rate the uncut version of the game, which went on to receive a MA15+ rating, and a patch was later released for the PS3, PC and Xbox 360 to uncensor the game.\n*''[[50 Cent: Bulletproof]]'' was banned for encouraging gang violence. A version removing the game's Arcade Mode, cutting down on gore, and with an automatic Game Over for killing innocents was given an MA15+ rating.\n*''[[Fallout 3]]'' was refused classification by the [[Office of Film and Literature Classification (Australia)|OFLC]]<ref name=\"No AUS Release\">[http://www.classification.gov.au/special.html?n=46&p=156&sTitle=fallout+3&sMature=1&sMediaGames=1&sDateFromM=1&sDateFromY=2008&sDateToM=12&sDateToY=2008&record=228415 OFLC listing] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090302235433/http://www.classification.gov.au/special.html?n=46&p=156&sTitle=fallout+3&sMature=1&sMediaGames=1&sDateFromM=1&sDateFromY=2008&sDateToM=12&sDateToY=2008&record=228415 |date=2 March 2009 }} for ''Fallout 3''. Retrieved 12 July 2008.</ref><ref>[http://xbox360.ign.com/articles/887/887547p1.html '&#39;Fallout 3'&#39; Officially Refused Classification in Australia]. Xbox360.ign.com.</ref> due to the \"realistic visual representations of drugs and their delivery method (bringing) the 'science-fiction' drugs in line with 'real-world' drugs.\" A revised version of the game was resubmitted to the OFLC and reclassified as MA15+ on 7 August 2008 after drug names were changed.<ref name=\"AUS Revised\">{{cite web|title=Fallout 3 Censorship Report|url=http://au.ign.com/articles/2008/08/13/fallout-3-censorship-report|publisher=IGN|accessdate=6 May 2015}}</ref> It was later clarified that the only change done to the final version of the game was the name Morphine changed to Med-x. This change was done to all versions worldwide; thus, Australia got the same version of the game as other countries uncut with a MA15+.\n\n===Adult (18+) ratings for video games===\nMany games were banned before 2011 on the basis that the R18+ rating did not apply to video games at the time. This was the subject of complaint in the gaming community, who argued that there is no reason why adults should be prevented from seeing content in games that they could see in a film. One of the main opponents to the introduction of a R18+ rating for video games was the former South Australian Attorney-General [[Michael Atkinson (politician)|Michael Atkinson]] who vetoed every attempt to induce one.<ref>{{cite news |first=Chloe |last=Lake |title=Attorney-general opposes R rating for games |url=http://www.news.com.au/technology/story/0,25642,23282288-5014239,00.html |work=News.com.au |publisher=News Limited |date=27 February 2008 |accessdate=27 February 2008}}</ref>\n\nOn 11 August 2010, at a public forum, then opposition leader [[Tony Abbott]] was asked a question about his views on the absence of an R18+ rating for video games and whether he had any policies relating to the subject, saying, \"if what happens with video games is not roughly analogous to what happens in other areas, that seems silly...Instinctively I'm with you, and it's something I'd be happy to look at, if we are in Government.\"<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.couriermail.com.au/news/national/tony-abbott-qa-from-rooty-hill/story-fn5z3z83-1225904099798 |title=Tony Abbott Q&A from Rooty Hill |newspaper=The Courier Mail |publisher=News Limited |date=11 August 2010 |first1=Michael |last1=Madigan |first2=Ben |last2=Packham}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.kotaku.com.au/2010/08/tony-abbott-happy-to-look-at-r18-rating/ |title=Tony Abbott: \"Happy To Look At\" R18+ Rating |work=Kotaku |first=David |last=Wildgoose |date=12 August 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.itwire.com/it-industry-news/strategy/41091-abbott-pledges-r18-gaming-review |title=Abbott pledges R18+ gaming review |first=Renai |last=LeMay |date=11 August 2010 |work=iTWire |access-date=23 May 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160303195526/http://www.itwire.com/it-industry-news/strategy/41091-abbott-pledges-r18-gaming-review |archive-date=3 March 2016 |url-status=dead |df=dmy-all }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://delimiter.com.au/2010/08/11/abbott-pledges-r18-gaming-review/ |title=Abbott pledges R18+ gaming review |first=Renai |last=LeMay |date=11 August 2010 |work=Delimiter |publisher= LeMay & Galt Media}}</ref> In December 2010, Attorney General Robert McClelland appeared to be moving on this issue following the release of telephone poll results conducted by the Minister for Home Affairs Brendan O'Connor, showing roughly 80% in support of a R18+ classification.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.ag.gov.au/www/agd/agd.nsf/Page/Consultationsreformsandreviews_AnR18+ClassificationforComputerGames-PublicConsultation?open&query=game |title=An R 18+ Classification for Computer Games |publisher=Commonwealth of Australia |work=Attorney-General's Department |date=8 December 2010 |access-date=23 May 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110403033305/http://www.ag.gov.au/www/agd/agd.nsf/Page/Consultationsreformsandreviews_AnR18+ClassificationforComputerGames-PublicConsultation?open&query=game |archive-date=3 April 2011 |url-status=dead |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\nOn 22 July 2011, at a meeting of State and Territories' Attorneys General, an agreement was reached for the introduction of an R18+ classification. It was planned to introduce the rating towards the end of 2011.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.smh.com.au/digital-life/games/historic-agreement-on-r18-video-games-20110722-1hs78.html|title='Historic agreement' on R18+ video games|work=The Sydney Morning Herald|publisher=Fairfax Media|date=22 July 2011|accessdate=24 February 2012}}</ref>\nOn 22 July 2011, a meeting of Attorneys-General produced an in-principle agreement to introduce the R18+ classification for video games; however, NSW Attorney-General Greg Smith abstained from the vote. The Home Affairs Minister, [[Brendan O'Connor (politician)|Brendan O'Connor]], said the federal government would over-ride NSW and implement the R18+ rating regardless of its decision and would be officially available before the end of 2011.<ref name=\"R18\">{{cite news |author=Asher Moses, Ben Grubb |title='Historic agreement' on R18+ video games |url=http://www.smh.com.au/digital-life/games/historic-agreement-on-r18-video-games-20110722-1hs78.html#ixzz1C7Pkl0Tl |date=22 July 2011 |accessdate=22 July 2011 |work=The Sydney Morning Herald}}</ref> On 10 August the NSW Attorney General agreed on the R18+; thus, the rating would be accepted and available to all states before the end of 2011.<ref>[http://au.gamespot.com/news/6328240/nsw-backs-r18-for-games NSW backs R18+ for games], By Laura Parker, 9 August 2011 \u2013 GameSpot.com</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.abc.net.au/news/2011-07-22/games-rating-agreement/2806200|title=Governments agree on R18+ games rating|work=ABC News|publisher=Australian Broadcasting Company|accessdate=3 November 2011|date=22 July 2011}}</ref>\n\nAs of 1 January 2013, the R18+ rating has been officially implemented for video games although it is apparently not being used to full effect as many games are still being [[List of banned video games in Australia|refused classification]].<ref>{{cite news| url=http://www.news.com.au/breaking-news/gamers-get-adults-only-r18-classification/story-e6frfku0-1226399228661 | agency=AAP | title=Gamers get adults-only R18+ classification | date=18 June 2012}}</ref> [[Michael Atkinson (politician)|Michael Atkinson]], who was the South Australian [[Attorney-General]] until 2010, was a continuous opponent against the introduction of the R18+ classification, and actively blocked the release of a discussion paper until just before his retirement from cabinet that canvassed the opinion of the Australian public on whether or not an R18+ classification should be introduced.{{cn|date=September 2018}}\n\nThe first game to be released with an R18+ rating was ''[[Ninja Gaiden Sigma 2 Plus]]''. The game ''[[Saints Row IV]]'' became the first game to be refused classification under the new standard on 25 June 2013.<ref name=\"IGN: banned\">{{cite news|last=Reilly|first=Luke|date=June 25, 2013|url=http://www.ign.com/articles/2013/06/25/saints-row-iv-banned-in-australia|title=Saints Row IV banned in Australia|work=[[IGN]]|publisher=[[Ziff Davis]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150403134526/http://www.ign.com/articles/2013/06/25/saints-row-iv-banned-in-australia|archive-date=April 3, 2015|url-status=dead|access-date=March 15, 2015}}</ref><ref>[http://www.classification.gov.au/News/Pages/25June2013SaintsRowIVfirstcomputergameRefusedClassification.aspx 25 June 2013: \u2018''Saints Row IV''\u2019 first computer game Refused Classification]. Australian Classification Board, 25 June 2013. Retrieved 26 June 2013.</ref> ''[[State of Decay (video game)|State of Decay]]'' became the second game to be refused classification less than 24 hours after the first (''Saints Row IV'') was banned.<ref>[http://www.news.com.au/technology/gaming/second-video-game-state-of-decay-banned-in-australia/story-e6frfrt9-1226670282295 26 June 2013: \"Second video game \u2013 State of Decay \u2013 banned in Australia\"]. News.com.au, 26 June 2013. Retrieved 26 June 2013.</ref>\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Australia}}\n* [[Censorship in Australia]]\n* [[Internet censorship in Australia]]\n* [[Pornography by region|List of pornography laws by region]] \u2013 Australian hardcore pornography laws\n* [[Television content rating systems#Australia|Television content rating]] \u2013 includes the rating system of Australian TV\n* [[Video game controversy]] \u2013 includes the history of games censorship in Australia\n* [[List of banned video games in Australia]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n== External links==\n* [http://www.classification.gov.au/ The Australian Government Classification Website] Includes info about classification system, Board member profiles and a public searchable database of classification decisions\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20120125050930/http://www.ag.gov.au/gamesclassification The R18+ Discussion Paper] Submissions due 28 February 2010.\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20091012083157/http://cenere.com.au/files/articles/pdf/Exratings.pdf Inside Film Magazine's Phillip Cenere reports on the ACB International Ratings Conference]\n* [http://www.refused-classification.com Refused-Classification.com] Database of films, games, and books that have had problems with the ACB.\n* [http://libertu.net/censor/ Libertus Australia]{{Dead link|date=May 2019 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }} Website maintained by Irene Graham, the executive director of EFA.\n* [http://www.facebook.com/MediaCensorshipInAustralia Media Censorship in Australia] A Facebook censorship news page started in 2013 with several updates a week.\n\n{{CinemaofAustralia}}\n\n{{Video game controversy}}\n{{Pornography legality|state=collapsed}}\n\n[[Category:1970 establishments in Australia]]\n[[Category:Australian classification system]]\n[[Category:Censorship in Australia]]\n[[Category:Cinema of Australia]]\n[[Category:Commonwealth Government agencies of Australia]]\n[[Category:Video game content ratings systems]]\n[[Category:Video game organizations]]\n[[Category:Motion picture rating systems]]\n[[Category:Entertainment rating organizations]]\n\n[[fr:Australian Classification Board]]\n", "name_user": "Damien Linnane", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eHistory:ref fix", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Australian_Classification_Board"}
{"title_page": "Social distancing", "text_new": "{{Short description|Infection control technique}}\n{{Distinguish|Social distance|Social isolation}}\n<noinclude>{{User:RMCD bot/subject notice|1=Physical distancing|2=Talk:Social distancing#Requested move 23 March 2020 }}\n</noinclude>\n{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2020|cs1-dates=y}}\n[[File:Social distancing queueing for the supermarket J. Sainsbury's north London Coronavirus Covid 19 pandemic - 30 March 2020.jpg|thumb|upright=1.85|People maintaining social distance while waiting to enter a store. To allow shoppers to maintain distance within the store, only a limited number are allowed inside at one time.]]\n[[File:Covid-19-Transmission-graphic-01.gif|thumb|upright=1.85|Social distancing reduces the rate of disease transmission and can stop an outbreak.]]\n'''Social distancing''', or '''physical distancing''',<ref name=\"WHO_20200320\">{{cite web |title=COVID-19 |author-first1=Margaret |author-last1=Harris |author-first2=Tedros |author-last2=Adhanom Ghebreyesus |author-link2=Tedros Adhanom Ghebreyesus |author-first3=Tu |author-last3=Liu |author-first4=Michael \"Mike\" J. |author-last4=Ryan |author-link4=Michael J. Ryan (doctor) |author5=Vadia<!-- Nowruz, Iran --> |author-first6=Maria D. |author-last6=Van Kerkhove |author-link6=Maria D. Van Kerkhove |author7=Diego<!-- Vortex --> |author-first8=Imogen |author-last8=Foulkes |author-first9=Charles |author-last9=Ondelam |author-first10=Corinne |author-last10=Gretler |author11=Costas<!-- ERT, Greece --> |date=2020-03-20 |publisher=[[World Health Organization]] |url=https://www.who.int/docs/default-source/coronaviruse/transcripts/who-audio-emergencies-coronavirus-press-conference-full-20mar2020.pdf?sfvrsn=1eafbff_0 |access-date=2020-03-29 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200325084602/https://www.who.int/docs/default-source/coronaviruse/transcripts/who-audio-emergencies-coronavirus-press-conference-full-20mar2020.pdf?sfvrsn=1eafbff_0 |archive-date=2020-03-25}}</ref><ref name=\"Hensley_20200323\">{{cite web |author-first=Laura |author-last=Hensley |title=Social distancing is out, physical distancing is in \u2014 here's how to do it |work=[[Global News]] |date=2020-03-23 |publisher=[[Corus Entertainment Inc.]] |url=https://globalnews.ca/news/6717166/what-is-physical-distancing/ |access-date=2020-03-29 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200326180136/https://globalnews.ca/news/6717166/what-is-physical-distancing/ |archive-date=2020-03-27}}</ref><ref name=\"Venske_20200326\">{{cite web |title=Die Wirkung von Sprache in Krisenzeiten |language=de |trans-title=The effect of language in times of crisis |date=2020-03-26 |editor-first=Andrea |editor-last=Schwyzer |author-first=Regula |author-last=Venske |author-link=:de:Regula Venske |type=Interview |publisher=[[Norddeutscher Rundfunk]] |series=NDR Kultur |url=https://www.ndr.de/kultur/Corona-Die-Wirkung-von-Sprache-in-Krisenzeiten,venske118.html |access-date=2020-03-27 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200327214038/https://www.ndr.de/kultur/Corona-Die-Wirkung-von-Sprache-in-Krisenzeiten,venske118.html |archive-date=2020-03-27}} (NB. Regula Venske is president of the [[PEN Centre Germany]].)</ref> is a set of non-pharmaceutical interventions or measures taken to [[infection control|prevent the spread]] of a [[infection|contagious disease]] by maintaining a physical distance between people and reducing the number of times people come into close contact with each other.<ref name=\"WHO_20200320\"/><ref name=\"JohnsonSunFreedman 2020\"/> It involves keeping a distance of six feet (two meters) from others and avoiding gathering together in large groups.<ref name=\"Pearce2020\"/><ref name=\"CDC22March2020\"/> it used for leaving their bf and gf.\n\nBy reducing the probability that a given uninfected person will come into physical contact with an infected person, the [[transmission (medicine)|disease transmission]] can be suppressed, resulting in [[Mortality rate|fewer deaths]].<ref name=\"WHO_20200320\"/><ref name=\"JohnsonSunFreedman 2020\">{{cite newspaper |author-last1=Johnson |author-first1=Carolyn Y. |author-last2=Sun |author-first2=Lena |author-last3=Freedman |author-first3=Andrew |title=Social distancing could buy U.S. valuable time against coronavirus: It's a make-or-break moment with coronavirus to test one of the most basic \u2014 but disruptive \u2014 public health tools |newspaper=[[The Washington Post]] |date=2020-03-10 |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/health/2020/03/10/social-distancing-coronavirus/ |access-date=2020-03-11 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200327163232/https://www.washingtonpost.com/health/2020/03/10/social-distancing-coronavirus/ |archive-date=2020-03-27}}</ref> The measures are combined with good respiratory hygiene and hand washing.<ref name=\"WHO2May2009\"/><ref name=\"gov.ukSD\">{{Cite web |title=Guidance on social distancing for everyone in the UK |author-last= |author-first= |date= |website=GOV.UK |language=en |url=https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/covid-19-guidance-on-social-distancing-and-for-vulnerable-people/guidance-on-social-distancing-for-everyone-in-the-uk-and-protecting-older-people-and-vulnerable-adults |access-date=2020-03-29 |url-status=live |archive-url= |archive-date=}}</ref> During the [[2019\u20132020 coronavirus pandemic]], the [[World Health Organization]] (WHO) suggested the reference to \"physical\" as an alternative to \"social\", in keeping with the notion that it is a physical distance which prevents transmission; people can remain socially connected via technology.<ref name=\"WHO_20200320\"/><ref name=\"Hensley_20200323\"/><ref name=\"Tangermann_20200324\">{{cite web |title=It's Officially Time to Stop Using The Phrase 'Social Distancing'<!-- The WHO Wants You to Ditch the Phrase \"Social Distancing\" --> |date=2020-03-24 |orig-year=2020-03-20 |author-first=Victor |author-last=Tangermann |work=science alert (Futurism / The Byte) |url=https://www.sciencealert.com/who-is-no-longer-using-the-phrase-social-distancing |access-date=2020-03-29 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200326180149/https://www.sciencealert.com/who-is-no-longer-using-the-phrase-social-distancing |archive-date=2020-03-29}} [https://web.archive.org/web/20200326180155/https://futurism.com/the-byte/who-ditch-phrase-social-distancing]</ref>\n\nTo slow down the spread of infectious diseases and avoid overburdening healthcare systems, particularly during a [[pandemic]], several social distancing measures are used, including the closing of schools and workplaces, [[isolation (health care)|isolation]], [[quarantine]], [[cordon sanitaire|restricting movement of people]] and the cancellation of [[mass gathering]]s.<ref name=\"JohnsonSunFreedman 2020\"/><ref name=\"cdc2007\"/> Such measures have been successfully implemented in several previous epidemics. In [[St.&nbsp;Louis]], shortly after the first cases of influenza were detected in the city during the [[1918 flu pandemic]], authorities implemented school closures, bans on public gatherings and other social distancing interventions. The death rates in St.&nbsp;Louis were much less than in [[Philadelphia]], which despite having cases of influenza, allowed a mass parade to continue and did not introduce social distancing until more than two weeks after its first cases.<ref name=\"Ryan2008\"/>\n\nSocial distancing measures are more effective when the infectious disease spreads via droplet contact (coughing or sneezing); direct physical contact, including sexual contact; indirect physical contact (e.g., by touching a contaminated surface); or [[Airborne disease|airborne transmission]] (if the microorganism can survive in the air for long periods).<ref name=\"cidrap\">{{cite web |title=Information About Social Distancing |date=2017 |website=www.cidrap.umn.edu |publisher=Public Health Department: [[Santa Clara Valley Health & Hospital System]] |url=http://www.cidrap.umn.edu/sites/default/files/public/php/185/185_factsheet_social_distancing.pdf |access-date=2020-03-17 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200327162348/http://www.cidrap.umn.edu/sites/default/files/public/php/185/185_factsheet_social_distancing.pdf |archive-date=2020-03-27}}</ref> The measures are less effective when an infection is transmitted primarily via [[fecal-oral transmission|contaminated water or food]] or by [[Vector (epidemiology)|vector]]s such as mosquitoes or other insects.<ref name=\"CDCFeb2007\">{{cite web |title=Interim Pre-Pandemic Planning Guidance: Community Strategy for Pandemic Influenza Mitigation in the United States\u2014Early, Targeted, Layered Use of Nonpharmaceutical Interventions |publisher=[[Centers for Disease Control and Prevention]] |date=February 2007 |id=CS10848 |url=https://www.cdc.gov/flu/pandemic-resources/pdf/community_mitigation-sm.pdf |access-date=2020-03-29 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200319205055/https://www.cdc.gov/flu/pandemic-resources/pdf/community_mitigation-sm.pdf |archive-date=2020-03-19}}</ref>\n\nDrawbacks of social distancing can include [[loneliness]], reduced [[productivity]] and the loss of other benefits associated with [[human interaction]].<ref name=\"Brooks26Feb2020\"/>\n\n==Definition==\nThe [[Centers for Disease Control and Prevention]] (CDC) have described social distancing as a set of \"methods for reducing frequency and closeness of contact between people in order to decrease the risk of transmission of disease\".<ref name=\"cdc2007\"/> During the 2019\u20132020 coronavirus pandemic, the CDC revised the definition of social distancing as \"remaining out of congregrate settings, avoiding mass gatherings, and maintaining distance (approximately 6 feet or 2 meters) from others when possible.\"<ref name=\"Pearce2020\">{{Cite web |title=What is social distancing and how can it slow the spread of COVID-19? |author-last=Pearce |author-first=Katie |date=2020-03-13 |website=The Hub |publisher=[[Johns Hopkins University]] |language=en |url=https://hub.jhu.edu/2020/03/13/what-is-social-distancing/ |access-date=2020-03-29 |url-status=live |archive-url= |archive-date=}}</ref><ref name=\"CDC22March2020\">{{Cite web |title=Risk Assessment and Management |date=2020-03-22 |publisher=[[Centers for Disease Control and Prevention]] |language=en-us |url=https://www.cdc.gov/coronavirus/2019-ncov/php/risk-assessment.html |access-date=2020-03-29 |url-status=live |archive-url= |archive-date=}}</ref>\n\nPreviously, in 2009, the WHO described social distancing as \"keeping at least an arm's length distance from others, [and] minimizing gatherings\".<ref name=\"WHO2May2009\">{{Cite web |title=Pandemic influenza prevention and mitigation in low resource communities |date=2009-05-02 |publisher=[[World Health Organization]] |url=https://www.who.int/csr/resources/publications/swineflu/PI_summary_low_resource_02_05_2009.pdf?ua=1 |access-date=2020-03-29 |url-status=live |archive-url= |archive-date=}}</ref> It is combined with good respiratory hygiene and hand washing, and is considered the most feasible way to reduce or delay a pandemic.<ref name=\"WHO2May2009\"/>\n\n== Measures ==\n{{Redirect-distinguish2|Flatten the curve}}\n\n[[File:Covid-19_flatten_the_curve_-_cropped_version_(no_cartoon).gif|thumb|upright=1.5|Social distancing helps prevent a sharp peak of infections (\"flattens the [[epidemic curve]]\") to keep healthcare services from being overwhelmed.<ref name=\"Wiles_20200309\">{{cite web |author-last=Wiles |author-first=Siouxsie |author-link=Siouxsie Wiles |title=The three phases of Covid-19 \u2013 and how we can make it manageable |date=2020-03-09 |work=[[The Spinoff]] |location=Morningside, Auckland, New Zealand |url=https://thespinoff.co.nz/society/09-03-2020/the-three-phases-of-covid-19-and-how-we-can-make-it-manageable/ |access-date=2020-03-09 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200327120015/https://thespinoff.co.nz/society/09-03-2020/the-three-phases-of-covid-19-and-how-we-can-make-it-manageable/ |archive-date=2020-03-27}}</ref><ref name=\"Wiles_20200314\">{{cite web |author-last=Wiles |author-first=Siouxsie |author-link=Siouxsie Wiles |title=After 'Flatten the Curve', we must now 'Stop the Spread'. Here's what that means |date=2020-03-14 |work=[[The Spinoff]] |location=Morningside, Auckland, New Zealand |url=https://thespinoff.co.nz/society/14-03-2020/after-flatten-the-curve-we-must-now-stop-the-spread-heres-what-that-means/ |access-date=2020-03-13 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200326232315/https://thespinoff.co.nz/society/14-03-2020/after-flatten-the-curve-we-must-now-stop-the-spread-heres-what-that-means/ |archive-date=2020-03-26}}</ref><ref name=\"Anderson_20200309\">{{cite journal |author-last1=Anderson |author-first1=Roy Malcom |author-link1=Roy Malcolm Anderson |author-last2=Heesterbeek |author-first2=Hans J. A. P. |author-last3=Klinkenberg |author-first3=Don |author-last4=Hollingsworth |author-first4=T. D\u00e9irdre |author-link4=:wikidata:Q42660467 |date=2020-03-09 |title=How will country-based mitigation measures influence the course of the COVID-19 epidemic? |journal=[[The Lancet]] |language=en |volume=395 |issue=10228 |pages=931\u2013934 |doi=10.1016/S0140-6736(20)30567-5 |issn=0140-6736 |pmid=32164834 |url=https://www.thelancet.com/journals/lancet/article/PIIS0140-6736(20)30567-5/abstract |access-date=2020-03-28 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200327110325/https://www.thelancet.com/journals/lancet/article/PIIS0140-6736(20)30567-5/fulltext |archive-date=2020-03-27 |quote=A key issue for epidemiologists is helping policy makers decide the main objectives of mitigation\u2014e.g., minimising morbidity and associated mortality, avoiding an epidemic peak that overwhelms health-care services, keeping the effects on the economy within manageable levels, and flattening the epidemic curve to wait for vaccine development and manufacture on scale and antiviral drug therapies.}}</ref>]]\n\nKnowing that a disease is circulating may trigger a [[behaviour change (public health)|change in behaviour]] by people choosing to stay away from public places and other people. When implemented to control epidemics, such social distancing can result in benefits but with an economic cost. Research indicates that measures must be applied rigorously and immediately in order to be effective.<ref name=\"Maharaj2012\">{{cite journal |author-last1=Maharaj |author-first1=Savi |author-last2=Kleczkowski |author-first2=Adam |date=2012 |title=Controlling epidemic spread by social distancing: Do it well or not at all |journal=[[BioMed Central|BMC Public Health]] |volume=12 |issue=1 |page=679 |doi=10.1186/1471-2458-12-679 |pmid=22905965 |pmc=3563464}}</ref> Several social distancing measures are used to control the spread of contagious illnesses.<ref name=\"cdc2007\">{{cite web |author-first1=Kathy |author-last1=Kinlaw |author-first2=Robert J. |author-last2=Levine |title=Ethical guidelines in Pandemic Influenza \u2013 Recommendations of the Ethics Subcommittee of the Advisory Committee to the Director, Centers for Disease Control and Prevention |publisher=[[Centers for Disease Control and Prevention]] |date=2007-02-15 |url=https://www.cdc.gov/od/science/integrity/phethics/docs/panflu_ethic_guidelines.pdf |access-date=2020-03-23 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200205095942/https://www.cdc.gov/od/science/integrity/phethics/docs/panflu_ethic_guidelines.pdf |archive-date=2020-02-05}} (12 pages)</ref><ref name=\"cidrap\"/><ref name=\"Pearce2020\"/>\n\n===Avoiding physical contact===\n[[File:Covid-19-Handshake-Alternatives-v3.gif|thumb|upright=1.5|Social distancing includes eliminating the physical contact that occurs with the typical [[handshake]], [[hug]], or [[hongi]]; this illustration offers eight alternatives.]]\nKeeping at least two-metre distance from each other and avoiding hugs and [[List of gestures|gestures]] that involve direct physical contact, reduce the risk of becoming infected during flu [[pandemic]]s and the coronavirus pandemic of 2020.<ref name=\"Pearce2020\"/><ref name=\"osha\">{{cite web |title=Guidance on Preparing Workplaces for an Influenza Pandemic |id=OSHA 3327-02N 2007 |work=[[Occupational Safety and Health Act of 1970]] |publisher=[[United States Department of Labor]] |url=https://www.osha.gov/Publications/influenza_pandemic.html |access-date=2020-03-18 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200325141049/https://www.osha.gov/Publications/influenza_pandemic.html |archive-date=2020-03-25}} [https://web.archive.org/web/20200319163737/https://www.osha.gov/Publications/OSHA3327pandemic.pdf]</ref> These distances of separation, in addition to personal hygiene measures, are also recommended at places of work.<ref name=\"UofCh\">{{Cite web |title=Social Distancing |publisher=Department of Safety & Security, [[The University of Chicago]] |date=2015 |website=safety-security.uchicago.edu |url=https://safety-security.uchicago.edu/emergency_management/all_hazard_safety_procedures/social_distancing/ |access-date=2020-03-29 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200324150358/https://safety-security.uchicago.edu/emergency_management/all_hazard_safety_procedures/social_distancing/ |archive-date=2020-03-24}}</ref> Where possible it may be recommended to [[telecommuting|work from home]].<ref name=\"gov.ukSD\"/>\n\nVarious alternatives have been proposed for the tradition of [[handshake|handshaking]]. The gesture of [[namaste]], placing one's palms together, fingers pointing upwards, drawing the hands to the heart, is one non-touch alternative. During the [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in the United Kingdom]], this gesture was used by [[Charles, Prince of Wales|Prince Charles]] upon greeting reception guests, and has been recommended by the Director-General of the WHO, [[Tedros Adhanom Ghebreyesus]], and Israeli Prime Minister [[Benjamin Netanyahu]].<ref name=\"Barajas13March2020\">{{Cite web |title=Joined palms, hands on hearts, Vulcan salutes: Saying hello in a no-handshake era |author-last1=Barajas |author-first1=Julia |author-last2=Etehad |author-first2=Melissa |date=2020-03-13 |website=[[Los Angeles Times]] |language=en-US |url=https://www.latimes.com/world-nation/story/2020-03-13/coronavirus-namaste-greetings-handshakes-noncontact |access-date=2020-03-18 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200327064424/https://www.latimes.com/world-nation/story/2020-03-13/coronavirus-namaste-greetings-handshakes-noncontact |archive-date=2020-03-27}}</ref> Other alternatives include the [[Wave (gesture)|wave]], the [[Shaka sign|shaka (or \"hang loose\") sign]], and placing a palm on your heart, as practiced in parts of Iran.<ref name=\"Barajas13March2020\"/>\n<gallery>File:Social Distancing in a Computer Lab.jpg|thumb|upright=1.85|In this computer lab, every other workstation has been closed off to increase the distance between people working\nFile:President of Taiwan greeting.jpg|thumb|upright=0.7|[[Taiwan]]ese president [[Tsai Ing-wen]] giving a traditional Chinese [[greeting]] instead of [[handshake|shaking hands]]\nFile:Social_Distancing_Sign_@_London_Drugs_(49684963711).jpg|thumb|upright=1|Floor markings can help people maintain distance in public places</gallery>\n\n===School closures===\n[[Image:Swineflu uk hpa model.svg|thumb|right|upright=1|\nSwine flu cases per week in the United Kingdom in 2009; schools typically [[Summer vacation|close for summer]] in mid-July and re-open in early September.<ref name=\"HPApress\">{{cite web |title=2009 Press Releases |date=2009-12-24 |publisher=[[Health Protection Agency]] |url=https://webarchive.nationalarchives.gov.uk/20100303155122/http://www.hpa.org.uk/HPA/NewsCentre/NationalPressReleases/2009PressReleases/ |access-date=2009-12-24 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20091224065403/http://www.hpa.org.uk/HPA/NewsCentre/NationalPressReleases/2009PressReleases/ |archive-date=2009-12-24}}</ref>]]\n\nMathematical modeling has shown that transmission of an outbreak may be delayed by closing schools. However, effectiveness depends on the contacts children maintain outside of school. Often, one parent has to take time off work, and prolonged closures may be required. These factors could result in social and economic disruption.<ref name=\"Zumla2010\">{{Cite book |author-last1=Zumla |author-first1=Alimuddin |author-link1=Alimuddin Zumla  |title=Emerging Respiratory Infections in the 21st Century, An Issue of Infectious Disease Clinics |author-last2=Yew |author-first2=Wing-Wai |author-last3=Hui |author-first3=David S. C. |date=2010-08-31 |publisher=[[Elsevier Health Sciences]] |volume=24 |number=3 |isbn=978-1-4557-0038-7 |pages=614 |language=en |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=c9CQn9C4JaQC&pg=PA614 |access-date=2020-03-29 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200329195321/https://books.google.de/books?id=c9CQn9C4JaQC&pg=PA614&redir_esc=y |archive-date=2020-03-29}}</ref><ref name=\"CauchemezFerguson2009\">{{cite journal |author-last1=Cauchemez |author-first1=Simon |author-last2=Ferguson |author-first2=Neil Morris |author-link2=Neil Ferguson (epidemiologist) |author-last3=Wachtel |author-first3=Claude |author-last4=Tegnell |author-first4=Anders |author-last5=Saour |author-first5=Guillaume |author-last6=Duncan |author-first6=Ben |author-last7=Nicoll |author-first7=Angus |title=Closure of schools during an influenza pandemic |journal=[[The Lancet Infectious Diseases]] |volume=9 |issue=8 |date=August 2009 |pages=473\u2013481 |issn=1473-3099 |doi=10.1016/S1473-3099(09)70176-8 |pmid=19628172 |url=https://www.thelancet.com/action/showPdf?pii=S1473-3099%2809%2970176-8 |access-date=2020-03-29 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n===Workplace closures===\n[[Modeling and simulation]] studies based on US data suggest that if 10% of affected workplaces are closed, the overall infection transmission rate is around 11.9% and the epidemic peak time is slightly delayed. In contrast, if 33% of affected workplaces are closed, the attack rate decreases to 4.9%, and the peak time is delayed by one week.<ref>{{cite journal  |author-last1=Rousculp |author-first1=Matthew D. |author-last2=Johnston |author-first2=Stephen S. |author-last3=Palmer |author-first3=Liisa A. |author-last4=Chu |author-first4=Bong-Chul |author-last5=Mahadevia |author-first5=Parthiv J. |author-last6=Nichol |author-first6=Kristin L. |date=October 2010 |title=Attending Work While Sick: Implication of Flexible Sick Leave Policies |journal=[[Journal of Occupational and Environmental Medicine]] |volume=52 |issue=10 |pages=1009\u20131013 |doi=10.1097/jom.0b013e3181f43844 |pmid=20881626}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |author-last1=Kumar |author-first1=Supriya |author-last2=Crouse Quinn |author-first2=Sandra |author-last3=Kim |author-first3=Kevin H. |author-last4=Daniel |author-first4=Laura H. |author-last5=Freimuth |author-first5=Vicki S. |title=The Impact of Workplace Policies and Other Social Factors on Self-Reported Influenza-Like Illness Incidence During the 2009 H1N1 Pandemic |date=January 2012 |journal=[[American Journal of Public Health]] |volume=102 |issue=1 |pages=134\u2013140 |doi=10.2105/AJPH.2011.300307 |pmid=22095353 |pmc=3490553}}</ref> Workplace closures include closure of \"non-essential\" businesses and social services (\"non-essential\" means those facilities that do not maintain primary functions in the community, as opposed to [[essential services]]).<ref>{{cite web |title=Social Distancing Support Guidelines For Pandemic Readiness |publisher=[[Colorado Department of Public Health and Environment]] |date=March 2008 |url=https://www.colorado.gov/pacific/sites/default/files/OEPR_Guidelines-for-Social-Distancing-Pandemic-Readiness.pdf |access-date=2017-02-13 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170213001535/https://www.colorado.gov/pacific/sites/default/files/OEPR_Guidelines-for-Social-Distancing-Pandemic-Readiness.pdf |archive-date=2017-02-13}}</ref>\n\n===Canceling mass gatherings===\nCancellation of [[mass gathering]]s includes sports events, films or musical shows.<ref>{{cite journal |author-first1=Robert |author-last1=Booy |author-first2=James |author-last2=Ward |title=Evidence compendium and advice on social distancing and other related measures for response to an influenza pandemic |journal=[[:de:Paediatric Respiratory Reviews|Paediatric Respiratory Reviews]] |date=2015 |volume=16 |issue=2 |pages=119\u2013126 |publisher=National Centre for Immunisation Research and Surveillance |doi=10.1016/j.prrv.2014.01.003 |pmid=24630149 |url=https://www.health.gov.au/internet/main/publishing.nsf/Content/519F9392797E2DDCCA257D47001B9948/$File/Social.pdf |access-date=2015-05-15 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150515032806/https://www.health.gov.au/internet/main/publishing.nsf/Content/519F9392797E2DDCCA257D47001B9948/$File/Social.pdf |archive-date=2015-05-15}} (13 pages)</ref> Evidence suggesting that mass gatherings increase the potential for infectious disease transmission is inconclusive.<ref>{{cite journal |author-first1=Thomas V. |author-last1=Inglesby |author-first2=Jennifer B. |author-last2=Nuzzo |author-first3=Tara |author-last3=O'Toole |author-link3=Tara O'Toole |author-first4=Donald Ainslie |author-last4=Henderson |author-link4=Donald Ainslie Henderson |doi=10.1089/bsp.2006.4.366 |title=Disease Mitigation Measures in the Control of Pandemic Influenza |journal=Biosecurity and Bioterrorism: Biodefense Strategy, Practice, and Science |date=2006 |volume=4 |issue=4 |pages=366\u2013375 |pmid=17238820 |citeseerx=10.1.1.556.2672}}</ref> [[Anecdotal evidence]] suggests that certain types of mass gatherings may be associated with increased risk of [[Influenza#Transmission|influenza transmission]], and may also \"seed\" new strains into an area, instigating community transmission in a pandemic. During the 1918 influenza pandemic, [[Philadelphia Liberty Loans Parade|military parades in Philadelphia]]<ref name=\"Davis_20180921\">{{cite magazine |author-first=Kenneth C. |author-last=Davis |author-link=Kenneth C. Davis |title=Philadelphia Threw a WWI Parade That Gave Thousands of Onlookers the Flu |magazine=[[Smithsonian Magazine]] |date=2018-09-21 |url=https://www.smithsonianmag.com/history/philadelphia-threw-wwi-parade-gave-thousands-onlookers-flu-180970372/ |access-date=2020-03-27 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200327222425/https://www.smithsonianmag.com/history/philadelphia-threw-wwi-parade-gave-thousands-onlookers-flu-180970372/ |archive-date=2020-03-27}}</ref> and Boston<ref>{{cite news |title=The Flu in Boston |work=[[American Experience]] |publisher=[[WGBH Educational Foundation]] |url=https://www.pbs.org/wgbh/americanexperience/features/influenza-boston/ |access-date=2020-03-28 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200320142051/https://www.pbs.org/wgbh/americanexperience/features/influenza-boston/ |archive-date=2020-03-20}}</ref> may have been responsible for spreading the disease by mixing infected sailors with crowds of civilians. Restricting mass gatherings, in combination with other social distancing interventions, may help reduce transmission.<ref>{{cite journal |author-last1=Ishola |author-first1=David A. |author-last2=Phin |author-first2=Nick |date=December 2011 |title=Could Influenza Transmission Be Reduced by Restricting Mass Gatherings? Towards an Evidence-Based Policy Framework |url= |journal=Journal of Epidemiology and Global Health |volume=1 |issue=1 |pages=33\u201360 |doi=10.1016/j.jegh.2011.06.004 |pmid=23856374}}</ref>\n\n===Travel restrictions===\nBorder restrictions or internal travel restrictions are unlikely to delay an epidemic by more than 2\u20133 weeks unless implemented with over 99% coverage.<ref>{{cite journal |author-last1=Ferguson |author-first1=Neil Morris |author-link1=Neil Ferguson (epidemiologist) |author-last2=Cummings |author-first2=Derek A. T. |author-last3=Fraser |author-first3=Christophe |author-last4=Cajka |author-first4=James C. |author-last5=Cooley |author-first5=Philip C. |author-last6=Burke |author-first6=Donald S. |author-link6=Donald S. Burke |date=2006 |title=Strategies for mitigating an influenza pandemic |journal=[[Nature (journal)|Nature]] |volume=442 |issue=7101 |pages=448\u2013452 |doi=10.1038/nature04795 |pmid=16642006 |pmc=7095311 |bibcode=2006Natur.442..448F}}</ref> Airport screening was found to be ineffective in preventing viral transmission during the 2003 SARS outbreak in Canada<ref>{{cite journal |author-last=Bell |author-first=David M. |date=2004 |title=Public health interventions and SARS spread, 2003 |journal=[[Emerging Infectious Diseases]] |volume=10 |issue=11 |pages=1900\u20131906 |doi=10.3201/eid1011.040729 |pmid=15550198 |pmc=3329045 |url=https://www.cdc.gov/ncidod/EID/vol10no11/04-0729.htm |access-date= |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20091105074656/https://www.cdc.gov/ncidod/EID/vol10no11/04-0729.htm |archive-date=2009-11-05}}</ref> and the US.<ref>{{cite book |author-first=Martin |author-last=Cetron |chapter-url=https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK92450/ |chapter=Isolation and Quarantine: Containment Strategies for SARS, 2003 |title=Learning from SARS: Preparing for the Next Disease Outbreak |publisher=[[National Academy of Sciences]] |date=2004 |isbn=0-30959433-2}}</ref> Strict border controls between [[Austria]] and the [[Ottoman Empire]], imposed from 1770 until 1871 to prevent persons infected with the [[bubonic plague]] from entering Austria, were reportedly effective, as there were no major outbreaks of plague in Austrian territory after they were established, whereas the Ottoman Empire continued to suffer frequent epidemics of plague until the mid-nineteenth century.<ref name=\"Kohn\">{{cite book |editor-first=George Childs |editor-last=Kohn |title=Encyclopedia of Plague and Pestilence: From Ancient Times to the Present |publisher=[[Infobase Publishing]] |series=Facts On File - Library Of World History |date=2008 |orig-year=2001, 1998 |page=30 |isbn=978-1-43812923-5 |edition=3 |publication-place=New York, USA |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=tzRwRmb09rgC&pg=PA30 |access-date=2020-03-29 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200329120426/https://books.google.com/books?id=tzRwRmb09rgC&pg=PA30 |archive-date=2020-03-29}}</ref><ref>{{cite book |title=Encyclopedia of Pestilence, Pandemics, and Plague |editor-first=Joseph P. |editor-last=Byrne |date=2008 |publisher=[[Greenwood Publishing Group, Inc.]] / [[Greenwood Press]] |publication-place=Westport, Connecticut, USA / London, UK |lccn=2008019487 |volume=1&2<!-- Volume 1, A\u2013M --> |isbn=<!-- 978\u20130\u2013313\u201334101\u20134 --> |id=978\u20130\u2013313\u201334102\u20131 (vol 1), 978\u20130\u2013313\u201334103\u20138 (vol 2) |url=http://www.academia.dk/MedHist/Sygdomme/PDF/Encyclopedia_of_Pestilence_Pandemics_and_Plagues.pdf |access-date=2020-03-29 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200215143932/https://www.academia.dk/MedHist/Sygdomme/PDF/Encyclopedia_of_Pestilence_Pandemics_and_Plagues.pdf |archive-date=2020-02-15}}</ref> \n\nA [[Northeastern University]] study published in March 2020 found that \"travel restrictions to and from China only slow down the international spread of [[COVID-19]] [when] combined with efforts to reduce transmission on a community and an individual level. [\u2026] Travel restrictions aren't enough unless we couple it with social distancing.\"<ref>{{cite news |author-first=Emily |author-last=Arntsen |title=Closing borders can delay, but can't stop the spread of COVID-19, new report says |work=News@Northeastern |publisher=[[Northeastern University]] |date=2020-03-06 |url=https://news.northeastern.edu/2020/03/06/to-slow-the-spread-of-covid-19-close-doors-not-borders-new-report-says/ |access-date=2020-03-28 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200323063603/https://news.northeastern.edu/2020/03/06/to-slow-the-spread-of-covid-19-close-doors-not-borders-new-report-says/ |archive-date=2020-03-23}}</ref> The study found that the travel ban in Wuhan only delayed the spread of the disease to other parts of mainland China by three to five days, although it did reduce the spread of international cases by as much as 80 percent. A primary reason that travel restrictions were less effective is that many people with COVID-19 do not show symptoms during the early stages of infection.<ref>{{cite journal |title=The effect of travel restrictions on the spread of the 2019 novel coronavirus (COVID-19) outbreak |author-last1=Chinazzi |author-first1=Matteo |author-last2=Davis |author-first2=Jessica T. |author-last3=Ajelli |author-first3=Marco |author-last4=Gioannini |author-first4=Corrado |author-last5=Litvinova |author-first5=Maria |author-last6=Merler |author-first6=Stefano |author-link6=:wikidata:Q56380887 |author-last7=Pastore y Piontti |author-first7=Ana |author-last8=Mu |author-first8=Kunpeng |author-last9=Rossi |author-first9=Luca |author-last10=Sun |author-first10=Kaiyuan |author-last11=Viboud |author-first11=C\u00e9cile |author-last12=Xiong |author-first12=Xinyue |author-last13=Yu |author-first13=Hongjie |author-last14=Halloran |author-first14=M. Elizabeth |author-last15=Longini, Jr. |author-first15=Ira M. |author-link15=Ira M. Longini, Jr. |author-last16=Vespignani |author-first16=Alessandro |author-link16=Alessandro Vespignani |journal=[[Science (journal)|Science]] |date=2020-03-06 |doi=10.1126/science.aba9757 |pages=eaba9757 |pmid=32144116 |url=https://science.sciencemag.org/content/early/2020/03/05/science.aba9757 |access-date=2020-03-29 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200328084850/https://science.sciencemag.org/content/early/2020/03/05/science.aba9757 |archive-date=2020-03-28}}</ref>\n\n===Self-shielding===\nSelf-shielding measures for individuals include limiting face-to-face contacts, conducting business by phone or online, avoiding public places and reducing unnecessary travel.<ref name=\"Glass\">{{cite journal |author-last1=Glass |author-first1=Robert J. |author-last2=Glass |author-first2=Laura M. |author-last3=Beyeler |author-first3=Walter E. |author-last4=Min |author-first4=H. Jason |doi=10.3201/eid1211.060255 |title=Targeted Social Distancing Designs for Pandemic Influenza |journal=[[Emerging Infectious Diseases]] |publisher=[[Centers for Disease Control and Prevention]] |date=November 2006 |volume=12 |issue=11 |pages=1671\u20131681 |pmid=17283616 |pmc=3372334 |url=https://wwwnc.cdc.gov/eid/article/12/11/06-0255_article |access-date=2020-03-29 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200323042313/https://wwwnc.cdc.gov/eid/article/12/11/06-0255_article |archive-date=2020-03-23}}</ref><ref name=\"SDG\">{{cite web |title=Social Distancing Guidelines (for workplace communicable disease outbreaks) |date=2017 |publisher=[[Society for Human Resource Management]] |url=https://www.shrm.org/resourcesandtools/tools-and-samples/policies/pages/cms_016204.aspx |access-date=2017-04-23 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170423071438/https://www.shrm.org/resourcesandtools/tools-and-samples/policies/pages/cms_016204.aspx |archive-date=2017-04-23}}</ref><ref name=HeartMatters>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bhf.org.uk/informationsupport/heart-matters-magazine/news/coronavirus-and-your-health/whats-the-difference-between-shielding-self-isolation-and-social-distancing|title=What's the difference between shielding, self-isolation and social distancing?|website=www.bhf.org.uk|language=en|access-date=2020-03-29}}</ref>\n\n===Quarantine of possible cases===\nDuring the 2003 [[SARS]] outbreak in Singapore, approximately {{val|8000}} people were subjected to mandatory home quarantine and an additional {{val|4300}} were required to self-monitor for symptoms and make daily telephone contact with health authorities as a means of controlling the epidemic. Although only 58 of these individuals were eventually diagnosed with SARS, public health officials were satisfied that this measure assisted in preventing further spread of the infection.<ref>{{cite journal |author-first=Chorh-Chuan |author-last=Tan |author-link=Tan Chorh Chuan |url=http://www.srmuniv.ac.in/sites/default/files/downloads/sars_outbreak_lessons.pdf |pmid=16830002 |title=SARS in Singapore \u2013 Key Lessons from an Epidemic |journal=Annals Academy of Medicine |date=May 2006 |volume=35 |number=5 |pages=345\u2013349}}</ref> Voluntary self-isolation may have helped reduce transmission of influenza in Texas in 2009.<ref>{{cite journal |author-last1=Teh |author-first1=Benjamin |author-last2=Olsen |author-first2=Karen |author-last3=Black |author-first3=Jim |author-last4=Cheng |author-first4=Allen C. |author-last5=Aboltins |author-first5=Craig |author-last6=Bull |author-first6=Kirstin |author-first7=Paul D. R. |author-last7=Johnson |author-first8=M. Lindsay |author-last8=Grayson |author-first9=Joseph |author-last9=Torresi |title=Impact of swine influenza and quarantine measures on patients and households during the H1N1/09 pandemic |date=2012 |orig-year=2011-11-22, 2011-09-26, 2011-06-29 |journal=[[Scandinavian Journal of Infectious Diseases]] |volume=44 |issue=4 |pages=289\u2013296 |doi=10.3109/00365548.2011.631572 |pmid=22106922}}</ref> Short and longterm negative psychological effects have been reported.<ref name=\"Brooks26Feb2020\">{{Cite journal |author-last1=Brooks |author-first1=Samantha K. |author-last2=Webster |author-first2=Rebecca K. |author-last3=Smith |author-first3=Louise E. |author-last4=Woodland |author-first4=Lisa |author-last5=Wessely |author-first5=Simon |author-link5=Simon Wessely |author-last6=Greenberg |author-first6=Neil |author-link6=Neil Greenberg |author-last7=Rubin |author-first7=Gideon James |date=2020-03-14 |title=The psychological impact of quarantine and how to reduce it: rapid review of the evidence |url=https://www.thelancet.com/action/showPdf?pii=S0140-6736%2820%2930460-8 |journal=[[The Lancet]] |language=en |volume=395 |issue=10227 |pages=912\u2013920 |doi=10.1016/S0140-6736(20)30460-8 |issn=0140-6736 |pmid=32112714}}</ref>\n\n===''Cordon sanitaire''===\n{{main|Cordon sanitaire}}\nIn 1995, a ''cordon sanitaire'' was used to control an outbreak of [[Ebola virus disease]] in [[Kikwit]], [[Zaire]].<ref>{{cite news |author-first=Laurie |author-last=Garrett |author-link=Laurie Garrett |url=https://newrepublic.com/article/119085/ebola-cordon-sanitaire-when-it-worked-congo-1995 |title=Heartless but Effective: I've Seen 'Cordon Sanitaire' Work Against Ebola |work=[[The New Republic]] |date=2014-08-14}}</ref><ref>{{cite newspaper |url=https://www.cdc.gov/mmwr/preview/mmwrhtml/00037078.htm |title=Outbreak of Ebola Viral Hemorrhagic Fever -- Zaire, 1995 |newspaper=[[Morbidity and Mortality Weekly Report]] |date=1995-05-19 |volume=44 |number=19 |pages=381\u2013382}}</ref><ref name=\"Kaplan\">{{cite journal |author-first1=Rachel |author-last1=Kaplan Hoffmann |author-first2=Keith |author-last2=Hoffmann |title=Ethical Considerations in the Use of Cordons Sanitaires |journal=Clinical Correlations |publisher=[[New York University]] |location=[[NYU Langone]], New York, USA |eissn=1944-0030 |date=2015-02-19 |url=https://www.clinicalcorrelations.org/2015/02/19/ethical-considerations-in-the-use-of-cordons-sanitaires/ |access-date=2020-03-29 |url-status=live |archive-url=http://archive.today/ztkqC |archive-date=2020-03-29}}</ref> President [[Mobutu Sese Seko]] surrounded the town with troops and suspended all flights into the community. Inside Kikwit, the [[World Health Organization]] and Zaire medical teams erected further ''cordons sanitaires'', isolating burial and treatment zones from the general population and successfully containing the infection.<ref>{{cite book |author-first=Laurie |author-last=Garrett |author-link=Laurie Garrett |title=Betrayal of Trust: The Collapse of Global Public Health |publisher=[[Hachette Books]] |date=2011 |isbn=1-40130386-2}}</ref>\n\n===Protective sequestration===\n{{main|Protective sequestration}}\nDuring the [[influenza pandemic of 1918|1918 influenza epidemic]], the town of [[Gunnison, Colorado]], isolated itself for two months to prevent an introduction of the infection. Highways were barricaded and arriving train passengers were quarantined for five days. As a result of the isolation, no one died of influenza in Gunnison during the epidemic.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://chm.med.umich.edu/research/1918-influenza-escape-communities/gunnison/ |title=Gunnison: Case Study |publisher=[[University of Michigan Medical School]] |work=Center for the History of Medicine}}</ref> Several other communities adopted similar measures.<ref name=\"Markel\">{{cite journal |title=Nonpharmaceutical Influenza Mitigation Strategies, US Communities, 1918\u20131920 Pandemic |author-last1=Markel |author-first1=Howard |author-link1=Howard Markel |author-last2=Stern |author-first2=Alexandra Minna |author-link2=Alexandra Minna Stern |author-last3=Navarro |author-first3=J. Alexander |author-last4=Michalsen |author-first4=Joseph R. |author-last5=Monto |author-first5=Arnold S. |author-last6=DiGiovanni, Jr. |author-first6=Cleto |journal=[[Emerging Infectious Diseases]] |date=December 2006 |volume=12 |issue=12 |pages=1961\u20131964 |pmid=17326953 |pmc=3291356 |doi=10.3201/eid1212.060506 |url=https://wwwnc.cdc.gov/eid/article/12/12/pdfs/06-0506.pdf}}</ref>\n\nOther measures include shutting down or limiting [[mass transit]]<ref>{{Cite news |author-last=Taylor |author-first=Kate |title=No Bus Service. Crowded Trains. Transit Systems Struggle With the Virus. - U.S. cities with public transit systems are being forced to adapt to the risks posed by the coronavirus, implementing new sanitation protocols while contending with fewer riders and workers. |date=2020-03-20 |orig-year=2020-03-17 |newspaper=[[The New York Times]] |language=en-US |issn=0362-4331 |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/03/17/us/coronavirus-buses-trains-detroit-boston.html |access-date=2020-03-25 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200325024853/https://www.nytimes.com/2020/03/17/us/coronavirus-buses-trains-detroit-boston.html |archive-date=2020-03-25}}</ref> and closure of recreational facilities (community swimming pools, youth clubs, gymnasiums).<ref>{{cite web |title=Flu Pandemic Mitigation - Social Distancing |website=globalsecurity.org |url=http://www.globalsecurity.org/security/ops/hsc-scen-3_flu-pandemic-distancing.htm |access-date=2020-03-23 |url-status= |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200322163703/https://www.globalsecurity.org/security/ops/hsc-scen-3_flu-pandemic-distancing.htm |archive-date=2020-03-22}}</ref>\n\n<gallery widths=\"200px\" heights=\"200px\" >\nFile:Mole2.JPG|The [[Lazzaretto of Ancona]] was constructed in the 18th century on an artificial island to serve as a [[quarantine station]] and [[leprosarium]] for the port town of [[Ancona]], Italy.\nFile:Leprosorium.jpg|Two lepers denied entrance to town. Woodcut by [[Vincent of Beauvais]], 14th century.\n</gallery>\n\n==History==\n[[Leper colonies]] and [[lazaretto]]s were established as a means of preventing the spread of [[leprosy]] and other contagious diseases through social distancing,<ref>{{cite book |author-first=Charles L\u00e9on |author-last=Souvay |title=Catholic Encyclopedia |title-link=Catholic Encyclopedia |date=1913 |volume=9 |chapter=Leprosy |chapter-url=https://en.wikisource.org/wiki/Catholic_Encyclopedia_%281913%29/Leprosy |access-date=2020-03-28 |url-status=live |archive-url=http://archive.today/ZCJlV |archive-date=2020-03-28}}</ref> until transmission was understood and effective treatments invented.\n\n===1916 New York City polio epidemic===\n[[File:Popular science monthly (1872) (14596283227).jpg|thumb|New York City parks and playgrounds were closed during a 1916 polio epidemic.<ref name=\"PopSci\">{{Cite book |url=https://archive.org/details/popularsciencemo89newyuoft/page/400/mode/2up/search/flexner |title=Popular science monthly |date=1916 |publication-place=New York, USA |publisher=[[D. Appleton]] |page=400}}</ref>]]\n \nDuring the [[1916 New York City polio epidemic]], when there were over {{val|27000}} cases and more than {{val|6000}} deaths due to polio in the United States, with over {{val|2000}} deaths in New York City alone, movie theatres were closed, meetings were cancelled, public gatherings were almost non-existent, and children were warned not to drink from water fountains, and told to avoid amusement parks, swimming pools and beaches.<ref name=\"Battin2009\">{{Cite book |title=The Patient as Victim and Vector: Ethics and Infectious Disease |author-last1=Pabst Battin |author-first1=Margaret |author-link1=Margaret Pabst Battin |author-last2=Francis |author-first2=Leslie P. |author-last3=Jacobson |author-first3=Jay A. |author-last4=Smith |author-first4=Charles B. |date=2009 |publisher=[[Oxford University Press]] |isbn=978-0-19-533583-5 |page=351 |language=en |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=bXDnCwAAQBAJ&pg=PA351 |access-date=2020-03-28 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200328174235/https://books.google.de/books?id=bXDnCwAAQBAJ&pg=PA351&redir_esc=y |archive-date=2020-03-28}}</ref><ref name=\"Melnick_1996\">{{cite journal |author-last=Melnick |author-first=Joseph L. |author-link=Joseph L. Melnick |title=Current Status of Poliovirus Infections |url=https://cmr.asm.org/content/cmr/9/3/293.full.pdf |journal=[[Clinical Microbiology Reviews]] |publisher=[[American Society for Microbiology]] |volume=9 |issue=3 |pages=293\u2013300 |date=1996-07-01 |pmid=8809461 |pmc=172894 |doi=10.1128/CMR.9.3.293 |access-date=2020-03-28 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190430072527/https://cmr.asm.org/content/cmr/9/3/293.full.pdf |archive-date=2019-04-30}}</ref>\n\n===Influenza, 1918 to present===\n[[File:165-WW-269B-11-trolley-l.jpg|thumb|Passenger without mask being refused boarding of a streetcar (Seattle, Washington, 1918)]]\n\nDuring the [[influenza pandemic of 1918]], Philadelphia saw its first cases of influenza on 17 September.<ref name=\"Hatchett\">{{cite journal |author-last1=Hatchett |author-first1=Richard J. |author-last2=Mecher |author-first2=Carter E. |author-last3=Lipsitch |author-first3=Marc |author-link3=:wikidata:Q28322531 |editor-first=Burton H. |editor-last=Singer |title=Public health interventions and epidemic intensity during the 1918 influenza pandemic |url=http://www.pnas.org/cgi/content/full/104/18/7582 |journal=[[Proceedings of the National Academy of Sciences of the United States of America]] |volume=104 |issue=18 |pages=7582\u20137587 |date=2007-05-01 |orig-year=2007-04-06, 2007-02-14, 2006-12-09 |pmid=17416679 |doi=10.1073/pnas.0610941104 |pmc=1849867}}</ref><ref name=\"Ryan2008\">{{Cite book |author-last=Ryan |author-first=Jeffrey R. |title=Pandemic Influenza: Emergency Planning and Community Preparedness |chapter=Chapter 6.3.3. Response and Containment: Lessons from the 1918 Pandemic Can Help Communities Today |date=2008-08-01 |publisher=[[CRC Press]] |isbn=978-1-4200-6088-1 |location= |pages=123\u2013133 [133] |language=en |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=t13C_eWhOX4C&pg=PA133 |access-date=2020-03-29 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200329073524/https://books.google.com/books?id=t13C_eWhOX4C&pg=PA133&redir_esc=y |archive-date=2020-03-29}}</ref> The city continued with its planned parade and gathering of more than {{val|200000}} people and over the subsequent three days, the city's 31 hospitals became fully occupied. Over one week, {{val|4500}} people died.<ref name=\"Davis_20180921\"/><ref>{{Cite journal |title=Influenza in 1918: Recollections of the Epidemic in Philadelphia |author-first=Isaac |author-last=Starr |author-link=Isaac Starr |journal=[[Annals of Internal Medicine]] |date=1976-10-01 |volume=85 |issue=4 |pages=516\u2013518 |doi=10.7326/0003-4819-85-4-516 |language=en |pmid=788585}}</ref> Social distancing measures were introduced on 3 October, more than two weeks after the first case.<ref name=\"Ryan2008\"/> Unlike Philadelphia, St.&nbsp;Louis experienced its first cases of influenza on 5 October and the city took two days to implement several social distancing measures,<ref name=\"Ryan2008\"/> including closing schools, theatres, and other places where people get together. It banned public gatherings, including funerals. The actions slowed the spread of influenza in St.&nbsp;Louis and a spike in cases and deaths, as had happened in Philadelphia, did not occur.<ref name=\"Smith2007\">{{Cite journal |author-last=Smith |author-first=Richard |author-link=Richard Smith (editor) |date=2007-06-30 |title=Social measures may control pandemic flu better than drugs and vaccines |journal=[[British Medical Journal]] |volume=334 |issue=7608 |page=1341 |doi=10.1136/bmj.39255.606713.DB |issn=0959-8138 |pmc=1906625 |pmid=17599996 |url=https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC1906625/pdf/bmj-334-7608-news-1341a.pdf |access-date=2020-03-27 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200327222703/https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC1906625/pdf/bmj-334-7608-news-1341a.pdf |archive-date=2020-03-27}}</ref> The final death rate in St.&nbsp;Louis increased following a second wave of cases, but remained overall less than in other cities.<ref name=\"Kalnins\">{{Cite journal |author-last=Kalnins |author-first=Irene |date=September 2006 |title=The Spanish influenza of 1918 in St. Louis, Missouri |journal=[[Public Health Nursing]] |location=Boston, Massachusetts, USA |volume=23 |issue=5 |pages=479\u2013483 |doi=10.1111/j.1525-1446.2006.00586.x |issn=0737-1209 |pmid=16961567}}</ref> Bootsma and [[Neil Ferguson (epidemiologist)|Ferguson]] analyzed social distancing interventions in 16 US cities during the 1918 epidemic and found that time-limited interventions reduced total mortality only moderately (perhaps 10\u201330%), and that the impact was often very limited because the interventions were introduced too late and lifted too early. It was observed that several cities experienced a second epidemic peak after social distancing controls were lifted, because susceptible individuals who had been protected were now exposed.<ref name=\"Bootsma\">{{cite journal |author-last1=Bootsma |author-first1=Martin C. J. |author-last2=Ferguson |author-first2=Neil Morris |author-link2=Neil Ferguson (epidemiologist) |editor-first=Burton H. |editor-last=Singer |title=The effect of public health measures on the 1918 influenza pandemic in U.S. cities |journal=[[Proceedings of the National Academy of Sciences of the United States of America]] |volume=104 |issue=18 |pages=7588\u20137593 |date=2007-05-01 |orig-year=2007-03-13, 2006-12-13 |pmid=17416677 |doi=10.1073/pnas.0611071104 |pmc=1849868 |url=http://www.pnas.org/cgi/content/full/104/18/7588 |access-date=2020-03-28 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200322145722/https://www.pnas.org/content/104/18/7588.full |archive-date=2020-03-22}} [https://web.archive.org/web/20200324115254/https://www.pnas.org/content/pnas/104/18/7588.full.pdf] (6 pages)</ref>\n\nSchool closures were shown to reduce [[morbidity]] from the [[Influenza A virus subtype H2N2|Asian flu]] by 90% during the 1957\u20131958 outbreak,<ref>{{cite journal |author-last1=Chin |author-first1=Tom D. Y. |author-last2=Foley |author-first2=John F. |author-last3=Doto |author-first3=Irene L. |author-last4=Gravelle |author-first4=Clifton R. |author-last5=Weston |author-first5=Jean |date=February 1960 |title=Morbidity and mortality characteristics of Asian strain influenza |url= |journal=[[Public Health Reports]] |publisher=[[Sage Publications, Inc.]] |volume=75 |issue=2 |pages=149\u2013158 |doi=10.2307/4590751 |pmid=19316351 |pmc=1929395 |jstor=4590751}} (19 pages)</ref> and up to 50% in controlling influenza in the US, 2004\u20132008.<ref>{{cite journal |author-last1=Wheeler |author-first1=Colleen C. |author-last2=Erhart |author-first2=Laura M. |author-last3=Jehn |author-first3=Megan L. |date=November\u2013December 2010 |title=Effect of School Closure on the Incidence of Influenza Among School-Age Children in Arizona |journal=[[Public Health Reports]] |volume=125 |issue=6 |pages=851\u2013859 |doi=10.1177/003335491012500612 |pmid=21121230 |pmc=2966666}}</ref> Similarly, mandatory school closures and other social distancing measures were associated with a 29% to 37% reduction in influenza transmission rates during the [[2009 influenza pandemic|2009 flu epidemic]] in Mexico.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.nih.gov/news-events/nih-research-matters/flu-pandemic-study-supports-social-distancing |title=Flu Pandemic Study Supports Social Distancing |work=NIH Research Matters |publisher=[[National Institutes of Health]] |date=2011-06-06}}</ref>\n\nDuring the [[2009 flu pandemic in the United Kingdom|swine flu outbreak in 2009 in the UK]], in an article titled \"Closure of schools during an influenza pandemic\" published in the ''[[The Lancet Infectious Diseases]]'', a group of epidemiologists endorsed the closure of schools in order to interrupt the course of the infection, slow further spread and buy time to research and produce a vaccine.<ref name=\"Wardrop2009\">{{Cite news |author-last=Wardrop |author-first=Murray |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/health/swine-flu/5874683/Swine-flu-schools-should-close-to-halt-spread-of-virus-ministers-told.html |title=Swine flu: schools should close to halt spread of virus, ministers told |date=2009-07-21 |work=[[The Telegraph (UK)|The Telegraph]] |access-date=2020-03-17 |url-status=live |language=en-GB |issn=0307-1235 |url-access=subscription}}</ref> Having studied previous influenza pandemics including the [[Spanish flu|1918 flu pandemic]], the [[Influenza A virus subtype H2N2|influenza pandemic of 1957]] and the [[1968 flu pandemic]], they reported on the economic and workforce effect school closure would have, particularly with a large percentage of doctors and nurses being women, of whom half had children under the age of 16. They also looked at the dynamics of the spread of influenza in France during French school holidays and noted that cases of flu dropped when schools closed and re-emerged when they re-opened. They noted that when teachers in Israel went on strike during the flu season of 1999\u20132000, visits to doctors and the number of respiratory infections dropped by more than a fifth and more than two fifths respectively.<ref name=\"Reuters2009\">{{Cite news |author-last= |author-first= |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-flu-schools-idUSTRE56J4OO20090720 |title=Closing schools won't stop pandemics: study |date=2009-07-20 |publisher=[[Reuters]] |access-date=2020-03-17 |url-status=live |editor-last=Walsh |editor-first=Eric |language=en}}</ref>\n\n===SARS 2003===\nDuring the [[2002\u20132004 SARS outbreak|SARS outbreak of 2003]], social distancing measures such as banning large gatherings, closing schools and theaters, and other public places, supplemented public health measures such as finding and isolating affected people, quarantining their close contacts, and infection control procedures. This was combined with wearing masks for certain people.<ref name=\"Bell2004\">{{Cite journal |author-last=Bell |author-first=David M. |date=November 2004 |title=Public Health Interventions and SARS Spread, 2003 |journal=[[Emerging Infectious Diseases]] |volume=10 |issue=11 |pages=1900\u20131906 |doi=10.3201/eid1011.040729 |issn=1080-6040 |pmc=3329045 |pmid=15550198}}</ref> During this time in Canada, \"community quarantine\" was used to reduce transmission of the disease with moderate success.<ref name=Bondy>{{cite journal |title=Quantifying the impact of community quarantine on SARS transmission in Ontario: estimation of secondary case count difference and number needed to quarantine |author-last1=Bondy |author-first1=Susan J. |author-last2=Russell |author-first2=Margaret L. |author-last3=Lafl\u00e8che |author-first3=Julie M. L. |author-last4=Rea |author-first4=Elizabeth |date=2009-12-24 |pmid=20034405 |doi=10.1186/1471-2458-9-488 |pmc=2808319 |volume=9 |journal=[[BMC Public Health]] |page=488 |issue=1}}</ref>\n\n===2019\u20132020 coronavirus pandemic===\n{{main|2019\u20132020 coronavirus pandemic}}\n\n[[File:Katapult importance social distancing.gif|thumb|upright=1.6|Simulations comparing rate of spread of infection, and number of deaths due to overrun of hospital capacity, when social interactions are \"normal\" (left, 200 people moving freely) and \"distanced\" (right, 25 people moving freely).<br/>Green&nbsp;= Healthy, uninfected individuals<br/>Red&nbsp;= Infected individuals<br/>Blue&nbsp;= Recovered individual<br/>Black&nbsp;= Dead individuals<br/>]]\n\nDuring the [[2019\u20132020 coronavirus pandemic]], social distancing and related measures were emphasised by several governments as alternatives to an enforced quarantine of heavily affected areas. According to [[UNESCO]] monitoring, over 100 countries have implemented nationwide [[Impact of the 2019\u20132020 coronavirus pandemic on education|school closures in response to COVID-19]], impacting over half the world's student population.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web |title=COVID-19 Educational Disruption and Response |date=2020-03-04 |website=[[UNESCO]] |language=en |url=https://en.unesco.org/themes/education-emergencies/coronavirus-school-closures |access-date=2020-03-23 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200329110914/https://en.unesco.org/themes/education-emergencies/coronavirus-school-closures |archive-date=2020-03-29}}</ref> In the United Kingdom, the government advised the public to avoid public spaces, and cinemas and theatres voluntarily closed to encourage the government's message.<ref>{{Cite news |title=Most UK cinemas shut after virus advice |language=en-GB |date=2020-03-17 |work=[[BBC News]] |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/entertainment-arts-51925490 |access-date=2020-03-21 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200323161040/https://www.bbc.com/news/entertainment-arts-51925490 |archive-date=2020-03-23}}</ref>\n\nSome teens and young adults refused to voluntarily adopt social distancing practices. In [[Belgium]], media reported a [[rave]] was attended by at least {{val|300}} before it was broken up by local authorities. In [[France]] teens making nonessential trips are fined up to {{currency|amount=150|code=$|linked=yes}}. Beaches were closed in [[Florida]] and [[Alabama]] to disperse partygoers during spring break.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.wthr.com/article/parents-police-struggle-social-distance-young-coronavirus-outbreak |title=Parents, police struggle to social distance the young in coronavirus outbreak |date=2020-03-20}}</ref> Weddings were broken up in New Jersey and an 8 p.m. [[curfew]] was imposed in [[Newark, New Jersey|Newark]]. New York, New Jersey, Connecticut and Pennsylvania were the first states to adopt coordinated social distancing policies that closed down non-essential businesses and restricted large gatherings. Shelter in place orders in [[California]] were extended to the entire state on 19 March. On the same day [[Texas]] declared a public disaster and imposed statewide restrictions.<ref>{{cite news |title=Uh-Oh Moment Finally Hits States Slow to Adopt Social Distancing |date=2020-03-20 |author-first1=Elise |author-last1=Young |author-first2=David R. |author-last2=Baker |work=[[Bloomberg News]] |publisher=[[Bloomberg L.P.]] |url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2020-03-20/uh-oh-moment-finally-hits-states-slow-to-adopt-social-distancing |access-date=2020-03-29 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200323063706/https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2020-03-20/uh-oh-moment-finally-hits-states-slow-to-adopt-social-distancing |archive-date=2020-03-23}}</ref>\n\nThese preventive measures such as social-distancing and [[Isolation (health care)|self-isolation]] prompted the widespread closure of [[Primary school|primary]], [[Secondary school|secondary]], and [[Tertiary education|post-secondary schools]] in over 120 countries. As of 23 March 2020, over 1.2 billion learners were out of school due to [[Impact of the 2019\u20132020 coronavirus pandemic on education|school closures in response to COVID-19]].<ref name=\":0\"/> Given low rates of COVID-19 infection among children, the effectiveness of school closures has been called into question.<ref>{{Cite web |title=Lessons from Ebola: The secret of successful epidemic response |author-last=Frieden |author-first=Tom |author-link=Tom Frieden |work=[[CNN]] |url=https://www.cnn.com/2020/03/11/health/coronavirus-lessons-from-ebola/index.html |access-date=2020-03-23 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200323214843/https://edition.cnn.com/2020/03/11/health/coronavirus-lessons-from-ebola/index.html |archive-date=2020-03-23}}</ref> Even when school closures are temporary, it carries high social and economic costs.<ref>{{Cite web |title=Coronavirus deprives nearly 300 million students of their schooling: UNESCO |newspaper=[[The Telegram]] |via=[[Reuters]] |language=en |url=http://www.thetelegram.com/news/world/coronavirus-deprives-nearly-300-million-students-of-their-schooling-unesco-419714/ |access-date=2020-03-23 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200328210511/https://www.thetelegram.com/news/world/coronavirus-deprives-nearly-300-million-students-of-their-schooling-unesco-419714/ |archive-date=2020-03-28}}</ref> However, the significance of children in spreading COVID-19 is unclear.<ref name=\"Lipsitch\">{{Cite journal |author-last1=Lipsitch |author-first1=Marc |author-link1=:wikidata:Q28322531 |author-last2=Swerdlow |author-first2=David L. |author-last3=Finelli |author-first3=Lyn |author-link3=:wikidata:Q59908394 |date=2020-03-26 |orig-year=2020-02-19 |title=Defining the Epidemiology of Covid-19 \u2014 Studies Needed |journal=[[New England Journal of Medicine]] |volume=382 |issue=13 |pages=1194\u20131196 |doi=10.1056/NEJMp2002125 |pmid=32074416 |issn=0028-4793}}</ref><ref name=\"lww18March2020\">{{Cite journal |author-last1=Zimmermann |author-first1=Petra |author-last2=Curtis |author-first2=Nigel |author-link2=:wikidata:Q30513816 |date=2020-03-18 |title=Coronavirus Infections in Children Including COVID-19: An Overview of the Epidemiology, Clinical Features, Diagnosis, Treatment and Prevention Options in Children |journal=[[The Pediatric Infectious Disease Journal]] |language=en-US |volume=Online First |pages= |doi=10.1097/INF.0000000000002660 |issn=0891-3668 |url=https://journals.lww.com/pidj/Abstract/onlinefirst/Coronavirus_Infections_in_Children_Including.96251.aspx |access-date=2020-03-30 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200324192956/https://journals.lww.com/pidj/Abstract/onlinefirst/Coronavirus_Infections_in_Children_Including.96251.aspx |archive-date=2020-03-24}}</ref> While the full impact of school closures during the coronavirus pandemic are not yet known, initial evidence suggests school closures have had negative impacts on local economies and learning outcomes for students.<ref>{{Cite web |title=Adverse consequences of school closures |date=2020-03-10 |website=[[UNESCO]] |language=en |url=https://en.unesco.org/themes/education-emergencies/coronavirus-school-closures/consequences |access-date=2020-03-23 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200325181733/https://en.unesco.org/themes/education-emergencies/coronavirus-school-closures/consequences |archive-date=2020-03-25}}</ref><ref name=\"Stevens14March2020\">{{Cite web |title=These simulations show how to flatten the coronavirus growth curve |author-last=Stevens |author-first=Harry |date=2020-03-14 |website=[[Washington Post]] |language=en |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/graphics/2020/world/corona-simulator/ |access-date=2020-03-29 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200330062958/https://www.washingtonpost.com/graphics/2020/world/corona-simulator/ |archive-date=2020-03-30}}</ref>\n\nIn early March 2020, the sentiment \"Stay The Fuck Home\" was coined by Florian Reifschneider, a German engineer and was quickly echoed by notable celebrities such as [[Taylor Swift]], [[Ariana Grande]]<ref>{{Cite web |title=Taylor Swift Urges Fans to Stay Home Amid COVID-19 Outbreak: \"I love you so much and I need to express my concern that things aren\u2019t being taken seriously enough right now,\" superstar writes |author-first=Brenna |author-last=Ehrlich |date=2020-03-15 |work=[[Rolling Stone]] |url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-news/taylor-swift-urges-fans-to-stay-home-amid-covid-19-outbreak-967629/ |access-date=2020-03-28 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200319124912/https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-news/taylor-swift-urges-fans-to-stay-home-amid-covid-19-outbreak-967629/ |archive-date=2020-03-28}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |author-first=Florian |author-last=Reifschneider |date=2020 |title=A Movement to Stop the COVID-19 Pandemic |website=#StayTheFuckHome |url=https://staythefuckhome.com/ |access-date=2020-03-29 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200329165848/https://staythefuckhome.com/ |archive-date=2020-03-29}}</ref> and [[Busy Philipps]]<ref>{{Cite web |title=Busy Philipps Joins Cameo to Record \"Stay the Fuck Home\" Messages for Coronavirus |author-first=Alex |author-last=Hudson |date=2020-03-17 |website=exclaim.ca |url=http://exclaim.ca/film/article/busy_philipps_joins_cameo_to_record_stay_the_fuck_home_messages_for_coronavirus |access-date=2020-03-29 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200327135529/http://exclaim.ca/film/article/busy_philipps_joins_cameo_to_record_stay_the_fuck_home_messages_for_coronavirus |archive-date=2020-03-27}}</ref> in hopes of reducing and delaying the peak of the outbreak. [[Facebook]], [[Twitter]] and [[Instagram]] also joined the campaign with similar hashtags, stickers and filters under #staythefhome, #stayhome, #staythefuckhome and began trending across social media.<ref>{{Cite web |title=AMA, AHA, ANA: #StayHome to confront COVID-19 |publisher=[[American Medical Association]] |location=Chicago, USA |url=https://www.ama-assn.org/press-center/press-releases/ama-aha-ana-stayhome-confront-covid-19 |access-date=2020-03-30 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200328063402/https://www.ama-assn.org/press-center/press-releases/ama-aha-ana-stayhome-confront-covid-19 |archive-date=2020-03-28}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |title=No, Netflix Is Not Spoiling Its Own Shows To Fight Coronavirus |author-first=Madeline |author-last=Berg |work=[[Forbes]] |url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/maddieberg/2020/03/26/no-netflix-is-not-spoiling-its-own-shows-to-fight-coronavirus-but-these-ad-guys-are/ |access-date=2020-03-30 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200327154558/https://www.forbes.com/sites/maddieberg/2020/03/26/no-netflix-is-not-spoiling-its-own-shows-to-fight-coronavirus-but-these-ad-guys-are/ |archive-date=2020-03-27}}</ref><ref>{{Cite newspaper |title='It feels like wartime': how street artists are responding to coronavirus - The pandemic may have closed museums and galleries down but artists have found other ways to comment on the crisis |author-first=Nadja |author-last=Sayej |date=2020-03-25 |newspaper=[[The Guardian]] |series=Street art |url=https://www.theguardian.com/artanddesign/2020/mar/25/street-artists-coronavirus-us-it-feels-like-wartime |access-date=2020-03-30 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200329005102/https://www.theguardian.com/artanddesign/2020/mar/25/street-artists-coronavirus-us-it-feels-like-wartime |archive-date=2020-03-29}}</ref><ref name=\"NewsweekSTFH\"/> The website claims to have reached about 2 million people online and states that the text has been translated in 17 languages.<ref name=\"NewsweekSTFH\">{{Cite magazine |title=The #StayTheF***kHome movement just wants you to, well, you know |author-first=Jorge |author-last=Solis |date=2020-03-16 |magazine=[[Newsweek]] |series=Culture |language=en |url=https://www.newsweek.com/staythefkhome-movement-just-wants-you-well-you-know-1492581 |access-date=2020-03-30 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200327145436/https://www.newsweek.com/staythefkhome-movement-just-wants-you-well-you-know-1492581 |archive-date=2020-03-27}}</ref>\n\n==Drawbacks==\n\nThere are concerns that social distancing can have adverse affects on participants' mental health.<ref>{{Cite newspaper |title=Social distancing can strain mental health. Here's how you can protect yourself. |author-last=Ao |author-first=Bethany |newspaper=[[The Philadelphia Inquirer]] |language=en-US |date=2020-03-19 |url=https://www.inquirer.com/health/coronavirus/coronavirus-mental-health-social-distancing-20200319.html |access-date=2020-03-24 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200326073833/https://www.inquirer.com/health/coronavirus/coronavirus-mental-health-social-distancing-20200319.html |archive-date=2020-03-26}}</ref> It may lead to [[psychological stress|stress]], [[anxiety]], [[depression (mood)|depression]] or panic, especially for individuals with preexisting conditions such as anxiety disorders, [[OCD|obsessive compulsive disorders]], and [[paranoia]].<ref>{{Cite web |title=Stress and Coping |series=Coronavirus Disease 2019 (COVID-19) |date=2020-03-23 |orig-year=2020-02-11 |publisher=[[Centers for Disease Control and Prevention]] |language=en-us |url=https://www.cdc.gov/coronavirus/2019-ncov/prepare/managing-stress-anxiety.html |access-date=2020-03-24 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200329113040/https://www.cdc.gov/coronavirus/2019-ncov/daily-life-coping/managing-stress-anxiety.html?CDC_AA_refVal=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.cdc.gov%2Fcoronavirus%2F2019-ncov%2Fprepare%2Fmanaging-stress-anxiety.html |archive-date=2020-03-29}}</ref> Widespread media coverage about a pandemic, its impact on economy, and resulting hardships may create anxiety. Change in daily circumstances and uncertainty about the future may add onto the mental stress of being away from other people.<ref>{{Cite web |title=Coronavirus: Social distancing and isolation can take a toll on your mental health, here's how some people are coping - Managing mental health in the time of coronavirus |author-last=Willis |author-first=Olivia |date=2020-03-22 |work=[[ABC News]] |language=en-AU |url=https://www.abc.net.au/news/health/2020-03-22/mental-health-coronavirus-quarantine-self-isolation/12078550 |access-date=2020-03-24 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200328041752/https://www.abc.net.au/news/health/2020-03-22/mental-health-coronavirus-quarantine-self-isolation/12078550 |archive-date=2020-03-28}}</ref>\n\n==Theoretical basis==\n\nFrom the perspective of epidemiology, the basic goal behind social distancing is to decrease the [[basic reproduction number]], <math>R_0</math>, which is the average number of secondary infected individuals generated from one primary infected individual in a population where all individuals are equally susceptible to a disease. In a basic model of social distancing,<ref name=\"Becker\">{{cite book |author-last=Becker |author-first=Niels |title=Modeling to Inform Infectious Disease Control |date=2015 |publisher=[[CRC Press]] |isbn=978-1-49873107-2 |page=104}}</ref> where a proportion <math>f</math> of the population engages in social distancing to decrease their interpersonal contacts to a fraction <math>a</math> of their normal contacts, the new effective reproduction number <math>R</math> is given by:<ref name=\"Becker\"/>\n\n<math display=\"block\"> R = [1-(1-a^2)f]R_0 </math>\n\nFor example, 25% of the population reducing their social contacts to 50% of their normal level gives an effective reproduction number about 81% of the basic reproduction number. A seemingly small reduction has a profound{{clarify|date=March 2020}} effect in delaying the exponential growth and spread of a disease.\n\n==See also==\n* [[Hand washing]]\n* [[Isolation (health care)]]\n* [[Pest house]]\n* [[Stay-at-home order]]\n{{clear}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category|Social distancing}}\n\n{{Public health}}\n\n[[Category:Infectious diseases]]\n[[Category:Quarantine]]\n[[Category:Epidemics]]\n[[Category:Epidemiology]]\n[[Category:Medical hygiene]]\n", "text_old": "{{Short description|Infection control technique}}\n{{Distinguish|Social distance|Social isolation}}\n<noinclude>{{User:RMCD bot/subject notice|1=Physical distancing|2=Talk:Social distancing#Requested move 23 March 2020 }}\n</noinclude>\n{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2020|cs1-dates=y}}\n[[File:Social distancing queueing for the supermarket J. Sainsbury's north London Coronavirus Covid 19 pandemic - 30 March 2020.jpg|thumb|upright=1.85|People maintaining social distance while waiting to enter a store. To allow shoppers to maintain distance within the store, only a limited number are allowed inside at one time.]]\n[[File:Covid-19-Transmission-graphic-01.gif|thumb|upright=1.85|Social distancing reduces the rate of disease transmission and can stop an outbreak.]]\n'''Social distancing''', or '''physical distancing''',<ref name=\"WHO_20200320\">{{cite web |title=COVID-19 |author-first1=Margaret |author-last1=Harris |author-first2=Tedros |author-last2=Adhanom Ghebreyesus |author-link2=Tedros Adhanom Ghebreyesus |author-first3=Tu |author-last3=Liu |author-first4=Michael \"Mike\" J. |author-last4=Ryan |author-link4=Michael J. Ryan (doctor) |author5=Vadia<!-- Nowruz, Iran --> |author-first6=Maria D. |author-last6=Van Kerkhove |author-link6=Maria D. Van Kerkhove |author7=Diego<!-- Vortex --> |author-first8=Imogen |author-last8=Foulkes |author-first9=Charles |author-last9=Ondelam |author-first10=Corinne |author-last10=Gretler |author11=Costas<!-- ERT, Greece --> |date=2020-03-20 |publisher=[[World Health Organization]] |url=https://www.who.int/docs/default-source/coronaviruse/transcripts/who-audio-emergencies-coronavirus-press-conference-full-20mar2020.pdf?sfvrsn=1eafbff_0 |access-date=2020-03-29 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200325084602/https://www.who.int/docs/default-source/coronaviruse/transcripts/who-audio-emergencies-coronavirus-press-conference-full-20mar2020.pdf?sfvrsn=1eafbff_0 |archive-date=2020-03-25}}</ref><ref name=\"Hensley_20200323\">{{cite web |author-first=Laura |author-last=Hensley |title=Social distancing is out, physical distancing is in \u2014 here's how to do it |work=[[Global News]] |date=2020-03-23 |publisher=[[Corus Entertainment Inc.]] |url=https://globalnews.ca/news/6717166/what-is-physical-distancing/ |access-date=2020-03-29 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200326180136/https://globalnews.ca/news/6717166/what-is-physical-distancing/ |archive-date=2020-03-27}}</ref><ref name=\"Venske_20200326\">{{cite web |title=Die Wirkung von Sprache in Krisenzeiten |language=de |trans-title=The effect of language in times of crisis |date=2020-03-26 |editor-first=Andrea |editor-last=Schwyzer |author-first=Regula |author-last=Venske |author-link=:de:Regula Venske |type=Interview |publisher=[[Norddeutscher Rundfunk]] |series=NDR Kultur |url=https://www.ndr.de/kultur/Corona-Die-Wirkung-von-Sprache-in-Krisenzeiten,venske118.html |access-date=2020-03-27 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200327214038/https://www.ndr.de/kultur/Corona-Die-Wirkung-von-Sprache-in-Krisenzeiten,venske118.html |archive-date=2020-03-27}} (NB. Regula Venske is president of the [[PEN Centre Germany]].)</ref> is a set of non-pharmaceutical interventions or measures taken to [[infection control|prevent the spread]] of a [[infection|contagious disease]] by maintaining a physical distance between people and reducing the number of times people come into close contact with each other.<ref name=\"WHO_20200320\"/><ref name=\"JohnsonSunFreedman 2020\"/> It involves keeping a distance of six feet (two meters) from others and avoiding gathering together in large groups.<ref name=\"Pearce2020\"/><ref name=\"CDC22March2020\"/>\n\nBy reducing the probability that a given uninfected person will come into physical contact with an infected person, the [[transmission (medicine)|disease transmission]] can be suppressed, resulting in [[Mortality rate|fewer deaths]].<ref name=\"WHO_20200320\"/><ref name=\"JohnsonSunFreedman 2020\">{{cite newspaper |author-last1=Johnson |author-first1=Carolyn Y. |author-last2=Sun |author-first2=Lena |author-last3=Freedman |author-first3=Andrew |title=Social distancing could buy U.S. valuable time against coronavirus: It's a make-or-break moment with coronavirus to test one of the most basic \u2014 but disruptive \u2014 public health tools |newspaper=[[The Washington Post]] |date=2020-03-10 |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/health/2020/03/10/social-distancing-coronavirus/ |access-date=2020-03-11 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200327163232/https://www.washingtonpost.com/health/2020/03/10/social-distancing-coronavirus/ |archive-date=2020-03-27}}</ref> The measures are combined with good respiratory hygiene and hand washing.<ref name=\"WHO2May2009\"/><ref name=\"gov.ukSD\">{{Cite web |title=Guidance on social distancing for everyone in the UK |author-last= |author-first= |date= |website=GOV.UK |language=en |url=https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/covid-19-guidance-on-social-distancing-and-for-vulnerable-people/guidance-on-social-distancing-for-everyone-in-the-uk-and-protecting-older-people-and-vulnerable-adults |access-date=2020-03-29 |url-status=live |archive-url= |archive-date=}}</ref> During the [[2019\u20132020 coronavirus pandemic]], the [[World Health Organization]] (WHO) suggested the reference to \"physical\" as an alternative to \"social\", in keeping with the notion that it is a physical distance which prevents transmission; people can remain socially connected via technology.<ref name=\"WHO_20200320\"/><ref name=\"Hensley_20200323\"/><ref name=\"Tangermann_20200324\">{{cite web |title=It's Officially Time to Stop Using The Phrase 'Social Distancing'<!-- The WHO Wants You to Ditch the Phrase \"Social Distancing\" --> |date=2020-03-24 |orig-year=2020-03-20 |author-first=Victor |author-last=Tangermann |work=science alert (Futurism / The Byte) |url=https://www.sciencealert.com/who-is-no-longer-using-the-phrase-social-distancing |access-date=2020-03-29 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200326180149/https://www.sciencealert.com/who-is-no-longer-using-the-phrase-social-distancing |archive-date=2020-03-29}} [https://web.archive.org/web/20200326180155/https://futurism.com/the-byte/who-ditch-phrase-social-distancing]</ref>\n\nTo slow down the spread of infectious diseases and avoid overburdening healthcare systems, particularly during a [[pandemic]], several social distancing measures are used, including the closing of schools and workplaces, [[isolation (health care)|isolation]], [[quarantine]], [[cordon sanitaire|restricting movement of people]] and the cancellation of [[mass gathering]]s.<ref name=\"JohnsonSunFreedman 2020\"/><ref name=\"cdc2007\"/> Such measures have been successfully implemented in several previous epidemics. In [[St.&nbsp;Louis]], shortly after the first cases of influenza were detected in the city during the [[1918 flu pandemic]], authorities implemented school closures, bans on public gatherings and other social distancing interventions. The death rates in St.&nbsp;Louis were much less than in [[Philadelphia]], which despite having cases of influenza, allowed a mass parade to continue and did not introduce social distancing until more than two weeks after its first cases.<ref name=\"Ryan2008\"/>\n\nSocial distancing measures are more effective when the infectious disease spreads via droplet contact (coughing or sneezing); direct physical contact, including sexual contact; indirect physical contact (e.g., by touching a contaminated surface); or [[Airborne disease|airborne transmission]] (if the microorganism can survive in the air for long periods).<ref name=\"cidrap\">{{cite web |title=Information About Social Distancing |date=2017 |website=www.cidrap.umn.edu |publisher=Public Health Department: [[Santa Clara Valley Health & Hospital System]] |url=http://www.cidrap.umn.edu/sites/default/files/public/php/185/185_factsheet_social_distancing.pdf |access-date=2020-03-17 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200327162348/http://www.cidrap.umn.edu/sites/default/files/public/php/185/185_factsheet_social_distancing.pdf |archive-date=2020-03-27}}</ref> The measures are less effective when an infection is transmitted primarily via [[fecal-oral transmission|contaminated water or food]] or by [[Vector (epidemiology)|vector]]s such as mosquitoes or other insects.<ref name=\"CDCFeb2007\">{{cite web |title=Interim Pre-Pandemic Planning Guidance: Community Strategy for Pandemic Influenza Mitigation in the United States\u2014Early, Targeted, Layered Use of Nonpharmaceutical Interventions |publisher=[[Centers for Disease Control and Prevention]] |date=February 2007 |id=CS10848 |url=https://www.cdc.gov/flu/pandemic-resources/pdf/community_mitigation-sm.pdf |access-date=2020-03-29 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200319205055/https://www.cdc.gov/flu/pandemic-resources/pdf/community_mitigation-sm.pdf |archive-date=2020-03-19}}</ref>\n\nDrawbacks of social distancing can include [[loneliness]], reduced [[productivity]] and the loss of other benefits associated with [[human interaction]].<ref name=\"Brooks26Feb2020\"/>\n\n==Definition==\nThe [[Centers for Disease Control and Prevention]] (CDC) have described social distancing as a set of \"methods for reducing frequency and closeness of contact between people in order to decrease the risk of transmission of disease\".<ref name=\"cdc2007\"/> During the 2019\u20132020 coronavirus pandemic, the CDC revised the definition of social distancing as \"remaining out of congregrate settings, avoiding mass gatherings, and maintaining distance (approximately 6 feet or 2 meters) from others when possible.\"<ref name=\"Pearce2020\">{{Cite web |title=What is social distancing and how can it slow the spread of COVID-19? |author-last=Pearce |author-first=Katie |date=2020-03-13 |website=The Hub |publisher=[[Johns Hopkins University]] |language=en |url=https://hub.jhu.edu/2020/03/13/what-is-social-distancing/ |access-date=2020-03-29 |url-status=live |archive-url= |archive-date=}}</ref><ref name=\"CDC22March2020\">{{Cite web |title=Risk Assessment and Management |date=2020-03-22 |publisher=[[Centers for Disease Control and Prevention]] |language=en-us |url=https://www.cdc.gov/coronavirus/2019-ncov/php/risk-assessment.html |access-date=2020-03-29 |url-status=live |archive-url= |archive-date=}}</ref>\n\nPreviously, in 2009, the WHO described social distancing as \"keeping at least an arm's length distance from others, [and] minimizing gatherings\".<ref name=\"WHO2May2009\">{{Cite web |title=Pandemic influenza prevention and mitigation in low resource communities |date=2009-05-02 |publisher=[[World Health Organization]] |url=https://www.who.int/csr/resources/publications/swineflu/PI_summary_low_resource_02_05_2009.pdf?ua=1 |access-date=2020-03-29 |url-status=live |archive-url= |archive-date=}}</ref> It is combined with good respiratory hygiene and hand washing, and is considered the most feasible way to reduce or delay a pandemic.<ref name=\"WHO2May2009\"/>\n\n== Measures ==\n{{Redirect-distinguish2|Flatten the curve}}\n\n[[File:Covid-19_flatten_the_curve_-_cropped_version_(no_cartoon).gif|thumb|upright=1.5|Social distancing helps prevent a sharp peak of infections (\"flattens the [[epidemic curve]]\") to keep healthcare services from being overwhelmed.<ref name=\"Wiles_20200309\">{{cite web |author-last=Wiles |author-first=Siouxsie |author-link=Siouxsie Wiles |title=The three phases of Covid-19 \u2013 and how we can make it manageable |date=2020-03-09 |work=[[The Spinoff]] |location=Morningside, Auckland, New Zealand |url=https://thespinoff.co.nz/society/09-03-2020/the-three-phases-of-covid-19-and-how-we-can-make-it-manageable/ |access-date=2020-03-09 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200327120015/https://thespinoff.co.nz/society/09-03-2020/the-three-phases-of-covid-19-and-how-we-can-make-it-manageable/ |archive-date=2020-03-27}}</ref><ref name=\"Wiles_20200314\">{{cite web |author-last=Wiles |author-first=Siouxsie |author-link=Siouxsie Wiles |title=After 'Flatten the Curve', we must now 'Stop the Spread'. Here's what that means |date=2020-03-14 |work=[[The Spinoff]] |location=Morningside, Auckland, New Zealand |url=https://thespinoff.co.nz/society/14-03-2020/after-flatten-the-curve-we-must-now-stop-the-spread-heres-what-that-means/ |access-date=2020-03-13 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200326232315/https://thespinoff.co.nz/society/14-03-2020/after-flatten-the-curve-we-must-now-stop-the-spread-heres-what-that-means/ |archive-date=2020-03-26}}</ref><ref name=\"Anderson_20200309\">{{cite journal |author-last1=Anderson |author-first1=Roy Malcom |author-link1=Roy Malcolm Anderson |author-last2=Heesterbeek |author-first2=Hans J. A. P. |author-last3=Klinkenberg |author-first3=Don |author-last4=Hollingsworth |author-first4=T. D\u00e9irdre |author-link4=:wikidata:Q42660467 |date=2020-03-09 |title=How will country-based mitigation measures influence the course of the COVID-19 epidemic? |journal=[[The Lancet]] |language=en |volume=395 |issue=10228 |pages=931\u2013934 |doi=10.1016/S0140-6736(20)30567-5 |issn=0140-6736 |pmid=32164834 |url=https://www.thelancet.com/journals/lancet/article/PIIS0140-6736(20)30567-5/abstract |access-date=2020-03-28 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200327110325/https://www.thelancet.com/journals/lancet/article/PIIS0140-6736(20)30567-5/fulltext |archive-date=2020-03-27 |quote=A key issue for epidemiologists is helping policy makers decide the main objectives of mitigation\u2014e.g., minimising morbidity and associated mortality, avoiding an epidemic peak that overwhelms health-care services, keeping the effects on the economy within manageable levels, and flattening the epidemic curve to wait for vaccine development and manufacture on scale and antiviral drug therapies.}}</ref>]]\n\nKnowing that a disease is circulating may trigger a [[behaviour change (public health)|change in behaviour]] by people choosing to stay away from public places and other people. When implemented to control epidemics, such social distancing can result in benefits but with an economic cost. Research indicates that measures must be applied rigorously and immediately in order to be effective.<ref name=\"Maharaj2012\">{{cite journal |author-last1=Maharaj |author-first1=Savi |author-last2=Kleczkowski |author-first2=Adam |date=2012 |title=Controlling epidemic spread by social distancing: Do it well or not at all |journal=[[BioMed Central|BMC Public Health]] |volume=12 |issue=1 |page=679 |doi=10.1186/1471-2458-12-679 |pmid=22905965 |pmc=3563464}}</ref> Several social distancing measures are used to control the spread of contagious illnesses.<ref name=\"cdc2007\">{{cite web |author-first1=Kathy |author-last1=Kinlaw |author-first2=Robert J. |author-last2=Levine |title=Ethical guidelines in Pandemic Influenza \u2013 Recommendations of the Ethics Subcommittee of the Advisory Committee to the Director, Centers for Disease Control and Prevention |publisher=[[Centers for Disease Control and Prevention]] |date=2007-02-15 |url=https://www.cdc.gov/od/science/integrity/phethics/docs/panflu_ethic_guidelines.pdf |access-date=2020-03-23 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200205095942/https://www.cdc.gov/od/science/integrity/phethics/docs/panflu_ethic_guidelines.pdf |archive-date=2020-02-05}} (12 pages)</ref><ref name=\"cidrap\"/><ref name=\"Pearce2020\"/>\n\n===Avoiding physical contact===\n[[File:Covid-19-Handshake-Alternatives-v3.gif|thumb|upright=1.5|Social distancing includes eliminating the physical contact that occurs with the typical [[handshake]], [[hug]], or [[hongi]]; this illustration offers eight alternatives.]]\nKeeping at least two-metre distance from each other and avoiding hugs and [[List of gestures|gestures]] that involve direct physical contact, reduce the risk of becoming infected during flu [[pandemic]]s and the coronavirus pandemic of 2020.<ref name=\"Pearce2020\"/><ref name=\"osha\">{{cite web |title=Guidance on Preparing Workplaces for an Influenza Pandemic |id=OSHA 3327-02N 2007 |work=[[Occupational Safety and Health Act of 1970]] |publisher=[[United States Department of Labor]] |url=https://www.osha.gov/Publications/influenza_pandemic.html |access-date=2020-03-18 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200325141049/https://www.osha.gov/Publications/influenza_pandemic.html |archive-date=2020-03-25}} [https://web.archive.org/web/20200319163737/https://www.osha.gov/Publications/OSHA3327pandemic.pdf]</ref> These distances of separation, in addition to personal hygiene measures, are also recommended at places of work.<ref name=\"UofCh\">{{Cite web |title=Social Distancing |publisher=Department of Safety & Security, [[The University of Chicago]] |date=2015 |website=safety-security.uchicago.edu |url=https://safety-security.uchicago.edu/emergency_management/all_hazard_safety_procedures/social_distancing/ |access-date=2020-03-29 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200324150358/https://safety-security.uchicago.edu/emergency_management/all_hazard_safety_procedures/social_distancing/ |archive-date=2020-03-24}}</ref> Where possible it may be recommended to [[telecommuting|work from home]].<ref name=\"gov.ukSD\"/>\n\nVarious alternatives have been proposed for the tradition of [[handshake|handshaking]]. The gesture of [[namaste]], placing one's palms together, fingers pointing upwards, drawing the hands to the heart, is one non-touch alternative. During the [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in the United Kingdom]], this gesture was used by [[Charles, Prince of Wales|Prince Charles]] upon greeting reception guests, and has been recommended by the Director-General of the WHO, [[Tedros Adhanom Ghebreyesus]], and Israeli Prime Minister [[Benjamin Netanyahu]].<ref name=\"Barajas13March2020\">{{Cite web |title=Joined palms, hands on hearts, Vulcan salutes: Saying hello in a no-handshake era |author-last1=Barajas |author-first1=Julia |author-last2=Etehad |author-first2=Melissa |date=2020-03-13 |website=[[Los Angeles Times]] |language=en-US |url=https://www.latimes.com/world-nation/story/2020-03-13/coronavirus-namaste-greetings-handshakes-noncontact |access-date=2020-03-18 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200327064424/https://www.latimes.com/world-nation/story/2020-03-13/coronavirus-namaste-greetings-handshakes-noncontact |archive-date=2020-03-27}}</ref> Other alternatives include the [[Wave (gesture)|wave]], the [[Shaka sign|shaka (or \"hang loose\") sign]], and placing a palm on your heart, as practiced in parts of Iran.<ref name=\"Barajas13March2020\"/>\n<gallery>File:Social Distancing in a Computer Lab.jpg|thumb|upright=1.85|In this computer lab, every other workstation has been closed off to increase the distance between people working\nFile:President of Taiwan greeting.jpg|thumb|upright=0.7|[[Taiwan]]ese president [[Tsai Ing-wen]] giving a traditional Chinese [[greeting]] instead of [[handshake|shaking hands]]\nFile:Social_Distancing_Sign_@_London_Drugs_(49684963711).jpg|thumb|upright=1|Floor markings can help people maintain distance in public places</gallery>\n\n===School closures===\n[[Image:Swineflu uk hpa model.svg|thumb|right|upright=1|\nSwine flu cases per week in the United Kingdom in 2009; schools typically [[Summer vacation|close for summer]] in mid-July and re-open in early September.<ref name=\"HPApress\">{{cite web |title=2009 Press Releases |date=2009-12-24 |publisher=[[Health Protection Agency]] |url=https://webarchive.nationalarchives.gov.uk/20100303155122/http://www.hpa.org.uk/HPA/NewsCentre/NationalPressReleases/2009PressReleases/ |access-date=2009-12-24 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20091224065403/http://www.hpa.org.uk/HPA/NewsCentre/NationalPressReleases/2009PressReleases/ |archive-date=2009-12-24}}</ref>]]\n\nMathematical modeling has shown that transmission of an outbreak may be delayed by closing schools. However, effectiveness depends on the contacts children maintain outside of school. Often, one parent has to take time off work, and prolonged closures may be required. These factors could result in social and economic disruption.<ref name=\"Zumla2010\">{{Cite book |author-last1=Zumla |author-first1=Alimuddin |author-link1=Alimuddin Zumla  |title=Emerging Respiratory Infections in the 21st Century, An Issue of Infectious Disease Clinics |author-last2=Yew |author-first2=Wing-Wai |author-last3=Hui |author-first3=David S. C. |date=2010-08-31 |publisher=[[Elsevier Health Sciences]] |volume=24 |number=3 |isbn=978-1-4557-0038-7 |pages=614 |language=en |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=c9CQn9C4JaQC&pg=PA614 |access-date=2020-03-29 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200329195321/https://books.google.de/books?id=c9CQn9C4JaQC&pg=PA614&redir_esc=y |archive-date=2020-03-29}}</ref><ref name=\"CauchemezFerguson2009\">{{cite journal |author-last1=Cauchemez |author-first1=Simon |author-last2=Ferguson |author-first2=Neil Morris |author-link2=Neil Ferguson (epidemiologist) |author-last3=Wachtel |author-first3=Claude |author-last4=Tegnell |author-first4=Anders |author-last5=Saour |author-first5=Guillaume |author-last6=Duncan |author-first6=Ben |author-last7=Nicoll |author-first7=Angus |title=Closure of schools during an influenza pandemic |journal=[[The Lancet Infectious Diseases]] |volume=9 |issue=8 |date=August 2009 |pages=473\u2013481 |issn=1473-3099 |doi=10.1016/S1473-3099(09)70176-8 |pmid=19628172 |url=https://www.thelancet.com/action/showPdf?pii=S1473-3099%2809%2970176-8 |access-date=2020-03-29 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n===Workplace closures===\n[[Modeling and simulation]] studies based on US data suggest that if 10% of affected workplaces are closed, the overall infection transmission rate is around 11.9% and the epidemic peak time is slightly delayed. In contrast, if 33% of affected workplaces are closed, the attack rate decreases to 4.9%, and the peak time is delayed by one week.<ref>{{cite journal  |author-last1=Rousculp |author-first1=Matthew D. |author-last2=Johnston |author-first2=Stephen S. |author-last3=Palmer |author-first3=Liisa A. |author-last4=Chu |author-first4=Bong-Chul |author-last5=Mahadevia |author-first5=Parthiv J. |author-last6=Nichol |author-first6=Kristin L. |date=October 2010 |title=Attending Work While Sick: Implication of Flexible Sick Leave Policies |journal=[[Journal of Occupational and Environmental Medicine]] |volume=52 |issue=10 |pages=1009\u20131013 |doi=10.1097/jom.0b013e3181f43844 |pmid=20881626}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |author-last1=Kumar |author-first1=Supriya |author-last2=Crouse Quinn |author-first2=Sandra |author-last3=Kim |author-first3=Kevin H. |author-last4=Daniel |author-first4=Laura H. |author-last5=Freimuth |author-first5=Vicki S. |title=The Impact of Workplace Policies and Other Social Factors on Self-Reported Influenza-Like Illness Incidence During the 2009 H1N1 Pandemic |date=January 2012 |journal=[[American Journal of Public Health]] |volume=102 |issue=1 |pages=134\u2013140 |doi=10.2105/AJPH.2011.300307 |pmid=22095353 |pmc=3490553}}</ref> Workplace closures include closure of \"non-essential\" businesses and social services (\"non-essential\" means those facilities that do not maintain primary functions in the community, as opposed to [[essential services]]).<ref>{{cite web |title=Social Distancing Support Guidelines For Pandemic Readiness |publisher=[[Colorado Department of Public Health and Environment]] |date=March 2008 |url=https://www.colorado.gov/pacific/sites/default/files/OEPR_Guidelines-for-Social-Distancing-Pandemic-Readiness.pdf |access-date=2017-02-13 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170213001535/https://www.colorado.gov/pacific/sites/default/files/OEPR_Guidelines-for-Social-Distancing-Pandemic-Readiness.pdf |archive-date=2017-02-13}}</ref>\n\n===Canceling mass gatherings===\nCancellation of [[mass gathering]]s includes sports events, films or musical shows.<ref>{{cite journal |author-first1=Robert |author-last1=Booy |author-first2=James |author-last2=Ward |title=Evidence compendium and advice on social distancing and other related measures for response to an influenza pandemic |journal=[[:de:Paediatric Respiratory Reviews|Paediatric Respiratory Reviews]] |date=2015 |volume=16 |issue=2 |pages=119\u2013126 |publisher=National Centre for Immunisation Research and Surveillance |doi=10.1016/j.prrv.2014.01.003 |pmid=24630149 |url=https://www.health.gov.au/internet/main/publishing.nsf/Content/519F9392797E2DDCCA257D47001B9948/$File/Social.pdf |access-date=2015-05-15 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150515032806/https://www.health.gov.au/internet/main/publishing.nsf/Content/519F9392797E2DDCCA257D47001B9948/$File/Social.pdf |archive-date=2015-05-15}} (13 pages)</ref> Evidence suggesting that mass gatherings increase the potential for infectious disease transmission is inconclusive.<ref>{{cite journal |author-first1=Thomas V. |author-last1=Inglesby |author-first2=Jennifer B. |author-last2=Nuzzo |author-first3=Tara |author-last3=O'Toole |author-link3=Tara O'Toole |author-first4=Donald Ainslie |author-last4=Henderson |author-link4=Donald Ainslie Henderson |doi=10.1089/bsp.2006.4.366 |title=Disease Mitigation Measures in the Control of Pandemic Influenza |journal=Biosecurity and Bioterrorism: Biodefense Strategy, Practice, and Science |date=2006 |volume=4 |issue=4 |pages=366\u2013375 |pmid=17238820 |citeseerx=10.1.1.556.2672}}</ref> [[Anecdotal evidence]] suggests that certain types of mass gatherings may be associated with increased risk of [[Influenza#Transmission|influenza transmission]], and may also \"seed\" new strains into an area, instigating community transmission in a pandemic. During the 1918 influenza pandemic, [[Philadelphia Liberty Loans Parade|military parades in Philadelphia]]<ref name=\"Davis_20180921\">{{cite magazine |author-first=Kenneth C. |author-last=Davis |author-link=Kenneth C. Davis |title=Philadelphia Threw a WWI Parade That Gave Thousands of Onlookers the Flu |magazine=[[Smithsonian Magazine]] |date=2018-09-21 |url=https://www.smithsonianmag.com/history/philadelphia-threw-wwi-parade-gave-thousands-onlookers-flu-180970372/ |access-date=2020-03-27 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200327222425/https://www.smithsonianmag.com/history/philadelphia-threw-wwi-parade-gave-thousands-onlookers-flu-180970372/ |archive-date=2020-03-27}}</ref> and Boston<ref>{{cite news |title=The Flu in Boston |work=[[American Experience]] |publisher=[[WGBH Educational Foundation]] |url=https://www.pbs.org/wgbh/americanexperience/features/influenza-boston/ |access-date=2020-03-28 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200320142051/https://www.pbs.org/wgbh/americanexperience/features/influenza-boston/ |archive-date=2020-03-20}}</ref> may have been responsible for spreading the disease by mixing infected sailors with crowds of civilians. Restricting mass gatherings, in combination with other social distancing interventions, may help reduce transmission.<ref>{{cite journal |author-last1=Ishola |author-first1=David A. |author-last2=Phin |author-first2=Nick |date=December 2011 |title=Could Influenza Transmission Be Reduced by Restricting Mass Gatherings? Towards an Evidence-Based Policy Framework |url= |journal=Journal of Epidemiology and Global Health |volume=1 |issue=1 |pages=33\u201360 |doi=10.1016/j.jegh.2011.06.004 |pmid=23856374}}</ref>\n\n===Travel restrictions===\nBorder restrictions or internal travel restrictions are unlikely to delay an epidemic by more than 2\u20133 weeks unless implemented with over 99% coverage.<ref>{{cite journal |author-last1=Ferguson |author-first1=Neil Morris |author-link1=Neil Ferguson (epidemiologist) |author-last2=Cummings |author-first2=Derek A. T. |author-last3=Fraser |author-first3=Christophe |author-last4=Cajka |author-first4=James C. |author-last5=Cooley |author-first5=Philip C. |author-last6=Burke |author-first6=Donald S. |author-link6=Donald S. Burke |date=2006 |title=Strategies for mitigating an influenza pandemic |journal=[[Nature (journal)|Nature]] |volume=442 |issue=7101 |pages=448\u2013452 |doi=10.1038/nature04795 |pmid=16642006 |pmc=7095311 |bibcode=2006Natur.442..448F}}</ref> Airport screening was found to be ineffective in preventing viral transmission during the 2003 SARS outbreak in Canada<ref>{{cite journal |author-last=Bell |author-first=David M. |date=2004 |title=Public health interventions and SARS spread, 2003 |journal=[[Emerging Infectious Diseases]] |volume=10 |issue=11 |pages=1900\u20131906 |doi=10.3201/eid1011.040729 |pmid=15550198 |pmc=3329045 |url=https://www.cdc.gov/ncidod/EID/vol10no11/04-0729.htm |access-date= |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20091105074656/https://www.cdc.gov/ncidod/EID/vol10no11/04-0729.htm |archive-date=2009-11-05}}</ref> and the US.<ref>{{cite book |author-first=Martin |author-last=Cetron |chapter-url=https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK92450/ |chapter=Isolation and Quarantine: Containment Strategies for SARS, 2003 |title=Learning from SARS: Preparing for the Next Disease Outbreak |publisher=[[National Academy of Sciences]] |date=2004 |isbn=0-30959433-2}}</ref> Strict border controls between [[Austria]] and the [[Ottoman Empire]], imposed from 1770 until 1871 to prevent persons infected with the [[bubonic plague]] from entering Austria, were reportedly effective, as there were no major outbreaks of plague in Austrian territory after they were established, whereas the Ottoman Empire continued to suffer frequent epidemics of plague until the mid-nineteenth century.<ref name=\"Kohn\">{{cite book |editor-first=George Childs |editor-last=Kohn |title=Encyclopedia of Plague and Pestilence: From Ancient Times to the Present |publisher=[[Infobase Publishing]] |series=Facts On File - Library Of World History |date=2008 |orig-year=2001, 1998 |page=30 |isbn=978-1-43812923-5 |edition=3 |publication-place=New York, USA |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=tzRwRmb09rgC&pg=PA30 |access-date=2020-03-29 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200329120426/https://books.google.com/books?id=tzRwRmb09rgC&pg=PA30 |archive-date=2020-03-29}}</ref><ref>{{cite book |title=Encyclopedia of Pestilence, Pandemics, and Plague |editor-first=Joseph P. |editor-last=Byrne |date=2008 |publisher=[[Greenwood Publishing Group, Inc.]] / [[Greenwood Press]] |publication-place=Westport, Connecticut, USA / London, UK |lccn=2008019487 |volume=1&2<!-- Volume 1, A\u2013M --> |isbn=<!-- 978\u20130\u2013313\u201334101\u20134 --> |id=978\u20130\u2013313\u201334102\u20131 (vol 1), 978\u20130\u2013313\u201334103\u20138 (vol 2) |url=http://www.academia.dk/MedHist/Sygdomme/PDF/Encyclopedia_of_Pestilence_Pandemics_and_Plagues.pdf |access-date=2020-03-29 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200215143932/https://www.academia.dk/MedHist/Sygdomme/PDF/Encyclopedia_of_Pestilence_Pandemics_and_Plagues.pdf |archive-date=2020-02-15}}</ref> \n\nA [[Northeastern University]] study published in March 2020 found that \"travel restrictions to and from China only slow down the international spread of [[COVID-19]] [when] combined with efforts to reduce transmission on a community and an individual level. [\u2026] Travel restrictions aren't enough unless we couple it with social distancing.\"<ref>{{cite news |author-first=Emily |author-last=Arntsen |title=Closing borders can delay, but can't stop the spread of COVID-19, new report says |work=News@Northeastern |publisher=[[Northeastern University]] |date=2020-03-06 |url=https://news.northeastern.edu/2020/03/06/to-slow-the-spread-of-covid-19-close-doors-not-borders-new-report-says/ |access-date=2020-03-28 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200323063603/https://news.northeastern.edu/2020/03/06/to-slow-the-spread-of-covid-19-close-doors-not-borders-new-report-says/ |archive-date=2020-03-23}}</ref> The study found that the travel ban in Wuhan only delayed the spread of the disease to other parts of mainland China by three to five days, although it did reduce the spread of international cases by as much as 80 percent. A primary reason that travel restrictions were less effective is that many people with COVID-19 do not show symptoms during the early stages of infection.<ref>{{cite journal |title=The effect of travel restrictions on the spread of the 2019 novel coronavirus (COVID-19) outbreak |author-last1=Chinazzi |author-first1=Matteo |author-last2=Davis |author-first2=Jessica T. |author-last3=Ajelli |author-first3=Marco |author-last4=Gioannini |author-first4=Corrado |author-last5=Litvinova |author-first5=Maria |author-last6=Merler |author-first6=Stefano |author-link6=:wikidata:Q56380887 |author-last7=Pastore y Piontti |author-first7=Ana |author-last8=Mu |author-first8=Kunpeng |author-last9=Rossi |author-first9=Luca |author-last10=Sun |author-first10=Kaiyuan |author-last11=Viboud |author-first11=C\u00e9cile |author-last12=Xiong |author-first12=Xinyue |author-last13=Yu |author-first13=Hongjie |author-last14=Halloran |author-first14=M. Elizabeth |author-last15=Longini, Jr. |author-first15=Ira M. |author-link15=Ira M. Longini, Jr. |author-last16=Vespignani |author-first16=Alessandro |author-link16=Alessandro Vespignani |journal=[[Science (journal)|Science]] |date=2020-03-06 |doi=10.1126/science.aba9757 |pages=eaba9757 |pmid=32144116 |url=https://science.sciencemag.org/content/early/2020/03/05/science.aba9757 |access-date=2020-03-29 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200328084850/https://science.sciencemag.org/content/early/2020/03/05/science.aba9757 |archive-date=2020-03-28}}</ref>\n\n===Self-shielding===\nSelf-shielding measures for individuals include limiting face-to-face contacts, conducting business by phone or online, avoiding public places and reducing unnecessary travel.<ref name=\"Glass\">{{cite journal |author-last1=Glass |author-first1=Robert J. |author-last2=Glass |author-first2=Laura M. |author-last3=Beyeler |author-first3=Walter E. |author-last4=Min |author-first4=H. Jason |doi=10.3201/eid1211.060255 |title=Targeted Social Distancing Designs for Pandemic Influenza |journal=[[Emerging Infectious Diseases]] |publisher=[[Centers for Disease Control and Prevention]] |date=November 2006 |volume=12 |issue=11 |pages=1671\u20131681 |pmid=17283616 |pmc=3372334 |url=https://wwwnc.cdc.gov/eid/article/12/11/06-0255_article |access-date=2020-03-29 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200323042313/https://wwwnc.cdc.gov/eid/article/12/11/06-0255_article |archive-date=2020-03-23}}</ref><ref name=\"SDG\">{{cite web |title=Social Distancing Guidelines (for workplace communicable disease outbreaks) |date=2017 |publisher=[[Society for Human Resource Management]] |url=https://www.shrm.org/resourcesandtools/tools-and-samples/policies/pages/cms_016204.aspx |access-date=2017-04-23 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170423071438/https://www.shrm.org/resourcesandtools/tools-and-samples/policies/pages/cms_016204.aspx |archive-date=2017-04-23}}</ref><ref name=HeartMatters>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bhf.org.uk/informationsupport/heart-matters-magazine/news/coronavirus-and-your-health/whats-the-difference-between-shielding-self-isolation-and-social-distancing|title=What's the difference between shielding, self-isolation and social distancing?|website=www.bhf.org.uk|language=en|access-date=2020-03-29}}</ref>\n\n===Quarantine of possible cases===\nDuring the 2003 [[SARS]] outbreak in Singapore, approximately {{val|8000}} people were subjected to mandatory home quarantine and an additional {{val|4300}} were required to self-monitor for symptoms and make daily telephone contact with health authorities as a means of controlling the epidemic. Although only 58 of these individuals were eventually diagnosed with SARS, public health officials were satisfied that this measure assisted in preventing further spread of the infection.<ref>{{cite journal |author-first=Chorh-Chuan |author-last=Tan |author-link=Tan Chorh Chuan |url=http://www.srmuniv.ac.in/sites/default/files/downloads/sars_outbreak_lessons.pdf |pmid=16830002 |title=SARS in Singapore \u2013 Key Lessons from an Epidemic |journal=Annals Academy of Medicine |date=May 2006 |volume=35 |number=5 |pages=345\u2013349}}</ref> Voluntary self-isolation may have helped reduce transmission of influenza in Texas in 2009.<ref>{{cite journal |author-last1=Teh |author-first1=Benjamin |author-last2=Olsen |author-first2=Karen |author-last3=Black |author-first3=Jim |author-last4=Cheng |author-first4=Allen C. |author-last5=Aboltins |author-first5=Craig |author-last6=Bull |author-first6=Kirstin |author-first7=Paul D. R. |author-last7=Johnson |author-first8=M. Lindsay |author-last8=Grayson |author-first9=Joseph |author-last9=Torresi |title=Impact of swine influenza and quarantine measures on patients and households during the H1N1/09 pandemic |date=2012 |orig-year=2011-11-22, 2011-09-26, 2011-06-29 |journal=[[Scandinavian Journal of Infectious Diseases]] |volume=44 |issue=4 |pages=289\u2013296 |doi=10.3109/00365548.2011.631572 |pmid=22106922}}</ref> Short and longterm negative psychological effects have been reported.<ref name=\"Brooks26Feb2020\">{{Cite journal |author-last1=Brooks |author-first1=Samantha K. |author-last2=Webster |author-first2=Rebecca K. |author-last3=Smith |author-first3=Louise E. |author-last4=Woodland |author-first4=Lisa |author-last5=Wessely |author-first5=Simon |author-link5=Simon Wessely |author-last6=Greenberg |author-first6=Neil |author-link6=Neil Greenberg |author-last7=Rubin |author-first7=Gideon James |date=2020-03-14 |title=The psychological impact of quarantine and how to reduce it: rapid review of the evidence |url=https://www.thelancet.com/action/showPdf?pii=S0140-6736%2820%2930460-8 |journal=[[The Lancet]] |language=en |volume=395 |issue=10227 |pages=912\u2013920 |doi=10.1016/S0140-6736(20)30460-8 |issn=0140-6736 |pmid=32112714}}</ref>\n\n===''Cordon sanitaire''===\n{{main|Cordon sanitaire}}\nIn 1995, a ''cordon sanitaire'' was used to control an outbreak of [[Ebola virus disease]] in [[Kikwit]], [[Zaire]].<ref>{{cite news |author-first=Laurie |author-last=Garrett |author-link=Laurie Garrett |url=https://newrepublic.com/article/119085/ebola-cordon-sanitaire-when-it-worked-congo-1995 |title=Heartless but Effective: I've Seen 'Cordon Sanitaire' Work Against Ebola |work=[[The New Republic]] |date=2014-08-14}}</ref><ref>{{cite newspaper |url=https://www.cdc.gov/mmwr/preview/mmwrhtml/00037078.htm |title=Outbreak of Ebola Viral Hemorrhagic Fever -- Zaire, 1995 |newspaper=[[Morbidity and Mortality Weekly Report]] |date=1995-05-19 |volume=44 |number=19 |pages=381\u2013382}}</ref><ref name=\"Kaplan\">{{cite journal |author-first1=Rachel |author-last1=Kaplan Hoffmann |author-first2=Keith |author-last2=Hoffmann |title=Ethical Considerations in the Use of Cordons Sanitaires |journal=Clinical Correlations |publisher=[[New York University]] |location=[[NYU Langone]], New York, USA |eissn=1944-0030 |date=2015-02-19 |url=https://www.clinicalcorrelations.org/2015/02/19/ethical-considerations-in-the-use-of-cordons-sanitaires/ |access-date=2020-03-29 |url-status=live |archive-url=http://archive.today/ztkqC |archive-date=2020-03-29}}</ref> President [[Mobutu Sese Seko]] surrounded the town with troops and suspended all flights into the community. Inside Kikwit, the [[World Health Organization]] and Zaire medical teams erected further ''cordons sanitaires'', isolating burial and treatment zones from the general population and successfully containing the infection.<ref>{{cite book |author-first=Laurie |author-last=Garrett |author-link=Laurie Garrett |title=Betrayal of Trust: The Collapse of Global Public Health |publisher=[[Hachette Books]] |date=2011 |isbn=1-40130386-2}}</ref>\n\n===Protective sequestration===\n{{main|Protective sequestration}}\nDuring the [[influenza pandemic of 1918|1918 influenza epidemic]], the town of [[Gunnison, Colorado]], isolated itself for two months to prevent an introduction of the infection. Highways were barricaded and arriving train passengers were quarantined for five days. As a result of the isolation, no one died of influenza in Gunnison during the epidemic.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://chm.med.umich.edu/research/1918-influenza-escape-communities/gunnison/ |title=Gunnison: Case Study |publisher=[[University of Michigan Medical School]] |work=Center for the History of Medicine}}</ref> Several other communities adopted similar measures.<ref name=\"Markel\">{{cite journal |title=Nonpharmaceutical Influenza Mitigation Strategies, US Communities, 1918\u20131920 Pandemic |author-last1=Markel |author-first1=Howard |author-link1=Howard Markel |author-last2=Stern |author-first2=Alexandra Minna |author-link2=Alexandra Minna Stern |author-last3=Navarro |author-first3=J. Alexander |author-last4=Michalsen |author-first4=Joseph R. |author-last5=Monto |author-first5=Arnold S. |author-last6=DiGiovanni, Jr. |author-first6=Cleto |journal=[[Emerging Infectious Diseases]] |date=December 2006 |volume=12 |issue=12 |pages=1961\u20131964 |pmid=17326953 |pmc=3291356 |doi=10.3201/eid1212.060506 |url=https://wwwnc.cdc.gov/eid/article/12/12/pdfs/06-0506.pdf}}</ref>\n\nOther measures include shutting down or limiting [[mass transit]]<ref>{{Cite news |author-last=Taylor |author-first=Kate |title=No Bus Service. Crowded Trains. Transit Systems Struggle With the Virus. - U.S. cities with public transit systems are being forced to adapt to the risks posed by the coronavirus, implementing new sanitation protocols while contending with fewer riders and workers. |date=2020-03-20 |orig-year=2020-03-17 |newspaper=[[The New York Times]] |language=en-US |issn=0362-4331 |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/03/17/us/coronavirus-buses-trains-detroit-boston.html |access-date=2020-03-25 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200325024853/https://www.nytimes.com/2020/03/17/us/coronavirus-buses-trains-detroit-boston.html |archive-date=2020-03-25}}</ref> and closure of recreational facilities (community swimming pools, youth clubs, gymnasiums).<ref>{{cite web |title=Flu Pandemic Mitigation - Social Distancing |website=globalsecurity.org |url=http://www.globalsecurity.org/security/ops/hsc-scen-3_flu-pandemic-distancing.htm |access-date=2020-03-23 |url-status= |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200322163703/https://www.globalsecurity.org/security/ops/hsc-scen-3_flu-pandemic-distancing.htm |archive-date=2020-03-22}}</ref>\n\n<gallery widths=\"200px\" heights=\"200px\" >\nFile:Mole2.JPG|The [[Lazzaretto of Ancona]] was constructed in the 18th century on an artificial island to serve as a [[quarantine station]] and [[leprosarium]] for the port town of [[Ancona]], Italy.\nFile:Leprosorium.jpg|Two lepers denied entrance to town. Woodcut by [[Vincent of Beauvais]], 14th century.\n</gallery>\n\n==History==\n[[Leper colonies]] and [[lazaretto]]s were established as a means of preventing the spread of [[leprosy]] and other contagious diseases through social distancing,<ref>{{cite book |author-first=Charles L\u00e9on |author-last=Souvay |title=Catholic Encyclopedia |title-link=Catholic Encyclopedia |date=1913 |volume=9 |chapter=Leprosy |chapter-url=https://en.wikisource.org/wiki/Catholic_Encyclopedia_%281913%29/Leprosy |access-date=2020-03-28 |url-status=live |archive-url=http://archive.today/ZCJlV |archive-date=2020-03-28}}</ref> until transmission was understood and effective treatments invented.\n\n===1916 New York City polio epidemic===\n[[File:Popular science monthly (1872) (14596283227).jpg|thumb|New York City parks and playgrounds were closed during a 1916 polio epidemic.<ref name=\"PopSci\">{{Cite book |url=https://archive.org/details/popularsciencemo89newyuoft/page/400/mode/2up/search/flexner |title=Popular science monthly |date=1916 |publication-place=New York, USA |publisher=[[D. Appleton]] |page=400}}</ref>]]\n \nDuring the [[1916 New York City polio epidemic]], when there were over {{val|27000}} cases and more than {{val|6000}} deaths due to polio in the United States, with over {{val|2000}} deaths in New York City alone, movie theatres were closed, meetings were cancelled, public gatherings were almost non-existent, and children were warned not to drink from water fountains, and told to avoid amusement parks, swimming pools and beaches.<ref name=\"Battin2009\">{{Cite book |title=The Patient as Victim and Vector: Ethics and Infectious Disease |author-last1=Pabst Battin |author-first1=Margaret |author-link1=Margaret Pabst Battin |author-last2=Francis |author-first2=Leslie P. |author-last3=Jacobson |author-first3=Jay A. |author-last4=Smith |author-first4=Charles B. |date=2009 |publisher=[[Oxford University Press]] |isbn=978-0-19-533583-5 |page=351 |language=en |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=bXDnCwAAQBAJ&pg=PA351 |access-date=2020-03-28 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200328174235/https://books.google.de/books?id=bXDnCwAAQBAJ&pg=PA351&redir_esc=y |archive-date=2020-03-28}}</ref><ref name=\"Melnick_1996\">{{cite journal |author-last=Melnick |author-first=Joseph L. |author-link=Joseph L. Melnick |title=Current Status of Poliovirus Infections |url=https://cmr.asm.org/content/cmr/9/3/293.full.pdf |journal=[[Clinical Microbiology Reviews]] |publisher=[[American Society for Microbiology]] |volume=9 |issue=3 |pages=293\u2013300 |date=1996-07-01 |pmid=8809461 |pmc=172894 |doi=10.1128/CMR.9.3.293 |access-date=2020-03-28 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190430072527/https://cmr.asm.org/content/cmr/9/3/293.full.pdf |archive-date=2019-04-30}}</ref>\n\n===Influenza, 1918 to present===\n[[File:165-WW-269B-11-trolley-l.jpg|thumb|Passenger without mask being refused boarding of a streetcar (Seattle, Washington, 1918)]]\n\nDuring the [[influenza pandemic of 1918]], Philadelphia saw its first cases of influenza on 17 September.<ref name=\"Hatchett\">{{cite journal |author-last1=Hatchett |author-first1=Richard J. |author-last2=Mecher |author-first2=Carter E. |author-last3=Lipsitch |author-first3=Marc |author-link3=:wikidata:Q28322531 |editor-first=Burton H. |editor-last=Singer |title=Public health interventions and epidemic intensity during the 1918 influenza pandemic |url=http://www.pnas.org/cgi/content/full/104/18/7582 |journal=[[Proceedings of the National Academy of Sciences of the United States of America]] |volume=104 |issue=18 |pages=7582\u20137587 |date=2007-05-01 |orig-year=2007-04-06, 2007-02-14, 2006-12-09 |pmid=17416679 |doi=10.1073/pnas.0610941104 |pmc=1849867}}</ref><ref name=\"Ryan2008\">{{Cite book |author-last=Ryan |author-first=Jeffrey R. |title=Pandemic Influenza: Emergency Planning and Community Preparedness |chapter=Chapter 6.3.3. Response and Containment: Lessons from the 1918 Pandemic Can Help Communities Today |date=2008-08-01 |publisher=[[CRC Press]] |isbn=978-1-4200-6088-1 |location= |pages=123\u2013133 [133] |language=en |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=t13C_eWhOX4C&pg=PA133 |access-date=2020-03-29 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200329073524/https://books.google.com/books?id=t13C_eWhOX4C&pg=PA133&redir_esc=y |archive-date=2020-03-29}}</ref> The city continued with its planned parade and gathering of more than {{val|200000}} people and over the subsequent three days, the city's 31 hospitals became fully occupied. Over one week, {{val|4500}} people died.<ref name=\"Davis_20180921\"/><ref>{{Cite journal |title=Influenza in 1918: Recollections of the Epidemic in Philadelphia |author-first=Isaac |author-last=Starr |author-link=Isaac Starr |journal=[[Annals of Internal Medicine]] |date=1976-10-01 |volume=85 |issue=4 |pages=516\u2013518 |doi=10.7326/0003-4819-85-4-516 |language=en |pmid=788585}}</ref> Social distancing measures were introduced on 3 October, more than two weeks after the first case.<ref name=\"Ryan2008\"/> Unlike Philadelphia, St.&nbsp;Louis experienced its first cases of influenza on 5 October and the city took two days to implement several social distancing measures,<ref name=\"Ryan2008\"/> including closing schools, theatres, and other places where people get together. It banned public gatherings, including funerals. The actions slowed the spread of influenza in St.&nbsp;Louis and a spike in cases and deaths, as had happened in Philadelphia, did not occur.<ref name=\"Smith2007\">{{Cite journal |author-last=Smith |author-first=Richard |author-link=Richard Smith (editor) |date=2007-06-30 |title=Social measures may control pandemic flu better than drugs and vaccines |journal=[[British Medical Journal]] |volume=334 |issue=7608 |page=1341 |doi=10.1136/bmj.39255.606713.DB |issn=0959-8138 |pmc=1906625 |pmid=17599996 |url=https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC1906625/pdf/bmj-334-7608-news-1341a.pdf |access-date=2020-03-27 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200327222703/https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC1906625/pdf/bmj-334-7608-news-1341a.pdf |archive-date=2020-03-27}}</ref> The final death rate in St.&nbsp;Louis increased following a second wave of cases, but remained overall less than in other cities.<ref name=\"Kalnins\">{{Cite journal |author-last=Kalnins |author-first=Irene |date=September 2006 |title=The Spanish influenza of 1918 in St. Louis, Missouri |journal=[[Public Health Nursing]] |location=Boston, Massachusetts, USA |volume=23 |issue=5 |pages=479\u2013483 |doi=10.1111/j.1525-1446.2006.00586.x |issn=0737-1209 |pmid=16961567}}</ref> Bootsma and [[Neil Ferguson (epidemiologist)|Ferguson]] analyzed social distancing interventions in 16 US cities during the 1918 epidemic and found that time-limited interventions reduced total mortality only moderately (perhaps 10\u201330%), and that the impact was often very limited because the interventions were introduced too late and lifted too early. It was observed that several cities experienced a second epidemic peak after social distancing controls were lifted, because susceptible individuals who had been protected were now exposed.<ref name=\"Bootsma\">{{cite journal |author-last1=Bootsma |author-first1=Martin C. J. |author-last2=Ferguson |author-first2=Neil Morris |author-link2=Neil Ferguson (epidemiologist) |editor-first=Burton H. |editor-last=Singer |title=The effect of public health measures on the 1918 influenza pandemic in U.S. cities |journal=[[Proceedings of the National Academy of Sciences of the United States of America]] |volume=104 |issue=18 |pages=7588\u20137593 |date=2007-05-01 |orig-year=2007-03-13, 2006-12-13 |pmid=17416677 |doi=10.1073/pnas.0611071104 |pmc=1849868 |url=http://www.pnas.org/cgi/content/full/104/18/7588 |access-date=2020-03-28 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200322145722/https://www.pnas.org/content/104/18/7588.full |archive-date=2020-03-22}} [https://web.archive.org/web/20200324115254/https://www.pnas.org/content/pnas/104/18/7588.full.pdf] (6 pages)</ref>\n\nSchool closures were shown to reduce [[morbidity]] from the [[Influenza A virus subtype H2N2|Asian flu]] by 90% during the 1957\u20131958 outbreak,<ref>{{cite journal |author-last1=Chin |author-first1=Tom D. Y. |author-last2=Foley |author-first2=John F. |author-last3=Doto |author-first3=Irene L. |author-last4=Gravelle |author-first4=Clifton R. |author-last5=Weston |author-first5=Jean |date=February 1960 |title=Morbidity and mortality characteristics of Asian strain influenza |url= |journal=[[Public Health Reports]] |publisher=[[Sage Publications, Inc.]] |volume=75 |issue=2 |pages=149\u2013158 |doi=10.2307/4590751 |pmid=19316351 |pmc=1929395 |jstor=4590751}} (19 pages)</ref> and up to 50% in controlling influenza in the US, 2004\u20132008.<ref>{{cite journal |author-last1=Wheeler |author-first1=Colleen C. |author-last2=Erhart |author-first2=Laura M. |author-last3=Jehn |author-first3=Megan L. |date=November\u2013December 2010 |title=Effect of School Closure on the Incidence of Influenza Among School-Age Children in Arizona |journal=[[Public Health Reports]] |volume=125 |issue=6 |pages=851\u2013859 |doi=10.1177/003335491012500612 |pmid=21121230 |pmc=2966666}}</ref> Similarly, mandatory school closures and other social distancing measures were associated with a 29% to 37% reduction in influenza transmission rates during the [[2009 influenza pandemic|2009 flu epidemic]] in Mexico.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.nih.gov/news-events/nih-research-matters/flu-pandemic-study-supports-social-distancing |title=Flu Pandemic Study Supports Social Distancing |work=NIH Research Matters |publisher=[[National Institutes of Health]] |date=2011-06-06}}</ref>\n\nDuring the [[2009 flu pandemic in the United Kingdom|swine flu outbreak in 2009 in the UK]], in an article titled \"Closure of schools during an influenza pandemic\" published in the ''[[The Lancet Infectious Diseases]]'', a group of epidemiologists endorsed the closure of schools in order to interrupt the course of the infection, slow further spread and buy time to research and produce a vaccine.<ref name=\"Wardrop2009\">{{Cite news |author-last=Wardrop |author-first=Murray |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/health/swine-flu/5874683/Swine-flu-schools-should-close-to-halt-spread-of-virus-ministers-told.html |title=Swine flu: schools should close to halt spread of virus, ministers told |date=2009-07-21 |work=[[The Telegraph (UK)|The Telegraph]] |access-date=2020-03-17 |url-status=live |language=en-GB |issn=0307-1235 |url-access=subscription}}</ref> Having studied previous influenza pandemics including the [[Spanish flu|1918 flu pandemic]], the [[Influenza A virus subtype H2N2|influenza pandemic of 1957]] and the [[1968 flu pandemic]], they reported on the economic and workforce effect school closure would have, particularly with a large percentage of doctors and nurses being women, of whom half had children under the age of 16. They also looked at the dynamics of the spread of influenza in France during French school holidays and noted that cases of flu dropped when schools closed and re-emerged when they re-opened. They noted that when teachers in Israel went on strike during the flu season of 1999\u20132000, visits to doctors and the number of respiratory infections dropped by more than a fifth and more than two fifths respectively.<ref name=\"Reuters2009\">{{Cite news |author-last= |author-first= |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-flu-schools-idUSTRE56J4OO20090720 |title=Closing schools won't stop pandemics: study |date=2009-07-20 |publisher=[[Reuters]] |access-date=2020-03-17 |url-status=live |editor-last=Walsh |editor-first=Eric |language=en}}</ref>\n\n===SARS 2003===\nDuring the [[2002\u20132004 SARS outbreak|SARS outbreak of 2003]], social distancing measures such as banning large gatherings, closing schools and theaters, and other public places, supplemented public health measures such as finding and isolating affected people, quarantining their close contacts, and infection control procedures. This was combined with wearing masks for certain people.<ref name=\"Bell2004\">{{Cite journal |author-last=Bell |author-first=David M. |date=November 2004 |title=Public Health Interventions and SARS Spread, 2003 |journal=[[Emerging Infectious Diseases]] |volume=10 |issue=11 |pages=1900\u20131906 |doi=10.3201/eid1011.040729 |issn=1080-6040 |pmc=3329045 |pmid=15550198}}</ref> During this time in Canada, \"community quarantine\" was used to reduce transmission of the disease with moderate success.<ref name=Bondy>{{cite journal |title=Quantifying the impact of community quarantine on SARS transmission in Ontario: estimation of secondary case count difference and number needed to quarantine |author-last1=Bondy |author-first1=Susan J. |author-last2=Russell |author-first2=Margaret L. |author-last3=Lafl\u00e8che |author-first3=Julie M. L. |author-last4=Rea |author-first4=Elizabeth |date=2009-12-24 |pmid=20034405 |doi=10.1186/1471-2458-9-488 |pmc=2808319 |volume=9 |journal=[[BMC Public Health]] |page=488 |issue=1}}</ref>\n\n===2019\u20132020 coronavirus pandemic===\n{{main|2019\u20132020 coronavirus pandemic}}\n\n[[File:Katapult importance social distancing.gif|thumb|upright=1.6|Simulations comparing rate of spread of infection, and number of deaths due to overrun of hospital capacity, when social interactions are \"normal\" (left, 200 people moving freely) and \"distanced\" (right, 25 people moving freely).<br/>Green&nbsp;= Healthy, uninfected individuals<br/>Red&nbsp;= Infected individuals<br/>Blue&nbsp;= Recovered individual<br/>Black&nbsp;= Dead individuals<br/>]]\n\nDuring the [[2019\u20132020 coronavirus pandemic]], social distancing and related measures were emphasised by several governments as alternatives to an enforced quarantine of heavily affected areas. According to [[UNESCO]] monitoring, over 100 countries have implemented nationwide [[Impact of the 2019\u20132020 coronavirus pandemic on education|school closures in response to COVID-19]], impacting over half the world's student population.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web |title=COVID-19 Educational Disruption and Response |date=2020-03-04 |website=[[UNESCO]] |language=en |url=https://en.unesco.org/themes/education-emergencies/coronavirus-school-closures |access-date=2020-03-23 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200329110914/https://en.unesco.org/themes/education-emergencies/coronavirus-school-closures |archive-date=2020-03-29}}</ref> In the United Kingdom, the government advised the public to avoid public spaces, and cinemas and theatres voluntarily closed to encourage the government's message.<ref>{{Cite news |title=Most UK cinemas shut after virus advice |language=en-GB |date=2020-03-17 |work=[[BBC News]] |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/entertainment-arts-51925490 |access-date=2020-03-21 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200323161040/https://www.bbc.com/news/entertainment-arts-51925490 |archive-date=2020-03-23}}</ref>\n\nSome teens and young adults refused to voluntarily adopt social distancing practices. In [[Belgium]], media reported a [[rave]] was attended by at least {{val|300}} before it was broken up by local authorities. In [[France]] teens making nonessential trips are fined up to {{currency|amount=150|code=$|linked=yes}}. Beaches were closed in [[Florida]] and [[Alabama]] to disperse partygoers during spring break.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.wthr.com/article/parents-police-struggle-social-distance-young-coronavirus-outbreak |title=Parents, police struggle to social distance the young in coronavirus outbreak |date=2020-03-20}}</ref> Weddings were broken up in New Jersey and an 8 p.m. [[curfew]] was imposed in [[Newark, New Jersey|Newark]]. New York, New Jersey, Connecticut and Pennsylvania were the first states to adopt coordinated social distancing policies that closed down non-essential businesses and restricted large gatherings. Shelter in place orders in [[California]] were extended to the entire state on 19 March. On the same day [[Texas]] declared a public disaster and imposed statewide restrictions.<ref>{{cite news |title=Uh-Oh Moment Finally Hits States Slow to Adopt Social Distancing |date=2020-03-20 |author-first1=Elise |author-last1=Young |author-first2=David R. |author-last2=Baker |work=[[Bloomberg News]] |publisher=[[Bloomberg L.P.]] |url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2020-03-20/uh-oh-moment-finally-hits-states-slow-to-adopt-social-distancing |access-date=2020-03-29 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200323063706/https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2020-03-20/uh-oh-moment-finally-hits-states-slow-to-adopt-social-distancing |archive-date=2020-03-23}}</ref>\n\nThese preventive measures such as social-distancing and [[Isolation (health care)|self-isolation]] prompted the widespread closure of [[Primary school|primary]], [[Secondary school|secondary]], and [[Tertiary education|post-secondary schools]] in over 120 countries. As of 23 March 2020, over 1.2 billion learners were out of school due to [[Impact of the 2019\u20132020 coronavirus pandemic on education|school closures in response to COVID-19]].<ref name=\":0\"/> Given low rates of COVID-19 infection among children, the effectiveness of school closures has been called into question.<ref>{{Cite web |title=Lessons from Ebola: The secret of successful epidemic response |author-last=Frieden |author-first=Tom |author-link=Tom Frieden |work=[[CNN]] |url=https://www.cnn.com/2020/03/11/health/coronavirus-lessons-from-ebola/index.html |access-date=2020-03-23 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200323214843/https://edition.cnn.com/2020/03/11/health/coronavirus-lessons-from-ebola/index.html |archive-date=2020-03-23}}</ref> Even when school closures are temporary, it carries high social and economic costs.<ref>{{Cite web |title=Coronavirus deprives nearly 300 million students of their schooling: UNESCO |newspaper=[[The Telegram]] |via=[[Reuters]] |language=en |url=http://www.thetelegram.com/news/world/coronavirus-deprives-nearly-300-million-students-of-their-schooling-unesco-419714/ |access-date=2020-03-23 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200328210511/https://www.thetelegram.com/news/world/coronavirus-deprives-nearly-300-million-students-of-their-schooling-unesco-419714/ |archive-date=2020-03-28}}</ref> However, the significance of children in spreading COVID-19 is unclear.<ref name=\"Lipsitch\">{{Cite journal |author-last1=Lipsitch |author-first1=Marc |author-link1=:wikidata:Q28322531 |author-last2=Swerdlow |author-first2=David L. |author-last3=Finelli |author-first3=Lyn |author-link3=:wikidata:Q59908394 |date=2020-03-26 |orig-year=2020-02-19 |title=Defining the Epidemiology of Covid-19 \u2014 Studies Needed |journal=[[New England Journal of Medicine]] |volume=382 |issue=13 |pages=1194\u20131196 |doi=10.1056/NEJMp2002125 |pmid=32074416 |issn=0028-4793}}</ref><ref name=\"lww18March2020\">{{Cite journal |author-last1=Zimmermann |author-first1=Petra |author-last2=Curtis |author-first2=Nigel |author-link2=:wikidata:Q30513816 |date=2020-03-18 |title=Coronavirus Infections in Children Including COVID-19: An Overview of the Epidemiology, Clinical Features, Diagnosis, Treatment and Prevention Options in Children |journal=[[The Pediatric Infectious Disease Journal]] |language=en-US |volume=Online First |pages= |doi=10.1097/INF.0000000000002660 |issn=0891-3668 |url=https://journals.lww.com/pidj/Abstract/onlinefirst/Coronavirus_Infections_in_Children_Including.96251.aspx |access-date=2020-03-30 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200324192956/https://journals.lww.com/pidj/Abstract/onlinefirst/Coronavirus_Infections_in_Children_Including.96251.aspx |archive-date=2020-03-24}}</ref> While the full impact of school closures during the coronavirus pandemic are not yet known, initial evidence suggests school closures have had negative impacts on local economies and learning outcomes for students.<ref>{{Cite web |title=Adverse consequences of school closures |date=2020-03-10 |website=[[UNESCO]] |language=en |url=https://en.unesco.org/themes/education-emergencies/coronavirus-school-closures/consequences |access-date=2020-03-23 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200325181733/https://en.unesco.org/themes/education-emergencies/coronavirus-school-closures/consequences |archive-date=2020-03-25}}</ref><ref name=\"Stevens14March2020\">{{Cite web |title=These simulations show how to flatten the coronavirus growth curve |author-last=Stevens |author-first=Harry |date=2020-03-14 |website=[[Washington Post]] |language=en |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/graphics/2020/world/corona-simulator/ |access-date=2020-03-29 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200330062958/https://www.washingtonpost.com/graphics/2020/world/corona-simulator/ |archive-date=2020-03-30}}</ref>\n\nIn early March 2020, the sentiment \"Stay The Fuck Home\" was coined by Florian Reifschneider, a German engineer and was quickly echoed by notable celebrities such as [[Taylor Swift]], [[Ariana Grande]]<ref>{{Cite web |title=Taylor Swift Urges Fans to Stay Home Amid COVID-19 Outbreak: \"I love you so much and I need to express my concern that things aren\u2019t being taken seriously enough right now,\" superstar writes |author-first=Brenna |author-last=Ehrlich |date=2020-03-15 |work=[[Rolling Stone]] |url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-news/taylor-swift-urges-fans-to-stay-home-amid-covid-19-outbreak-967629/ |access-date=2020-03-28 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200319124912/https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-news/taylor-swift-urges-fans-to-stay-home-amid-covid-19-outbreak-967629/ |archive-date=2020-03-28}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |author-first=Florian |author-last=Reifschneider |date=2020 |title=A Movement to Stop the COVID-19 Pandemic |website=#StayTheFuckHome |url=https://staythefuckhome.com/ |access-date=2020-03-29 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200329165848/https://staythefuckhome.com/ |archive-date=2020-03-29}}</ref> and [[Busy Philipps]]<ref>{{Cite web |title=Busy Philipps Joins Cameo to Record \"Stay the Fuck Home\" Messages for Coronavirus |author-first=Alex |author-last=Hudson |date=2020-03-17 |website=exclaim.ca |url=http://exclaim.ca/film/article/busy_philipps_joins_cameo_to_record_stay_the_fuck_home_messages_for_coronavirus |access-date=2020-03-29 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200327135529/http://exclaim.ca/film/article/busy_philipps_joins_cameo_to_record_stay_the_fuck_home_messages_for_coronavirus |archive-date=2020-03-27}}</ref> in hopes of reducing and delaying the peak of the outbreak. [[Facebook]], [[Twitter]] and [[Instagram]] also joined the campaign with similar hashtags, stickers and filters under #staythefhome, #stayhome, #staythefuckhome and began trending across social media.<ref>{{Cite web |title=AMA, AHA, ANA: #StayHome to confront COVID-19 |publisher=[[American Medical Association]] |location=Chicago, USA |url=https://www.ama-assn.org/press-center/press-releases/ama-aha-ana-stayhome-confront-covid-19 |access-date=2020-03-30 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200328063402/https://www.ama-assn.org/press-center/press-releases/ama-aha-ana-stayhome-confront-covid-19 |archive-date=2020-03-28}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |title=No, Netflix Is Not Spoiling Its Own Shows To Fight Coronavirus |author-first=Madeline |author-last=Berg |work=[[Forbes]] |url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/maddieberg/2020/03/26/no-netflix-is-not-spoiling-its-own-shows-to-fight-coronavirus-but-these-ad-guys-are/ |access-date=2020-03-30 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200327154558/https://www.forbes.com/sites/maddieberg/2020/03/26/no-netflix-is-not-spoiling-its-own-shows-to-fight-coronavirus-but-these-ad-guys-are/ |archive-date=2020-03-27}}</ref><ref>{{Cite newspaper |title='It feels like wartime': how street artists are responding to coronavirus - The pandemic may have closed museums and galleries down but artists have found other ways to comment on the crisis |author-first=Nadja |author-last=Sayej |date=2020-03-25 |newspaper=[[The Guardian]] |series=Street art |url=https://www.theguardian.com/artanddesign/2020/mar/25/street-artists-coronavirus-us-it-feels-like-wartime |access-date=2020-03-30 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200329005102/https://www.theguardian.com/artanddesign/2020/mar/25/street-artists-coronavirus-us-it-feels-like-wartime |archive-date=2020-03-29}}</ref><ref name=\"NewsweekSTFH\"/> The website claims to have reached about 2 million people online and states that the text has been translated in 17 languages.<ref name=\"NewsweekSTFH\">{{Cite magazine |title=The #StayTheF***kHome movement just wants you to, well, you know |author-first=Jorge |author-last=Solis |date=2020-03-16 |magazine=[[Newsweek]] |series=Culture |language=en |url=https://www.newsweek.com/staythefkhome-movement-just-wants-you-well-you-know-1492581 |access-date=2020-03-30 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200327145436/https://www.newsweek.com/staythefkhome-movement-just-wants-you-well-you-know-1492581 |archive-date=2020-03-27}}</ref>\n\n==Drawbacks==\n\nThere are concerns that social distancing can have adverse affects on participants' mental health.<ref>{{Cite newspaper |title=Social distancing can strain mental health. Here's how you can protect yourself. |author-last=Ao |author-first=Bethany |newspaper=[[The Philadelphia Inquirer]] |language=en-US |date=2020-03-19 |url=https://www.inquirer.com/health/coronavirus/coronavirus-mental-health-social-distancing-20200319.html |access-date=2020-03-24 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200326073833/https://www.inquirer.com/health/coronavirus/coronavirus-mental-health-social-distancing-20200319.html |archive-date=2020-03-26}}</ref> It may lead to [[psychological stress|stress]], [[anxiety]], [[depression (mood)|depression]] or panic, especially for individuals with preexisting conditions such as anxiety disorders, [[OCD|obsessive compulsive disorders]], and [[paranoia]].<ref>{{Cite web |title=Stress and Coping |series=Coronavirus Disease 2019 (COVID-19) |date=2020-03-23 |orig-year=2020-02-11 |publisher=[[Centers for Disease Control and Prevention]] |language=en-us |url=https://www.cdc.gov/coronavirus/2019-ncov/prepare/managing-stress-anxiety.html |access-date=2020-03-24 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200329113040/https://www.cdc.gov/coronavirus/2019-ncov/daily-life-coping/managing-stress-anxiety.html?CDC_AA_refVal=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.cdc.gov%2Fcoronavirus%2F2019-ncov%2Fprepare%2Fmanaging-stress-anxiety.html |archive-date=2020-03-29}}</ref> Widespread media coverage about a pandemic, its impact on economy, and resulting hardships may create anxiety. Change in daily circumstances and uncertainty about the future may add onto the mental stress of being away from other people.<ref>{{Cite web |title=Coronavirus: Social distancing and isolation can take a toll on your mental health, here's how some people are coping - Managing mental health in the time of coronavirus |author-last=Willis |author-first=Olivia |date=2020-03-22 |work=[[ABC News]] |language=en-AU |url=https://www.abc.net.au/news/health/2020-03-22/mental-health-coronavirus-quarantine-self-isolation/12078550 |access-date=2020-03-24 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200328041752/https://www.abc.net.au/news/health/2020-03-22/mental-health-coronavirus-quarantine-self-isolation/12078550 |archive-date=2020-03-28}}</ref>\n\n==Theoretical basis==\n\nFrom the perspective of epidemiology, the basic goal behind social distancing is to decrease the [[basic reproduction number]], <math>R_0</math>, which is the average number of secondary infected individuals generated from one primary infected individual in a population where all individuals are equally susceptible to a disease. In a basic model of social distancing,<ref name=\"Becker\">{{cite book |author-last=Becker |author-first=Niels |title=Modeling to Inform Infectious Disease Control |date=2015 |publisher=[[CRC Press]] |isbn=978-1-49873107-2 |page=104}}</ref> where a proportion <math>f</math> of the population engages in social distancing to decrease their interpersonal contacts to a fraction <math>a</math> of their normal contacts, the new effective reproduction number <math>R</math> is given by:<ref name=\"Becker\"/>\n\n<math display=\"block\"> R = [1-(1-a^2)f]R_0 </math>\n\nFor example, 25% of the population reducing their social contacts to 50% of their normal level gives an effective reproduction number about 81% of the basic reproduction number. A seemingly small reduction has a profound{{clarify|date=March 2020}} effect in delaying the exponential growth and spread of a disease.\n\n==See also==\n* [[Hand washing]]\n* [[Isolation (health care)]]\n* [[Pest house]]\n* [[Stay-at-home order]]\n{{clear}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category|Social distancing}}\n\n{{Public health}}\n\n[[Category:Infectious diseases]]\n[[Category:Quarantine]]\n[[Category:Epidemics]]\n[[Category:Epidemiology]]\n[[Category:Medical hygiene]]\n", "name_user": "BabyofJungle", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(Undid revision 948829879 byKinu(talk))", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Social_distancing"}
{"title_page": "I Still Believe (film)", "text_new": "{{short description|American biographical drama film}}\n{{Use American English|date=January 2020}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=January 2020}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name                 = I Still Believe\n| image                = I Still Believe promotional poster.jpg\n| caption              = Theatrical release poster\n| director             = [[Erwin Brothers]]\n| producer             = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Kevin Downes]]\n* Jon Erwin\n* Andrew Erwin<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://tickets.istillbelieve.movie/|title=I Still Believe \u2013 Official Ticketing Site - KJ Apa, Britt Robertson, Shania Twain, Gary Sinise|via=tickets.istillbelieve.movie}}</ref>\n}}\n| screenplay           = {{Plainlist|\n* Jon Erwin\n* [[Jon Gunn]]\n* [[Madeline Carrol]]<ref name=\"F\">{{Cite web |url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/scottmendelson/2020/02/11/box-office-imax-positions-i-still-believe-as-next-big-faith-based-hit/#3c57de145399 |title=Box Office: IMAX Positions \u2018I Still Believe\u2019 As Next Big Faith-Based Hit |last=Mendelson |first=Scott |date=February 11, 2020 |publisher=[[Forbes (magazine)|Forbes]] |access-date=February 12, 2020}}</ref>\n}}\n| based on             = {{Based on|''I Still Believe''|[[Jeremy Camp]]}}\n| starring             = {{Plainlist|\n* [[KJ Apa]]\n* [[Britt Robertson]]\n* [[Melissa Roxburgh]]\n* [[Nathan Parsons]]\n* [[Shania Twain]]\n* [[Gary Sinise]]\n}}\n| music                = [[John Debney]]\n| cinematography       = Kristopher Kimlin\n| editing              = {{Plainlist|\n* Parker Adams\n* Ben Smallbone\n}}\n| production companies = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Kingdom Story Company]]\n* Kevin Downes Productions\n* Erwin Brothers Entertainment\n}}\n| distributor          = [[Lionsgate]]\n| released             = {{Film date|2020|03|07|[[ArcLight Hollywood]]|2020|03|13|United States}}\n| runtime              = 115 minutes\n| country              = United States\n| language             = English\n| budget               = $12&nbsp;million<ref name=IndieWireOpen/>\n| gross                = $10.5&nbsp;million<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.the-numbers.com/movie/I-Still-Believe-(2020)#tab=summary|title=I Still Believe (2020) - Financial Information|publisher=[[The Numbers (website)|The Numbers]]|accessdate=March 18, 2020}}</ref><ref name=BOM>{{cite web|url=https://www.boxofficemojo.com/title/tt9779516/?ref_=bo_rl_ti|title=I Still Believe (2020)|work=[[Box Office Mojo]]|accessdate=March 26, 2020}}</ref>\n}}\n\n'''''I Still Believe''''' is a 2020 American [[Christian film industry|Christian]] [[romantic drama]] film directed by the [[Erwin Brothers]] and starring [[KJ Apa]], [[Britt Robertson]], [[Shania Twain]], [[Melissa Roxburgh]] and [[Gary Sinise]]. It is based on the life of American [[contemporary Christian music]] singer-songwriter [[Jeremy Camp]] and his first wife, Melissa Lynn Henning-Camp, who was diagnosed with [[ovarian cancer]] shortly before they married. Camp's song \"[[I Still Believe (Jeremy Camp song)|I Still Believe]]\" is the film's namesake.\n\nThe film is the first production by [[Kingdom Story Company]], the Erwin Brothers' fifth feature film, and their second to be released under the [[Lionsgate]] banner. It premiered at [[ArcLight Hollywood]] on March 7, 2020, and was theatrically released in the United States on March 13, 2020. It received generally unfavorable reviews from critics, who commended the film for depicting faith in the midst of suffering, but criticized the plot and characters. Lionsgate released the film to [[video on demand]] on March 27, 2020, due to theater closures related to the [[2019-20 coronavirus pandemic]].\n\n== Plot ==\nBased on Camp's memoir of the same title, it focuses on Camp's romance with his first wife, Melissa, whom he married in October 2000 despite knowing she was dying.<ref>[https://www1.cbn.com/music/jeremy-camp:-melissa%27s-dying-wish Jeremy Camp: Melissa's Dying Wish] (CBN)</ref> The couple were informed after their [[honeymoon]] that Melissa's cancer had spread. She died in February 2001, 4\u00bd months after they married.<ref name=\"fnc4819\">[https://www.foxnews.com/entertainment/gary-sinise-kj-apa-to-role-in-faith-based-film-i-still-believe-about-singer-jeremy-camp Gary Sinise, KJ Apa will star in faith-based film 'I Still Believe' about singer Jeremy Camp] (Fox News)</ref> It dramatizes Camp's college years, his rise as a well-known singer, and eventually meeting his second wife, [[Adrienne Camp|Adrienne]].<ref name=\"fnc4819\" />\n\n==Cast==\n{{cast listing|\n*[[KJ Apa]] as [[Jeremy Camp]]\n*[[Britt Robertson]] as Melissa Lynn Henning-Camp\n*[[Gary Sinise]] as Tom Camp, Jeremy's father\n*[[Shania Twain]] as Terry Camp, Jeremy's mother\n*[[Melissa Roxburgh]] as Heather Henning, Melissa's sister\n*[[Nathan Parsons]] as Jean-Luc Lajoie, a mutual friend also interested in Melissa<ref name=\"Federalist\" />\n*Abigail Cowen as [[Adrienne Camp]], Jeremy's second wife\n}}\n\n==Production==\nThe film is the first project of a deal struck between the Erwin Brothers and [[Lionsgate]] after the success of their film ''[[I Can Only Imagine (film)|I Can Only Imagine]]'' in 2018.<ref name=\"deadline51319\">[https://deadline.com/2019/05/i-still-believe-shania-twain-melissa-roxburgh-britt-robertson-nathan-dean-parsons-cast-jeremy-camp-movie-1202613705/ \u2018I Still Believe\u2019: Shania Twain, Melissa Roxburgh & More Join Lionsgate/Kingdom Studios\u2019 Faith-Based Drama] (Deadline)</ref> It is also the first film produced by Kingdom Story Company, a [[film studio]] founded by the [[Erwin Brothers]], [[Kevin Downes]], and Tony Young,<ref>[https://www.bizjournals.com/birmingham/news/2019/04/01/erwin-brothers-launching-new-film-studio.html Erwin brothers launching new film studio] (Birmingham Business Journal)</ref> and the Erwin Brothers' second [[Biopic|music biopic]] after ''I Can Only Imagine''.\n\nJeremy Camp was actively involved in the production of the film,<ref name=\"TCB2\">{{cite web|url=https://www.thechristianbeat.org/index.php/news/7228-jeremy-camp-pens-new-book-i-still-believe-a-memoir|title=Jeremy Camp Pens New Book 'I Still Believe: A Memoir'|author=Herb Longs|publisher=TheChristianBeat.com|date=February 22, 2020|accessdate=February 24, 2020}}</ref> while singer-songwriter [[Bart Millard]] of [[MercyMe]] (whose life story was told in the Erwin Brothers' ''I Can Only Imagine'') acted as an executive producer,<ref name=\"TCB\">{{Cite web |url=https://www.thechristianbeat.org/index.php/news/6817-mercyme-s-bart-millard-announced-as-executive-producer-of-i-still-believe |title=MercyMe's Bart Millard Announced As Executive Producer Of 'I Still Believe' |last=Clarks |first=Jessie |date=October 30, 2019 |publisher=The Christian Beat |access-date=December 24, 2019}}</ref> along with Camp, [[Jon Gunn]], and others.\n\n===Casting===\n[[KJ Apa]] was announced as the star of the film, playing Camp, and [[Gary Sinise]] was announced for the role of Camp's father, at CinemaCon in April 2019.<ref>[https://deadline.com/2019/04/k-j-apa-gary-sinise-join-lionsgate-kingdom-studio-faith-based-film-i-still-believe-1202588789/ K.J. Apa & Gary Sinise Join Lionsgate/Kingdom Studio Faith-Based Film \u2018I Still Believe\u2019 \u2013 CinemaCon] (Deadline)</ref> That same month it was announced that [[Britt Robertson]] would co-star as Melissa Camp, joined by [[Shania Twain]] as Camp's mother, [[Melissa Roxburgh]] as Melissa's sister, and [[Nathan Parsons]] as Jean-Luc Lajoie, lead singer for the band The Kry, a mutual friend.<ref name=\"deadline51319\" />\n\nApa, who did his own singing for the film, said he was drawn to the story because \"[t]heir love is seriously put to the test in this movie,\" adding, \"it's about journeying through your biggest fears and disappointments and coming out still believing. I believe that anyone, everyone can relate to this film because it's a story about love, loss, and hope.\"<ref>[https://people.com/movies/riverdale-kj-apa-first-trailer-i-still-believe/ WATCH: Riverdale's KJ Apa Sings and Romances Britt Robertson in Moving I Still Believe Trailer] (People)</ref> Apa later related that his role in ''I Still Believe'' is \"the coolest thing I've ever done\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.goodmorningamerica.com/culture/story/riverdale-star-returning-set-luke-perry-69482365|title='Riverdale' star on returning to set without Luke Perry|publisher=[[Good Morning America]]|author=Kelly McCarthy|date=March 9, 2020|accessdate=March 9, 2020}}</ref> Jeremy Camp stated that Apa was concerned about detail and would often consult him whenever he was in doubt regarding how to play his character in certain scenes.<ref name=\"Federalist\" />\n\nCo-director Andrew Erwin related that he hoped the cast, particularly Apa and Robertson, would attract non-Christians in addition to a Christian audience.<ref name=\"crossover appeal\">{{cite web|url=https://www.christianheadlines.com/contributors/michael-foust/director-i-still-believe-is-a-huge-opportunity-to-reach-the-unchurched.html|title=Director: \"I Still Believe\" Is a 'Huge Opportunity' to Reach the Unchurched|date=February 19, 2020|author=Michael Foust|publisher=Christian Headlines|accessdate=February 19, 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Music===\nComposer [[John Debney]] was hired to write the score for the film,<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://filmmusicreporter.com/2020/01/13/john-debney-to-score-the-erwin-brothers-i-still-believe/ |title=John Debney to Score the Erwin Brothers' 'I Still Believe' |date=January 13, 2020 |publisher=FilmMusicReporter.com |access-date=January 24, 2020}}</ref> while KJ Apa sang his own renditions of several songs written by Jeremy Camp during the period of his life accounted in the film, including \"I Still Believe\", \"[[Walk by Faith]]\", and \"[[This Man (song)|This Man]]\".<ref name=\"FMR\">{{cite web|url=https://filmmusicreporter.com/2020/03/05/i-still-believe-soundtrack-details/|title=\u2018I Still Believe\u2019 Soundtrack Details|publisher=FilmMusicReporter.com|author=|date=March 5, 2020|accessdate=March 9, 2020}}</ref> ''I Still Believe'' is John Debney's third time composing the score for a Christian film, after ''[[The Passion of the Christ]]'' in 2004 and ''[[The Young Messiah]]'' in 2016.\n\n===Writing===\nJon Erwin, [[Jon Gunn]], and [[Madeline Carrol]] (who starred in ''I Can Only Imagine'') wrote the screenplay for ''I Still Believe''.<ref name=\"F\" /> The film is Madeline Carrol's screenwriting debut. Jeremy Camp, initially apprehensive about how the film's script would read, was surprised to find that he liked it right off for \"[h]ow accurate and beautifully done it was.\"<ref name=\"Federalist\">{{cite web|url=https://thefederalist.com/2020/03/09/romance-flick-i-still-believe-seeks-to-set-new-standard-for-faith-driven-films/|title=Romance Flick \u2018I Still Believe\u2019 Seeks To Set New Standard For Faith-Driven Films|publisher=TheFederalist.com|author=Josh Shepherd|date=March 9, 2020|accessdate=March 9, 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Filming===\nFilming began in the [[Mobile, Alabama]] area in May 2019,<ref>[https://variety.com/2019/film/news/shania-twain-i-still-believe-1203212871/ Film News Roundup: Shania Twain, Britt Robertson Join Faith-Based \u2018I Still Believe\u2019] (Variety)</ref><ref>[https://www.al.com/life/2019/05/new-erwin-brothers-movie-i-still-believe-seeks-extras-for-filming-in-mobile.html New Erwin brothers movie, \u2018I Still Believe,\u2019 seeks extras for filming in Mobile] (AL.com)</ref> where it was filmed entirely.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.patheos.com/blogs/kateohare/2020/03/i-still-believe-jeremy-camp-kj-apa/|title='I Still Believe' Tells Jeremy Camp's Story of Love Amid Suffering|first=Kate O'Hare's Pax|last=Culturati|date=March 11, 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe film's cinematographer, Kristopher Kimlin, had collaborated with the Erwin Brothers on their past productions, ''[[Moms' Night Out]]'', ''[[Woodlawn (film)|Woodlawn]]'', and ''I Can Only Imagine''.\n\n==Theme==\nRegarding the film's main theme, Jeremy Camp, on whose life the film is based, said that it \"tells my story and shares what God has done amidst all the hard things I went through. It shows hope in the midst of pain.\"<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www1.cbn.com/cbnnews/entertainment/2019/august/shania-twain-gary-sinise-starring-in-i-still-believe-true-story-of-christian-singer-jeremy-camp |title=Shania Twain, Gary Sinise Starring in 'I Still Believe', True Story of Christian Singer Jeremy Camp |last=Morris |first=Andrea |date=August 23, 2019 |publisher=[[Christian Broadcasting Network]] |access-date=January 9, 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe film's stars, Apa, Robertson and Twain, also shared their thoughts on the film's themes, with Twain commenting that \"[t]his is [about] a love that goes beyond fear, that goes beyond any doubt[.]\" Apa said that {{quote|text=it's [about] journeying through your biggest fear and coming out on the other side and still loving God ... I hope people, after seeing the love between Jeremy and Melissa, think, 'I hope that I could one day be in love like that[.]<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.christianpost.com/news/i-still-believe-movie-inspire-viewers-to-love-beyond-fear-heart-of-the-story-video.html |title='I Still Believe' movie aims to inspire viewers to 'love beyond fear' ('Heart of the Story' video) |last=Law |first=Jeannie |date=November 30, 2019 |website=[[The Christian Post]] |access-date=January 9, 2020}}</ref>}}\n\n''I Still Believe'''s co-director, Jon Erwin, said in an interview with the Baptist Press that \n{{Quote|\nquotetext=[the] film grapples with [the question of why God allows suffering.] ... I think we forget so many times that there is a beauty, and a purpose, and a meaning in the difficult things we go through. And that sometimes God uses those things more than He uses the good things that happen to shape us, to mold us and to give us our voice. ... It's a love story as God intended, between these two people and God, and between these two people and each other[.]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bpnews.net/54367/i-still-believe-touted-as-evangelistic-love-story|title='I Still Believe' touted as evangelistic love story|author=Diana Chandler|publisher=Baptist Press|date=February 24, 2020|accessdate=February 24, 2020}}</ref>\n}}\n\n==Soundtrack==\n{{Infobox album\n| name       = I Still Believe: Original Motion Picture Soundtrack\n| type       = soundtrack\n|cover     =\n| artist     = [[John Debney]], [[Jeremy Camp]], [[All Sons & Daughters|David Leonard]], and [[JJ Heller]]\n| released   = March 6, 2020\n| recorded   = \n| venue      =\n| studio     =\n| genre      = [[Soundtrack]]\n| length     = \n| label      = [[Capitol Records|Capitol]]\n| producer   = \n| chronology = [[John Debney]] film scores\n| prev_title = [[Dora and the Lost City of Gold]]\n| prev_year  = 2019\n| next_title = [[Clifford the Big Red Dog (film)|Clifford the Big Red Dog]]\n| next_year  = 2020\n}}\nThe original motion picture soundtrack was released digitally by [[Capital Records]] on March 6, 2020, and included Debney's score, Apa's renditions of Camp's songs \"[[This Man]]\", \"[[I Still Believe (Jeremy Camp song)|I Still Believe]]\", \"[[Live Unplugged (Jeremy Camp album)|My Desire]]\", and \"[[Right Here (Jeremy Camp song)|Right Here]]\", as well as new versions of \"I Still Believe\" and \"[[Walk By Faith]]\" performed by Jeremy Camp, and two tracks featuring dialog from the film.<ref name=\"FMR\" />\n{{Track listing\n| headline        = Track listing\n| total_length    = \n| title1          = [[I Still Believe (Jeremy Camp song)|I Still Believe]]\n| note1           = performed by KJ Apa; written by Jeremy Camp\n| length1         = 3:42\n\n| title2          = Jeremy Says Goodbye\n| note2           = written by Debney\n| length2         = 4:05\n\n| title3          = [[This Man (song)|This Man]]\n| note3           = performed by KJ Apa; written by Jeremy Camp\n| length3         = 3:09\n\n| title4          = Take My Hand\n| note4           = performed by [[All Sons & Daughters|David Leonard]] written by Jean-Luc Lajoie & Yves Lajoie \n| length4         = 4:20\n\n| title5          = Find Me in the River\n| note5           = performed by KJ Apa and [[JJ Heller]]\n| length5         = 3:03\n\n| title6          = Some Stars Shine Brighter Than Others\n| note6           = written by Debney\n| length6         = 3:12\n\n| title7          = [[Live Unplugged (Jeremy Camp album)|My Desire]]\n| note7           = performed by KJ Apa; written by Jeremy Camp\n| length7         = 3:19\n\n| title8          = Dwelling Places (Dialog)\n| note8           = dialog by cast of ''I Still Believe''\n| length8         = 0:59\n\n| title9          = [[Right Here (Jeremy Camp song)|Right Here]]\n| note9           = performed by KJ Apa; written by Jeremy Camp \n| length9         = 3:29\n\n| title10         = Melissa Loves Jeremy\n| note10          = written by Debney\n| length10        = 2:07\n\n| title11         = You Call I'll Answer\n| note11          = performed by David Leonard\n| length11        = 4:03\n\n| title12         = Walk By Faith (Dialog)\n| note12          = dialog by cast of ''I Still Believe''\n| length12        = 2:35\n\n| title13         = Ancient Stories Still Relevant\n| note13          = written by Debney\n| length13        = 4:44\n\n| title14         = Hey, What's Your Name Again?\n| note14          = written by Debney\n| length14        = 3:21\n\n| title15         = [[Walk By Faith|Walk By Faith (2020 Version)]]\n| note15          = written and performed by Jeremy Camp\n| length15        = 3:41\n\n| title16         = I Still Believe (2020 Version)\n| note16          = written and performed by Jeremy Camp\n| length16        = 4:31\n\n| title17         = I Can't Save Myself (Bonus Track)\n| note17          = performed by [[Adrienne Camp]]\n| length17        = 3:12\n}}\n\n==Release==\n''I Still Believe'' premiered at [[ArcLight Hollywood]] in [[Hollywood, California]] on March 7, 2020,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nydailynews.com/snyde/ny-i-still-believe-movie-premiere-2020-20200308-wpygrxpj3rdurfjlbsfxv43gz4-photogallery.html|title='I Still Believe' movie premiere|date=|author=|publisher=NYDailyNews.com|accessdate=March 8, 2020}}</ref> and was released in North American theaters on March 13 by [[Lionsgate]],<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.christianpost.com/news/i-still-believe-trailer-shows-star-studded-cast-tells-true-love-story-of-jeremy-camp.html |title='I Still Believe' trailer shows star-studded cast, tells true love story of Jeremy Camp |website=The Christian Post}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.lionsgatepublicity.com/theatrical/i-still-believe |title=I Still Believe |publisher=Lionsgate Publicity|access-date=January 1, 2020}}</ref> with early showings on [[IMAX|IMAX theaters]] on March 11. ''I Still Believe'' is the first [[feature-length]] [[Christian film industry|faith-based film]] to be released on IMAX screens.<ref name=\"F\" /> \n\n===Rating===\n''I Still Believe'' was rated [[Motion picture content rating system|PG]] by the [[Motion Picture Association of America]] for \"thematic material\".<ref name=\"The Numbers\">{{cite web|url=https://www.the-numbers.com/movie/I-Still-Believe-(2020)#tab=summary|title=I Still Believe (2020) - Financial Information|publisher=The Numbers|author=|date=|accessdate=March 9, 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Marketing===\nThe film's first trailer was released in August 2019,<ref>[https://ew.com/movies/2019/08/22/i-still-believe-trailer-kj-apa/ See Riverdale star K.J. Apa in first trailer for Christian romance I Still Believe] (EW)</ref> while the second was released in January 2020.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.flickeringmyth.com/2020/01/new-trailer-for-i-still-believe-starring-kj-apa-britt-robertson-gary-sinise-and-shania-twain/ |title=New trailer for I Still Believe starring KJ Apa, Britt Robertson, Gary Sinise and Shania Twain |last=Cranswick |first=Amie |date=January 15, 2020 |publisher=FlickeringMyth.com |access-date=January 22, 2020}}</ref>\n\nChristian band [[MercyMe]] announced in October 2019 that it would be promoting the film through their winter-spring 20/20 tour with Jeremy Camp as a special guest.<ref name=\"TCB\" /><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.christianheadlines.com/contributors/michael-foust/i-still-believe-to-become-1st-faith-based-movie-on-imax.html|title=I Still Believe to Become 1st Faith-Based Movie on IMAX|date=February 12, 2020|author=Michael Foust|publisher=Christian Headlines|accessdate=February 12, 2020}}</ref> In February 2020, Camp wrote and released ''I Still Believe: A Memoir'' in promotion of the film.<ref name=\"TCB2\" /> Jeremy and Adrienne Camp and Jon Erwin spoke at [[Liberty University]] in early March prior to the film's release to promote ''I Still Believe''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.liberty.edu/news/index.cfm?PID=18495&MID=377793|title=Singer Jeremy Camp promotes 'I Still Believe' film with director Jon Erwin|date=March 4, 2020|author=Jacob Couch|publisher=[[Liberty University|Liberty News]]|accessdate=March 8, 2020}}</ref>\n\nRegarding Lionsgate's role behind the film's marketing, co-director Jon Erwin related that {{Quote|quotetext=[h]aving the full support of Lionsgate is new for us [him, his brother Andrew, and frequent collaborator Kevin Downes] . . . They\u2019re treating this [film] no different [sic] than they would \u2018[[Twilight (2008 film)|Twilight]]\u2019 or \u2018[[The Hunger Games film series|The Hunger Games]]\u2019 or any of their huge releases. The ad buy is . . . big, just like any other movie. We\u2019ve never experienced anything like it.<ref name=\"Federalist\" />}}\n\n===Video on demand===\nDue to theaters closing nationwide in the face of the [[COVID-19|COVID-19 pandemic]], Lionsgate and Kingdom Story Company announced that the film would get an early [[video-on-demand]] release on March 27, just two weeks after the film's theatrical debut.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://collider.com/kj-apa-i-still-believe-early-vod-release-details/|title=KJ Apa's Faith-Based Drama \u2018I Still Believe\u2019 Gets Early VOD Release|date=March 19, 2020|publisher=[[Collider.com]]|author=Jeff Sneider|accessdate=March 19, 2020}}</ref> Lionsgate chairman Joe Drake said in a statement, \"With theaters closed nationwide due to these unprecedented events, we want to continue to make ''I Still Believe'' available to consumers... We're enormously proud of the movie that the Erwin Brothers created and are grateful to be able to share it with audiences for their home viewing pleasure.\"<ref name=\"movieguide\">[https://www.movieguide.org/news-articles/popular-articles/i-still-believe-heads-to-video-on-demand-due-to-coronavirus.html I STILL BELIEVE Heads to Video on Demand Due to Coronavirus]</ref> The Erwin brothers added, \"As filmmakers, we are heartbroken that we can\u2019t share ''I Still Believe'' on a big screen the way we intended. We make movies because we love movies and we stand firmly behind the nation\u2019s theater chains, from the largest circuits to the smallest mom and pop indies that have been so dramatically affected by these unprecedented closures. But the safety of guests comes first, and we're proud to have the opportunity to share online a movie whose inspiring message of love, hope and faith is perfect for these uncertain times.\"<ref name=\"movieguide\"/>\n\n==Reception==\n\n===Box office===\nIn the United States and Canada, the film was released alongside ''[[The Hunt (2020 film)|The Hunt]]'' and ''[[Bloodshot (film)|Bloodshot]]'', and was projected to gross $11\u201315&nbsp;million from 3,250 theaters in its opening weekend.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2020/03/vin-diesel-bloodshot-kj-apa-i-still-believe-the-hunt-onward-box-office-coronavirus-1202880173/|title=Vin Diesel Pic \u2018Bloodshot\u2019, K.J. Apa's \u2018I Still Believe\u2019 & Blumhouse's \u2018The Hunt\u2019 Hit Theaters Amid Coronavirus Jitters|website=[[Deadline Hollywood]]|author=Anthony D'Alessandro|accessdate=March 12, 2020|date=March 11, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url= https://www.thewrap.com/i-still-believe-bloodshot-hunt-box-office/ |title= \u2018I Still Believe\u2019 Expected to Top \u2018Bloodshot\u2019 and \u2018The Hunt\u2019 at Weekend Box Office |website=[[TheWrap]]|author=Jeremy Fuster|accessdate=March 10, 2020|date=March 10, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.boxofficemojo.com/article/ed2792358916/?ref_=bo_hm_hp|title='I Still Believe', 'The Hunt', and 'Bloodshot' To Hit Theaters This Weekend|author=Brad Brevet|publisher=[[Box Office Mojo]]|date=March 12, 2020|accessdate=March 12, 2020}}</ref> The film was number one at the box office on its first day at $4&nbsp;million, including $780,000 from Wednesday [[IMAX]] screenings and Thursday night previews. It went on to debut to just $9.1&nbsp;million, finishing third behind holdover ''[[Onward (film)|Onward]]'' and ''Bloodshot''. The weekend was also noteworthy for being the lowest combined grossing since October 1998, with all films totaling only $55.3&nbsp;million, which was attributed to [[COVID-19]] concerns.<ref name=opening>{{Cite web|url= https://deadline.com/2020/03/vin-diesel-bloodshot-i-still-believe-the-hunt-weekend-box-office-coronavirus-1202882333/ |title= Weekend Box Office Headed To 22-Year-Low At $58M+ As Coronavirus Fears Grip Nation |website=[[Deadline Hollywood]]|author=Anthony D'Alessandro|accessdate=March 15, 2020|date=March 15, 2020}}</ref><ref name=IndieWireOpen>{{cite web|title= With Attendance at a 40-Year Low, This Is a Box-Office Weekend When No One Wins |url= https://www.indiewire.com/2020/03/box-office-attendance-40-year-low-coronavirus-i-still-believe-1202217868/ |publisher=[[IndieWire]]|date=March 15, 2020|accessdate=March 15, 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Critical response===\nOn [[review aggregator]] [[Rotten Tomatoes]], ''I Still Believe'' holds an approval rating of 44% based on 34 reviews, with an average rating of 5.5/10. The website's critics consensus reads: \"''I Still Believe''{{'}}s palpable good intentions are offset by its predictable handling of a fact-based story that ends up preaching to the choir.\"<ref name=\"RT\">{{cite web |title=I Still Believe (2020)|url= https://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/i_still_believe/ |website=[[Rotten Tomatoes]] |publisher=[[Fandango]] |accessdate=April 1, 2020}}</ref> On [[Metacritic]], the film has a weighted average score of 37 out of 100, based on 11 critics, indicating \"generally unfavorable reviews\".<ref>{{cite web |title=I Still Believe Reviews |url= https://www.metacritic.com/movie/i-still-believe |website=[[Metacritic]] |publisher=[[CBS Interactive]] |accessdate=March 13, 2020}}</ref> Audiences polled by [[CinemaScore]] gave the film an average grade of \"A\" on an A+ to F scale, and [[PostTrak]] reported it received an average 4.5 out of 5 stars.<ref name=opening/>\n\nIn a favorable review, Pete Hammond of ''[[Deadline Hollywood]]'' said that \"''I Still Believe'' doesn't rewrite any of the rules of this genre, but it does ask the right questions of faith in light of unimaginable tragedy without trying to sugarcoat them. For those who truly want to 'still believe', it should be enough. Fans of Apa also ought to be happy. Cynics should quarantine themselves from this; it's not for you.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://deadline.com/video/i-still-believe-review-kj-apa-britt-robertson-jeremy-camp/|title=\u2018I Still Believe\u2019 Review: KJ Apa Impressively Hits A Different Note As Singer Jeremy Camp In Faith-Based Tragic Love Story|author=Pete Hammond|publisher=[[Deadline Hollywood]]|date=March 12, 2020|accessdate=March 13, 2020}}</ref> Megan Basham of ''[[World (magazine)|World]]'' also wrote a positive review for the film, and, while criticizing it for its \"melodramatic raging\", similarly praised its depiction of faith amidst suffering, saying, \"[t]he Erwins are careful to show that God is faithful even when He says 'no.'\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://world.wng.org/2020/03/emotional_under_load|title=Emotional underload|author=Megan Basham|publisher=[[World (magazine)|World]]|date=March 6, 2020|accessdate=March 12, 2020}}</ref> Joe Leydon of ''[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]'', in a positive review for the film, praised Apa's and Robertson's performances and commended the Erwin Brothers' direction, saying that in ''I Still Believe'' \"they amp the emotional power \u2013 subtly at first, then gradually more aggressively \u2013 with a 'Love Story'-style scenario that is all the more potent for being based on real-life events.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://variety.com/2020/film/reviews/i-still-believe-review-1203530986/|title='I Still Believe' Review - Variety|author=Joe Leydon|publisher=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|date=March 11, 2020|accessdate=March 12, 2020}}</ref>\n\nFrank Scheck of ''[[The Hollywood Reporter]]'' commended the film for dealing with \"the difficulty of maintaining faith when tragedy strikes for no apparent reason\", although his review was ultimately negative, with him stating as a bottom line that \"[t]ears will be jerked, but you'll feel the machinations.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/review/i-still-believe-1284043|title='I Still Believe': Film Review|author=Frank Scheck|publisher=[[The Hollywood Reporter]]|date=March 11, 2020|accessdate=March 12, 2020}}</ref> Carla Meyer of ''[[The San Francisco Chronicle]]'', while praising Robertson's acting and her chemistry with Apa, derided the film for the lack of \"any character development for Jeremy beyond caretaker and worried partner.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://datebook.sfchronicle.com/movies-tv/review-britt-robertson-keeps-i-still-believe-somewhat-believable|title=Review: Britt Robertson keeps \u2018I Still Believe\u2019 somewhat believable|author=Carla Meyer|publisher=[[The San Francisco Chronicle]]|date=March 11, 2020|accessdate=March 12, 2020}}</ref> Similarly, ''[[IndieWire]]'' writer David Ehrlich gave the film a \"C-\", stating that \"[t]he power of the Camps' story is hard to deny, but it would almost be impossible to make it seem more hollow. Maybe if the Erwins depicted people with half the same detail with which they dote upon Jesus, ''I Still Believe'' wouldn't feel so insufferably forced to those of us who don't.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.indiewire.com/2020/03/i-still-believe-review-christian-biopic-jeremy-camp-1202216945/|title=\u2018I Still Believe\u2019 Review: A Christian Rock Biopic So Earnest It Makes \u2018Walk to Remember\u2019 Seem Like \u2018Sal\u00f2\u2019|date=March 11, 2020|author=David Ehrlich|publisher=[[IndieWire]]|accessdate=March 13, 2020}}</ref> Similarly, ''[[TheWrap]]'' contributor Carlos Aguilar, while praising Kristopher Kimlin's cinematography and the \"above-average production value\", called the film \"[s]accharine\" and \"[f]ormulaic to the core, from the protagonist's short-lived moment of doubt to the epiphany that sets him back on course.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thewrap.com/i-still-believe-film-review-kj-apa-jeremy-camp/|title=\u2018I Still Believe\u2019 Film Review: KJ Apa Croons His Way Through Another Saccharine Faith-Based Biopic|date=March 12, 2020|author=Carlos Aguilar|publisher=[[TheWrap]]|accessdate=March 13, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{Official website|https://www.istillbelievemovie.com/}}\n* {{IMDb title|tt9779516}}\n* {{tcmdb title|9779516|I Still Believe}}\n* {{Mojo title|istillbelieve}}\n\n{{Portal bar|Film|United States}}\n{{Erwin Brothers}}\n\n[[Category:2020s biographical drama films]]\n[[Category:American films]]\n[[Category:American biographical drama films]]\n[[Category:American independent films]]\n[[Category:Drama films based on actual events]]\n[[Category:English-language films]]\n[[Category:Films shot in Alabama]]\n[[Category:Films about Christianity]]\n[[Category:Films directed by the Erwin Brothers]]\n[[Category:Films scored by John Debney]]\n[[Category:IMAX films]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|American biographical drama film}}\n{{Use American English|date=January 2020}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=January 2020}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name                 = I Still Believe\n| image                = I Still Believe promotional poster.jpg\n| caption              = Theatrical release poster\n| director             = [[Erwin Brothers]]\n| producer             = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Kevin Downes]]\n* Jon Erwin\n* Andrew Erwin<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://tickets.istillbelieve.movie/|title=I Still Believe \u2013 Official Ticketing Site - KJ Apa, Britt Robertson, Shania Twain, Gary Sinise|via=tickets.istillbelieve.movie}}</ref>\n}}\n| screenplay           = {{Plainlist|\n* Jon Erwin\n* [[Jon Gunn]]\n* [[Madeline Carrol]]<ref name=\"F\">{{Cite web |url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/scottmendelson/2020/02/11/box-office-imax-positions-i-still-believe-as-next-big-faith-based-hit/#3c57de145399 |title=Box Office: IMAX Positions \u2018I Still Believe\u2019 As Next Big Faith-Based Hit |last=Mendelson |first=Scott |date=February 11, 2020 |publisher=[[Forbes (magazine)|Forbes]] |access-date=February 12, 2020}}</ref>\n}}\n| based on             = {{Based on|''I Still Believe''|[[Jeremy Camp]]}}\n| starring             = {{Plainlist|\n* [[KJ Apa]]\n* [[Britt Robertson]]\n* [[Melissa Roxburgh]]\n* [[Nathan Parsons]]\n* [[Shania Twain]]\n* [[Gary Sinise]]\n}}\n| music                = [[John Debney]]\n| cinematography       = Kristopher Kimlin\n| editing              = {{Plainlist|\n* Parker Adams\n* Ben Smallbone\n}}\n| production companies = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Kingdom Story Company]]\n* Kevin Downes Productions\n* Erwin Brothers Entertainment\n}}\n| distributor          = [[Lionsgate]]\n| released             = {{Film date|2020|03|07|[[ArcLight Hollywood]]|2020|03|13|United States}}\n| runtime              = 115 minutes\n| country              = United States\n| language             = English\n| budget               = $12&nbsp;million<ref name=IndieWireOpen/>\n| gross                = $10.5&nbsp;million<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.the-numbers.com/movie/I-Still-Believe-(2020)#tab=summary|title=I Still Believe (2020) - Financial Information|publisher=[[The Numbers (website)|The Numbers]]|accessdate=March 18, 2020}}</ref><ref name=BOM>{{cite web|url=https://www.boxofficemojo.com/title/tt9779516/?ref_=bo_rl_ti|title=I Still Believe (2020)|work=[[Box Office Mojo]]|accessdate=March 26, 2020}}</ref>\n}}\n\n'''''I Still Believe''''' is a 2020 American [[Christian film industry|Christian]] [[romantic drama]] film directed by the [[Erwin Brothers]] and starring [[KJ Apa]], [[Britt Robertson]], [[Shania Twain]], [[Melissa Roxburgh]] and [[Gary Sinise]]. It is based on the life of American [[contemporary Christian music]] singer-songwriter [[Jeremy Camp]] and his first wife, Melissa Lynn Henning-Camp, who was diagnosed with [[ovarian cancer]] shortly before they married. Camp's song \"[[I Still Believe (Jeremy Camp song)|I Still Believe]]\" is the film's namesake.\n\nThe film is the first production by [[Kingdom Story Company]], the Erwin Brothers' fifth feature film, and their second to be released under the [[Lionsgate]] banner. It premiered at [[ArcLight Hollywood]] on March 7, 2020, and was theatrically released in the United States on March 13, 2020. It received generally unfavorable reviews from critics, who commended the film for depicting faith in the midst of suffering, but criticized the plot and characters. Lionsgate announced released the film [[video on demand]] on March 27, 2020, due to theater closures related to the [[2019-20 coronavirus pandemic]].\n\n== Plot ==\nBased on Camp's memoir of the same title, it focuses on Camp's romance with his first wife, Melissa, whom he married in October 2000 despite knowing she was dying.<ref>[https://www1.cbn.com/music/jeremy-camp:-melissa%27s-dying-wish Jeremy Camp: Melissa's Dying Wish] (CBN)</ref> The couple were informed after their [[honeymoon]] that Melissa's cancer had spread. She died in February 2001, 4\u00bd months after they married.<ref name=\"fnc4819\">[https://www.foxnews.com/entertainment/gary-sinise-kj-apa-to-role-in-faith-based-film-i-still-believe-about-singer-jeremy-camp Gary Sinise, KJ Apa will star in faith-based film 'I Still Believe' about singer Jeremy Camp] (Fox News)</ref> It dramatizes Camp's college years, his rise as a well-known singer, and eventually meeting his second wife, [[Adrienne Camp|Adrienne]].<ref name=\"fnc4819\" />\n\n==Cast==\n{{cast listing|\n*[[KJ Apa]] as [[Jeremy Camp]]\n*[[Britt Robertson]] as Melissa Lynn Henning-Camp\n*[[Gary Sinise]] as Tom Camp, Jeremy's father\n*[[Shania Twain]] as Terry Camp, Jeremy's mother\n*[[Melissa Roxburgh]] as Heather Henning, Melissa's sister\n*[[Nathan Parsons]] as Jean-Luc Lajoie, a mutual friend also interested in Melissa<ref name=\"Federalist\" />\n*Abigail Cowen as [[Adrienne Camp]], Jeremy's second wife\n}}\n\n==Production==\nThe film is the first project of a deal struck between the Erwin Brothers and [[Lionsgate]] after the success of their film ''[[I Can Only Imagine (film)|I Can Only Imagine]]'' in 2018.<ref name=\"deadline51319\">[https://deadline.com/2019/05/i-still-believe-shania-twain-melissa-roxburgh-britt-robertson-nathan-dean-parsons-cast-jeremy-camp-movie-1202613705/ \u2018I Still Believe\u2019: Shania Twain, Melissa Roxburgh & More Join Lionsgate/Kingdom Studios\u2019 Faith-Based Drama] (Deadline)</ref> It is also the first film produced by Kingdom Story Company, a [[film studio]] founded by the [[Erwin Brothers]], [[Kevin Downes]], and Tony Young,<ref>[https://www.bizjournals.com/birmingham/news/2019/04/01/erwin-brothers-launching-new-film-studio.html Erwin brothers launching new film studio] (Birmingham Business Journal)</ref> and the Erwin Brothers' second [[Biopic|music biopic]] after ''I Can Only Imagine''.\n\nJeremy Camp was actively involved in the production of the film,<ref name=\"TCB2\">{{cite web|url=https://www.thechristianbeat.org/index.php/news/7228-jeremy-camp-pens-new-book-i-still-believe-a-memoir|title=Jeremy Camp Pens New Book 'I Still Believe: A Memoir'|author=Herb Longs|publisher=TheChristianBeat.com|date=February 22, 2020|accessdate=February 24, 2020}}</ref> while singer-songwriter [[Bart Millard]] of [[MercyMe]] (whose life story was told in the Erwin Brothers' ''I Can Only Imagine'') acted as an executive producer,<ref name=\"TCB\">{{Cite web |url=https://www.thechristianbeat.org/index.php/news/6817-mercyme-s-bart-millard-announced-as-executive-producer-of-i-still-believe |title=MercyMe's Bart Millard Announced As Executive Producer Of 'I Still Believe' |last=Clarks |first=Jessie |date=October 30, 2019 |publisher=The Christian Beat |access-date=December 24, 2019}}</ref> along with Camp, [[Jon Gunn]], and others.\n\n===Casting===\n[[KJ Apa]] was announced as the star of the film, playing Camp, and [[Gary Sinise]] was announced for the role of Camp's father, at CinemaCon in April 2019.<ref>[https://deadline.com/2019/04/k-j-apa-gary-sinise-join-lionsgate-kingdom-studio-faith-based-film-i-still-believe-1202588789/ K.J. Apa & Gary Sinise Join Lionsgate/Kingdom Studio Faith-Based Film \u2018I Still Believe\u2019 \u2013 CinemaCon] (Deadline)</ref> That same month it was announced that [[Britt Robertson]] would co-star as Melissa Camp, joined by [[Shania Twain]] as Camp's mother, [[Melissa Roxburgh]] as Melissa's sister, and [[Nathan Parsons]] as Jean-Luc Lajoie, lead singer for the band The Kry, a mutual friend.<ref name=\"deadline51319\" />\n\nApa, who did his own singing for the film, said he was drawn to the story because \"[t]heir love is seriously put to the test in this movie,\" adding, \"it's about journeying through your biggest fears and disappointments and coming out still believing. I believe that anyone, everyone can relate to this film because it's a story about love, loss, and hope.\"<ref>[https://people.com/movies/riverdale-kj-apa-first-trailer-i-still-believe/ WATCH: Riverdale's KJ Apa Sings and Romances Britt Robertson in Moving I Still Believe Trailer] (People)</ref> Apa later related that his role in ''I Still Believe'' is \"the coolest thing I've ever done\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.goodmorningamerica.com/culture/story/riverdale-star-returning-set-luke-perry-69482365|title='Riverdale' star on returning to set without Luke Perry|publisher=[[Good Morning America]]|author=Kelly McCarthy|date=March 9, 2020|accessdate=March 9, 2020}}</ref> Jeremy Camp stated that Apa was concerned about detail and would often consult him whenever he was in doubt regarding how to play his character in certain scenes.<ref name=\"Federalist\" />\n\nCo-director Andrew Erwin related that he hoped the cast, particularly Apa and Robertson, would attract non-Christians in addition to a Christian audience.<ref name=\"crossover appeal\">{{cite web|url=https://www.christianheadlines.com/contributors/michael-foust/director-i-still-believe-is-a-huge-opportunity-to-reach-the-unchurched.html|title=Director: \"I Still Believe\" Is a 'Huge Opportunity' to Reach the Unchurched|date=February 19, 2020|author=Michael Foust|publisher=Christian Headlines|accessdate=February 19, 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Music===\nComposer [[John Debney]] was hired to write the score for the film,<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://filmmusicreporter.com/2020/01/13/john-debney-to-score-the-erwin-brothers-i-still-believe/ |title=John Debney to Score the Erwin Brothers' 'I Still Believe' |date=January 13, 2020 |publisher=FilmMusicReporter.com |access-date=January 24, 2020}}</ref> while KJ Apa sang his own renditions of several songs written by Jeremy Camp during the period of his life accounted in the film, including \"I Still Believe\", \"[[Walk by Faith]]\", and \"[[This Man (song)|This Man]]\".<ref name=\"FMR\">{{cite web|url=https://filmmusicreporter.com/2020/03/05/i-still-believe-soundtrack-details/|title=\u2018I Still Believe\u2019 Soundtrack Details|publisher=FilmMusicReporter.com|author=|date=March 5, 2020|accessdate=March 9, 2020}}</ref> ''I Still Believe'' is John Debney's third time composing the score for a Christian film, after ''[[The Passion of the Christ]]'' in 2004 and ''[[The Young Messiah]]'' in 2016.\n\n===Writing===\nJon Erwin, [[Jon Gunn]], and [[Madeline Carrol]] (who starred in ''I Can Only Imagine'') wrote the screenplay for ''I Still Believe''.<ref name=\"F\" /> The film is Madeline Carrol's screenwriting debut. Jeremy Camp, initially apprehensive about how the film's script would read, was surprised to find that he liked it right off for \"[h]ow accurate and beautifully done it was.\"<ref name=\"Federalist\">{{cite web|url=https://thefederalist.com/2020/03/09/romance-flick-i-still-believe-seeks-to-set-new-standard-for-faith-driven-films/|title=Romance Flick \u2018I Still Believe\u2019 Seeks To Set New Standard For Faith-Driven Films|publisher=TheFederalist.com|author=Josh Shepherd|date=March 9, 2020|accessdate=March 9, 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Filming===\nFilming began in the [[Mobile, Alabama]] area in May 2019,<ref>[https://variety.com/2019/film/news/shania-twain-i-still-believe-1203212871/ Film News Roundup: Shania Twain, Britt Robertson Join Faith-Based \u2018I Still Believe\u2019] (Variety)</ref><ref>[https://www.al.com/life/2019/05/new-erwin-brothers-movie-i-still-believe-seeks-extras-for-filming-in-mobile.html New Erwin brothers movie, \u2018I Still Believe,\u2019 seeks extras for filming in Mobile] (AL.com)</ref> where it was filmed entirely.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.patheos.com/blogs/kateohare/2020/03/i-still-believe-jeremy-camp-kj-apa/|title='I Still Believe' Tells Jeremy Camp's Story of Love Amid Suffering|first=Kate O'Hare's Pax|last=Culturati|date=March 11, 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe film's cinematographer, Kristopher Kimlin, had collaborated with the Erwin Brothers on their past productions, ''[[Moms' Night Out]]'', ''[[Woodlawn (film)|Woodlawn]]'', and ''I Can Only Imagine''.\n\n==Theme==\nRegarding the film's main theme, Jeremy Camp, on whose life the film is based, said that it \"tells my story and shares what God has done amidst all the hard things I went through. It shows hope in the midst of pain.\"<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www1.cbn.com/cbnnews/entertainment/2019/august/shania-twain-gary-sinise-starring-in-i-still-believe-true-story-of-christian-singer-jeremy-camp |title=Shania Twain, Gary Sinise Starring in 'I Still Believe', True Story of Christian Singer Jeremy Camp |last=Morris |first=Andrea |date=August 23, 2019 |publisher=[[Christian Broadcasting Network]] |access-date=January 9, 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe film's stars, Apa, Robertson and Twain, also shared their thoughts on the film's themes, with Twain commenting that \"[t]his is [about] a love that goes beyond fear, that goes beyond any doubt[.]\" Apa said that {{quote|text=it's [about] journeying through your biggest fear and coming out on the other side and still loving God ... I hope people, after seeing the love between Jeremy and Melissa, think, 'I hope that I could one day be in love like that[.]<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.christianpost.com/news/i-still-believe-movie-inspire-viewers-to-love-beyond-fear-heart-of-the-story-video.html |title='I Still Believe' movie aims to inspire viewers to 'love beyond fear' ('Heart of the Story' video) |last=Law |first=Jeannie |date=November 30, 2019 |website=[[The Christian Post]] |access-date=January 9, 2020}}</ref>}}\n\n''I Still Believe'''s co-director, Jon Erwin, said in an interview with the Baptist Press that \n{{Quote|\nquotetext=[the] film grapples with [the question of why God allows suffering.] ... I think we forget so many times that there is a beauty, and a purpose, and a meaning in the difficult things we go through. And that sometimes God uses those things more than He uses the good things that happen to shape us, to mold us and to give us our voice. ... It's a love story as God intended, between these two people and God, and between these two people and each other[.]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bpnews.net/54367/i-still-believe-touted-as-evangelistic-love-story|title='I Still Believe' touted as evangelistic love story|author=Diana Chandler|publisher=Baptist Press|date=February 24, 2020|accessdate=February 24, 2020}}</ref>\n}}\n\n==Soundtrack==\n{{Infobox album\n| name       = I Still Believe: Original Motion Picture Soundtrack\n| type       = soundtrack\n|cover     =\n| artist     = [[John Debney]], [[Jeremy Camp]], [[All Sons & Daughters|David Leonard]], and [[JJ Heller]]\n| released   = March 6, 2020\n| recorded   = \n| venue      =\n| studio     =\n| genre      = [[Soundtrack]]\n| length     = \n| label      = [[Capitol Records|Capitol]]\n| producer   = \n| chronology = [[John Debney]] film scores\n| prev_title = [[Dora and the Lost City of Gold]]\n| prev_year  = 2019\n| next_title = [[Clifford the Big Red Dog (film)|Clifford the Big Red Dog]]\n| next_year  = 2020\n}}\nThe original motion picture soundtrack was released digitally by [[Capital Records]] on March 6, 2020, and included Debney's score, Apa's renditions of Camp's songs \"[[This Man]]\", \"[[I Still Believe (Jeremy Camp song)|I Still Believe]]\", \"[[Live Unplugged (Jeremy Camp album)|My Desire]]\", and \"[[Right Here (Jeremy Camp song)|Right Here]]\", as well as new versions of \"I Still Believe\" and \"[[Walk By Faith]]\" performed by Jeremy Camp, and two tracks featuring dialog from the film.<ref name=\"FMR\" />\n{{Track listing\n| headline        = Track listing\n| total_length    = \n| title1          = [[I Still Believe (Jeremy Camp song)|I Still Believe]]\n| note1           = performed by KJ Apa; written by Jeremy Camp\n| length1         = 3:42\n\n| title2          = Jeremy Says Goodbye\n| note2           = written by Debney\n| length2         = 4:05\n\n| title3          = [[This Man (song)|This Man]]\n| note3           = performed by KJ Apa; written by Jeremy Camp\n| length3         = 3:09\n\n| title4          = Take My Hand\n| note4           = performed by [[All Sons & Daughters|David Leonard]] written by Jean-Luc Lajoie & Yves Lajoie \n| length4         = 4:20\n\n| title5          = Find Me in the River\n| note5           = performed by KJ Apa and [[JJ Heller]]\n| length5         = 3:03\n\n| title6          = Some Stars Shine Brighter Than Others\n| note6           = written by Debney\n| length6         = 3:12\n\n| title7          = [[Live Unplugged (Jeremy Camp album)|My Desire]]\n| note7           = performed by KJ Apa; written by Jeremy Camp\n| length7         = 3:19\n\n| title8          = Dwelling Places (Dialog)\n| note8           = dialog by cast of ''I Still Believe''\n| length8         = 0:59\n\n| title9          = [[Right Here (Jeremy Camp song)|Right Here]]\n| note9           = performed by KJ Apa; written by Jeremy Camp \n| length9         = 3:29\n\n| title10         = Melissa Loves Jeremy\n| note10          = written by Debney\n| length10        = 2:07\n\n| title11         = You Call I'll Answer\n| note11          = performed by David Leonard\n| length11        = 4:03\n\n| title12         = Walk By Faith (Dialog)\n| note12          = dialog by cast of ''I Still Believe''\n| length12        = 2:35\n\n| title13         = Ancient Stories Still Relevant\n| note13          = written by Debney\n| length13        = 4:44\n\n| title14         = Hey, What's Your Name Again?\n| note14          = written by Debney\n| length14        = 3:21\n\n| title15         = [[Walk By Faith|Walk By Faith (2020 Version)]]\n| note15          = written and performed by Jeremy Camp\n| length15        = 3:41\n\n| title16         = I Still Believe (2020 Version)\n| note16          = written and performed by Jeremy Camp\n| length16        = 4:31\n\n| title17         = I Can't Save Myself (Bonus Track)\n| note17          = performed by [[Adrienne Camp]]\n| length17        = 3:12\n}}\n\n==Release==\n''I Still Believe'' premiered at [[ArcLight Hollywood]] in [[Hollywood, California]] on March 7, 2020,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nydailynews.com/snyde/ny-i-still-believe-movie-premiere-2020-20200308-wpygrxpj3rdurfjlbsfxv43gz4-photogallery.html|title='I Still Believe' movie premiere|date=|author=|publisher=NYDailyNews.com|accessdate=March 8, 2020}}</ref> and was released in North American theaters on March 13 by [[Lionsgate]],<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.christianpost.com/news/i-still-believe-trailer-shows-star-studded-cast-tells-true-love-story-of-jeremy-camp.html |title='I Still Believe' trailer shows star-studded cast, tells true love story of Jeremy Camp |website=The Christian Post}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.lionsgatepublicity.com/theatrical/i-still-believe |title=I Still Believe |publisher=Lionsgate Publicity|access-date=January 1, 2020}}</ref> with early showings on [[IMAX|IMAX theaters]] on March 11. ''I Still Believe'' is the first [[feature-length]] [[Christian film industry|faith-based film]] to be released on IMAX screens.<ref name=\"F\" /> \n\n===Rating===\n''I Still Believe'' was rated [[Motion picture content rating system|PG]] by the [[Motion Picture Association of America]] for \"thematic material\".<ref name=\"The Numbers\">{{cite web|url=https://www.the-numbers.com/movie/I-Still-Believe-(2020)#tab=summary|title=I Still Believe (2020) - Financial Information|publisher=The Numbers|author=|date=|accessdate=March 9, 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Marketing===\nThe film's first trailer was released in August 2019,<ref>[https://ew.com/movies/2019/08/22/i-still-believe-trailer-kj-apa/ See Riverdale star K.J. Apa in first trailer for Christian romance I Still Believe] (EW)</ref> while the second was released in January 2020.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.flickeringmyth.com/2020/01/new-trailer-for-i-still-believe-starring-kj-apa-britt-robertson-gary-sinise-and-shania-twain/ |title=New trailer for I Still Believe starring KJ Apa, Britt Robertson, Gary Sinise and Shania Twain |last=Cranswick |first=Amie |date=January 15, 2020 |publisher=FlickeringMyth.com |access-date=January 22, 2020}}</ref>\n\nChristian band [[MercyMe]] announced in October 2019 that it would be promoting the film through their winter-spring 20/20 tour with Jeremy Camp as a special guest.<ref name=\"TCB\" /><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.christianheadlines.com/contributors/michael-foust/i-still-believe-to-become-1st-faith-based-movie-on-imax.html|title=I Still Believe to Become 1st Faith-Based Movie on IMAX|date=February 12, 2020|author=Michael Foust|publisher=Christian Headlines|accessdate=February 12, 2020}}</ref> In February 2020, Camp wrote and released ''I Still Believe: A Memoir'' in promotion of the film.<ref name=\"TCB2\" /> Jeremy and Adrienne Camp and Jon Erwin spoke at [[Liberty University]] in early March prior to the film's release to promote ''I Still Believe''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.liberty.edu/news/index.cfm?PID=18495&MID=377793|title=Singer Jeremy Camp promotes 'I Still Believe' film with director Jon Erwin|date=March 4, 2020|author=Jacob Couch|publisher=[[Liberty University|Liberty News]]|accessdate=March 8, 2020}}</ref>\n\nRegarding Lionsgate's role behind the film's marketing, co-director Jon Erwin related that {{Quote|quotetext=[h]aving the full support of Lionsgate is new for us [him, his brother Andrew, and frequent collaborator Kevin Downes] . . . They\u2019re treating this [film] no different [sic] than they would \u2018[[Twilight (2008 film)|Twilight]]\u2019 or \u2018[[The Hunger Games film series|The Hunger Games]]\u2019 or any of their huge releases. The ad buy is . . . big, just like any other movie. We\u2019ve never experienced anything like it.<ref name=\"Federalist\" />}}\n\n===Video on demand===\nDue to theaters closing nationwide in the face of the [[COVID-19|COVID-19 pandemic]], Lionsgate and Kingdom Story Company announced that the film would get an early [[video-on-demand]] release on March 27, just two weeks after the film's theatrical debut.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://collider.com/kj-apa-i-still-believe-early-vod-release-details/|title=KJ Apa's Faith-Based Drama \u2018I Still Believe\u2019 Gets Early VOD Release|date=March 19, 2020|publisher=[[Collider.com]]|author=Jeff Sneider|accessdate=March 19, 2020}}</ref> Lionsgate chairman Joe Drake said in a statement, \"With theaters closed nationwide due to these unprecedented events, we want to continue to make ''I Still Believe'' available to consumers... We're enormously proud of the movie that the Erwin Brothers created and are grateful to be able to share it with audiences for their home viewing pleasure.\"<ref name=\"movieguide\">[https://www.movieguide.org/news-articles/popular-articles/i-still-believe-heads-to-video-on-demand-due-to-coronavirus.html I STILL BELIEVE Heads to Video on Demand Due to Coronavirus]</ref> The Erwin brothers added, \"As filmmakers, we are heartbroken that we can\u2019t share ''I Still Believe'' on a big screen the way we intended. We make movies because we love movies and we stand firmly behind the nation\u2019s theater chains, from the largest circuits to the smallest mom and pop indies that have been so dramatically affected by these unprecedented closures. But the safety of guests comes first, and we're proud to have the opportunity to share online a movie whose inspiring message of love, hope and faith is perfect for these uncertain times.\"<ref name=\"movieguide\"/>\n\n==Reception==\n\n===Box office===\nIn the United States and Canada, the film was released alongside ''[[The Hunt (2020 film)|The Hunt]]'' and ''[[Bloodshot (film)|Bloodshot]]'', and was projected to gross $11\u201315&nbsp;million from 3,250 theaters in its opening weekend.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2020/03/vin-diesel-bloodshot-kj-apa-i-still-believe-the-hunt-onward-box-office-coronavirus-1202880173/|title=Vin Diesel Pic \u2018Bloodshot\u2019, K.J. Apa's \u2018I Still Believe\u2019 & Blumhouse's \u2018The Hunt\u2019 Hit Theaters Amid Coronavirus Jitters|website=[[Deadline Hollywood]]|author=Anthony D'Alessandro|accessdate=March 12, 2020|date=March 11, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url= https://www.thewrap.com/i-still-believe-bloodshot-hunt-box-office/ |title= \u2018I Still Believe\u2019 Expected to Top \u2018Bloodshot\u2019 and \u2018The Hunt\u2019 at Weekend Box Office |website=[[TheWrap]]|author=Jeremy Fuster|accessdate=March 10, 2020|date=March 10, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.boxofficemojo.com/article/ed2792358916/?ref_=bo_hm_hp|title='I Still Believe', 'The Hunt', and 'Bloodshot' To Hit Theaters This Weekend|author=Brad Brevet|publisher=[[Box Office Mojo]]|date=March 12, 2020|accessdate=March 12, 2020}}</ref> The film was number one at the box office on its first day at $4&nbsp;million, including $780,000 from Wednesday [[IMAX]] screenings and Thursday night previews. It went on to debut to just $9.1&nbsp;million, finishing third behind holdover ''[[Onward (film)|Onward]]'' and ''Bloodshot''. The weekend was also noteworthy for being the lowest combined grossing since October 1998, with all films totaling only $55.3&nbsp;million, which was attributed to [[COVID-19]] concerns.<ref name=opening>{{Cite web|url= https://deadline.com/2020/03/vin-diesel-bloodshot-i-still-believe-the-hunt-weekend-box-office-coronavirus-1202882333/ |title= Weekend Box Office Headed To 22-Year-Low At $58M+ As Coronavirus Fears Grip Nation |website=[[Deadline Hollywood]]|author=Anthony D'Alessandro|accessdate=March 15, 2020|date=March 15, 2020}}</ref><ref name=IndieWireOpen>{{cite web|title= With Attendance at a 40-Year Low, This Is a Box-Office Weekend When No One Wins |url= https://www.indiewire.com/2020/03/box-office-attendance-40-year-low-coronavirus-i-still-believe-1202217868/ |publisher=[[IndieWire]]|date=March 15, 2020|accessdate=March 15, 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Critical response===\nOn [[review aggregator]] [[Rotten Tomatoes]], ''I Still Believe'' holds an approval rating of 44% based on 34 reviews, with an average rating of 5.5/10. The website's critics consensus reads: \"''I Still Believe''{{'}}s palpable good intentions are offset by its predictable handling of a fact-based story that ends up preaching to the choir.\"<ref name=\"RT\">{{cite web |title=I Still Believe (2020)|url= https://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/i_still_believe/ |website=[[Rotten Tomatoes]] |publisher=[[Fandango]] |accessdate=April 1, 2020}}</ref> On [[Metacritic]], the film has a weighted average score of 37 out of 100, based on 11 critics, indicating \"generally unfavorable reviews\".<ref>{{cite web |title=I Still Believe Reviews |url= https://www.metacritic.com/movie/i-still-believe |website=[[Metacritic]] |publisher=[[CBS Interactive]] |accessdate=March 13, 2020}}</ref> Audiences polled by [[CinemaScore]] gave the film an average grade of \"A\" on an A+ to F scale, and [[PostTrak]] reported it received an average 4.5 out of 5 stars.<ref name=opening/>\n\nIn a favorable review, Pete Hammond of ''[[Deadline Hollywood]]'' said that \"''I Still Believe'' doesn't rewrite any of the rules of this genre, but it does ask the right questions of faith in light of unimaginable tragedy without trying to sugarcoat them. For those who truly want to 'still believe', it should be enough. Fans of Apa also ought to be happy. Cynics should quarantine themselves from this; it's not for you.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://deadline.com/video/i-still-believe-review-kj-apa-britt-robertson-jeremy-camp/|title=\u2018I Still Believe\u2019 Review: KJ Apa Impressively Hits A Different Note As Singer Jeremy Camp In Faith-Based Tragic Love Story|author=Pete Hammond|publisher=[[Deadline Hollywood]]|date=March 12, 2020|accessdate=March 13, 2020}}</ref> Megan Basham of ''[[World (magazine)|World]]'' also wrote a positive review for the film, and, while criticizing it for its \"melodramatic raging\", similarly praised its depiction of faith amidst suffering, saying, \"[t]he Erwins are careful to show that God is faithful even when He says 'no.'\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://world.wng.org/2020/03/emotional_under_load|title=Emotional underload|author=Megan Basham|publisher=[[World (magazine)|World]]|date=March 6, 2020|accessdate=March 12, 2020}}</ref> Joe Leydon of ''[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]'', in a positive review for the film, praised Apa's and Robertson's performances and commended the Erwin Brothers' direction, saying that in ''I Still Believe'' \"they amp the emotional power \u2013 subtly at first, then gradually more aggressively \u2013 with a 'Love Story'-style scenario that is all the more potent for being based on real-life events.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://variety.com/2020/film/reviews/i-still-believe-review-1203530986/|title='I Still Believe' Review - Variety|author=Joe Leydon|publisher=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|date=March 11, 2020|accessdate=March 12, 2020}}</ref>\n\nFrank Scheck of ''[[The Hollywood Reporter]]'' commended the film for dealing with \"the difficulty of maintaining faith when tragedy strikes for no apparent reason\", although his review was ultimately negative, with him stating as a bottom line that \"[t]ears will be jerked, but you'll feel the machinations.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/review/i-still-believe-1284043|title='I Still Believe': Film Review|author=Frank Scheck|publisher=[[The Hollywood Reporter]]|date=March 11, 2020|accessdate=March 12, 2020}}</ref> Carla Meyer of ''[[The San Francisco Chronicle]]'', while praising Robertson's acting and her chemistry with Apa, derided the film for the lack of \"any character development for Jeremy beyond caretaker and worried partner.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://datebook.sfchronicle.com/movies-tv/review-britt-robertson-keeps-i-still-believe-somewhat-believable|title=Review: Britt Robertson keeps \u2018I Still Believe\u2019 somewhat believable|author=Carla Meyer|publisher=[[The San Francisco Chronicle]]|date=March 11, 2020|accessdate=March 12, 2020}}</ref> Similarly, ''[[IndieWire]]'' writer David Ehrlich gave the film a \"C-\", stating that \"[t]he power of the Camps' story is hard to deny, but it would almost be impossible to make it seem more hollow. Maybe if the Erwins depicted people with half the same detail with which they dote upon Jesus, ''I Still Believe'' wouldn't feel so insufferably forced to those of us who don't.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.indiewire.com/2020/03/i-still-believe-review-christian-biopic-jeremy-camp-1202216945/|title=\u2018I Still Believe\u2019 Review: A Christian Rock Biopic So Earnest It Makes \u2018Walk to Remember\u2019 Seem Like \u2018Sal\u00f2\u2019|date=March 11, 2020|author=David Ehrlich|publisher=[[IndieWire]]|accessdate=March 13, 2020}}</ref> Similarly, ''[[TheWrap]]'' contributor Carlos Aguilar, while praising Kristopher Kimlin's cinematography and the \"above-average production value\", called the film \"[s]accharine\" and \"[f]ormulaic to the core, from the protagonist's short-lived moment of doubt to the epiphany that sets him back on course.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thewrap.com/i-still-believe-film-review-kj-apa-jeremy-camp/|title=\u2018I Still Believe\u2019 Film Review: KJ Apa Croons His Way Through Another Saccharine Faith-Based Biopic|date=March 12, 2020|author=Carlos Aguilar|publisher=[[TheWrap]]|accessdate=March 13, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{Official website|https://www.istillbelievemovie.com/}}\n* {{IMDb title|tt9779516}}\n* {{tcmdb title|9779516|I Still Believe}}\n* {{Mojo title|istillbelieve}}\n\n{{Portal bar|Film|United States}}\n{{Erwin Brothers}}\n\n[[Category:2020s biographical drama films]]\n[[Category:American films]]\n[[Category:American biographical drama films]]\n[[Category:American independent films]]\n[[Category:Drama films based on actual events]]\n[[Category:English-language films]]\n[[Category:Films shot in Alabama]]\n[[Category:Films about Christianity]]\n[[Category:Films directed by the Erwin Brothers]]\n[[Category:Films scored by John Debney]]\n[[Category:IMAX films]]\n", "name_user": "Instaurare", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/I_Still_Believe_(film)"}
{"title_page": "Former Residence of Liu Shaoqi", "text_new": "{{Short description|Historical site}}{{Infobox building\n| name                = Former Residence of Liu Shaoqi\n| native_name         = \u5218\u5c11\u5947\u6545\u5c45\n| native_name_lang    = zh\n| image               = Liu Shaoqi's former residence 2.jpg\n| image_caption       = Former Residence of Liu Shaoqi\n| map_type            = China Hunan#China\n| map_caption         = \n| map_size            = 225px\n| former_names        = \n| building_type       = Traditional folk houses\n| architectural_style = \n| location            = [[Huaminglou|Huaminglou Town]], [[Ningxiang|Ningxiang City]], [[Hunan|Hunan Province]]\n| location_country    = [[China]]\n| coordinates         = {{coord|28.032175|N|112.645609|E|type:landmark_region:China|format=dms|display=title,inline}}\n| altitude            = <!-- \u6d77\u62d4 -->\n| groundbreaking_date = \n| start_date          = \n| topped_out_date     = <!-- \u9884\u5b9a\u65e5\u671f -->\n| completion_date     = 1796\n| opened_date         = 1959\n| inauguration_date   = \n| relocated_date      = <!-- \u642c\u8fc1\u65e5\u671f -->\n| renovation_date     = <!-- \u4fee\u590d\u65e5\u671f -->\n| closing_date        = \n| demolition_date     = <!-- \u7206\u7834\u65e5\u671f -->\n| cost                = \n| owner               = Government of Ningxiang\n| landlord            = \n| affiliation         = <!-- \u96b6\u5c5e\u4e8e -->\n| height              = <!-- {{convert||m|adj=on}} -->\n| architectural       = \n| roof                = \n| material            = <!-- \u5efa\u7b51\u6750\u8d28\uff1a\u77f3\u5934\u3001\u7816\u6728 -->\n| floor_area          = {{convert|20000|m2|adj=on}}\n| grounds_area        = {{convert|4000000|m2|adj=on}}\n| architect           = <!-- \u8bbe\u8ba1\u8005 -->\n| architecture_firm   = <!-- \u5efa\u7b51\u516c\u53f8 -->\n| awards              = \n| known_for           = \n| rooms               = <!-- or | unit_count          = -->\n| website             = <!-- {{URL|example.com}} -->\n| references          = \n| footnotes           = \n}}\n\nThe '''Former Residence of Liu Shaoqi''' or '''Liu Shaoqi's Former Residence''' ({{zh|s=\u5218\u5c11\u5947\u6545\u5c45|t=\u5289\u5c11\u5947\u6545\u5c45|p=Li\u00fa Sh\u00e0oq\u00ed G\u00f9j\u016b}}) was built in the late [[Qing Dynasty]] (1644&ndash;1911).{{sfnb|Wang Xijia|2014|p=16}} It is located in [[Huaminglou|Huaminglou Town]] of [[Ningxiang]], [[Hunan]], [[China]].{{sfnb|Wang Xijia|2014|p=16}}<ref>{{cite news|author= |url=http://www.discoverchinatours.com/china-tours/CPCS02.html |title=1 Day Red China Tour from Changsha To Shaoshan - Hometown Of Chinaman Mao |newspaper=discoverchinatours.com |date=2015 |language= }}</ref> It has an area of about {{convert|4000000|m2|adj=on}} and a building area of about {{convert|20000|m2|adj=on}}, embodies buildings such as the old houses, the Liu Shaoqi Memorial Hall, the Bronze Statue of Liu Shaoqi, the Cultural relics Exhibition Hall.<ref>{{cite news|author= |url= http://www.enghunan.gov.cn/SP/Christmas2015/TBHDiH/201512/t20151210_1940036.html|title=Huaminglou, Liu Shaoqi's former residence |newspaper= |date= |language= }}</ref>\n\n==History==\nIn 1796, in the first year of the age of the [[Jiaqing Emperor]], it was built by Liu Shaoqi's forebear.<ref name=\"fish\">{{cite web|url=http://news.xinhuanet.com/travel/2011-06/23/c_121573977.htm|script-title=zh:\u5b81\u4e61\u53bf\u82b1\u660e\u697c\u5218\u5c11\u5947\u6545\u5c45\u548c\u7eaa\u5ff5\u9986|date=2011|work=Xinhuanews|language=zh|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161121235113/http://news.xinhuanet.com/travel/2011-06/23/c_121573977.htm|archivedate=2016-11-21}}</ref>\n\nIn 1898, Liu Shaoqi was born here.{{sfnb|Wang Xijia|2014|p=16}}<ref name=\" fish\" />\n\nOn its opening late in 1959, it was listed as a \"Historical and Cultural Sites Protected at the Provincial Level\".<ref name=\"fish\" />\n\nIn May 1961, Chinese President [[Liu Shaoqi]] and his wife, first lady [[Wang Guangmei]] returned to Hunan and they lived here. During the [[Great Leap Forward]], Liu Shaoqi handed out their own daily necessities to farmers.\n\nIn 1966, during the [[Cultural Revolution]], the house was broken down by the [[Red Guards (China)|Red Guards]] and the cultural relics were stolen.<ref name=\" fish\" /> On October 1, 1966, the site was closed.<ref name=\"fish\" />\n\nIn February 1980, President Liu Shaoqi was rehabilitated. The People's Government of Hunan Province and the People's Government of Ningxiang rebuilt the house.<ref name=\" fish\" /> On March 5, it was opened to the public again.<ref name=\"fish\" />\n\nIn 1982, China's leader [[Deng Xiaoping]] wrote \"Liu Shao-qi's Former Residence\" on the horizontal tablet.<ref name=\"fish\" />\n\nIn January 1988, it was listed as a \"[[Major Historical and Cultural Site Protected at the National Level]]\" by the [[State Council of China]].{{sfnb|Wang Xijia|2014|p=16}}<ref name=\"fish\" />\n\n==Gallery==\n{{Gallery\n|align=center\n|File:Liu Shaoqi's former residence 4.jpg\n |The Liu Shaoqi Memorial Hall.\n|File:Liu Shaoqi's former residence 3.jpg\n |The Huaming Tower.\n|File:Liu Shaoqi's Former Residence 057.jpg\n |Bronze statue of Liu Shaoqi.\n|File:Liu Shaoqi's Former Residence 105.jpg\n |[[Paifang]] at the Former Residence of Liu Shaoqi.\n}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n===Bibliography===\n* {{cite book |language=zh|author=Wang Xijia |script-chapter=zh:\u6587\u5316\u53e4\u8ff9|chapter=Cultural Relics |script-title=zh:\u957f\u6c99\u53f2\u8bdd |trans-title=A Brief History of Changsha |year=2014 |publisher=Social Sciences Academic Press |location=Beijing |isbn=978-7-5097-6662-0|ref=harv}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Liu Shaoqi's former residence|Liu Shaoqi's Former Residence}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Liu Shaoqi's Former Residence}}\n[[Category:Buildings and structures in Ningxiang]]\n[[Category:Tourist attractions in Changsha]]\n[[Category:Traditional folk houses in Hunan]]\n[[Category:Major National Historical and Cultural Sites in Hunan]]\n[[Category:1796 establishments in China]]\n[[Category:National first-grade museums of China]]\n[[Category:Historic house museums in China]]\n[[Category:Museums in Hunan]]\n", "text_old": "{{Short description|Historical site}}{{Infobox building\n| name                = Former Residence of Liu Shaoqi\n| native_name         = \u5218\u5c11\u5947\u6545\u5c45\n| native_name_lang    = zh\n| image               = Liu Shaoqi's former residence 2.jpg\n| image_caption       = Former Residence of Liu Shaoqi\n| map_type            = China Hunan#China\n| map_caption         = \n| map_size            = 225px\n| former_names        = \n| building_type       = Traditional folk houses\n| architectural_style = \n| location            = [[Huaminglou|Huaminglou Town]], [[Ningxiang|Ningxiang City]], [[Hunan|Hunan Province]]\n| location_country    = [[China]]\n| coordinates         = {{coord|28.032175|N|112.645609|E|type:landmark_region:China|format=dms|display=title,inline}}\n| altitude            = <!-- \u6d77\u62d4 -->\n| groundbreaking_date = \n| start_date          = \n| topped_out_date     = <!-- \u9884\u5b9a\u65e5\u671f -->\n| completion_date     = 1796\n| opened_date         = 1959\n| inauguration_date   = \n| relocated_date      = <!-- \u642c\u8fc1\u65e5\u671f -->\n| renovation_date     = <!-- \u4fee\u590d\u65e5\u671f -->\n| closing_date        = \n| demolition_date     = <!-- \u7206\u7834\u65e5\u671f -->\n| cost                = \n| owner               = Government of Ningxiang\n| landlord            = \n| affiliation         = <!-- \u96b6\u5c5e\u4e8e -->\n| height              = <!-- {{convert||m|adj=on}} -->\n| architectural       = \n| roof                = \n| material            = <!-- \u5efa\u7b51\u6750\u8d28\uff1a\u77f3\u5934\u3001\u7816\u6728 -->\n| floor_area          = {{convert|20000|m2|adj=on}}\n| grounds_area        = {{convert|4000000|m2|adj=on}}\n| architect           = <!-- \u8bbe\u8ba1\u8005 -->\n| architecture_firm   = <!-- \u5efa\u7b51\u516c\u53f8 -->\n| awards              = \n| known_for           = \n| rooms               = <!-- or | unit_count          = -->\n| website             = <!-- {{URL|example.com}} -->\n| references          = \n| footnotes           = \n}}\n\nThe '''Former Residence of Liu Shaoqi''' or '''Liu Shaoqi's Former Residence''' ({{zh|s=\u5218\u5c11\u5947\u6545\u5c45|t=\u5289\u5c11\u5947\u6545\u5c45|p=Li\u00fa Sh\u00e0oq\u00ed G\u00f9j\u016b}}) was built in the late [[Qing Dynasty]] (1644&ndash;1911). It is located in [[Huaminglou|Huaminglou Town]] of [[Ningxiang]], [[Hunan]], [[China]].<ref>{{cite news|author= |url=http://www.discoverchinatours.com/china-tours/CPCS02.html |title=1 Day Red China Tour from Changsha To Shaoshan - Hometown Of Chinaman Mao |newspaper=discoverchinatours.com |date=2015 |language= }}</ref> It has an area of about {{convert|4000000|m2|adj=on}} and a building area of about {{convert|20000|m2|adj=on}}, embodies buildings such as the old houses, the Liu Shaoqi Memorial Hall, the Bronze Statue of Liu Shaoqi, the Cultural relics Exhibition Hall.<ref>{{cite news|author= |url= http://www.enghunan.gov.cn/SP/Christmas2015/TBHDiH/201512/t20151210_1940036.html|title=Huaminglou, Liu Shaoqi's former residence |newspaper= |date= |language= }}</ref>\n\n==History==\nIn 1796, in the first year of the age of the [[Jiaqing Emperor]], it was built by Liu Shaoqi's forebear.<ref name=\"fish\">{{cite web|url=http://news.xinhuanet.com/travel/2011-06/23/c_121573977.htm|script-title=zh:\u5b81\u4e61\u53bf\u82b1\u660e\u697c\u5218\u5c11\u5947\u6545\u5c45\u548c\u7eaa\u5ff5\u9986|date=2011|work=Xinhuanews|language=zh|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161121235113/http://news.xinhuanet.com/travel/2011-06/23/c_121573977.htm|archivedate=2016-11-21}}</ref>\n\nIn 1898, Liu Shaoqi was born there.<ref name=\" fish\" />\n\nOn its opening late in 1959, it was listed as a \"Historical and Cultural Sites Protected at the Provincial Level\".<ref name=\"fish\" />\n\nIn May 1961, Chinese President [[Liu Shaoqi]] and his wife, first lady [[Wang Guangmei]] returned to Hunan and they lived here. During the [[Great Leap Forward]], Liu Shaoqi handed out their own daily necessities to farmers.\n\nIn 1966, during the [[Cultural Revolution]], the house was broken down by the [[Red Guards (China)|Red Guards]] and the cultural relics were stolen.<ref name=\" fish\" /> On October 1, 1966, the site was closed.<ref name=\"fish\" />\n\nIn February 1980, President Liu Shaoqi was rehabilitated. The People's Government of Hunan Province and the People's Government of Ningxiang rebuilt the house.<ref name=\" fish\" /> On March 5, it was opened to the public again.<ref name=\"fish\" />\n\nIn 1982, China's leader [[Deng Xiaoping]] wrote \"Liu Shao-qi's Former Residence\" on the horizontal tablet.<ref name=\"fish\" />\n\nIn January 1988, it was listed as a \"[[Major Historical and Cultural Site Protected at the National Level]]\" by the [[State Council of China]].<ref name=\"fish\" />\n\n==Gallery==\n{{Gallery\n|align=center\n|File:Liu Shaoqi's former residence 4.jpg\n |The Liu Shaoqi Memorial Hall.\n|File:Liu Shaoqi's former residence 3.jpg\n |The Huaming Tower.\n|File:Liu Shaoqi's Former Residence 057.jpg\n |Bronze statue of Liu Shaoqi.\n|File:Liu Shaoqi's Former Residence 105.jpg\n |[[Paifang]] at the Former Residence of Liu Shaoqi.\n}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Liu Shaoqi's former residence|Liu Shaoqi's Former Residence}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Liu Shaoqi's Former Residence}}\n[[Category:Buildings and structures in Ningxiang]]\n[[Category:Tourist attractions in Changsha]]\n[[Category:Traditional folk houses in Hunan]]\n[[Category:Major National Historical and Cultural Sites in Hunan]]\n[[Category:1796 establishments in China]]\n[[Category:National first-grade museums of China]]\n[[Category:Historic house museums in China]]\n[[Category:Museums in Hunan]]\n", "name_user": 