{"title_page": "Naujoji Akmen\u0117", "text_new": "{{Infobox settlement <!--more fields are available for this Infobox--See Template:Infobox Settlement-->\n|name = Naujoji Akmen\u0117\n|nickname = \n|settlement_type=City\n|pushpin_map            =Lithuania \n|pushpin_label_position =bottom<!-- the position of the pushpin label: left, right, top, bottom, none -->\n|pushpin_map_caption    =Location of Naujoji Akmen\u0117\n|image_flag = Flag of Naujoji Akmene.gif\n|image_shield = Naujoji Akmen\u0117 COA.svg\n|coordinates       = {{coord|56|19|N|22|54|E|region:LT_type:city(12000)|display=inline,title}}\n|\n|subdivision_type  =[[Countries of the world|Country]]\n|subdivision_name  ={{LTU}}\n|subdivision_type1 =[[Regions of Lithuania|Ethnographic&nbsp;region]]\n|subdivision_name1 =[[Samogitia]]\n|subdivision_type2 =[[Counties of Lithuania|County]]\n|subdivision_name2 =[[\u0160iauliai County]]\n|subdivision_type3 =[[List of municipalities of Lithuania|Municipality]]\n|subdivision_name3 =[[Akmen\u0117 district municipality]]\n|subdivision_type4 =[[Elderships of Lithuania|Eldership]]\n|subdivision_name4 =Naujoji Akmen\u0117 town eldership\n|subdivision_type6 =[[Capital (political)|Capital of]]\n|subdivision_name6 =[[Akmen\u0117 district municipality]] <br> Naujoji Akmen\u0117 town eldership <br> Naujoji Akmen\u0117 rural eldership\n|established_date  =1949\n|established_title =First mentioned\n|established_date2 =1965\n|established_title2=Granted city rights\n|population_total  =9,300\n|population_as_of  =2011\n|timezone=[[Eastern European Time|EET]]\n|utc_offset=+2\n|timezone_DST=[[Eastern European Summer Time|EEST]]\n|utc_offset_DST=+3\n}}\n\n'''Naujoji Akmen\u0117''' ({{pronunciation|Naujoji Akmene.ogg}}, [[Samogitian dialect|Samogitian]]: ''Naujuoj\u0117 Akmen\u0117'') is a [[new town]] that was established in 1952 and is one of the newest cities in [[Lithuania]]. Its name means ''New [[Akmen\u0117]]''. It is an industrial base with concrete as its main product, with [[Public company]] ''[[Akmen\u0117s cementas]]'' (English: ''Akmen\u0117 Concrete'') producing 700,000 [[tonne]]s of [[concrete]] annually. As a new city, it did initially have well-developed infrastructure. For example, a special branch of the railway had to be built for the factory needs. The road network was rapidly developing before the city even existed.\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category|Naujoji Akmen\u0117}}\n*[http://www.cementas.lt/?obj=changeLng&lng=en Akmen\u0117s Cementas Official Website]\n\n{{Siauliai County}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Naujoji Akmene}}\n[[Category:Cities in Lithuania]]\n[[Category:Cities in \u0160iauliai County]]\n[[Category:Populated places established in 1952]]\n[[Category:Cities and towns built in the Soviet Union]]\n[[Category:Municipalities administrative centres of Lithuania]]\n[[Category:Kovno Governorate]]\n[[Category:Akmen\u0117 District Municipality]]\n\n{{lithuania-geo-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox settlement <!--more fields are available for this Infobox--See Template:Infobox Settlement-->\n|name = Naujoji Akmen\u0117\n|nickname = \n|settlement_type=City\n|pushpin_map            =Lithuania \n|pushpin_label_position =bottom<!-- the position of the pushpin label: left, right, top, bottom, none -->\n|pushpin_map_caption    =Location of Naujoji Akmen\u0117\n|image_flag = Flag of Naujoji Akmene.gif\n|image_shield = Akmen\u0117 COA.svg\n|coordinates       = {{coord|56|19|N|22|54|E|region:LT_type:city(12000)|display=inline,title}}\n|\n|subdivision_type  =[[Countries of the world|Country]]\n|subdivision_name  ={{LTU}}\n|subdivision_type1 =[[Regions of Lithuania|Ethnographic&nbsp;region]]\n|subdivision_name1 =[[Samogitia]]\n|subdivision_type2 =[[Counties of Lithuania|County]]\n|subdivision_name2 =[[\u0160iauliai County]]\n|subdivision_type3 =[[List of municipalities of Lithuania|Municipality]]\n|subdivision_name3 =[[Akmen\u0117 district municipality]]\n|subdivision_type4 =[[Elderships of Lithuania|Eldership]]\n|subdivision_name4 =Naujoji Akmen\u0117 town eldership\n|subdivision_type6 =[[Capital (political)|Capital of]]\n|subdivision_name6 =[[Akmen\u0117 district municipality]] <br> Naujoji Akmen\u0117 town eldership <br> Naujoji Akmen\u0117 rural eldership\n|established_date  =1949\n|established_title =First mentioned\n|established_date2 =1965\n|established_title2=Granted city rights\n|population_total  =9,300\n|population_as_of  =2011\n|timezone=[[Eastern European Time|EET]]\n|utc_offset=+2\n|timezone_DST=[[Eastern European Summer Time|EEST]]\n|utc_offset_DST=+3\n}}\n\n'''Naujoji Akmen\u0117''' ({{pronunciation|Naujoji Akmene.ogg}}, [[Samogitian dialect|Samogitian]]: ''Naujuoj\u0117 Akmen\u0117'') is a [[new town]] that was established in 1952 and is one of the newest cities in [[Lithuania]]. Its name means ''New [[Akmen\u0117]]''. It is an industrial base with concrete as its main product, with [[Public company]] ''[[Akmen\u0117s cementas]]'' (English: ''Akmen\u0117 Concrete'') producing 700,000 [[tonne]]s of [[concrete]] annually. As a new city, it did initially have well-developed infrastructure. For example, a special branch of the railway had to be built for the factory needs. The road network was rapidly developing before the city even existed.\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category|Naujoji Akmen\u0117}}\n*[http://www.cementas.lt/?obj=changeLng&lng=en Akmen\u0117s Cementas Official Website]\n\n{{Siauliai County}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Naujoji Akmene}}\n[[Category:Cities in Lithuania]]\n[[Category:Cities in \u0160iauliai County]]\n[[Category:Populated places established in 1952]]\n[[Category:Cities and towns built in the Soviet Union]]\n[[Category:Municipalities administrative centres of Lithuania]]\n[[Category:Kovno Governorate]]\n[[Category:Akmen\u0117 District Municipality]]\n\n{{lithuania-geo-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Tekstman", "label": "safe", "comment": "(GR)File renamed:File:Akmen\u0117 COA.svg\u2192File:Naujoji Akmen\u0117 COA.svgCriterion 1(original uploader\u2019s request)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Naujoji_Akmen%C4%97"}
{"title_page": "Akmen\u0117 District Municipality", "text_new": "{{Infobox settlement\n<!-- See Template:Infobox settlement for additional fields and descriptions -->\n| name                    = Akmen\u0117 District Municipality\n| native_name             = Akmen\u0117s rajono savivaldyb\u0117\n| native_name_lang        = lt<!-- ISO 639-2 code e.g. \"lt\" for Lithuanian -->\n| settlement_type         = [[List of municipalities of Lithuania|Municipality]]\n| image_skyline           = Paprtyn\u0117su\u017etvanka.JPG\n| image_alt               = \n| image_caption           = Hydroelectric power plant in Rudikiai\n| image_shield            = Naujoji Akmen\u0117 COA.svg\n| shield_alt              = \n| image_map               = Akmene district location.png\n| map_alt                 = \n| map_caption             = Location of Akmen\u0117 District Municipality within Lithuania\n| image_map1              = \n| map_alt1                = \n| map_caption1            = Map of Akmen\u0117 District Municipality\n| pushpin_map             = <!-- Lithuania -->\n| pushpin_label_position  = \n| pushpin_map_alt         = \n| pushpin_map_caption     = \n| coordinates             = {{coord|56|15|22|N|22|45|14|E|type:adm2nd_region:LT_source:nlwiki|display=inline,title}}\n| coor_pinpoint           = \n| coordinates_footnotes   = \n| subdivision_type        = [[List of sovereign states|Country]]\n| subdivision_name        = {{flag|Lithuania}}\n| subdivision_type1       = [[Regions of Lithuania|Ethnographic region]]\n| subdivision_name1       = [[Samogitia]]\n| subdivision_type2       = [[Counties of Lithuania|County]]\n| subdivision_name2       = [[\u0160iauliai County]]\n| parts_style             = para\n| parts_type              = [[Elderships of Lithuania|Elderships]]\n| p1                      = 6\n| established_title       = <!-- Founded -->\n| established_date        = \n| seat_type               = [[Capital (political)|Capital]]\n| seat                    = [[Naujoji Akmen\u0117]]\n| leader_party            = \n| leader_title            = \n| leader_name             = \n| leader_title1           = \n| leader_name1            =\n| leader_title2           = \n| leader_name2            = \n| unit_pref               = Metric<!-- or US or UK -->\n| area_footnotes          = \n| area_total_km2          = 844\n| area_rank               = 43rd\n| elevation_footnotes     = \n| elevation_m             = \n| population_footnotes    = \n| population_total        = 30300\n| population_as_of        = 2001 census\n| population_rank         = 42nd\n| population_density_km2  = auto\n| population_density_rank = 24th\n| timezone1               = [[Eastern European Time|EET]]\n| utc_offset1             = +2\n| timezone1_DST           = [[Eastern European Summer Time|EEST]]\n| utc_offset1_DST         = +3\n| postal_code_type        = <!-- Postal code -->\n| postal_code             = \n| area_code_type          = Telephone code\n| area_code               = 425 \n| blank_name_sec1         = Major settlements\n| blank_info_sec1         = {{unbulleted list\n  |[[Naujoji Akmen\u0117]] (pop.&nbsp;12,345)\n  |[[Venta]] (pop. 3,412)\n  |[[Akmen\u0117]] (pop. 3,140)\n  }}\n| website                 = {{URL|http://www.akmene.lt/go.php/lit/english}}\n| footnotes               = \n}}\n\n'''Akmen\u0117 District Municipality''' ({{lang-lt|Akmen\u0117s rajono savivaldyb\u0117}}) is one of 60 municipalities in [[Lithuania]]. It lies in the northwest of the country, with administrative centre in [[Naujoji Akmen\u0117]] and borders [[Latvia]] in the north, [[Joni\u0161kis District Municipality]] in the east, [[\u0160iauliai District Municipality]] in the southeast, [[Tel\u0161iai District Municipality]] in the southwest, and [[Ma\u017eeikiai District Municipality]] in the west. The area of the municipality covers ca. 844&nbsp;km\u00b2, its population counts 30,300 (2001 census): 47,19% men, 52,81% women.\n\n== History ==\nAkmen\u0117 district was established in 1950, when the reform of territorial-administrative units was introduced to the [[Lithuanian SSR]]. The region merged part of [[Kur\u0161\u0117nai]] and [[Ma\u017eeikiai]] regions. The administrative centre was settled in [[Akmen\u0117]] town, and in 1962 it was moved to [[Naujoji Akmen\u0117]]. In the same year, the district was merged into [[Ma\u017eeikiai]] district, and in 1965 it emerged as a separate administrative unit. The district municipality was composed from former Akmen\u0117 district in 1995 and in 1999, pursuant to national reform of [[municipality|municipalities]], its territory was expanded by incorporating Viek\u0161niai [[seni\u016bnija]] (elderate).\n\n== Elderates ==\nAkmen\u0117 district municipality is divided into 6 elderates:\n* [[Akmen\u0117]] eldership (administrative centre - [[Akmen\u0117]])\n* [[Kruopiai]] eldership (administrative centre - [[Kruopiai]])\n* [[Naujoji Akmen\u0117]] town eldership (administrative centre - [[Naujoji Akmen\u0117]])\n* [[Naujoji Akmen\u0117 rural eldership|Naujoji Akmen\u0117]] rural eldership (administrative centre - [[Naujoji Akmen\u0117]])\n* [[Papil\u0117]] eldership (administrative centre - [[Papil\u0117]])\n* [[Venta]] eldership (administrative centre - [[Venta]])\n\n== Structure ==\nDistrict structure:   \n* 3 cities \u2013 [[Akmen\u0117]], [[Naujoji Akmen\u0117]] and [[Venta]];\n* 2 towns \u2013 [[Kruopiai]] and [[Papil\u0117]];\n* 165 villages.\n  \nBiggest population (2001):   \n*[[Naujoji Akmen\u0117]] \u2013 12345\n*[[Venta]] \u2013 3412\n*[[Akmen\u0117]] \u2013 3140\n*[[Papil\u0117]] \u2013 1449\n*[[Kruopiai]] \u2013 614\n*[[Kivyliai]] \u2013 551\n*[[Daubi\u0161kiai]] \u2013 493\n*[[Ramu\u010diai]] \u2013 490\n*[[Sablauskiai]] \u2013 477\n*[[Alki\u0161kiai]] \u2013 444\n\n== External links ==\n* {{Official website|http://www.akmene.lt}}\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20061027184120/http://www.vic.akmene.lt/content/tourism.en.html Tourism information]\n* [http://www.lietuva.lt/IMI/i_en.jsp?nr=akmene_raj_teritorija Map of the district]\n\n{{Siauliai County}}\n{{Municipalities of Lithuania}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Akmene District Municipality}}\n[[Category:Akmen\u0117 District Municipality| ]]\n[[Category:Municipalities of \u0160iauliai County]]\n[[Category:Municipalities of Lithuania]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox settlement\n<!-- See Template:Infobox settlement for additional fields and descriptions -->\n| name                    = Akmen\u0117 District Municipality\n| native_name             = Akmen\u0117s rajono savivaldyb\u0117\n| native_name_lang        = lt<!-- ISO 639-2 code e.g. \"lt\" for Lithuanian -->\n| settlement_type         = [[List of municipalities of Lithuania|Municipality]]\n| image_skyline           = Paprtyn\u0117su\u017etvanka.JPG\n| image_alt               = \n| image_caption           = Hydroelectric power plant in Rudikiai\n| image_shield            = Akmen\u0117 COA.svg\n| shield_alt              = \n| image_map               = Akmene district location.png\n| map_alt                 = \n| map_caption             = Location of Akmen\u0117 District Municipality within Lithuania\n| image_map1              = \n| map_alt1                = \n| map_caption1            = Map of Akmen\u0117 District Municipality\n| pushpin_map             = <!-- Lithuania -->\n| pushpin_label_position  = \n| pushpin_map_alt         = \n| pushpin_map_caption     = \n| coordinates             = {{coord|56|15|22|N|22|45|14|E|type:adm2nd_region:LT_source:nlwiki|display=inline,title}}\n| coor_pinpoint           = \n| coordinates_footnotes   = \n| subdivision_type        = [[List of sovereign states|Country]]\n| subdivision_name        = {{flag|Lithuania}}\n| subdivision_type1       = [[Regions of Lithuania|Ethnographic region]]\n| subdivision_name1       = [[Samogitia]]\n| subdivision_type2       = [[Counties of Lithuania|County]]\n| subdivision_name2       = [[\u0160iauliai County]]\n| parts_style             = para\n| parts_type              = [[Elderships of Lithuania|Elderships]]\n| p1                      = 6\n| established_title       = <!-- Founded -->\n| established_date        = \n| seat_type               = [[Capital (political)|Capital]]\n| seat                    = [[Naujoji Akmen\u0117]]\n| leader_party            = \n| leader_title            = \n| leader_name             = \n| leader_title1           = \n| leader_name1            =\n| leader_title2           = \n| leader_name2            = \n| unit_pref               = Metric<!-- or US or UK -->\n| area_footnotes          = \n| area_total_km2          = 844\n| area_rank               = 43rd\n| elevation_footnotes     = \n| elevation_m             = \n| population_footnotes    = \n| population_total        = 30300\n| population_as_of        = 2001 census\n| population_rank         = 42nd\n| population_density_km2  = auto\n| population_density_rank = 24th\n| timezone1               = [[Eastern European Time|EET]]\n| utc_offset1             = +2\n| timezone1_DST           = [[Eastern European Summer Time|EEST]]\n| utc_offset1_DST         = +3\n| postal_code_type        = <!-- Postal code -->\n| postal_code             = \n| area_code_type          = Telephone code\n| area_code               = 425 \n| blank_name_sec1         = Major settlements\n| blank_info_sec1         = {{unbulleted list\n  |[[Naujoji Akmen\u0117]] (pop.&nbsp;12,345)\n  |[[Venta]] (pop. 3,412)\n  |[[Akmen\u0117]] (pop. 3,140)\n  }}\n| website                 = {{URL|http://www.akmene.lt/go.php/lit/english}}\n| footnotes               = \n}}\n\n'''Akmen\u0117 District Municipality''' ({{lang-lt|Akmen\u0117s rajono savivaldyb\u0117}}) is one of 60 municipalities in [[Lithuania]]. It lies in the northwest of the country, with administrative centre in [[Naujoji Akmen\u0117]] and borders [[Latvia]] in the north, [[Joni\u0161kis District Municipality]] in the east, [[\u0160iauliai District Municipality]] in the southeast, [[Tel\u0161iai District Municipality]] in the southwest, and [[Ma\u017eeikiai District Municipality]] in the west. The area of the municipality covers ca. 844&nbsp;km\u00b2, its population counts 30,300 (2001 census): 47,19% men, 52,81% women.\n\n== History ==\nAkmen\u0117 district was established in 1950, when the reform of territorial-administrative units was introduced to the [[Lithuanian SSR]]. The region merged part of [[Kur\u0161\u0117nai]] and [[Ma\u017eeikiai]] regions. The administrative centre was settled in [[Akmen\u0117]] town, and in 1962 it was moved to [[Naujoji Akmen\u0117]]. In the same year, the district was merged into [[Ma\u017eeikiai]] district, and in 1965 it emerged as a separate administrative unit. The district municipality was composed from former Akmen\u0117 district in 1995 and in 1999, pursuant to national reform of [[municipality|municipalities]], its territory was expanded by incorporating Viek\u0161niai [[seni\u016bnija]] (elderate).\n\n== Elderates ==\nAkmen\u0117 district municipality is divided into 6 elderates:\n* [[Akmen\u0117]] eldership (administrative centre - [[Akmen\u0117]])\n* [[Kruopiai]] eldership (administrative centre - [[Kruopiai]])\n* [[Naujoji Akmen\u0117]] town eldership (administrative centre - [[Naujoji Akmen\u0117]])\n* [[Naujoji Akmen\u0117 rural eldership|Naujoji Akmen\u0117]] rural eldership (administrative centre - [[Naujoji Akmen\u0117]])\n* [[Papil\u0117]] eldership (administrative centre - [[Papil\u0117]])\n* [[Venta]] eldership (administrative centre - [[Venta]])\n\n== Structure ==\nDistrict structure:   \n* 3 cities \u2013 [[Akmen\u0117]], [[Naujoji Akmen\u0117]] and [[Venta]];\n* 2 towns \u2013 [[Kruopiai]] and [[Papil\u0117]];\n* 165 villages.\n  \nBiggest population (2001):   \n*[[Naujoji Akmen\u0117]] \u2013 12345\n*[[Venta]] \u2013 3412\n*[[Akmen\u0117]] \u2013 3140\n*[[Papil\u0117]] \u2013 1449\n*[[Kruopiai]] \u2013 614\n*[[Kivyliai]] \u2013 551\n*[[Daubi\u0161kiai]] \u2013 493\n*[[Ramu\u010diai]] \u2013 490\n*[[Sablauskiai]] \u2013 477\n*[[Alki\u0161kiai]] \u2013 444\n\n== External links ==\n* {{Official website|http://www.akmene.lt}}\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20061027184120/http://www.vic.akmene.lt/content/tourism.en.html Tourism information]\n* [http://www.lietuva.lt/IMI/i_en.jsp?nr=akmene_raj_teritorija Map of the district]\n\n{{Siauliai County}}\n{{Municipalities of Lithuania}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Akmene District Municipality}}\n[[Category:Akmen\u0117 District Municipality| ]]\n[[Category:Municipalities of \u0160iauliai County]]\n[[Category:Municipalities of Lithuania]]\n", "name_user": "Tekstman", "label": "safe", "comment": "(GR)File renamed:File:Akmen\u0117 COA.svg\u2192File:Naujoji Akmen\u0117 COA.svgCriterion 1(original uploader\u2019s request)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Akmen%C4%97_District_Municipality"}
{"title_page": "Siege of Exeter (1642)", "text_new": "{{short description|Siege during the First English Civil War}}\n{{Use British English|date=March 2020}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2020}}\n{{Infobox military conflict\n|conflict= The Siege of Exeter (1642)\n|image= River Exe at Exeter Quay.jpg\n|caption= Exeter Quay; its position on the [[River Exe]] made Exeter an important transport hub \n|partof= [[Wars of the Three Kingdoms]]\n|date= December 1642 \u2013 6 January 1643\n|place= [[Exeter]], [[Devon]]\n|result= Parliamentary victory\n|combatant1= {{flagicon image|Royal Standard of England (1603\u20131689).svg|size=22px}} [[Cavalier|Royalists]]\n|combatant2= {{flagicon|Kingdom of England}} [[Roundhead|Parliamentarians]]\n|commander1= {{flagicon image|Royal Standard of England (1603\u20131689).svg|size=22px}} [[Ralph Hopton, 1st Baron Hopton|Sir Ralph Hopton]] <br> {{flagicon image|Royal Standard of England (1603\u20131689).svg|size=22px}} Sir [[Bevil Grenville]]\n|commander2= {{flagicon|Kingdom of England}} [[Henry Grey, 1st Earl of Stamford|Earl of Stamford]] <br> {{flagicon|Kingdom of Scotland}} Colonel Ruthven\n|strength1= 3,000 \n|strength2= <br />\n|casualties1= minimal\n|casualties2= minimal\n|}}\n{{Campaignbox First English Civil War|collapsed=yes}}\nThe '''Siege of Exeter (1642)''', or '''First Siege of Exeter''', took place during the [[First English Civil War]], from 18 November 1642 to 4 January 1643. During this period, a [[Roundhead|Parliamentary]] garrison frustrated two attempts to capture the city by [[Cavalier|Royalists]] under [[Ralph Hopton, 1st Baron Hopton|Sir Ralph Hopton]].\n\nAlthough much of the [[West Country]] was strongly Royalist, the ports of [[Exeter]] and [[Plymouth]] were controlled by Parliament, hindering the import of vital military supplies. From October 1642 to January 1643, the Royalists made several efforts to take one of them.\n\nIn the early stages of the war, neither side was equipped or trained for siege warfare, relying on surprise or treachery. When Hopton arrived at Exeter on 18 November, he found it occupied, and withdrew. In late December, he made a more serious attempt, before retreating on 4 January.\n\nFollowing a series of victories in summer 1643, the Royalists captured Exeter on 6 September; it remained in their possession until April 1646.\n\n==Background==\n[[File:Ralph Hopton, 1st Baron Hopton of Stratton from NPG.jpg|thumb|left|upright|Royalist commander in the west, [[Ralph Hopton, 1st Baron Hopton|Sir Ralph Hopton]]]]\nWhen the war began in August 1642, [[Roundhead|Parliamentary]] forces secured most of southern England, including the ports of [[Southampton]] and [[Dover]], as well as the bulk of the [[Royal Navy]]. After [[Siege of Portsmouth|capturing Portsmouth]] in September, they controlled every major port from [[Plymouth]] to [[Siege of Hull (1642)|Hull]], hampering Royalist efforts to import arms and men from Europe.{{sfn|Wedgwood|1958|pp=119\u2013120}}\n\nBy the end of September, most of [[Devon]] was held by Parliament, while Royalists under [[Ralph Hopton, 1st Baron Hopton|Sir Ralph Hopton]] secured [[Cornwall]]. In the early stages of the war, most soldiers on both sides were poorly trained and equipped [[Trained bands|militia]]. An exception was Plymouth, where the garrison was commanded by Colonel William Ruthven, and a contingent of experienced Scots mercenaries; their ship stopped to pick up supplies returning from Ireland in early October, and the Parliamentary town council hired them to defend the city.{{sfn|Barratt|2005|pp=35\u201338}}\n\nRuthven easily repulsed attempts to take Plymouth, and in early November Hopton crossed the [[River Tamar]], heading for [[Exeter]], although his troops refused to leave Cornwall until paid in advance. Royalist sympathisers told him it was largely undefended, although the town itself was controlled by supporters of Parliament.{{sfn|Royle|2004|p=235}} Its capture meant control of a vital port on the southern coast, an important export point for Devon wool, and whose position on the [[River Exe]] gave access to internal waterways, vital for transporting bulk supplies. It would also provide a base for Royalist [[privateers]].\n\nBy the time Hopton arrived at Exeter on 18 November, it had been occupied by a small force of Parliamentary cavalry under Captain Alexander Pym. After a brief exchange of artillery fire, the Royalists retreated to [[Tavistock]], and made another attempt on Plymouth.{{sfn|Barratt|2005|p=40}}\n\n==Siege==\n{{Location map many|West Country|caption = Western England, 1642 to 1646|relief=yes|border = black| width = 300| float = right\n|label =  BraddockDown|pos=left|lat_deg= 50|lat_min= 26|lon_deg = -4 |lon_min = -34\n|label2 = Exeter|pos2=right|lat2_deg= 50|lat2_min= 43|lon2_deg = -3 |lon2_min = -32\n|label3 = Bridestowe |pos3= top|lat3_deg=50|lat3_min = 44|lon3_deg = -4|lon3_min = 0\n|label4 = Wells|pos4= top|lat4_deg=51|lat4_min = 13|lon4_deg = -2|lon4_min = -39\n|label5 = Barnstaple|pos5=left|lat5_deg=51|lat5_min =05 |lon5_deg = -4 |lon5_min = -3\n|label6 = Sherborne|pos6=bottom|lat6_deg=50|lat6_min =57 |lon6_deg = -2 |lon6_min = -31\n|label7 = |pos7=left|lat7_deg=50|lat7_min = 28 |lon7_deg = -4 |lon7_min = -43\n|label8 = Launceston|pos8=left|lat8_deg=50|lat8_min = 38 |lon8_deg = -4 |lon8_min = -22\n|label9 = Roundway Down|pos9=top|lat9_deg=51|lat9_min = 21 |lon9_deg = -2 |lon9_min = 00\n|label10 = Minehead|pos10=left|lat10_deg=51|lat10_min = 12 |lon10_deg = -3 |lon10_min = -29\n|label12 = Stratton|pos12=left|lat12_deg=50|lat12_min = 50 |lon12_deg = -4 |lon12_min = -31\n|label13 = Plymouth|pos13=right|lat13_deg=50|lat13_min = 22 |lon13_deg = -4 |lon13_min = -9\n|label11 = Torrington|pos11=left|lat11_deg=50|lat11_min = 57 |lon11_deg = -4 |lon11_min = -8\n|label14 = Langport|pos14=left|lat14_deg=51|lat14_min = 03 |lon14_deg = -2 |lon14_min = -48\n|label15 = Truro|pos15=bottom|lat15_deg=50|lat15_min = 16 |lon15_deg = -5 |lon15_min = -03\n}}\nOnce again assured of local support, on 24 December Hopton attacked Exeter again, this time capturing [[Topsham]] and [[Powderham]] to the south, in order to prevent supplies being shipped in via the River Exe. Anticipating this, Colonel Ruthven had already brought in reinforcements from Plymouth, and repulsed a Royalist assault on 1 January.\n\nShort of supplies, and with his troops threatening to mutiny, Hopton was forced to retreat into Cornwall. Ruthven pursued him, hoping to capture the Royalist artillery, but was halted by a successful rearguard action at [[Bridestowe]].\n\n==Aftermath==\nRoyalist victories at [[Battle of Braddock Down|Braddock Down]] in January, then [[Battle of Stratton|Stratton]] in April, destroyed the Parliamentary field army in Cornwall and Devon. This was followed by [[Battle of Roundway Down|Roundway Down]], on 13 July, arguably their most comprehensive victory of the war. On 26 July, [[Prince Rupert of the Rhine|Prince Rupert]] stormed [[Storming of Bristol|Bristol]], gaining the second largest city in Britain.{{sfn|Royle|2004|pp=238\u2013239}}\n\nThis secured Royalist control of the West Country, with the exception of isolated ports like Exeter, which was captured in September 1643; they held it until April 1646.    \n    \n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==Sources==\n* {{cite book |last1=Barratt |first1=John |title=The Civil War in the South-West England 1642\u20131646 (Battlefield Britain) |date=2005 |publisher=Pen & Sword Military |isbn=978-1783460410 |ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book|ref=harv |last=Royle |first=Trevor |year=2004 |edition=2006|title=Civil War: The Wars of the Three Kingdoms 1638\u20131660 |publisher=Abacus |isbn=978-0-349-11564-1}}\n* {{cite book |last1=Wedgwood |first1=CV |title=The King's War, 1641-1647 |date=1958 |publisher=Penguin Classics |isbn=978-0141390727 |ref=harv |edition=2001}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Exeter (1642), Siege of}}\n[[Category:Sieges of the English Civil Wars]]\n[[Category:Military history of Devon]]\n[[Category:1642 in England]]\n[[Category:Conflicts in 1642]]\n[[Category:17th century in Devon]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Siege during the First English Civil War}}\n{{Use British English|date=March 2020}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2020}}\n{{Infobox military conflict\n|conflict= The Siege of Exeter (1642)\n|image= River Exe at Exeter Quay.jpg\n|caption= Exeter Quay; its position on the [[River Exe]] made Exeter an important transport hub \n|partof= [[Wars of the Three Kingdoms]]\n|date= December 1642 - 6 January 1643\n|place= [[Exeter]], [[Devon]]\n|result= Parliamentary victory\n|combatant1= {{flagicon image|Royal Standard of England (1603\u20131689).svg|size=22px}} [[Cavalier|Royalists]]\n|combatant2= {{flagicon|Kingdom of England}} [[Roundhead|Parliamentarians]]\n|commander1= {{flagicon image|Royal Standard of England (1603\u20131689).svg|size=22px}} [[Ralph Hopton, 1st Baron Hopton|Sir Ralph Hopton]] <br> {{flagicon image|Royal Standard of England (1603\u20131689).svg|size=22px}} Sir [[Bevil Grenville]]\n|commander2= {{flagicon|Kingdom of England}} [[Henry Grey, 1st Earl of Stamford|Earl of Stamford]] <br> {{flagicon|Kingdom of Scotland}} Colonel Ruthven\n|strength1= 3,000 \n|strength2= <br />\n|casualties1= minimal\n|casualties2= minimal\n|}}\n{{Campaignbox First English Civil War|collapsed=yes}}\nThe '''Siege of Exeter (1642)''', or '''First Siege of Exeter''', took place during the [[First English Civil War]], from 18 November 1642 to 4 January 1643. During this period, a [[Roundhead|Parliamentary]] garrison frustrated two attempts to capture the city by [[Cavalier|Royalists]] under [[Ralph Hopton, 1st Baron Hopton|Sir Ralph Hopton]].\n\nAlthough much of the [[West Country]] was strongly Royalist, the ports of [[Exeter]] and [[Plymouth]] were controlled by Parliament, hindering the import of vital military supplies. From October 1642 to January 1643, the Royalists made several efforts to take one of them.\n\nIn the early stages of the war, neither side was equipped or trained for siege warfare, relying on surprise or treachery. When Hopton arrived at Exeter on 18 November, he found it occupied, and withdrew. In late December, he made a more serious attempt, before retreating on 4 January.\n\nFollowing a series of victories in summer 1643, the Royalists captured Exeter on 6 September; it remained in their possession until April 1646.\n\n==Background==\n[[File:Ralph Hopton, 1st Baron Hopton of Stratton from NPG.jpg|thumb|left|upright|Royalist commander in the west, [[Ralph Hopton, 1st Baron Hopton|Sir Ralph Hopton]]]]\nWhen the war began in August 1642, [[Roundhead|Parliamentary]] forces secured most of southern England, including the ports of [[Southampton]] and [[Dover]], as well as the bulk of the [[Royal Navy]]. After [[Siege of Portsmouth|capturing Portsmouth]] in September, they controlled every major port from [[Plymouth]] to [[Siege of Hull (1642)|Hull]], hampering Royalist efforts to import arms and men from Europe.{{sfn|Wedgwood|1958|pp=119-120}}\n\nBy the end of September, most of [[Devon]] was held by Parliament, while Royalists under [[Ralph Hopton, 1st Baron Hopton|Sir Ralph Hopton]] secured [[Cornwall]]. In the early stages of the war, most soldiers on both sides were poorly trained and equipped [[Trained bands|militia]]. An exception was Plymouth, where the garrison was commanded by Colonel William Ruthven, and a contingent of experienced Scots mercenaries; their ship stopped to pick up supplies returning from Ireland in early October, and the Parliamentary town council hired them to defend the city.{{sfn|Barratt|2005|pp=35-38}}\n\nRuthven easily repulsed attempts to take Plymouth, and in early November Hopton crossed the [[River Tamar]], heading for [[Exeter]], although his troops refused to leave Cornwall until paid in advance. Royalist sympathisers told him it was largely undefended, although the town itself was controlled by supporters of Parliament.{{sfn|Royle|2004|p=235}} Its capture meant control of a vital port on the southern coast, an important export point for Devon wool, and whose position on the [[River Exe]] gave access to internal waterways, vital for transporting bulk supplies. It would also provide a base for Royalist [[privateers]].\n\nBy the time Hopton arrived at Exeter on 18 November, it had been occupied by a small force of Parliamentary cavalry under Captain Alexander Pym. After a brief exchange of artillery fire, the Royalists retreated to [[Tavistock]], and made another attempt on Plymouth.{{sfn|Barratt|2005|p=40}}\n\n==Siege==\n{{Location map many|West Country|caption = Western England, 1642 to 1646|relief=yes|border = black| width = 300| float = right\n|label =  BraddockDown|pos=left|lat_deg= 50|lat_min= 26|lon_deg = -4 |lon_min = -34\n|label2 = Exeter|pos2=right|lat2_deg= 50|lat2_min= 43|lon2_deg = -3 |lon2_min = -32\n|label3 = Bridestowe |pos3= top|lat3_deg=50|lat3_min = 44|lon3_deg = -4|lon3_min = 0\n|label4 = Wells|pos4= top|lat4_deg=51|lat4_min = 13|lon4_deg = -2|lon4_min = -39\n|label5 = Barnstaple|pos5=left|lat5_deg=51|lat5_min =05 |lon5_deg = -4 |lon5_min = -3\n|label6 = Sherborne|pos6=bottom|lat6_deg=50|lat6_min =57 |lon6_deg = -2 |lon6_min = -31\n|label7 = |pos7=left|lat7_deg=50|lat7_min = 28 |lon7_deg = -4 |lon7_min = -43\n|label8 = Launceston|pos8=left|lat8_deg=50|lat8_min = 38 |lon8_deg = -4 |lon8_min = -22\n|label9 = Roundway Down|pos9=top|lat9_deg=51|lat9_min = 21 |lon9_deg = -2 |lon9_min = 00\n|label10 = Minehead|pos10=left|lat10_deg=51|lat10_min = 12 |lon10_deg = -3 |lon10_min = -29\n|label12 = Stratton|pos12=left|lat12_deg=50|lat12_min = 50 |lon12_deg = -4 |lon12_min = -31\n|label13 = Plymouth|pos13=right|lat13_deg=50|lat13_min = 22 |lon13_deg = -4 |lon13_min = -9\n|label11 = Torrington|pos11=left|lat11_deg=50|lat11_min = 57 |lon11_deg = -4 |lon11_min = -8\n|label14 = Langport|pos14=left|lat14_deg=51|lat14_min = 03 |lon14_deg = -2 |lon14_min = -48\n|label15 = Truro|pos15=bottom|lat15_deg=50|lat15_min = 16 |lon15_deg = -5 |lon15_min = -03\n}}\nOnce again assured of local support, on 24 December Hopton attacked Exeter again, this time capturing [[Topsham]] and [[Powderham]] to the south, in order to prevent supplies being shipped in via the River Exe. Anticipating this, Colonel Ruthven had already brought in reinforcements from Plymouth, and repulsed a Royalist assault on 1 January.\n\nShort of supplies, and with his troops threatening to mutiny, Hopton was forced to retreat into Cornwall. Ruthven pursued him, hoping to capture the Royalist artillery, but was halted by a successful rearguard action at [[Bridestowe]].\n\n==Aftermath==\nRoyalist victories at [[Battle of Braddock Down|Braddock Down]] in January, then [[Battle of Stratton|Stratton]] in April, destroyed the Parliamentary field army in Cornwall and Devon. This was followed by [[Battle of Roundway Down|Roundway Down]], on 13 July, arguably their most comprehensive victory of the war. On 26 July, [[Prince Rupert of the Rhine|Prince Rupert]] stormed [[Storming of Bristol|Bristol]], gaining the second largest city in Britain.{{sfn|Royle|2004|pp=238-239}}\n\nThis secured Royalist control of the West Country, with the exception of isolated ports like Exeter, which was captured in September 1643; they held it until April 1646.    \n    \n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==Sources==\n* {{cite book |last1=Barratt |first1=John |title=The Civil War in the South-West England 1642-1646 (Battlefield Britain) |date=2005 |publisher=Pen & Sword Military |isbn=978-1783460410 |ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book|ref=harv |last=Royle |first=Trevor |year=2004 |edition=2006|title=Civil War: The Wars of the Three Kingdoms 1638\u20131660 |publisher=Abacus |isbn=978-0-349-11564-1}}\n* {{cite book |last1=Wedgwood |first1=CV |title=The King's War, 1641-1647 |date=1958 |publisher=Penguin Classics |isbn=978-0141390727 |ref=harv |edition=2001}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Exeter (1642), Siege of}}\n[[Category:Sieges of the English Civil Wars]]\n[[Category:Military history of 