{"title_page": "Municipalities of Lithuania", "text_new": "[[File:EU-Lithuania.svg|thumb|right|250px|alt=Map of the European Union with Lithuania highlighted in green|Location of [[Lithuania]] in the [[European Union]]]]\n{{Politics of Lithuania}}\n__NOTOC__\n[[Lithuania]] is divided into three layers of [[administrative division of Lithuania|administrative divisions]]. The first-level division consists of [[Counties of Lithuania|10 counties]] ([[Lithuanian language|Lithuanian]]: singular \u2013 ''apskritis'', plural \u2013 ''apskritys''). These are sub-divided into 60 municipalities (Lithuanian: plural \u2013 ''savivaldyb\u0117s'', singular \u2013 ''savivaldyb\u0117''), which in turn are further sub-divided into over 500 smaller groups, known as [[elderships of Lithuania|elderships]] (Lithuanian: plural \u2013 ''seni\u016bnijos'', singular \u2013 ''seni\u016bnija'').\n\nAt the end of its tenure as a Soviet Socialist Republic, Lithuania's administrative divisions consisted of 44 regions, 12 cities, 80 towns, 19 settlements, and 426 rural districts.<ref name=conf>{{cite book|title=Conference on Local and Regional Authority Co-operation in the Baltic Sea Area: proceedings, Kaunas, Lithuania, 21-23, April 1999|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Mwf_B72sxDoC&pg=PA9|accessdate=16 February 2011|date=January 2000|publisher=Council of Europe|isbn=978-92-871-4538-3|page=9}}</ref> The reform of this system was an immediate concern for the new government.<ref name=coe>{{cite web|url=http://www.coe.int/t/dgap/localdemocracy/programmes_democratic_stability/imc/Warsaw_Documents/Warsaw_Vaiciuniene.pdf|publisher=[[Council of Europe]]|author=Jolanta Vai\u010di\u016bnien\u0117|date=2008-11-14|accessdate=16 February 2011|title=The Administrative\u2013Territorial Reform in Lithuania: History and Today}}</ref> The [[Constitution of Lithuania]], ratified in 1992, delegated the power of establishing future administrative units to the Lithuanian Parliament ([[Seimas]]). Accordingly, the Seimas passed two fundamental laws: a 1993 law on government representation and a 1994 law specifying the territorial-administrative units and their boundaries.<ref name=coe/> The current system of a set of municipalities under 10 counties was codified by 1995.<ref name=coe/> Several changes were made in 2000, resulting in 60 municipalities.<ref name=\"(Program)Development2007\">{{cite book|author1=Local Economic and Employment Development (Program)|author2=Organisation for Economic Co-operation and Development|title=Baltic partnerships: integration, growth and local governance in the Baltic Sea Region|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=g7TJcbAm2gEC&pg=PA75|accessdate=23 February 2011|date=April 2007|publisher=OECD Publishing|isbn=978-92-64-02928-6|page=75}}</ref> Ordinary municipal councilors are elected every four years from electoral lists using proportional representation. The mayor, who is a member of the council, is elected directly by the residents in a majority vote.<ref name=\"MunicipalLaw\">{{cite web |url=http://www3.lrs.lt/pls/inter3/dokpaieska.showdoc_l?p_id=491878 |title=Law on elections to municipal councils |publisher=The Seimas of the Republic of Lithuania |access-date=31 July 2015}}</ref> Before 2015, the mayors were elected by the municipal councils.\n\nThe largest municipality by population in Lithuania is [[Vilnius City Municipality]] with 542,626 residents, home to one fifth ({{percentage|542626|2921262\n|1}}) of the country's population. The smallest municipality by population is [[Neringa Municipality]] with 2,879 residents. The largest municipality by land area is [[Var\u0117na District Municipality]], which spans {{convert|2216|km2|mi2|abbr=on}}, while the smallest is [[Alytus City Municipality]] at {{convert|40|km2|mi2|abbr=on}}.\n\n==Powers and functions==\nThe processes of integration into [[international organization|international organizations]] - like the [[European Union|EU]] and NATO - are considered to be important external factors influencing the development of municipal [[Power (social and political)|powers]] in the country. [[Lithuania]], which has become a member of these organizations, has been assigned completely new responsibilities, some of which, naturally, also belonged to municipalities. In the case of EU integration, municipalities have been assigned the necessary information supply to the [[European Commission]], and in the case of integration into [[NATO]], [[municipality|municipalities]] have had new functions related to [[security]] issues.<ref>Burbulyt\u0117-Tsiskarishvili, G., Dvorak,J., \u017dernyt\u0117, A. (2018). Savivaldybi\u0173 funkcij\u0173 ir gali\u0173 kaita 1994 - 2016 metais. Vie\u0161oji politika ir administravimas, t.17, No.3 Access through Internet: https://www.mruni.eu/upload/iblock/db3/5_Burbulyt%C4%97-Tsiskarishvili_Dvorak_%C5%BDernyt%C4%97.pdf</ref>\n\n[[Image:Municipalities in Lithuania.png|alt=A map divided into ten sections all filled in with a different colour and further subdivided into subsections]]\n{|\n|-\n|valign=top width=225px|\n1 \u2013 [[Vilnius City Municipality]]<br>\n2 \u2013 [[Kaunas City Municipality]]<br>\n3 \u2013 [[Klaip\u0117da City Municipality]]\n|valign=top width=225px|\n4 \u2013 [[Panev\u0117\u017eys City Municipality]]<br>\n5 \u2013 [[\u0160iauliai City Municipality]]<br>\n6 \u2013 [[Alytus City Municipality]]\n|\n7 \u2013 [[Bir\u0161tonas Municipality]]<br>\n8 \u2013 [[Palanga City Municipality]]<br>\n9 \u2013 [[Visaginas Municipality]]<br>\n10 \u2013 [[Neringa Municipality]]<br>\n|-\n|}\n\n==Municipalities==\n{|class=\"sortable wikitable\" style=\"text-align: left; margin: 0 0 0 0;\"\t\n|- \t\n! height=50px scope=\"col\" | Municipality\t\n! scope=\"col\" | County\t\n! scope=\"col\" | Administrative center<ref>Municipality administrative centers and coats of arms are given by [[Statistics Lithuania]] in subpages under the Portrait of the Regions of Lithuania; e.g. [http://regionai.stat.gov.lt/en/alytaus_apskritis/alytaus_miesto_savivaldybe.html Alytus town municipality] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110526195834/http://regionai.stat.gov.lt/en/alytaus_apskritis/alytaus_miesto_savivaldybe.html |date=2011-05-26 }}.</ref>\t\n! scope=\"col\" | Area<ref name=stat>{{cite web|url=http://osp.stat.gov.lt/en/statistiniu-rodikliu-analize?portletFormName=visualization&hash=96dcad8d-50ae-4150-b72f-bc644a038cde |title=Area (land) at the beginning of the year, Population density at the beginning of the year, Resident population at the beginning of the year  |publisher=[[Statistics Lithuania]] |accessdate=4 February 2016}}</ref>\t\n! scope=\"col\" | [[Populations|Pop.]] (2015)<ref name=stat/>\t\n! scope=\"col\" | [[Population density|Density]] (2015)<ref name=stat/>\t\n|-\t\n| height=50px scope=\"row\" |[[Image:Naujoji Akmen\u0117 COA.svg|alt=A coat of arms depicting orange tools on a white background on the top and an orange sun on a dark green background on the bottom|left|30px]] [[Akmen\u0117 District Municipality]] || {{sort|Siauliai|[[\u0160iauliai County|\u0160iauliai]]}} || [[Naujoji Akmen\u0117]]  || align=center| {{convert|844|km2|acre sqmi|2|lk=off|sortable=on|abbr=on}} || align=center| 21,332 || align=center| 25.3\t\n|-\t\n| height=50px scope=\"row\" |[[Image:Coat of arms of Alytus (Lithuania).svg|alt=A coat of arms depicting a white flower in the middle that has a yellow stamen and green leaves all on a red background|left|30px]] [[Alytus City Municipality]] || [[Alytus County|Alytus]] || [[Alytus]]  || align=center| {{convert|40|km2|acre sqmi|2|lk=off|sortable=on|abbr=on}} || align=center| 55,614 || align=center| 1,390.4 \t\n|-\t\n| height=50px scope=\"row\" |[[Image:Alytus district COA.svg|alt=A coat of arms depicting three flowers that have red petals, green stalks, and green leaves all sprouting from green earth|left|30px]] [[Alytus District Municipality]] || [[Alytus County|Alytus]] || [[Alytus]]<ref group=nb name=note/>  || align=center| {{convert|1,403|km2|acre sqmi|